<HTML><!--created by Oyster Systems--><!--May 1996--><HEAD><TITLE>EMWL: Euromoney Magazine: March 1996</TITLE></HEAD><body bgcolor="FFFFFF" vlink="7C1568" text="000000" link="7C1568"><center><table border=0><tr><td colspan=2 align=left><nobr><img width=199 height=44 name="top" border=0 hspace=0 src="../../../images/conban7.gif" alt="Euromoney Magazine"><a href="../../../../../index.html"><img width=141 height=45 border=0 hspace=0 src="../../../../images/conban1.gif" alt="EMWL Home"></a></nobr><br></td></tr><font size=3><tr><td></td><td valign=top><h2>March 1996</h2></td></tr> <tr><td valign=top align=left><img width=121 height=34 src="../../../images/conra10.gif" alt="Supplement"></td><td valign=top align=left><H3>SPAIN</H3> <H4>A EUROMONEY SURVEY - MARCH 1996 </H4> <H2>Legal guide</H2><H4>BACKGROUND </H4>The structure of Spanish legislation is comparable to that of leading worldwideeconomies. This is partly due to the demands of the European Union of whichSpain is a member, but also due to the desire of the Spanish governmentto internationalize its financial markets. Liberalization in Spain in thelast 10 years has been widespread and rapid. <H3>LEGAL FRAMEWORK </H3>The legal framework for the financial sector is based upon several importantpieces of legislation. The central bank is responsible for a monetary policybased on economic stability and meeting the challenges of the changing financialservices sector. It is also responsible for credit guidelines, banking disciplineand questions of solvency. <BR><BR>The securities market regulation is based on the 1988 Securities MarketAct and its amendments and provisions. This covers all aspects of the financialmarkets from listing to trading and control of markets and participants.<H3>EQUITIES: SHARES </H3>A share is a security which represents an equal division or proportionalpart of a corporation (sociedad an&oacute;nima). The fundamental characteristicof a sociedad an&oacute;nima is the division of its capital into shares,which incorporate the shareholders' rights. Shares can be represented bycertificates (registered or bearer) or by book-entries. With registeredshares, the owner's identity appears among the certificates' registers,while if they are represented by book-entries, such information does notappear. <BR><BR><B><I>Transfer</I></B> <BR><BR>The transfer of those shares materialized in book-entries takes place througha complex process known as an accounting transfer. If the shares are inregistered form, they may be transferred by a much simpler endorsement procedure.<BR><BR>Shares not listed on an exchange are governed by the Companies Act (Leyde Sociedades An&oacute;nimas) of 1989, as amended. If the shares are listedon an exchange, the base rule is the Securities Market Act (Ley del Mercadode Valores) of 1988. <BR><BR><B><I>Tax aspects</I></B> <BR><BR>Following the 1988 introduction of the Securities Market Act, a transferof shares, whether or not admitted to an official secondary market, is exemptfrom both transfer tax (Impuesto sobre Transmisiones Patrimoniales; ITP)and value-added tax. However, transfers on the secondary market of securitiesof companies, funds, associations and other entities, whose assets are atleast 50% formed by property located in Spain, are the exception and thereforesubject to transfer tax. <H4>EQUITIES: CORPORATE PARTICIPATIONS </H4>In accordance with the provisions of Law 2/1995, in respect of limited liabilitycompanies (&quot;Sociedades de Responsabilidad Limitada&quot;), the corporatecapital must be divided into indivisible and cumulative corporate participations.These are not considered to be securities, may not be represented eitherby book-entries or physical certificates, and may not be referred to asshares. Lack of classification as a security implies on the one hand thatthey may not be traded on an organized securities market and, on the otherhand, that such limited liability companies may not be listed on an exchange.<BR><BR><B><I>Transfers</I></B> <BR><BR>Voluntary transfers of participations among partners, as well as those carriedout in favour of a spouse, ascendant or descendant of the partner or infavour of companies belonging to the same group as the transferor, are freelypermitted, unless otherwise provided in the company's by-laws. <H3>CORPORATE BONDS </H3>Bonds may be represented by certificates (in registered or bearer form)or by book-entries. In the event that the bonds are represented by certificates,these are issued in a numbered series and are negotiable. <BR><BR>In the case of default, there is a very quick procedure (juicio ejecutivo)which allows auction of the debtor's property. The representation of bondsthrough book-entries is obligatory if it is intended that the bonds become,or remain, admitted to trading on an official securities market. <BR><BR>Sociedades an&oacute;nimas, in terms of bond issuance, are governed by theCompanies Act, the Securities Market Act and the Mercantile Registry Regulations.Limited liability companies may not issue bonds. <BR><BR>Normally sociedades an&oacute;nimas use bond issues as a means of financing.There is a requirement that the total amount of the issue not exceed thesum of paid-in share capital, any reserves which appear on the latest approvedbalance sheet, regularization accounts and balance sheet updates. <BR><BR>There are some exceptions to this limit: <BR><BR>1) When the issue is guaranteed by mortgages, pledges, the state, an autonomouscommunity, a province or a municipality <BR><BR>2) When the issue is carried out by banks <BR><BR>3) When the issue is carried out by highway licensee companies. <BR><BR>Bonds may be classified either as simple or convertible, and as ordinaryor guaranteed. The difference between simple and convertible is based onwhether or not they incorporate the right to be converted into shares ina new issue of the company, while the difference between ordinary and guaranteedlies in whether or not they are backed by a special guarantee (mortgages,pledge, guarantee of the state, the autonomous community, province or municipality).<H3>TREASURY SECURITIES </H3>The Spanish government securities market is distinguished between short-termtreasury debt, both bills and notes (Deuda del Tesoro) and longer term statedebt (Deuda del Estado). <BR><BR><B><I>Deuda del Tesoro</I></B> <BR><BR>Deuda del Tesoro are short-term securities issued by the Bank of Spain tobolster cash flow or to fulfil monetary policy goals. <BR><BR>The Bank of Spain issues treasury bills or notes (Letras del Tesoro or Pagar&eacute;sdel Tesoro) which are normally acquired by private banks, savings banksand by money market dealers. Letras del Tesoro usually have a duration of12 months. Pagar&eacute;s del Tesoro have a maximum redemption period of18 months. <BR><BR><B><I>Deuda del Estado</I></B> <BR><BR>Deuda del Estado are medium-term and long-term bonds issued to finance publicexpenditure and official credit. State bonds are medium-term (five years),while debentures are 10 years. The structure of the Spanish government debtmarket structure was altered to a book-entry system with the 1986 StateBudgetary Act, based on articles of the General Budgetary Act. This newsystem permits greater speed in securities trading. <BR><BR>Both the short-term and long-term treasury markets have experienced stronggrowth in Spain in recent years, due principally to a decline in interestrates. Investors have been able to secure high returns which enjoy the guaranteeof the state. <H3>FOREIGN EXCHANGE </H3>Currency market regulations have changed profoundly because of liberalizationin the European Union. This liberalization has created significant modificationsin both the spot and forward markets. One important change is the tradingof the peseta directly against all of the EU currencies instead of calculatingforeign exchange by cross-rates via the dollar. In addition, because ofthe new foreign exchange freedom, banks can now establish their own fixingor average foreign currency exchange rates which may differ from those publishedby the Bank of Spain. <BR><BR>Furthermore, individuals and legal entities, either resident or non-residentin Spain, may obtain loans and credits in foreign currencies or in pesetas,granted either from within or outside Spain. When a resident or non-residentapplies to a bank for financing in Spain it is not necessary to obtain anyprevious authorization on the part of the government, no matter what theamount is. If the financing is applied for abroad, a resident will needto obtain a financial transaction number (N&uacute;mero de Operaci&oacute;nFinanciera or NOF). This is generally assigned by the Bank of Spain, andits purpose is to allow the central bank to obtain statistical data on thecountry's foreign indebtedness. Loans and credits from non-residents toresidents and vice versa are regulated by Bank of Spain Circular 23/1992.<BR><BR>Both resident and non-resident persons (individuals or legal entities) mayopen and maintain current accounts, savings accounts and term deposits,in pesetas or foreign currency, within or outside Spain. Non-resident personswho wish to open this type of account in Spain must demonstrate their non-residentstatus to the registered entity and confirm such status every two years.Such accounts are regulated by a 1991 ministry of economy and finance orderand the Bank of Spain Circular 1/1994. <H3>DERIVATIVES </H3><B><I>Futures and Options</I></B> <BR><BR>In Spain, there are two official organized markets for financial futures.On one, options and financial futures on fixed-income are traded. It isgoverned by a company called MEFF Sociedad Rectora de Productos FinancierosDerivados de Renta Fija, headquartered in Barcelona. The other market tradesequity derivatives, and is governed by a company named MEFF Renta Variable,headquartered in Madrid. The capital of both companies is wholly owned byMEFF Sociedad Holding de Productos Financieros Derivados, also headquarteredin Barcelona. MEFF is the equivalent of the London International FInancialFutures Exchange (Liffe). <BR><BR>Bearing in mind that derivatives contracts are recent creations in Spain,the regulations are generally insufficient. For purely contractual aspects,the Royal Decree 1814/1991 regulates the official futures and options markets.In addition there are other laws and acts which regulate different aspectsof the market such as the 1993 amended Bank of Spain Circular 4/1991 whichrefers to contracts and their form of accounting; articles 31, 59 and 77of the Securities Market Act, which created the futures and options marketsin Spain; and the 1989 treasury and financial policy resolution which allowsfutures and options on public debt book entries. <BR><BR>In Spain, no specific rules regulate commodities although in 1995 a newmarket for futures and options on citrus fruit was created in Valencia.This market follows the model of the Chicago commodities exchange. <H3>CUSTODY AND SETTLEMENT </H3>Settlement refers to the delivery of securities subject to trading. It alsorefers to the payment for such securities. Initially, because all securitieswere represented by physical certificates, settlement implied the physicalmovement of the certificates. This is what is now known as the traditionalsystem. <BR><BR>The proliferation of sociedades anonimas with high levels of capital createda massive onset of certificates, the possession of which became necessaryin order to exercise shareholder rights. Therefore, a system was neededwhich would be capable of transferring shares, bonds and coupons, as wellas a system for the exercise of the rights they incorporate, without theneed physically to mobilize, manipulate or materially transfer anything.A 1974 decree implemented by ministerial order in the same year createda new system for clearing and settling securities transactions. <BR><BR>Only securities which officially trade on the securities exchanges (Madrid,Barcelona, Bilbao and Valencia) may be admitted to this system. In addition,they must meet certain requirements: <BR><BR>1) that the governing bodies of the exchanges on which they trade allowthem to be so traded <BR><BR>2) that they be possessed by a member entity of the system <BR><BR>3) that they not be subject to any condition which prevents their beingtreated as fungible <BR><BR>4) that they not be subject to any pledge, retention, or lien. <BR><BR>In order to settle securities transactions, the governing body of each exchangeorganizes a settlement and clearing service which, in addition to controllingthe securities included in the system, takes care of their accounting instrumentationand registration. The service will open accounts, in respect of the movementsof securities, in the names of the member entities of the system. Theseaccounts will be set off on each class of security, in which the securitiesbought and sold during each securities exchange session are paid and chargedto them. <BR><BR>The 1992 General Directorate of International Economy and Foreign Transactions(Direcci&oacute;n General de Econom&iacute;a Internacional y TransaccionesExteriores or DGEITE) resolution states that investors non-resident in Spainwho subscribe or acquire securities which are negotiable on the Spanishmarket must maintain their securities accounts or custody of certificatesat a Spanish entity (banks, savings banks, credit cooperatives, and evenbroker/dealers). The holders of these accounts may freely transfer themfrom one entity to another. <H3>DIRECT INVESTMENT </H3>In recent years, liberalization has bolstered foreign capital inflows toSpain. The Royal Decree 671/1992 establishes the legal framework for thistype of investment and was adapted to take into account the current statusof the Spanish economy and European Community regulations. (Directive 88/361in 1988 liberalized the movements of capital between persons residing inmember states of the EU.) <BR><BR>Those investments made by governments and entities of foreign sovereigntybelonging to non-community states require authorization by the Spanish councilof ministers, unless they are allowed by virtue of international treatiessigned and ratified by Spain. <BR><BR>According to the royal decree, direct foreign investments are deemed tobe those which are: <BR><BR>* participation in Spanish companies where the investor may effectivelyinfluence the management or control of the company by its participationor what its participation would become <BR><BR>* the establishment and expansion of branches, as well as the granting ofrepayable advances <BR><BR>* the granting of long-term (greater than five years) loans to Spanish companies<BR><BR>* the capitalization of reserves and reinvestment of undistributed profits<BR><BR>* the acquisition of property when such acquisition in itself constitutesa business activity. <BR><BR><B><I>Scheme of direct investments</I></B> <BR><BR>In general, this type of investment is freely permitted and only requiresprior administrative clearance from the General Directorate of InternationalEconomy and Foreign Transactions (DGEITE) in certain circumstances. <BR><BR>These are when: <BR><BR>* the foreign holding exceeds 50% of the capital of the Spanish companywhich receives the investment and any of the following circumstances arepresent: <BR><BR>- that the amount of the investment exceeds Pta500 million <BR><BR>- that the foreign holding in the share capital plus reserves of the Spanishcompany is greater than Pta500 million <BR><BR>* the amount of the loans or the amount of the establishment or expansionof branches exceeds Pta500 million or comes from natural persons or legalentities resident in tax havens; <BR><BR>* the foreign holding exceeds 50% of the capital of the Spanish companyreceiving the investment and any of the investors is a natural person orlegal entity resident in a tax haven. <BR><BR><B><I>Declaration and registration</I></B> <BR><BR>Foreign investments must formally be made by means of a document authorizedby a Spanish certifying official and declared to the investment registryof the ministry of economy and finance. <H3>TRADE FINANCE </H3><B><I>Official export credit</I></B> <BR><BR>This is an officially-backed credit which is granted to finance the amountof an export contract for Spanish goods and services. Not all types of goodsare included, but rather equipment and factories, second-hand goods, boatsand aircraft, etc. Consumer goods and agricultural products, as well asmilitary goods, are excluded. <BR><BR>The following forms of credit exist: <BR><BR>* credit to the domestic supplier; <BR><BR>* credit to the foreign purchaser. <BR><BR>With regard to the first type of credit, the exporter receives from theimporter at least 15% of the amount of the commercial contract (advancepayment) and receives from the financial entity a credit for 85%, whichit is obliged to repay. <BR><BR>The importer will pay the deferred amount of the commercial contract (85%),the amount of which the exporter will normally apply towards cancellingthe credit granted by the bank. <BR><BR>In the second case, the importer is bound to the financial entity. Normally,however, a financing entity other than the importer and from the same countrymay appear, who will assume the payment obligation in the name of the importer.This credit only becomes effective when the exporter receives the advancepayment, which is also referred to as a deposit or down payment (at least15% of the amount of the commercial contract). Within this form, two typesexist: <BR><BR>* individual credit agreement: this refers to a credit designed and negotiatedto finance a specific export contract <BR><BR>* line of credit: this is a standard agreement or global credit limit againstwhich, and up until the limit of which, operations in respect of variouscommercial agreements may be financed. <BR><BR>The following regulations govern these credits: <BR><BR>* Law 11/1983; <BR><BR>* Royal Decree 322/1987 ; <BR><BR>* Ministerial Order of March 5 1987 <BR><BR>* Resolution of March 13 1987 of the General Directorate of Commercial Policy<BR><BR>* Ministerial Order of March 8 1988 <BR><BR>These regulations are compatible with the international frame of reference,called OECD consensus, for this type of financing. The consensus becameeffective in April 1978, and is an informal agreement which establishesa self-imposed limitation on the conditions and practices in respect ofexport credit (minimum interest rates, amortization periods, prepayment,etc). <BR><BR><B><I>Export credit insurance</I></B> <BR><BR>Normally, entities financing these operations take out a policy with Compa&ntilde;&iacute;aEspa&ntilde;ola de Seguros de Cr&eacute;dito a la Exportaci&oacute;n (CESCE),an insurance and underwriting company the majority of whose capital is ownedby the Spanish state. The policy covers any credit (or non-payment) risksderiving from these operations. Such risks of non-payment may be due tocommercial, political, or extraordinary natural causes. <BR><BR>One of the characteristics of these export credits is that they often aresubject to fixed, below-market interest rates. This characteristic, togetherwith others, such as customarily long amortization periods, make them inadvisableas an investment alternative. <BR><BR>In order to pay the difference between the cost of funds for the financingbank and the OECD consensus rate, in 1983 the state introduced an agreementfor reciprocal interest adjustment, called Contrato de Ajuste Reciprocode Intereses or CARI. Through the system, the Official Credit Institute(Instituto de Cr&eacute;dito Oficial or ICO) is required to pay to the financingentity a constant return during the life of the credit, in order that thebank will grant the credit under conditions which are more advantageousto the borrower than those which would otherwise prevail in the market.<HR><BR><BR><B>Foreign investment in Spanish stock exchanges</B> <IMG SRC="images/em.96.03.26.6.gif"WIDTH="442" HEIGHT="241" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"> <BR>For further information, contact: <H3>ESTUDIO LEGAL <BR>ABOGADOS </H3>_____________________________ <BR><BR>Luis Fernando Lopez-Chicheri <BR><BR>c/ Vel&aacute;zquez, 51 <BR><BR>28001-Madrid <BR><BR>Tel: (34-1) 578.06.43 <BR><BR>Fax: (34-1) 431.21.52 <p></td></tr></table><br><nobr><a href="em.96.03.26.index.html" onMouseOver="window.status='Back a Page';return true"><img width=22 height=22 border=0 src="../../../../../images/navt1.gif" alt="Back"></a><a href="../../../../../services/faqs.html" onMouseOver="window.status='Help';return true"><img width=22 height=22 hspace=90 border=0 src="../../../../../images/navt2.gif" alt="Help"></a><a href="#top" onMouseOver="window.status='Top of the Page';return true"><img width=22 height=22 border=0 src="../../../../../images/navt3.gif" alt="Top"></a></nobr><br><br><nobr><a href="../../../../../alert/index.html" onMouseOver="window.status='ALERT - Discussion Groups, Latest News, Site Updates, Sponsors and Events Diary';return true"><img width=120 height=31 border=0 hspace=0 src="../../../../../images/nav1.gif" alt="Alert"></a><a href="../../../../../search/index.html" onMouseOver="window.status='SEARCH - Keyword and Structured Searches';return true"><img width=120 height=31 border=0 hspace=0 src="../../../../../images/nav2.gif" alt="Search"></a><a href="../../../../../services/index.html" onMouseOver="window.status='SERVICES - FAQs, Feedback, Problems and EMWL Team';return true"><img width=120 height=31 border=