<HTML><!--created by Oyster Systems--><!--May 1996--><HEAD><TITLE>EMWL: Euromoney Magazine: March 1996</TITLE></HEAD><body bgcolor="FFFFFF" vlink="7C1568" text="000000" link="7C1568"><center><table border=0><tr><td colspan=2 align=left><nobr><img width=199 height=44 name="top" border=0 hspace=0 src="../../../images/conban7.gif" alt="Euromoney Magazine"><a href="../../../../../index.html"><img width=141 height=45 border=0 hspace=0 src="../../../../images/conban1.gif" alt="EMWL Home"></a></nobr><br></td></tr><font size=3><tr><td></td><td valign=top><h2>March 1996</h2></td></tr> <tr><td valign=top align=left><img width=121 height=34 src="../../../images/conra10.gif" alt="Supplement"></td><td valign=top align=left> <H3>SWITZERLAND</H3><H4>A EUROMONEY SURVEY - MARCH 1996 </H4><H2>Custody and settlement </H2><H4>A special report prepared by Union Bank of Switzerland</h4><H3>INTRODUCTION </H3>Stable political, economic and social conditions, a strong Swiss franc andthe efficiency and know-how of the Swiss institutions have made Switzerlanda top-ranking financial centre. Swiss securities are included in any significantinternational investment portfolio and volumes from overseas investors continueto increase. Switzerland has the third-largest equity market in Europe witha market capitalization in 1995 of over Swfr458.6 billion and a turnoverof approximately Swfr374 billion for domestic equities. <BR><BR>Over the past five years the Swiss market has undergone tremendous changesand its market participants can now take full advantage of one of the world'sleading technically-advanced infrastructures. Today, the Swiss financialnetwork electronically links SOFFEX (The Swiss Options and Financial FuturesExchange), EBS (Electronic Stock Exchange), SECOM (SEGA communication system),SIC (Swiss interbank clearing) and Telekurs (market information provider),thereby increasing the liquidity and transparency of the market and reducingsettlement risk to a minimum. These developments could only be achievedthrough extraordinary cooperation between the leading Swiss financial institutionsand the longsightedness of the federal and cantonal bodies. <BR><BR>Standardized options and futures, ranging from options on individual sharesand index-linked options to index- and interest-linked futures contracts,are traded on SOFFEX, which started in 1988 and ranks amongst the leadingEuropean derivatives exchanges. Trading and clearing are fully integratedand automated. <BR><BR>EBS commenced the first phase of its operations with the trading of foreignequities on December 8 1995. It is a computerized and continuous order-driventrading system, replacing the existing exchange floors of the three regionalexchanges (Zurich, Basle and Geneva) and assuming their central tasks. Thenext phases will occur later in 1996. The floors will finally cease to existwhen the remaining products are also traded through EBS. The electronicexchange will enable all market participants to have access to a centralpricing mechanism and order size will be visible via computer screen. Aswas the case under the old open outcry system, the investors still placetheir orders with a bank, and in this respect the new electronic exchangedoes not affect them. Nevertheless, the investor is indirectly affectedby numerous changes such as new trading hours (from 9:30am to 4:30pm) andcompulsory trading of small and middle-sized transactions. For investors,the main advantage of EBS is a fairer market due to the increased transparencywhich results from the continuous reporting of prices as well as volumes.These changes will not only lead to a greater flexibility in the operationof the Swiss stock exchange, but, above all, to greater efficiency in theback offices. <BR><BR>With the introduction of EBS, settlement on a rolling basis of trade dateplus zero becomes a technical possibility. On the completion of automatictrade matching on EBS, settlement in SEGA takes place without separate settlementinstructions from the respective EBS members. SEGA, the Swiss securitiesclearing corporation, was founded in 1970 as a joint undertaking by Swissbanks, with the patronage of the Swiss Bankers Association. The companyis owned by some 160 Swiss banks and no one bank possesses a majority stake.SEGA provides for collective custody of eligible Swiss securities and forclearing services. Securities are immobilized and change of ownership takesplace through a book-entry system. Custody, clearing and settlement-relatedpayments are made via electronic link to SIC, which is operated by Telekurs,owned by the Swiss banks and guaranteed by the Swiss National Bank. <H3>CLEARING AND SETTLEMENT </H3>On a consolidated level, the securities industry has, for a number of years,been using the nine recommendations on <BR><BR>clearing and settlement, issued by the Group of Thirty as a benchmark forthe service quality offered by a national market as a whole. <BR><BR>At the time the recommendations were published in 1989, Switzerland wasin the comfortable position of already meeting six out of the followingnine recommendations: <BR><BR>*Trade comparison for direct market participants <BR><BR>*Trade comparison for indirect market participants <BR><BR>*Central securities depository <BR><BR>*Trade netting system <BR><BR>*Delivery versus payment <BR><BR>*Same day funds <BR><BR>*Rolling settlement <BR><BR>*Securities lending and borrowing <BR><BR>*International securities identification number (ISIN) and other ISO securitystandards. <BR><BR>Today, Switzerland meets all but recommendation number two, that is, tradecomparison for indirect participants. This is due to the prevailing Swissmarket practice of banks acting as principal (for their own account), asan effective contracting party and as a member of the stock exchange. <BR><BR>In a series of international conferences organized by the InternationalSociety of Securities Administrators (ISSA) last year, 35 national marketstook the opportunity to present status reports about their compliance withthe G-30 recommendations. Switzerland's report demonstrated forcefully thatthe very substantial joint-efforts of the Swiss securities industry weredirected towards reducing settlement risk and improving the efficiency ofmarket systems and procedures. With EBS and SECOM/SIC, Switzerland now hasone of the most advanced and integrated trading, clearing and settlementinfrastructures in the world. True, irrevocable real-time simultaneous exchangeof securities and cash on a transaction-by-transaction basis takes place.<BR><BR>The G-30 status updates were an outcome of the ISSA conferences. The mainpurpose of ISSA's G-30 review was to amend the original recommendations,where appropriate, in order to reflect today's market demands more accurately.Some of the benchmarks were set higher. Switzerland once again meets mostof the more stringent criteria, which ultimately benefits investors. Apartfrom EBS, the SEGA communications system SECOM, which has replaced the oldSEGA system, is the key factor for this achievement. <BR><BR>Via SECOM, clearing and settlement with SEGA/Intersettle and its participantsin Switzerland and abroad is effected by electronic book entry which ison-line and real-time. Users can trace the current status of settlementand payment transactions almost 24 hours a day. The unique simultaneousdelivery-versus-payment facility provides for risk-free settlement betweenparticipants, in that securities and cash are available and blocked beforethe matched transaction is irrevocably settled. The market deadline fordelivery-versus-payment instructions at SECOM/SIC is 2:00pm on value day.Free delivery instructions for same-day settlement can be input into theSECOM system up until the start of the end-of-day processing at 7:00pm.This procedure pertains to all SEGA-eligible securities, which include bearerand registered shares, bonds, listed mutual funds, rights etc. The settlementof Swiss registered securities is usually not influenced by the registrationprocess. <BR><BR>However, since the process required to complete registration varies fromcompany to company based on their specific and individual by-laws, the foreigninvestor may have some questions on this topic which deserves further explanationin the next section. <H3>SWISS REGISTERED SHARES </H3>On July 1 1992 the current shareholders' rights law came into effect. Theregistered share market was liberalized and general sales restrictions regardingforeign investors were lifted. <BR><BR><B><I>Shareholders' rights</I></B> <BR><BR>When investing in registered shares quoted on the Swiss stock exchange,the investor buys not only the ownership of the security, but also the associatedrights. Listed companies can no longer block the transfer of these rightsto investors and on the correct lodgement of a registration form must acceptthe shareholder with rights and obligations. However, some companies' articlesof association may still limit the type of shareholder or the percentageof equity per shareholder. Should the company refuse full acceptance ofthe investor, they will be registered as a &quot;shareholder without votingright&quot;, but still receive the dividend and right to participate incorporate actions. Communications on voting eligibility are directed tothe shareholder by the company. <BR><BR><B><I>Settlement procedures</I></B> <BR><BR>In the past, all registered shares were physically settled between investors,banks and the companies, who acted as their own registrar. However, in 1988SEGA introduced a new clearing facility for this type of share and it becamepossible for certain companies to settle their shares through SEGA. Today,depending on the company, there are three procedures by which stock exchangequoted registered shares can be settled. <BR><BR>The first and most common is delivery-versus-payment/book-entry settlementvia SEGA. On settlement of the transaction, the custodian bank sends registrationdocuments to the buyer for due completion, and the completed documents arethen lodged with the company by the custodian. The shares remain in SEGAthroughout the registration process (See diagram on page 18). <BR><BR>The second settlement procedure is basically the same as the first. However,the shares are physically held by the custodian and the selling shareholder'sname has to be removed from the company's register before settlement isarranged. After settlement and registration formalities, share certificatesare forwarded to the custodian bank for safekeeping. <BR><BR>The third method is for the few remaining non-SEGA-eligible registered shares,which are all physically settled via the company registrar. The shares arekept by the custodian bank. <BR><BR>It is important to note that registered shares which have been purchasedbut not duly registered can be sold at any time, regardless of the registrationstatus. <BR><BR><B><I>Registration process</I></B> <BR><BR>Investors should duly complete and return the form to the custodian bank,usually within 20 working days of receipt. If the custodian does not receivethe investor's reply within this period, a reminder is usually sent. Ifthe reply is still not forthcoming after a further period of time, custodianswill continue to hold the shares in unregistered form. However, the sharescan still be registered at a later date, when a duly completed registrationform is received. Voting rights may not be exercised until completed registrationforms have been lodged and accepted by each individual company. <BR><BR>Furthermore, Swiss corporation law mandates that registrars have 20 daysto respond to registration requests otherwise they are considered to begranted. <BR><BR><B><I>Registration names</I></B> <BR><BR>Usually companies require their shares to be registered in the name of thebeneficial owner, though some companies may have a special nominee arrangementand will allow registration in fiduciary names. The nominee can either bea person or a company and is usually accepted with voting rights if theyare prepared to give details such as beneficial owner's name, nationality,place of domicile and number of shares. <BR><BR>Shares can also be held in a &quot;disposable position&quot;, which meansthat the shares are held at the company at the disposal of the custodianon a client's behalf. If the investor does not complete the registrationform within the required time-frame, the securities are recorded as beingin a disposable position at the custodian bank and at the company register.The custodian is not obliged to disclose names/details of the investor tothe company. The investor retains the right to receive a dividend, but forfeitsvoting rights. <BR><BR>Market participants are looking at the existing practice of each Swiss companyhaving its own registration form and the associated administration formalitiesin the market. A new development is a standardized one-time applicationfor a registration form, which will also include a power of attorney. Ifthis form is deemed acceptable by Swiss companies, the investor will onlyneed to complete and sign it the one time and their custodian will be ableto automatically register any further purchases of shares. However, to dateonly a few Swiss companies have given their consent to use this form. <BR><BR>With the present integration of all but a very few listed shares into theSEGA clearing system, and the growing automatic exchange of data betweencustodians and the companies, the handling of Swiss registered shares inthe near future will be more transparent to foreign investors. <H3>CUSTODY </H3><B><I>Collection of entitlements</I></B> <BR><BR>The Swiss market does not usually differentiate between the ex-date andthe payable date; they are the same, with very rare exceptions. The custodianreceives the dividend/interest funds either from the principal agent orfrom SEGA, if the securities are re-deposited there. Swiss custodians usuallycredit clients' cash accounts under re-serve, with income and good value,that is, dividends and interest due on securities held in the clients safe-custodyaccount/s on the payable date. The same principle applies to the redemptionof bonds and notes on their expiration date. Professional Swiss custodiansalso offer a dividend claim service. This will be supported by a futureSEGA development, whereby automatic dividend payments will be made for cum-dividendtransactions within a certain period of time after ex-date. Based on thetrade date, the dividend for the seller will be cancelled and the buyerwill be credited with the dividend. <BR><BR><B><I>Tax reclamation</I></B> <BR><BR>In Switzerland a tax of 35% is automatically levied on all income from dividendsand interest on Swiss securities, with no relief at source. Interest onSwiss franc bonds issued internationally (Eurobonds), is generally not subjectto withholding tax. The withholding tax is not related to the nature anddomicile of the beneficial owner's securities, nor is it legally or operationallylinked to ownership of the cash account. The reclaiming of this tax is dependenton the tax treaty concluded between Switzerland and the domicile of thebeneficial owner. As a rule, the tax relief takes the form of a refund.<BR><BR>Tax returns must be signed by the beneficial owner or his representative.The forms used are defined under the current double taxation treaties betweenSwitzerland and the domicile country of the beneficial owner. Due to thisprocess, claimants generally file the appropriate refund claim forms directlywith the Swiss federal tax administration in Berne. The reclaiming timeperiod is within three years from the end of the calendar year in whichthe income was received. Refunds for more than one year may be claimed onthe same form. Claims are usually dealt with by the Swiss tax administrationwithin three to six months of being lodged. The Swiss tax authorities willonly remit a cheque to claimants who do not hold a cash account with a Swissbank. <BR><BR><B><I>Corporate actions</I></B> <BR><BR>In Switzerland the most common corporate actions are capital increases,bonus issues, stock splits, stock option/cash dividends and conversion ofbonds. On the official announcement date of a corporate action, the custodianbank provides its clients with information such as an announcement date,a description of the action and restrictions, entitled share positions,response deadlines and taxes or deductions that may apply. Corporate actionsare executed according to clients' instructions. The rights claim processis similar to the dividend claim process, and in the future will be supportedby the SEGA development mentioned under entitlements for cum-dividend transactions.<BR><BR><B><I>Proxy voting</I></B> <BR><BR>Swiss companies have to announce details on annual general shareholders'and/or any other extraordinary meetings at least 20 days before the meeting.Custodians in turn advise investors of the meetings. The official publicationwith full agenda/proposals is mostly in the company's native language, ieGerman, French or Italian. Only in a few cases is it in English. Swiss custodianswith international institutional clients usually provide a short Englishtranslation with all the relevant information. <BR><BR>Market practice in Switzerland differentiates on the information flow forbearer and registered shares. Bearer shareholders receive the respectivedocumentation from their custodian bank. Registered shareholders receiveinformation direct from the company. However, as mentioned under the shareholders'rights section, until investors of registered shares have lodged a dulycompleted registration form and been fully recognized by the company, thevoting right cannot be exercised. Should the company refuse full acceptance,the investor will be registered as a &quot;shareholder without voting right&quot;,and will be directly advised of this fact by the company. <BR><BR>If bearer shareholders cannot personally attend the shareholders' meeting,they can give their proxy vote to their custodian bank, or to the officialindependent proxy representative. <H3>CONCLUSION </H3>After the steps taken by the Swiss financial community over the past fewyears, 1996 will be a year of consolidation and system optimization. Dueto all these achievements, Switzerland will be in an excellent positionto meet the ever increasing demands of the professional international investor.<BR><BR>The Swiss market is one of the best organized, and also has the flexibilityto cope with the ongoing developments in various current and future financialproducts, as well as the related communication needs. Therefore Switzerlandwill undoubtedly confirm its traditional leading position in the cross-borderinvestment streams. <BR><B>Union Bank of Switzerland</B> <BR><BR><B>Bahnhofstrasse 45 <BR><BR>CH-8021 Zurich <BR><BR>Switzerland</B> <BR><BR><B>SWIFT: UBSWCHZH80A</B> <BR><BR><B>Telex: 813 811 UB CH <BR><BR>Custody servicesMarc R&uuml;ttimann <BR><BR>head of custody services</B> <BR><BR><B>Tel: +41 1 235 31 15</B> <BR><BR><B>Facsimile: +41 1 235 34 05 <BR><BR>Ronald Akkermans <BR><BR>head of relationship management</B> <BR><BR><B>Tel: +41 1 235 65 01</B> <BR><BR><B>Facsimile: +41 1 235 34 05</B> <BR><BR><B>Doris Rein <BR><BR>relationship manager</B> <BR><BR><B>Tel: +41 1 235 50 38 <BR><BR>Facsimile: +41 1 235 34 05 <BR><BR>Securities borrowing and lendingFelix Oegerli <BR><BR>head of securities lending and prime brokerage</B> <BR><BR><B>Tel: +41 1 235 61 04</B> <BR><BR><B>Facsimile: + 41 1 235 32 32 <BR><BR>Martin Schoenenberger <BR><BR>head of global market