<H2> SEPARATE SUPPLEMENT </H2>

<a href="wl.96.06.17.html"><H3> EGYPT </H3> </a>



<H4> The impact of reform is starting to show up in the economic statistics, but
major weaknesses remain </H4>

 <H3> Tiger in training </H3> 
 
 <P> <I>By Jon Marks</I> 
 
  <P> Structural reform is finally having a marked effect on the
economy. The question is whether this can create sustained growth and allow one
of the great under-achievers of the Arab world to mimic Asia's tiger economies.

<P> Key indicators certainly point to a much-improved performance:

<P> <li> A budget deficit cut to just 1.5% of GDP in 1994/95

<P> <li> Inflation down to about 8% by July, with government projections that in the
long term it can be reduced to 3%

<P> <li>  Growth rising: most donors and government officials agree that GDP, worth
E&#163;205 billion ($60 billion) in 1994/95, will grow by about 4.5%-5% this year
as a rebound in tourism supports an extended construction boom.

<P> With tiger-style growth of about 8% required to absorb some 500,000 new
entrants to the labour market each year, ministers are looking to increase
current investment levels of 17%-18% of GDP and savings levels of about 15%.

<P> According to Nawal el-Tatawi, minister of economy and international
co-operation: "To step up the growth rate, we have to increase investment to
something like 25% and hopefully... even higher."

<P> In the short term this means attracting foreign investment to fill in some
very weak links in the economy:

<P> <li> The trade gap was estimated by the state statistical agency CAPMAS at $8.3
billion last year, representing a widening of the deficit by over one-third as
imports rose from E&#163;34.5 billion to E&#163;39.9 billion. Exports proved
disappointing after a 48.5% surge in 1994/95. Non-oil sales rose by about 3% to
E&#163;7.58 billion, but the total fell from E&#163;11.7 billion. There will have
been some benefit from higher oil prices this year

<P> <li> Agriculture: the country remains one of the world's largest food importers.
It is able to grow only 45% of its wheat requirements. But agriculture is still
the most important sector of the economy, providing 32% of employment and 16.3%
of GDP in 1994/95.

<P> There is good news. Since the liberalisation drives of the mid-'80s, there
have been continuous gains in productivity. Much of the non-oil export growth
registered in 1994/95 was due to increased agricultural sales, notably potatoes,
rice and cotton. According to Tatawi: "It is likely in the medium term that our
competitive edge is greater in agriculture and agriculture-based products than in
manufacturing. I am sure the scope is much, much bigger than what we are already
doing."

<P> Liberalisation of the cotton industry last year offers the promise of an
increasing crop after a slump. The agriculture ministry estimated a 35% rise in
cotton yield and new exports.

<P> <li> Industry contributed about 17% of GDP in 1994/95 but growth has been
sluggish due to weak domestic demand and heavy public-sector debt. With profits
rising in private-sector industry, manufacturing growth is expected. But projects
to be presented at the MENA summit include only smaller high-tech schemes and the
proposed $1.5 billion expansion of Alexandria National Iron &amp; Steel Company.

<P> Higher world prices, good results from exploration and the dash for gas mean
the oil sector is booming. Despite an increase of 8.3% in domestic hydrocarbon
consumption, the oil trade surplus rose by 10.3% last year to $1.47 billion.
Crude oil production averaged 878,685 barrels a day (b/d) in 1995.

<P> Among other major revenue earners:

<P> <li> Suez Canal vessel usage fell by 8.1% to 15,051 in 1995, but the volume of
cargoes increased to 293 million tonnes and revenues rose 1.6% to $1.94 billion

<P> <li> Remittances from migrant workers remain a major source of foreign exchange,
with private transfers rising to $3.3 billion in 1995

<P> <li> Tourism income rose by 30% to a record $3 billion and the number of
visitors rose by 28% to 3.6 million in 1995/ 96. 

<P> Yet other forms of investment are now required so the economy can take off.
"We are interested in employment generation so some investments that are more
labour-intensive are welcome," Tatawi says. Regional development projects are
also urgently required.

<P> According to Tatawi: "We are interested in large investments that utilise
natural resources such as petroleum, natural gas, petrochemicals, cement and
fertilisers. Each kind of investment has its attractions, but we are definitely
looking to foreigners for the larger ones and for help in the most
technology-oriented investments."

<p>

</td>
</tr>
</table>

