<tr>
<td valign=top align=left>
<img width=121 height=34 src="../../../images/conra17.gif" alt="Area Profile">
</td>
<td valign=top align=left> 

<H2> SEPARATE SUPPLEMENT </H2>

<a href="wl.96.06.17.html"><H3> EGYPT </H3> </a>




<H4> The lengthening list of privatised companies has become a key indicator of
success for the reform programme </H4>

 <H3> Chalking up the menu </H3>
 
  <P>
<I>By Jon Marks</I> 

 <P> The Egyptian government and its critics are agreed:
privatisation has joined growth, deficits and other more traditional measures as
a key indicator of economic performance.

<P> "The fact that the Ganzouri government is so committed to privatisation
showed the IMF and donors that, this time, there is a clearly reformist
government in Cairo," a European diplomat observes. "Privatisation has become one
of the most important indicators."

<P> "We started in a low voice and the voice started to get louder as we went
on," says the policy's architect, public enterprise minister Atef Ebeid. It was
necessary to overcome criticism to create a programme that worked for Egypt. "We
knew there was a credibility gap," Ebeid adds.

<P> Partly to overcome the gap, Egypt has taken to privatisation with a
vengeance. Twelve companies have been offered for sale in the October-December
period alone. Nine of these were to be offered on a revitalised Cairo stock
exchange and six involved the sell-off of a majority stake.

<P> In the period to June 1998, 91 companies worth a total E&#163;18 billion will
be put on sale, 27 of them through public offerings. "We have a wonderful,
attractive menu for investors," says Ebeid.

<P> As policy indicators go, Egyptian privatisation is now good enough for the
IMF, whose new standby agreement is being put in place accompanied by a final
tranche of Paris Club debt relief.

<P> Creditors react with enthusiasm to Cairo's apparent conversion to divestment
of public assets and its parallel move towards small government. Although Cairo
brokers and foreign investors remain sceptical about the government's proposed
timetable, they agree that the policy changes are dramatic, coming as they do
after years of disputes over macroeconomic indicators and stalled reforms.

<P> Since the programme began three years ago, the 17 state holding companies for
public assets have sold stakes worth more than $700 million in 34 affiliates
through the stockmarket. Four industrial companies have been sold directly for
$177 million and Arab investors bought two Cairo hotels for $220 million.

<P> But the process has been difficult. In private, officials say the holding
company system is very hard to manage. While privatisation offers potentially
huge rewards &#173; with 314 state-owned companies worth $25 billion slated for
privatisation &#173; progress has been slow. The government appeared to lose its
nerve in 1994 and 1995, when it sold just five companies.

<P><B> Beverages leave sour taste </B> <P> So far, one high-profile sell-off, Al
Ahram Beverages, has failed. Problems included the high offer price, unattractive
labour situation, the brewery's antiquated machinery and concerns that the
monopoly beer-maker might suffer an Islamist backlash or competition in a
liberalised market.

<P> Al Ahram Beverages is being offered again, one of several larger industrial
enterprises seeking anchor investors. This follows a model whereby unprofitable
companies are offered to anchor groups that can provide technology transfer,
markets and other added value. Other better-off concerns are sold through the
bourse.

<P> Officials are confident that the beer-maker, the Egyptian Company for Food
and the Industrial Gases Company will sell to anchor investors that can reverse
their fortunes. Their confidence reflects the progress made this year. Forecasts
suggest $1.5 billion worth of assets will have been sold by the end of this year
and up to $3 billion-$4 billion by the end of next year.

<P> But not everybody is carried away on the bandwagon. Critics of the strategy
argue that it does not necessarily bring foreign investors into productive
job-creating sectors. "Privatisation is bandied about as the panacea for Egypt's
ills, and it certainly generates goodwill abroad and brings in portfolio funds,"
a Cairo banker comments. "Recent policy shifts have been encouraging, but policy
must focus on the physical world and not so much on financial machinery."

<P> The government argues that essential investment &#173; and growth &#173; will
follow from the focus on the &THORN;nancial machinery. The World Bank agrees and
is pushing hard for Egypt to raise investment levels, which now stand at 16%-17%
of GDP. "This needs to double if Egypt is going to achieve the 7% annual growth
needed to meet a very large employment problem," a World Bank official in Cairo
observes. "The only way to achieve the 500,000 jobs a year target is through
faster growth."

<P> Demand for all types of new instruments is growing, signalled this autumn by
the popularity of a seven-year Egyptian pound Treasury bond issue. As the
E&#163;4 billion issue was announced, &THORN;nance minister Mohieddin al-Ghareib
said foreign institutions had already signalled their wish to invest in the new
bonds: "It is the first time these investors have wanted to buy into Egyptian
currency instruments... It shows that perceptions have changed." The minister
sees this as evidence that foreign investors are picking up on trends in the
economy, which he forecasts will grow by 5.7% this year.

<P> These developments are under way in an increasingly sophisticated market
where banks and corporations have become rare issuers of global depository
receipts (GDRs) to raise capital.

<P> These were used to float tranches of stock in the Commercial International
Bank (CIB) and, most recently, Suez Cement Company, two stocks that account for
some 16% of the Cairo bourse's $10.5 billion capitalisation.

<P><B> Over-subscribed and credible </B> <P> The CIB led Egypt's invasion of the
capital markets through a $119 million GDR launched in London. The issue was five
times over-subscribed. The CIB's experience is that fund managers will take up
such issues if the issuer is credible, managing director Adel el-Labban says.

<P> "Peace in the region and publicity about the new Egyptian 'tiger' may have
helped attract some attention, but the election of [Israeli prime minister
Benjamin] Netanyahu and events in Lebanon put the regional argument on the
backburner in June as the issue came out," Labban recalls. "Many fund managers
were either neutral or negative at first, no one was all-out bullish."

<P> The performance of CIB &#173; whose part-privatisation was the first
divestment of a state holding in a bank since 1952 &#173; was the determining
factor, Labban argues. The record of CIB since has been impressive and
"eventually it was the CIB story that sold it". Private banks are also turning to
the market for funds.

<P> According to Ahmed Elbardai, vice-chairman of Citibank, this funding is
essential, not least because about 90% of Egyptian deposits are for less than
three or six nights and the system has to take a longer view. The old drawbacks
of holding funds in the banking system are diminishing fast, he says: "Exchange
rate concerns are no longer a problem... I hope we're going to see the rapid
growth of deposits for one, two and three years."

<P> Bankers expect mergers and acquisitions activity to follow, adding momentum
to a market where GDRs, domestic Treasury and bond issues are attracting
significant interest. But it is privatisation that has excited most comment.
Until recently, "fund managers were looking mainly at Latin America and eastern
Europe: Egypt was not high on their list," Labban says. "The fact that so much
portfolio investment is coming in was helped by the government's decision to
speed the privatisation process."

<P><B> Exchange set for boom </B> <P> The pricing and quality of the sale assets
have drawn foreign institutional investors, who have provided more than half the
funds coming into the programme and triggered a mini-boom in the Cairo
stockmarket. The markets are set to invest more heavily still in coming months,
especially after the World Bank's International Finance Corporation (IFC) puts
Egypt on to its daily emerging markets index in January.

<P> "As soon as Egypt goes into the IFC index, that immediately allows us to put
as much money as we feel is appropriate within our overall risk guidelines," Alan
Conway, overseas portfolio manager of Hermes Investment Management, the UK's
largest pension fund manager, was quoted recently as saying. "I've got Egypt down
to be one of the best performing markets over the next couple of years, but
[until now] I've been limited in my ability to put money into it."

<P> At home privatisation is not popular with everyone, but political obstacles
have been tackled, not least by the declaration in May that those who resisted
privatisation would lose their jobs. Six boards of directors and eight chairmen
of holding companies have been replaced, while objections from three opposition
parties have been ignored.

<P> A watershed came the same month with the decision by the cabinet
privatisation committee to increase the proportion of shares on offer in Nasr
City Housing and Development Company from 15% to 75%.

<P> This paved the way for the first public offering of a majority stake in a
<BR> public-sector firm, in which 1 million of the 2.8 million shares sold went
to 43 foreign institutions and investment funds, raising E&#163;435 million. The
stock exchange is booming as a result. Following the launch of the privatisation
initiative in May, daily trading volumes rose to E&#163;22 million, about 10
times the previous year's level.

<P> A series of fund management companies has emerged to handle the new funds,
the most prominent the brokerage and corporate finance house EFG-Hermes, one
result of the recent merger of the Egyptian Financial Group and Hermes Financial.

<P> Hermes Financial Management (Egypt) has created the offshore semi-closed
Egypt Fund, which recently floated a second tranche of shares valued at $34
million, following a $16 million initial share offer placed mainly with European
institutional investors. Gulf-based investors are another target. Other offshore
funds set up this year include a $46 million vehicle managed by HSBC James Capel
and a $74 million trust run by Lazard Freres Asset Management in New York. At
least 126 funds are investing in the market, says minister of economy and
international cooperation Nawal el-Tatawi: "This is because it is profitable. If
you take the PE ratio, compared to almost anywhere else it is good."

<P><B> Bureaucratic delays still hit market </B> <P> Much still has to be done to
improve the trading environment. A significant backlog of share transactions has
built up, meaning that it can take weeks to obtain ownership certificates.
Officials counter that this will be cut to three days after the start-up of a new
central depository, scheduled for November.

<P> The quest for private finance will remain central to policy because the state
can no longer finance infrastructure and industry. A move into private projects,
as much as privatisation of public assets, is intended to help avoid a return to
debt problems.

<P> Egypt has learned from its past mistakes and is committed not to raise the
debt burden again. Privatisation can help to balance the budget and attract
investment. But it cannot do everything. "Unemployment remains the critical
question &#173; it needs the inward investment policy to work if Egypt is not to
face real new problems, which could well be exacerbated by privatisation," a
western embassy analyst comments. "And then there is the level of poverty, which
must be addressed at a time when privatisation and measures to downsize the state
seem to be increasing the poverty gap."

<P> Institutional investors are warming to Egypt. In a country where balancing
the interests of different groups is so important, privatisation must be shown to
benefit the population at large.

<p>

</td>
</tr>
</table>

