<H2> SEPARATE SUPPLEMENT </H2>

<a href="wl.96.06.17.html"><H3> EGYPT </H3> </a>


<H4> The tourist industry is moving up-market to sustain growth in a
 sector that is a major employer </H4>
 
<H3> Pyramid selling </H3>

 <P>
In a year when tourists have been arriving in ever bigger numbers, the shooting
of a group of Greek holidaymakers in April has had no lasting effect. Income from
tourism rose 30% to a record $3 billion and the number of visitors rose by 28% to
3.6 million in 1995/96, fuelled by rapid development along the Red Sea coast.

<P> "Tourism is witnessing a real boom in Egypt," says tourism minister Mamdouh
el-Beltagui. Since July 1994, numbers have increased month by month; in the
&THORN;rst six months of 1996 the growth rate exceeded 32%. He believes 1996
could set a record with more than 4 million visitors, an important step towards
his target of 6 million arrivals a year by 2000. This would make tourism Egypt's
largest export revenue earner.

<P> Hoteliers and tour operators had worried that the massacre in Giza by gunmen
from the Gama'a al-Islamiya would lead to a new slump in the market, just as it
was recovering from the 1993-94 period when tourism was badly hit by Islamist
attacks. The latest attack near the Pyramids was the bloodiest incident in over
four years.

<P> It did not prove to be the case. "Egypt is safer than London, Paris,
Frankfurt, Florida, Madrid or Florence," argues Beltagui. "No tourist has been a
target as such since the autumn of 1994: the Greeks incident was a political,
criminal act against tourists considered to be Israelis." As a sign of the times,
the Islamist underground is said to have been criticised even by its sympathisers
for undermining an industry that employs thousands of poorer Egyptians.

<P> Egyptian tourism is now looking to go up-market. "We are attracting more
segments of the tourist movement," says Beltagui. "Egypt used to be considered
the elite cultural destination but we have diversi&THORN;ed by adding
recreational tourism, mainly in the Red Sea and Sinai, as well as curative
tourism, safaris, desert tourism and <BR> eco-tourism."

<P> Hotel capacity is expected to double from the current 70,000 rooms when a
raft of construction projects is complete. German, French and Italian investors
are among those striking signi&THORN;cant partnerships with the local private
sector.

<P> Privatisation will provide more opportunities. "Some assets have already been
sold, but many more are to come," Beltagui says. "We are planning to sell all our
hotels and cruise ships, with the exception of four historic monuments ... and
these, of course, will still be run privately under management contracts."

<p>

</td>
</tr>
</table>

