<tr>
<td valign=top align=left>
<img width=121 height=34 src="../../../images/conra17.gif" alt="Area Profile">
</td>
<td valign=top align=left> 

<H2> SEPARATE SUPPLEMENT </H2>

<a href="wl.96.06.17.html"><H3> EGYPT </H3> </a>


<H4> As Egypt &THORN;nally joins the global economy, businesses face up to the
threat of greater foreign competition </H4>

 <H3> Brave new world </H3>
 
  <P>
<I>By Jon Marks</I> 

 <P> Take the temperature in 10 Ramadan City, a rapidly
expanding industrial zone in the desert outside Cairo, and you find marked
variations on the thermometer of business confidence.

<P> Many businesses feel recession in the air but some are better able to adapt
than others. "July and August were very bad months for most people," reports
Waleed A Helal of household goods maker El Helal &amp; Golden Star Factories.
But, "for El Helal the same period was very good: our turnover increased 20%
year-on-year."

<P> The key is growth in areas where the Egyptian economy must expand if it is to
integrate into the global economy. "Our growth is partly explained by an increase
in the distribution network," says Helal, who is proud that his trucks serve
wholesale and retail outlets all over the country. "It is also due to more
exports, especially to new markets such as South Africa and Europe."

<P> Moving out of Cairo has speeded growth for the family-owned El Helal group.
"Since we came here 10 years ago we have been able to develop a big area for our
factories," Helal says. The company has steadily expanded its range of household
products and developed export markets, increasingly through joint ventures with
established partners.

<P> A short drive up the highway that bisects 10 Ramadan City, Redallah Mohamed
Helmy &#173; who is chairman of The Egyptian Fibre Manufacturing &amp; Products
Company and leading light in the Federation of Egyptian Industries &#173; muses
on macroeconomic problems. "Ask any business and they will tell you there is a
recession, which has spread to our markets in the Gulf."

<P> Keeping factories open is very difficult when "everybody is trying to delay
his payments". Helmy is not sanguine about the future: "I don't think this
problem will end in the next two years." Privatisation can help Egyptian industry
become more competitive in the long run, Helmy believes. "It is something the
country needs, but for change to be effective it needs the majority to
understand."

<P> Foreign investors complain about rigidities in a labour law that protects
workers from dismissal, but also keeps many on very low pay. British Gas country
manager M Hugh Miller says employment controls are an issue even for incomers
able to start recruitment from scratch. "We need to be able to pay at
international standards and make changes where required," he told the
Euromoney/World Link Egyptian Capital Markets and Investment Conference in
September.

<P> "You can't expect to hire and fire here," Xerox Egypt managing director
Gilles Acogny told the same forum. "So you have to do good recruitment."

<P> Structures of local companies remain largely hierarchical. Some line managers
at one of 10 Ramadan City's more go-ahead firms, disposable syringe-maker Arab
Medical Equipment Company, have been promoted from the production line and
trained to develop in directions unimaginable for their parents. But for most
workers, the future holds little beyond the same job.

<P> Companies will have to work hard to ensure that future industrialists have a
responsibility to protect jobs, argues Helmy. "We are bidding for tenders at
margins, which mean very low profits just to keep the machines running."

<P> Growth is seen as the key to job creation and a new entrepreneurial class is
emerging. "It is no longer bad to be rich, provided you can account for your
wealth," observes a Cairo banker.

<P> In entrepreneurs like the Oriental Weavers chief Mohamed Ferid Khamis, "a new
breed of Egyptian entrepreneurs is beginning to emerge," says the International
Finance Corporation's acting regional representative, Tarek Allouba. "The
<I>infitah </I>[late president Sadat's liberal opening] brought the private
sector into trading and contracting, but there was very little productive
investment," Allouba says. "It has taken nearly 20 years for it to happen, to get
over the easy money... Macroeconomic stabilisation since 1991 has made Egypt a
different country."

<P> But the government is still moving too cautiously for some. Cairo's
reluctance to cede control of strategic industries has produced a 40% limit on
divestment in sectors such as pharmaceuticals, flour milling, steel, aluminium
and electricity.

<P> A recent report compiled by the US Embassy in Cairo noted that the pace of
business deregulation remained relatively slow when measured against the
freeing-up of Asia's "tiger" markets. Key challenges, said the report, include
tackling "the propensity of Egypt's ponderous bureaucracy to mask or avoid the
decision-making process, causing delays in implementing projects, and a corollary
ability of ingenious and turf-conscious bureaucrats to insert themselves and
their regulations in many business decisions".

<P><B> Overbearing bureaucracy </B> <P> Foreign investors complain about a range
of problems, often focusing on bureaucracy, which officials concede can be
overbearing. "We still have not managed to bring [into the bureaucracy] the new
generation that started work in the free market economy," admits General
Authority for Investment (GAI) chairman Ibrahim Fawzy. But, he adds, "the rate of
improvement really is accelerating".

<P> Infrastructure weaknesses are also being overcome quickly, although
inefficiencies remain. Club Med's regional director Mustapha Engin leavened a
glowing report delivered to the investment conference by warning potential
investors, "it is best to get two [telephone] lines, because one will be cut for
non-payment of an invoice settled seven years before."

<P> The slow pace of trade liberalisation, a pillar of the reform programme, has
also been criticised. But remaining tariffs are to be slashed in the next decade
in line with agreements with the EU and World Trade Organisation.

<P> "Our people are going to have to learn to live with the consequences of the
GATT and other accords," Helmy observes. The government agrees. As Egypt
integrates into the EU's new Euro-Med zone and WTO structures, "the most
difficult competition will be with the industrial, manufacturing sector", says
economy and international cooperation minister Nawal el-Tatawi. The desire to
protect Egyptian business may jeopardise the government's goal of accelerating
GDP growth to 8% by 2000, which calls for a more dynamic business environment.

<P> Some sectors, such as vehicle assembly, are showing impressive results. This
business has grown rapidly in the past two years. Most major international models
are now produced at 12 assembly plants employing 75,000 workers, most of them
private. Existing production by General Motors, Peugeot, Suzuki, Citro&euml;n,
Daimler-Benz and Hyundai will rise following GAI approval of plans by a prominent
local businessman to invest E&#163;140 million in two new projects to assemble
under licence for Daewoo Corporation of South Korea and Germany's BMW. Skoda, Kia
and Nissan are all expected to begin production in the next two years, while
Germany's Volkswagen may source a number of components from Egypt if suppliers
meet international standards.

<P> Rapid industrial expansion will require new means of financing. The IFC is
developing a local leasing company with Commercial International Investment
Company, a Commercial International Bank affiliate.

<P> For bigger firms, "using the capital market is one way of growing businesses,
but it is not enough," says Citibank's Ahmed Elbardai. "It needs other forms of
capital formation, such as the development of venture capital funds." These are
starting to emerge.

<P> Family-run companies remain wary of using the stock exchange to raise
capital, resisting public disclosure in a corporate culture where the most basic
facts can be treated as valuable business secrets. "Family firms can be very
strong but they need capital to develop," Elbardai says. Some have agreed to
part-equity sales, which banks have bought into. "The bank does that to cement
relations," he observes. But innovation is critical "if Egypt is to become a
vibrant exporter".

<P><B> Payment innovation </B> <P> Ironically, traditional approaches to
financing may hold up innovation. At the El Helal complex in 10 Ramadan City, new
equipment is being installed and a $2 million order of plastic injection machines
is on its way from Cincinnati. Money will be provided by one of the business
development lines at the US Agency for International Development. The buyer pays
in Egyptian pounds through a local bank at local interest rates after two years.

<P> "Of course, we know we are paying a higher price," Helal concludes. "But if
you know you are being given two years' credit it is so much better... If the
Europeans knew what was good for them they would do the same."

<p>

</td>
</tr>
</table>

