<HTML><!--created by Oyster Systems--><!--May 1996--><HEAD><TITLE>EMWL: Euromoney Magazine: June 1996</TITLE></HEAD><!--START_TAG_SPACE-->
<!--00009200 Germany -->
<!--END_TAG_SPACE-->
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" vlink="7C1568" text="000000" link="7C1568"><center><table border=0><tr><td colspan=2 align=left><nobr><img width=199 height=44 name="top" border=0 hspace=0 src="../../../images/conban7.gif" alt="Euromoney Magazine"><a href="../../../../../index.html"><img width=141 height=45 border=0 hspace=0 src="../../../../images/conban1.gif" alt="EMWL Home"></a></nobr><br></td></tr><font size=3><tr><td></td><td valign=top><h2>June 1996</h2></td></tr> <tr><td valign=top align=left><img width=121 height=34 src="../../../images/conra10.gif" alt="Supplement"></td><td valign=top align=left> <H3>GERMANY</H3><H4>A EUROMONEY SURVEY - June 1996 </H4><H4><BR>A special report prepared by Deutsche Morgan Grenfell </H4><H2>DOMESTIC BONDS</H2>Prepared by Helmut Kaiser, Head of Fixed-Income Research, Frankfurt, andWerner Kr&auml;mer, Senior Analyst, <BR><BR>Deutsche Morgan Grenfell <BR>Measured in terms of the nominal amount of bonds outstanding, the Germanbond market ranks third in the world after the US and Japanese markets (seeChart 1: year-end 1994 data). In terms of net sales of fixed-interest securities,it has been the second largest market since 1992 by international standards.In Europe, the German bond market, with a turnover of Dm2.870 billion atyear-end 1995, occupies the leading position. The total volume of Deutschmarkbonds outstanding has roughly doubled compared with 1990. <BR><BR><B>Market segments and issuers</B> <BR><BR>In terms of turnover, bank bonds play a leading role in the German bondmarket (49% share in 1995), ranking above public sector issues (38.5% sharein 1995). Deutschmark-denominated Eurobonds accounted for 12% of issuancewhile corporate bonds play only a minor role in the German bond market,accounting for less than 1% of issuance in 1995. <BR><BR>The public sector, as a group of issuers, comprises the following agencies:<BR><BR>* The Federal government and its special funds, accounting for 56.6% and10.4% of public-sector debt respectively; <BR><BR>* the Treuhand agency (which ceased to exist at the end of 1994), accountingfor 12.7% of public-sector debt; <BR><BR>* the L&auml;nder governments, or federal states, accounting for 9.6% ofpublic sector debt; and <BR><BR>* the rail and postal services, accounting for 10.7% of public-sector debt.<BR><BR>The securities falling under the generic term of bank bonds comprise mortgagebonds, communal bonds and other bank bonds issued by mortgage banks, Landesbanks,credit institutions with special functions, and commercial banks. The marketfor foreign Deutschmark bonds is used by public and private issuers. ForeignDeutschmark bonds are issued in particular by public corporations and issuersfrom neighbouring European countries whose bonds are guaranteed by nationalpublic institutions, and by supranational issuers (such as the World Bank,the European Investment Bank, etc.). For details on Deutschmark-denominatedEurobonds see the following Euro-Deutschmark section. <BR><BR><B>Federal government bonds</B> <BR><BR>The Federal government uses a number of instruments to finance its debt(see Chart 4), the most significant being Bunds, which have a maturity atissue of 10-30 years and a volume per issue of up to Dm25 billion. At theend of 1994, the volume of Bunds outstanding amounted to Dm377 billion,corresponding to 51.7% of tradable government paper. Preliminary estimatesfor 1995 show that these figures increased to roughly Dm430 billion and55% respectively. <BR><BR>Up until now, Germany has concentrated its secured refinancing in 10-yearBunds and five-year Bobls. In the past, it also issued four-year Bundeskassenobligationenand four-year Bundesschatzanweisungen (Sch&auml;tze or Treasury notes),but these issues were stopped in 1995. Additionally, there were two 30-yearBunds in 1986 and 1993/94 but these were never issued on a regular basis.A certain part of refinancing also took place via retail paper (includingtwo-year zero-coupon bonds and some long-term paper; these were not tradedon exchanges and were not available for foreign investors). Table 1 givesan overview of the capital market financing activities of the federal governmentfrom 1990 to 1994 (1995 data not yet available). <BR><BR>Intermediate maturities are covered by Bobls, unlisted Bundesschatzbriefe(federal savings bonds) and - until mid 1995 - Sch&auml;tze (Treasury notes),which were discontinued in favour of Bobls. In the short-term sector, theFederal government issues unlisted Finanzierungssch&auml;tze (Treasury financingpaper), U-Sch&auml;tze (Treasury discount paper) and Schuldscheindarlehen(borrower's note loans). Federal government paper is issued through a syndicateand/or by auction or sale in the market as a tap issue. The average bid/offerspread in the liquid 10-year sector of the Bund market is usually 6bp. <BR><BR><B>Futures and options for government bonds</B> <BR><BR>For the hedging and arbitrage of interest rate risks, there is a wide rangeof futures and options contracts available (principally Liffe's and DTB'sBund and Euromark futures and options contracts; for further details seederivatives section). However, the exchanges do not cover the entire maturityspectrum, particularly at the ultra-long end, since the DTB's 30-year Bund(Buxl future) was discontinued in June 1995. <BR><BR><B>Bank bonds</B> <BR><BR>Bank bonds can be divided into three main categories: <BR><BR>* Mortgage bonds (Hypotheken-Pfandbriefe); <BR><BR>* municipal bonds (&Ouml;ffentliche Pfandbriefe) and <BR><BR>* other bank bonds. <BR><BR>Hypotheken-Pfandbriefe are a special instrument created to fund housingloans. They are subject to the Mortgage Bank Act or the Shipbuilding BankAct. These laws require the bonds to be fully collaterized by first-rankingmortgages. Pfandbriefe are covered by mortgages with an upper lending limitof 60 per cent of the property's lending value which itself tends to belower than the property's market value, thus eliminating the risk of realestate collateral being wiped out by a property crash. &Ouml;ffentlichePfandbriefe are issued to fund public sector loans (Schuldscheindarlehen).These act as the collateral. <BR><BR>In 1995, a new liquid segment of the Pfandbrief market emerged: the JumboPfandbrief. May 1995 was the turning point when Frankfurter Hypo launchedthe first-ever Dm1 billion Jumbo deal with a maturity of four years. Sincethen more than 60 Jumbos with a nominal value of more than Dm90 billionand maturities ranging from 2.5 to ten years have come onto the market.The term 'Jumbo' is used to denote Pfandbrief issues which have a minimumnominal value of Dm1 billion and which their issuers or a consortium quoteat a fixed bid/offer spread of 5bp to 10bp, depending on the maturity. Thisonly applies to trading lots of up to Dm25 million. Currently, more than90% of Jumbos are &Ouml;ffentliche Pfandbriefe (for details see Pfandbriefsection). <BR><BR>The other bank bonds may be divided into issues by special purpose banks(Kreditanstalt f&uuml;r Wiederaufbau, Industriekreditbank, Staatsbank Berlin)and private bank bonds. Special purpose banks issue bearer bonds with ahigher credit standing as they are guaranteed by the state. Bearer bondsissued by private banks are secured by the issuing banks' assets. <BR><BR><B>Investors: Foreign participation increases ...</B> <BR><BR>In the five years since reunification, foreign participants have steadilyincreased their share of the German bond market. In 1990, foreigners heldabout 15% of all outstanding Deutschmark bonds from domestic issuers. Sincethen, they have nearly doubled their market share to about 28% (they haveactually increased their holdings of all Deutschmark bonds by 450%). Inparticular during the bond rally in 1992/1993, they were strong buyers ofDeutschmark bonds absorbing the largest share of new government bond issues.<BR><BR>This was at a time when the government had to issue an historically highvolume of bonds to finance the restructuring of eastern Germany. This hugeamount of new government bond issues would obviously have triggered muchhigher bond yields in 1992/93 if foreigners had not been prepared to buyall these new issues. <BR><BR><B>... as domestic market share is down</B> <BR><BR>In contrast, domestic banks have been less active in the German bond market.Their market share has fallen fell from more than 40% in 1990 to less than37% in 1995, although their absolute holdings of Deutschmark bonds morethan doubled due to the increase in issuance. Domestic non-banks (includingprivate investors, funds, insurance companies and corporates) have alsoseen their market share fall since 1990 to 35.1% in 1995, However, sincea low of 32.4% in 1993, their market share may increase and these institutionsmay regain their former importance. (See Table 2.) <BR><BR>A more detailed analysis of foreign investors in Germany (for all capitalmarket products, i.e. including equities, derivatives and money market instruments)is given in Table 3. It underlines that investors in - or rather via - theUK are the most important international investors in German securities andthat this group shows the most volatile behaviour of all foreign investors.Investments from Japan and South-East Asia are also quite volatile. Theimportance of Luxembourg depends strongly on tax decisions in Germany, whilethere is quite stable demand from Switzerland and the US. <BR><BR><B>Foreign interest uneven</B> <BR><BR>However, the importance of the different investors for certain specificsectors of the bond market can only be seen by separately analysing theirmarket share in these specific sectors. This is because of uneven distributionof buying and selling activity between different investor groups and betweendifferent market sectors. <BR><BR>Although issuers of bank bonds have had some success in their recent effortsto boost foreign investors' interest in the German Pfandbrief market, manyforeigners still concentrate their investments in government bonds and Eurobonds.Nevertheless, this is changing gradually and the launch of a new segmentof the Pfandbrief market, the Jumbo market, has made Pfandbriefe much moreattractive to foreigners today. <BR><BR>Table 4 gives an overview of the market share of certain investor groupsfor the Pfandbrief and public sector bond markets since German unification.Foreigners are now the single most important investor group in public sectorbonds (including Bunds, L&auml;nderanleihen, Treuhand, Unity, Bahn, Postetc.) with a market share of nearly 40%, this even reaching 44.3% in thebull market of 1993 on the back of the strong appreciation of the Deutschmarkand the severe recession in Germany. <BR><BR>In contrast, all domestic non-banks have a relatively low market share,while foreigners held only 15% of all banks bonds in 1994 - though theyincreased their share in that segment from 3.5% in 1989. Table 4 also showsthat domestic funds, insurance companies and private investors are moreactive in bank bonds than in public bonds. This is partly a result of speciallegal rules, but is also caused by the yield pick-up that bank bonds offer.The importance of insurance companies in the bank bond market would be evenclearer if the table included registered bonds, but data on these bondsis not available. The statistical remainder (the part which can not be attributedto a special investor group) is revealed in the Bundesbank data and is addedto the banks in Table 4. <BR><BR>The rising market share of foreigners in recent years can be mainly attributedto the changing behaviour of funds and other institutional investors towardsmore international diversification. Furthermore, reforms to the German capitalmarkets have modernised them and made them much more accessible to foreigninvestors. <BR><BR>As a result, the dependency of the German bond market on international developments,in particular those in the US, has increased tremendously in the last coupleof years. This is also confirmed by our correlation analysis (see Table5) which reveals the strong influence of US Treasuries in the 1990s (onBunds and other bond markets). <BR><BR><B>Market perspectives</B> <BR><BR>The biggest challenge for the German bond market is without doubt the introductionof Emu from 1999 onwards. Even in an Emu environment, national governmentswill continue to play an important role as issuers. To enhance the Germangovernment's chances of becoming the Euro benchmark issuer and to strengthenGermany's ability to compete as a financial centre, further reforms to theGerman capital markets are needed. They include, inter alia, therapid conversion of all securities to Euros, the admission of short-termdebt paper, the introduction of a primary dealer system and regular issuanceof ultra-long bonds. Otherwise, when confronted with a future Eurobond market,German market participants may be at a competitive disadvantage, in particularagainst France. The German government and the Bundesbank are aware of thissituation and have already indicated that short-term debt paper (two-yearTreasury notes and six-month Bu-Bills), along with coupon-stripped bondswill be issued during the second half of 1996. <BR><BR>The Bundesbank also urges Germany to re-establish 30-year Bunds issuanceon a more regular basis. As far as the new Bu-Bills are concerned, it seemsthat Germany will be able to issue six-month paper via regular auctionsstarting in the third quarter of 1996 at the earliest. From a current perspectivethe third quarter looks rather ambitious, however. <BR><BR>These auctions may take place quarterly or every six months. To gain theBundesbank's approval, the volume of the new issues will be limited to afixed number (the exact number still has to be decided on, but a volumeof Dm50 billion seems to be the maximum). A rough indication for a possiblelimit can be taken from the so-called Bulis. This special short-term paperwas issued via the Bundesbank in 1993 and 1994 and reached a maximum volumeof Dm25 billion in 1993. There are plans to begin with two quarterly auctionsof Dm10 billion each. Thereafter an issuance of Dm20 billion every six monthsis envisaged. Note, however, that these plans are not officially confirmedyet - neither by the finance ministry nor by the Bundesbank. <BR><BR><BR><B>Chart 1: Size of the international bond market </B><BR><BR><IMG SRC="images/em.96.06.24.2.gif"WIDTH="212" HEIGHT="107" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><B>Table1: Gross borrowing of Federal Government </B><TABLE BORDER=1 CELLPADDING=1 CELLSPACING=1><TR><TD></TD> <TD COLSPAN=6>in billions of Deutschmarks</TD> <TD></TD> <TD></TD><TD></TD> <TD></TD> <TD COLSPAN=2>in %</TD> <TD></TD> <TD></TD> <TD></TD><TD></TD> <TD></TD> <TD></TD> <TD></TD> <TD></TD> </TR><TR><TD></TD> <TD COLSPAN=2><B>1990</B></TD><TD COLSPAN=2><B>1991</B></TD> <TD COLSPAN=2><B>1992</B></TD> <TD COLSPAN=2><B>1993</B></TD><TD COLSPAN=2><B>1994</B></TD> <TD COLSPAN=2><B>1990</B></TD> <TD COLSPAN=2><B>1991</B></TD><TD COLSPAN=2><B>1992</B></TD> <TD COLSPAN=2><B>1993</B></TD> <TD COLSPAN=2><B>1994</B></TD></TR><TR ALIGN="DECIMAL" DP="."><TD ALIGN="LEFT">30Y bonds</TD> <TD></TD><TD></TD> <TD></TD> <TD></TD> <TD></TD> <TD></TD> <TD></TD> <TD>10.0</TD><TD></TD> <TD>10.0</TD> <TD></TD> <TD></TD> <TD></TD> <TD></TD> <TD></TD><TD></TD> <TD></TD> <TD>6.7</TD> <TD></TD> <TD>8.6</TD> </TR><TR ALIGN="DECIMAL" DP="."><TD ALIGN="LEFT">10Ybonds</TD> <TD></TD> <TD>53.0</TD> <TD></TD> <TD>34.0</TD> <TD></TD> <TD>29.0</TD><TD></TD> <TD>48.0</TD> <TD></TD> <TD>42.0</TD> <TD></TD> <TD>38.9</TD><TD></TD> <TD>27.9</TD> <TD></TD> <TD>24.6</TD> <TD></TD> <TD>32.2</TD><TD></TD> <TD>35.9</TD> </TR><TR ALIGN="DECIMAL" DP="."><TD ALIGN="LEFT">5Y O