<!--00009200 Germany -->
<!--END_TAG_SPACE-->
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" vlink="7C1568" text="000000" link="7C1568"><center><table border=0><tr><td colspan=2 align=left><nobr><img width=199 height=44 name="top" border=0 hspace=0 src="../../../images/conban7.gif" alt="Euromoney Magazine"><a href="../../../../../index.html"><img width=141 height=45 border=0 hspace=0 src="../../../../images/conban1.gif" alt="EMWL Home"></a></nobr><br></td></tr><font size=3><tr><td></td><td valign=top><h2>June 1996</h2></td></tr> <tr><td valign=top align=left><img width=121 height=34 src="../../../images/conra10.gif" alt="Supplement"></td><td valign=top align=left> <H3>GERMANY</H3><H4>A EUROMONEY SURVEY - June 1996 </H4><H2>DMG Eurobonds </H2><H3>DEUTSCHMARK EUROBONDS </H3><B>Historical roots</B> <BR><BR>In the last few years the Deutschmark bond market has gained increasingimportance as an attractive investment alternative to the US dollar bondmarket for many international investors. The Euro-Deutschmark bond markethas steadily increased its market share over the years. The Deutschmarkis now the second most important reserve currency. This process has notbeen only triggered by the secular trend of Deutschmark appreciation versusthe major currencies but also due to a switch of the Bundesbank's marketregulation policy to an attitude which is much more investor-oriented thanin earlier years. In the last 10 years, the Bundesbank has abolished manyobstacles which had reduced the attractiveness of the Deutschmark-denominatedEurobond markets for foreign issuers and investors. <BR><BR>In 1985 the Bundesbank allowed German-based subsidiaries of foreign banksto lead manage Eurodeutschmark bond issues and opened the market to moreinnovative debt instruments such as FRNs, zero-coupon and dual-currencybonds. <BR><BR>Since 1989, the Bundesbank no longer requires lead managers to inform itahead of a planned issue, paving the way for issues on a standby basis suchas medium-term notes and commercial paper programmes. In 1992, the Bundesbanksaid it no longer requires Deutschmark bond issues to be governed by Germanlaw or to be listed on a German stock exchange. However, the lead managerof a Deutschmark issue must still be a bank domiciled in Germany. <BR><BR>In the last 4 years (since the beginning of the 1992/93 bull market forDeutschmark bonds), the outstanding volume of the Deutschmark Eurobond markethas surged and in fact nearly doubled. 1995 and 1996 has seen a very strongrise of the Deutschmark Eurobond market. <BR><BR><B>Issuers</B> <BR><BR>Private and public banks have been the most active issuers in the DeutschmarkEurobond market in the last 15 months but sovereigns, supranational issuers,several European governments and other authorities are also important playersin the market (see Table 1 and Chart 1). In comparison to those groups,international and private corporates play only a minor role in the DeutschmarkEurobond market. <BR><BR>Non-German corporates tap the market when swap rates are attractive, butare reluctant to carry unhedged Deutschmark debt on their balance sheetsdue to the secular appreciation of the Deutschmark. In the early monthsof 1996 the market has seen long-term issues low-rated central governmentcredits for the first time, namely the 10 and 15-year Eurobonds for theRepublic of Argentina. Table 2 gives an overview on the top borrowers inthe Euro-Dm bond market. <BR><BR><B>Investors</B> <BR><BR>Traditionally, the Deutschmark Eurobond market has been a retail marketbut this situation has changed slightly in recent years. However, althoughno official statistics are available for this market segment, it is wellknown that retail investors in Germany, Switzerland and the Benelux countriesstill play an important role, mainly due to tax reasons. <BR><BR><B>Instruments</B> <BR><BR>The range of debt instruments available in the Deutschmark sector is verylarge. Straight bonds are still the most widely used instrument in Eurobondfinancings, where fixed-rate issues have accounted for more than 50% ofthe market on a year-on-year basis. In the 1980s, bonds with warrants, eitherfor equity or debt, made their appearance in the Deutschmark sector. <BR><BR>At times, the issue volume in these instruments was very large, and recentlythe issuance of covered warrants without accompanying debt financing hasreplaced the traditional issuing method. Their share is currently around30%. Though convertibles were also sometimes popular with the issuers andinvestors and substantial amounts of these instruments have been issuedin the 1980s and early 1990s, their share has come down significantly. Floating-ratenotes (FRNs) are capital market instruments with variable-rate coupons linkedto money-market interest rates - most often Libor but increasingly Fibor.<BR><BR>In 1994, there was a surge in the issuance of new Deutschmark FRNs, whichwere designed to satisfy investor needs. In 1995 and so far in 1996 theirshare is about 7 % (see also Chart 2). The introduction of money marketfunds in Germany in August 1994 created further demand for Deutschmarksand for Deutschmark FRN issues. <BR><BR>FRNs can also be combined with a floor or a cap, providing the investorwith some downside protection against sharp falls in money market rates(floor) or providing the investor with a higher spread over the base rate;thus compensating the investor for giving up the opportunity of stronglyrising rates (cap). <BR><BR>Apart from the usual syndicated bond offerings, MTN or CP programmes providethe issuer with more flexibility. Under an existing credit line, the issuerhas the flexibility to draw new lines under an existing programme as andwhen necessary. <BR><BR>Global bonds are a relatively new innovation to the Euro-Deutschmark bondmarket, with the first Deutschmark global bond launched by the World Bankunder the lead management of Deutsche Bank and Salomon Brothers in 1993.Through intensive marketing with both foreign and domestic investors, aglobal bond issue helps raise the issuer's profile. And by concentratingon a few big issues and active market-making, funding costs can be reduced.<BR><BR><B>Underwriting and Syndication</B> <BR><BR>A few years ago it was customary in the Deutschmark bond market to launchan issue with large syndicates consisting of managing and sub-underwritingbanks (selling groups) involving smaller banks with only limited regionalplacement capabilities. <BR><BR>Increasing competition, declining management fees and the issuer's desireto maintain an active market in an issue for a sustained period of timehave considerably changed the traditional practice of bond issuance. <BR><BR>Today, Eurobond issues are launched by small groups of banks, meeting certainrequirements. The most important requirement is a strong international salesforceto ensure the necessary international placement capability. A lead managershould also have the ability to underwrite and successfully manage evenlarge issues, a fact that is often demonstrated by a high ranking in theinternational league tables. For Deutschmark Euro and global bonds the correspondingfigures are shown in Tabl e 3 with DMG as the leading bookrunner - benefitingfrom its triple-A rating and its widely recognized competence in Deutschmarkinstruments. <BR><BR>A lead manager should also play a prominent role in secondary market activities-otherwise the issue could attract only a limited number of investors dueto the perceived lack of liquidity. The ability to generate attractive swaps,often linked to the lead manager's international credit rating, is alsogaining importance. <BR><BR><B>Pricing</B> <BR><BR>Increasing market volatility and intensive competition have lead the issuingbanks and issuers to abandon the traditional syndication methods in favourof the so-called fixed price, re-offer system. The fixed price, re-offersystem was designed to return profitability and syndicate discipline tothe market, where cut-throat competition had become the norm. Under thissystem the lead manager would normally indicate the price as a spread relativeto a certain benchmark. <BR><BR>For a few hours the issuing banks would then offer their clients the issueat the fixed price. Once a sufficient amount of the issue has been placedthe lead manager announces the final terms of the issue and declares theissue to be 'free-to-trade'. Only then should normal primary market tradingstart. This procedure should ''theoretically' prevent the issuing banksfrom underbidding each other by offering early discounts from the offerprice, driving the price down and eroding management fees. <BR><BR><B>Trading</B> <BR><BR>Generally issue sizes in the Eurobond market are smaller than in the domesticgovernment bond market. Hence, an issue tends to become illiquid sooner.Therefore, it is important for the issuer as well as for the investor tofind lead managers committed to making a market in the issue for a sustainedtime period. <BR><BR>As an issue becomes more firmly placed with retail investors, liquiditygenerally decreases. For big issue sizes - Dm1bn or more - banks usuallymake an active market for one or two years. For liquid issues, the usualbid/offer spread is Dm0.05. Illiquid issues are quoted at a bid/offer spreadof Dm0.25 or Dm0.50. For liquid issues the average trade ticket at DeutscheMorgan Grenfell would be between Dm10m-Dm25m, while the average trade ticketfor less liquid issues is around Dm250,000-Dm1m. <BR><BR><B>Clearing and form of bonds <BR></B><BR>As a rule Euro-Deutschmark bonds are issued in bearer form, although someregistered bonds exist. A certain percentage of bearer bonds are still physicallydeliverable, but the trend is toward book entry only. Retail clients, inparticular, still have a pronounced preference for definitive bonds, andconsequently issues targeted at retail clients still provide for definitivebonds. Bearer bonds can be settled via the Deutscher Kassenverein, Euroclearor Cedel. For Deutschmark global bonds settlement via DTC is also possible.<BR><BR><B>Table 1: Issuers of Dm Eurobonds</B> <TABLE BORDER=1 CELLPADDING=1 CELLSPACING=1><TR><TD COLSPAN=8 ALIGN="CENTER"> </TD> </TR><BR><TR><TD></TD> <TD COLSPAN=2><B>1995</B></TD> <TD COLSPAN=2><B> 1996 (upto April)</B></TD> <TD COLSPAN=3><B> Total</B></TD> <TD></TD> </TR><TR><TD></TD><TD>Amount in mn (Dm)</TD> <TD>No of issues</TD> <TD>Amount in mn</TD> <TD>Noof issues</TD> <TD>Amount in mn</TD> <TD>Amount mn</TD> <TD>No of issues</TD> </TR><TR><TD>Sov/CG/SA/Sup</TD> <TD>30,667.35</TD> <TD>50</TD> <TD>16,290.00</TD> <TD>25</TD> <TD>46,957.35</TD> <TD> 32,680.05</TD> <TD>75</TD> </TR><TR><TD>PTE Corporates</TD> <TD>12,029.73</TD> <TD>60</TD> <TD>2,543.52</TD> <TD>12</TD> <TD>14,573.25</TD> <TD> 10,149.65</TD> <TD>72</TD></TR><TR><TD>Pub Corporates</TD> <TD>300.00</TD> <TD>1</TD> <TD> 0.00</TD><TD> 0</TD> <TD>300.00</TD> <TD> 207.60</TD> <TD> 1</TD> </TR><TR><TD>PTEBank/Fin</TD> <TD>73,998.41</TD> <TD>1697</TD> <TD> 28,970.35</TD> <TD>911</TD><TD>102,968.76</TD> <TD> 71,524.04</TD> <TD>2608</TD> </TR><TR><TD>Pub Bank/Fin</TD><TD>32,606.31</TD> <TD>121</TD> <TD> 16,495.10</TD> <TD>88</TD> <TD>49,101.41</TD><TD> 33,912.07</TD> <TD>209 </TD> </TR><TR><TD>Others</TD> <TD>4,150.00</TD><TD>12</TD> <TD> 350.00</TD> <TD> 2 </TD> <TD>4,500.00</TD> <TD> 3,142.05</TD><TD>14</TD> </TR><TR><TD><B>Total</B></TD> <TD><B>153,751.80</B></TD> <TD><B>1941</B></TD><TD><B> 64,648.97</B></TD> <TD><B>1038</B></TD> <TD><B>218,400.77</B></TD><TD><B> 151,615.45</B></TD> <TD><B>2979</B></TD> </TR></TABLE> <B>Chart1: Composition of Dm Eurobonds<BR><BR></B><IMG SRC="images/em.96.06.24.3.1.gif" WIDTH="212" HEIGHT="205"NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"> <B>Chart 2: Gross sales of Dm Eurobonds<BR><BR></B><IMG SRC="images/em.96.06.24.3.2.gif" WIDTH="212" HEIGHT="205"NATUR