<H2> SEPARATE SUPPLEMENT </H2>

<a href="wl.96.06.17.html"><H3> EGYPT </H3> </a>



<H4> Egypt's long-promised economic reforms, spearheaded by privatisation, at
last seem to be in full &thorn;ow </H4>

 <H3> Flood tide for reform </H3> 
 
 <P>
<I>By Jon Marks</I> 

<P> Egyptians have been crowding Cairo's cinemas to see
a film dramatising the former leader Gamel Abdel Nasser's role in the Suez
crisis. <I>Nasser 1956</I> marks a return to form for Egypt's once-great film
industry and underlines its subject's continuing fascination for the Arab world.
But 40 years after the Anglo-French invasion the shadow of Nasser also hangs over
Egypt's economic planners, who face the daunting challenge of restructuring his
less glorious legacy of bureaucracy and state management.

<P> Since President Hosni Mubarak appointed Kamal el-Ganzouri prime minister at
the start of this year, there have been clear signs that this legacy is finally
being paid out.

<P> After years of stop-start reforms, the IMF and World Bank are fulsome in
their praise for the latest economic programme which centres on privatisation. As
the influential minister of state for economic follow-up, Youssef Boutros Ghali,
likes to put it, "The 21st century in Egypt has started in 1996." Not least, this
is a recognition that the country can no longer ignore the global economy in its
domestic policy. Critics argue that commitments to reform, although welcome, are
not the same as its implementation. But their voices are drowned by praise from
international organisations and investors lining up to put their funds into
Egyptian markets.

<P><B> Personal commitment to results </B> <P> The apparent success of Ganzouri's
appointment as Egypt's first new premier in nine years has surprised many
observers. "In many respects his commitment to reform has been very impressive: I
had thought that as a long-time minister he would just continue with old
approaches to policies, but so far this has not proved the case," says one Cairo
banker.

<P> Ganzouri is identifying personally with key aspects of policy, giving the
reform process a focus it has long required, diplomats say. "The first wave of
reforms in 1991 did not really affect people's lives, except for a few measures
such as lifting subsidies," a US official observes. "This time the government
wants to go further and Ganzouri has taken responsibility for success or failure
at a personal level."

<P> Underpinning the new mood is Egypt's access to generous international
support. Since the late Anwar Sadat signed the Camp David peace accords with
Israel in 1979 Egypt has received massive US aid, now running at more than $2
billion a year. Because Egypt was lynchpin in the 1990-91 Gulf war coalition it
has also benefited from substantial debt relief. Few countries have enjoyed the
benefits of a $10 billion debt write-off or such large aid flows.

<P> This has underwritten the economic take-off. Contrary to the situation faced
by most liberalising economies, Egypt's foreign reserves are estimated at over
$18 billion and rising. Cairo bankers would like to see some of this channelled
into the economy to increase liquidity, but finance minister Mohieddin al-Ghareib
says it is not necessary: "We are now following the free market &#173; if we have
been able to build up our reserves, it is a result of the confidence of the
international community."

<P> With foreign exchange flowing in through the stock exchange and
privatisations, investment is starting to feature in an economy previously
dependent on aid. The more investment expands, Ghareib observes, "the more
foreign funds come in to be converted into Egyptian pounds, and stronger reserves
are a by-product".

<P> For macroeconomists and capital markets investors this is Egypt's year in the
sun, which even the gloom surrounding the stalled Middle East peace process
cannot darken. Arguably the world's oldest national entity or country, Egypt is
finally speaking the language of the global economy.

<P> "We have all the indicators in the right proportions in 1996 &#173; and we
have financial infrastructure in terms of banking and the capital market,"
enthuses economy and international cooperation minister Nawal el-Tatawi. Stable
and improving macroeconomic balances and an opening of local markets are
essential, Tatawi says: "So we can start looking for acceleration of the overall
growth rate and, in different sectors, look to improve productivity, promote
exports and, with the objective of improving the well-being of the people,
generate employment, per capita income growth and regional development to spread
the benefits of development."

<P><B> Unveiling of new projects at MENA </B> <P> The government's message will
be reiterated as the third Middle East/North Africa (MENA) Economic Summit
unfolds in Cairo. In a year when economic reforms have finally yielded fruit, the
summit has become the centrepiece of Egypt's economic policy push. A
comprehensive list of projects for private-sector financing, involving
investments worth some $16 billion concentrated in transport, oil and gas,
tourism and electricity, was set to be presented to the world during the November
meeting.

<P> The marketing campaign will be backed by further commitments to a
liberalising policy by the leaders of the self-proclaimed "new tiger on the
Nile". According to IMF executive director Abdel Shakour Shaalan, "tighter
monetary policy and improved regulation have restored confidence and stopped the
dollarisation of the Egyptian economy". He should know, having helped steer a
rocky course through the troubled waters of relations with the Fund over many
years.

<P> The intensity of the government's approach and its adherence to a tight
reform timetable since Ganzouri's appointment have surprised cynics and persuaded
some that this time things will be different. Others prefer to wait and see,
echoing a western diplomat who says: "We are very encouraged, but it is too early
to say if the pace of change can be maintained."

<P> Further and faster structural reforms are embodied in Egypt's new IMF standby
agreement, which was to be signed as <I>World Link</I> went to press. The
24-month standby loan will replace the IMF's extended fund facility (EFF), which
was approved in 1993.

<P> The EFF failed to pass its first review when differences over economic
indicators, including exchange rates, proved irreconcilable. It is a sign of
changing times that devaluation is no longer an issue and neither is the pace of
reform, which in the past has usually solicited comparisons with the timeless
flow of the country's defining physical feature, the River Nile.

<P> Closing the book on the protracted debt crisis of the '80s, Egypt has waited
three years for the IMF deal. This allows it to tap other financing facilities
and obtain a final $3.9 billion tranche of debt-forgiveness agreed with Paris
Club creditor governments in 1991. The resulting saving of up to $300 million in
annual interest payments will help to compensate for reductions in customs duties
and other import tariff fees.

<P> Reforms agreed with the IMF include cuts to the civil service, which is set
to cause new controversies in a country where so many are employed (or
under-employed) by the state. According to Ghareib, "The IMF agreement says that
we must cut the size of government by 2% a year, but we are working to reduce it
by even more this year."

<P><B> Ready for reform </B> <P> Officials argue that careful management of
popular opinion means that Egyptians are ready for such reforms. "There have been
many criticisms and we have had to be patient," public enterprise minister Atef
Ebeid told an investment conference in September. "But the pace can now be
accelerated: we have to continue the reform."

<P> The government is convinced that the greatest challenge of recent years,
radical Islam, is now under control. Islamist underground groups have reportedly
killed nearly 1,000 people since 1992, but they also suffered heavy losses which
have reduced their operational capacity. Analysts predict that as long as
President Mubarak, aged 68, remains healthy and continues to be seen as a
guarantor of political stability, the substantial majority of Egyptians will
overlook calls for radical change to a moribund party political system and
re-elect the head of state for a fourth presidential term in 1999.

<P> While radical Islam has posed a real threat, the government has benefited
from the relatively equanimical nature of the population. This often leads
political commentators to decry the lack of an ideology or common vision among
Egyptians.

<P> Commenting on a rare opinion poll, carried out in 1994, political scientist
Nader Fergany noted that many Egyptians remain at the margins of political life.
Fergany noted: "In societies where educational attainment is poor [only half the
population is literate], minds are subject to the pervasive influence of
one-sided mass media and effective political participation is penalised, social
consciousness tends to be feeble and one should not expect people to hold strong,
logically articulated opinions. In such a society, it is probably more accurate
to speak of public sentiment than public opinion."

<P> The government is well aware of the volatility of "public sentiment" and has
worked harder than before to prepare the population for strong reforms. According
to Ebeid: "Privatisation will lead to a reduction in the labour force, but labour
organisations understand this and are willing to co-operate." This, the powerful
minister concludes, is because "they know it will lead to some unemployment in
the short run, but in the medium term it will help the masses of workers".

<P> There are limits to how fast change can be brought about in a country where
poverty and unemployment remain critical problems. Diplomats in Cairo believe
basic food subsidies will remain in place, especially as Egypt looks to the
experience of its neighbours and remembers the turbulence caused in Jordan this
summer by the removal of bread subsidies.

<P> Resistance is also expected to higher prices for other items. But the right
to charge more for services may be essential to the government's ambitious plans
for infrastructure development, using build-own-operate-transfer (BOOT) and other
private financing techniques. As one donor official observes: "In Egypt, things
like water for irrigation and agriculture are free: it is a precedent established
by the Pharaohs and no one has changed it since."

<P> Elsewhere, the next few years could see radical change, with the pace set by
a further overhaul of business practices. Drafts of a unified Companies Act and a
new unified investment law, which would replace the current Law 230 and other
conflicting legislation, are ready.

<P> There are continued complaints by foreign operators about the blockages still
caused by Egypt's ponderous bureaucracy and other legacies of Nasserite
economics. As the private sector learns to stand alone, a deregulated environment
is seen as essential.

<P><B> Get up, stand up </B> <P> "If you are privatising, the private sector
entity has to stand on its own feet: it may need a bank guarantee, but it should
not lean on the state to do its job for it," argues Boutros Ghali.

<P> The current policy in Cairo is to ask all Egyptians to stand on their own
feet. It will not be easy for anyone, from the rural poor of Upper Egypt and
state-sector employees, used to low-paid jobs for life, to industrialists
accustomed to the cushion of high tariffs and cheap money. A challenge has been
thrown down. Egypt can meet it provided investment flows create the 500,000 new
jobs a year the government wants and much-needed safety nets like the social fund
can function adequately.

<P> A Cairo banker observes that past reforms failed to deliver the expected
results: "When it came to the crunch we had no growth and no real development
strategy, and we ignored a very skewed income strategy." This time, the
government promises it will be different. According to Boutros Ghali: "We have to
move on all fronts simultaneously and we have the means to do it."

<P> Backed by debt relief and political impetus on a scale that few similarly
placed countries have enjoyed, Egypt is poised to show doubters that when it
comes to liberal reform, the traditionally slow-moving Nile is in full flood.

<p>

</td>
</tr>
</table>

<br>
