<H2> SEPARATE SUPPLEMENT </H2>

<a href="wl.96.06.17.html"><H3> EGYPT </H3> </a>



<H4> Population growth and chronic pollution are damaging the health and economic
prospects of Cairo's people </H4> 

<H3> Shadow over the sun </H3> 

<P><I>By Jon Marks</I> 

 <P> Cairo is choking under the weight of people struggling to make
a living. It is also choking from pollution, which even a raft of big-ticket
projects financed by donor funding cannot hope to eradicate in the foreseeable
future.

<P> On the Nile waterfront, prestige buildings give Cairo a glamorous image. But
in the shadows are a maze of narrow lanes in which poorer families crowd. Some
newcomers even sleep in makeshift shelters in the street as they wait to obtain a
tenement.

<P> And the street is crowded after 5,000 years of settlement. In 1800, there
were about 300,000 people in Greater Cairo. By 1930, the number had quadrupled.
The population officially stood at 4.4 million in 1960, growing to 11.5 million
in 1990 and a projected 16.6 million by the end of the century. These could well
be conservative estimates.

<P> The city's environmental crisis is now so bad that the forest of minarets,
which help give traditional Islamic neighbourhoods their unique flavour,
disappear into an orange haze during rush hour and shroud the pyramids from
passers-by in Giza.

<P> Studies have identified lead pollution as the most serious of Cairo's many
environmental problems. A USAID-funded comparative risk assessment, undertaken in
1994, showed that Cairo had the world's worst air pollution in terms of suspended
particulates and lead, which causes 25,000 deaths or more every year.

<P> Lead pollution significantly increases the blood pressure of all Cairo
residents. According to the USAID report, children raised in Cairo are in danger
of losing on average an estimated 4.25 IQ points as a result of lead pollution.
The economic cost of this IQ loss is estimated at $13 billion.

<P> Projects such as the massive Cairo wastewater scheme, efforts to reduce lead
and other emissions and the benefits of economic growth are improving the
situation. But there is a long way to go.

<P> Egypt's minister responsible for the environment, Atef Ebeid, speaks proudly
of his country's fast-developing gas industry and clean-up campaigns. Buses and
vans are being fitted with gas tanks but the majority remain dependent on leaded
petrol.

<P> Multilateral agencies are lining up substantial support, with the World Bank
and European Investment Bank focusing on a huge Mediterranean clean-up campaign.
In October, the Bank announced that the Middle East region's first Mediterranean
Environmental Technical Assistance Programme (METAP) office would open in Cairo.
In addition, the World Bank has approved a $20 million loan while the
International Development Association has given a $15 million credit.

<P> The World Bank loan is planning to part-finance the $48.7 million pollution
abatement project, set to include a pollution-fighting fund established with the
country's largest bank, National Bank of Egypt.

<P> Environmentally friendly sources of fuel such as gas, wind and solar power
hold the key to a less polluted future. But the city's current generation seems
condemned to suffer from the motor car and factory chimney in ways their parents
could not envisage. Earlier generations saw the sun rise over pyramids and
mosques: modern inhabitants see a mix of smog and desert dust.

<p>

</td>
</tr>
</table>

