<tr>
<td valign=top align=left>
<img width=121 height=34 src="../../../images/conra17.gif" alt="Area Profile">
</td>
<td valign=top align=left> 

<H2> SEPARATE SUPPLEMENT </H2>

<a href="wl.96.06.17.html"><H3> EGYPT </H3> </a>




<H4> Private &THORN;nance is being sought for major infrastructure projects,
notably in the power and transport sectors </H4>

 <H3> If the boot &THORN;ts </H3>
<P>
<I>By Jon Marks</I>

<P> Egypt has joined the roster of countries
seeking private finance to develop infrastructure. Not that this means the state
is surrendering all responsibility. If veteran electricity and energy minister
Mohamed Maher Abaza is correct, the policy shift will create a judicious balance
of private investment to build infrastructure and some state involvement where
public sector management gives good value to consumers.

<P> There are three major power programmes slated for development using the
increasingly popular build-own-operate-transfer (BOOT) method. International
attention has focused on the BOOT contract for Egypt's first independent power
project (IPP). This would build a two-by-325-MW unit to supply power to the
Egyptian Electricity Authority (EEA) from Sidi Khraier in the Nile Delta.

<P> Underlining international interest, 54 companies applied for documents for
Sidi Khraier. Between seven and 10 are expected to form a shortlist from the 34
requested to prequalify by October 31. The contract may not be awarded until next
July, according to Abaza &#173; not least so that due care is taken with very
complex documentation.

<P> Two further BOOT power plants are planned: a pump storage unit at Gallala in
Sinai and a 300-MW wind farm at Zafarana on the Gulf of Suez where, Abaza says,
wind speeds are among the highest in the world. Henceforth, "all new power
stations will be built by the private sector and privatisation is planned for
distribution companies".

<P> This does not mean an end to state activity, however. All existing power
stations will remain with the state sector, Abaza says, "because there is no need
to privatise them. They are already well-managed; indeed, we have always tried to
run them as if they were privately managed". Production costs are very low and
competitive.

<P> A measure of privatisation is planned for distribution companies, but no
dates have yet been set. Based on experience elsewhere, the transfer of
distribution into private hands can be problematic.

<P> The expected IPP boom will make headlines, but as Cairo tightens its spending
belt the government is opening the way for innovative private sector financing
techniques in the transport and water sectors. The potential for BOOT schemes
extends to a planned airport at Marsa Allum on the Red Sea, for which 37 bids
have been already been received. "This will be needed in three to five years as
tourism projects develop," comments tourism minister Mamdouh el-Beltagui. Four
toll-road schemes are also to be offered for tender. Private water projects are
envisaged but may be more difficult to implement.

<P><B> Multilateral support for private sector </B> <P> As an incentive for
private participation, international organisations are ready to provide strong
support. For the Sidi Khraier power scheme, for example, commitments have come
from agencies including the World Bank and its investment arm, the International
Finance Corporation.

<P> But securing international guarantees may not be easy. The World Bank's offer
to support aspects of commercial risk is dependent on the government providing
counter-guarantees. Ministers say they are unconvinced of the need to provide
sovereign guarantees for private-sector schemes. They argue that if
infrastructure is to be opened up to investors, they should take the risk.

<P> Such backing is essential as only a few priority infrastructure schemes,
notably the Middle East Oil Refinery (Midor) project, continue to attract Export
Credit Agency (ECA) financing. Midor, an Egyptian/Israeli joint venture building
a refinery at Alexandria, has a regional impact in keeping with the spirit of the
Middle East peace process as it was conceived in 1993-95.

<P> But for most projects, one legacy of past debts is that cover from many ECAs
remains limited. "ECAs have been much slower than other financiers to appreciate
the changes under way since debt reduction," comments a western banker visiting
Cairo. "Consequently the government is almost forced to turn to independently
financed schemes."

<P> This sentiment is mirrored by a US official. "Investment companies are
upgrading their attitudes to Egyptian risk quicker than governments," he
concludes. "While ECA activity remains relatively low, private investment is
moving steeply upwards."

<p>

</td>
</tr>
</table>

