<TITLE>
Joan Claybrook Testifies on FMVSS 208 and Air Bags
</TITLE>
<BODY bgcolor="white">

<CENTER>
<IMG src="pclogo.gif" width=185><BR>

<FONT size="1" color="#0a5397">Buyers Up </FONT><FONT size="1" color="red">&#149;</FONT><FONT size="1" color="#0a5397"></FONT>
<FONT size="1" color="#0a5397">Congress Watch </FONT><FONT size="1" color="red">&#149;</FONT><FONT size="1" color="#0a5397"></FONT>
<FONT size="1" color="#0a5397">Critical Mass </FONT><FONT size="1" color="red">&#149;</FONT><FONT size="1" color="#0a5397"></FONT>
<FONT size="1" color="#0a5397">Global Trade Watch </FONT><FONT size="1" color="red">&#149;</FONT><FONT size="1" color="#0a5397"></FONT>
<FONT size="1" color="#0a5397">Health Research Group </FONT><FONT size="1" color="red">&#149;</FONT><FONT size="1" color="#0a5397"></FONT>
<FONT size="1" color="#0a5397">Litigation Group </FONT>
<BR>
<FONT size="1" color="#0a5397">Joan Claybrook, President<BR></FONT>
</CENTER>
<P>
<FONT size="3" face="times">
<center>
Statement by Joan Claybrook<BR>
President of Public Citizen<BR>
On FMVSS 208 and Air Bags<BR>
Transportation Subcommittee<BR>
Committee on Appropriations<BR>
House of Representatives<BR>
Washington, D.C.<BR>
December l9, l996<BR>
</center>

<P>
Mr. Chairman, Members of the Committee:
<P>
I am pleased to be invited to testify before you today on Federal Motor Vehicle Safety Standard 208 and air bags. I am President of Public Citizen, a national consumer advocacy organization with l20,000 members nationwide, and former Administrator of the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (l977-l98l).
<P>
Safety standard 208 is the most important one ever issued by the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration.  It has saved over l600 lives to date, and promises to save tens of thousands more in the future.  Air bags will also mitigate millions of serious head, facial, neck and chest injuries.  In addition, it was the spark for the enactment of mandatory safety belt use laws now in place in all but one state.  
<P>
However, there have been tragic side-effects from air bag inflation in crashes, particularly low speed crashes.  These deaths should not occur.  Some 32 children and 20 adults, most of small stature, have been killed.   Almost a third of the children were in rearward facing infant carriers which must never be used in the front seat of an air bag equipped vehicle.  Most of the other children were unrestrained, which means they were probably thrown during vehicle braking into the dashboard area where the air bag inflates.  The adult deaths likewise appear to be caused by the occupant being very close to or almost on top of the air bag located in the steering wheel.  For air bags with only one inflation force level, the forces generated by the air bag designed to protect people in higher speed crashes can be too severe for occupants right next to the air bag module when it inflates.
<P>
Airbag injuries do not occur with the same frequency in all models because some manufacturers have better airbag designs than others.  Honda has a much less aggressive airbag than other manufacturers and has no reported deaths.  The Ford Taurus and Chevrolet Corsica account for 47% of the driver side deaths (9 out of 19) but account for only 3% of driver side air bags.  And the Chrysler minivan accounts for 25% of passenger side deaths (8 out of 32) but accounts for only 8% of passenger air bags.  While these numbers are too small to be statistically valid, they certainly suggest a trend.  Very simple design changes such as mounting the airbag module in the top middle of the dash rather than at the front of the dash or recessing the module in the bottom of a dished steering wheel could make airbags much more friendly to occupants and less likely to cause injury.
<P>
There are a number of courses of action now under way that are critical to stop this terrible situation.  
<P>
First, warnings in vehicles.   The fastest way to stop fatal air bag injuries from continuing is to make sure drivers and occupants know how to ride in air-bag equipped vehicles.  The warnings in current vehicles are totally inadequate. Last month the NHTSA issued a requirement for bolder and clearer warnings installed on new vehicles beginning in 90 days to make sure parents know to place their children in the back seat and properly restrain them.  At the same time, most auto manufacturers are sending notification letters to current owners of air bag equipped vehicles notifying them about the potential dangers of proximity to the air bag when it is inflating. 
<P>
Second, informing the public.  There are a number of public information programs in progress, including government efforts,  the national Air Bag Safety Program funded by the auto and insurance industries that is being described in the hearing today, and activities by safety advocates.  With the same messages coming from all sectors, the media seem to be increasingly aware of the importance of informing the public about taking several simple precautions.  The word is definitely spreading throughout the nation.  But these efforts must continue for driving behavior to truly change. While warnings and public information should have been issued much sooner, the message now is being heard. 
<P>
Third, improved air bag designs.  In my view, this is the heart of the problem we are facing today. Unfortunately, many manufacturers have not used effective technologies designed and tested as much as 20 years ago. 
<P>
The government standard, FMVSS 208, is a broad performance standard, allowing manufacturers the opportunity to develop a variety of innovative designs to meet the safety standard.  Manufacturers could install automatic belt restraints or air bags (or any other automatic protection system that meets the injury prevention levels in the standard).  Virtually every manufacturer has now chosen to install air bags which will be fully required by statute in l998 models cars and in l999 model vans, sport utility vehicles and pick up trucks.  Many manufacturers have designed their systems quite precisely to meet the basic specifications of the standard:  a 30 mph full frontal barrier crash using a 50th percentile male test dummy automatically protected to avoid specified injury levels.   
<P>
One of the most important elements in air bag design that determines the level of protection as well as the likelihood of inadvertent injury is the inflation flow rate.  Most current vehicles on the highway have a single inflation level.  This means that whether the crash is at l5 mph or 35 mph, the air bag inflates with the same force.  But as far back as the mid-l970's, General Motors installed (albeit with stored gas and a heating charge, a different type of technology than the pyrotechnic systems being used today) dual stage inflation air bags in l0,000 l973-l976 vehicles sold to the public.  As described in a paper presented by NHTSA, private contractor and air bag supplier engineers to the 8th International Experimental Safety Vehicle Conference in Wolfsburg, West Germany in October l980, "For low level deployment the stored gas only was used while for high level deployment the solid propellant charge heated the stored gas for augmented flow." (p. 343).
<P>
While the numbers are too small to be statistically valid, I would note that in several hundred crashes involving over 300 hundred occupants, including more than a dozen children and some small adults in these l970's GM cars, the injury effects we are seeing today were not evident.  It is also noteworthy that child passenger safety was an issue GM was concerned about in designing these systems.  As long ago as l972, GM engineers in a Society of Automotive Engineers paper, reported "favorable results" testing standing child dummies using air bags with "...variable inflation, which lessens the initial deployment surge to ease the action of the cushion on the occupants..." (Klove and Oglesby, Publication No. 720411).
<P>
The l980 Wolfsburg paper was derived from NHTSA funded research on how to protect out-of-position, unrestrained child occupants in crashes.  The paper summarizes the "design wisdom" of dual inflation systems as follows:  "The passenger bag should not, to the extent possible, be deployed at a faster rate than is justified by the crash severity." (p.349)  
<P>
I want to emphasize that designing an air bag is a complex task for engineering experts and involves many factors, including the vehicle crash pulse, bag fabric weight and mass, shape and volume, folding, location of the mounting in the dashboard, cover opening and other variables.  However, it appears that the protection needed for various size occupants can be provided by dual or multi-stage inflation systems. But this uncomplicated technology has been largely ignored by manufacturers of today's air bag equipped vehicles and should be reviewed as part of NHTSA's forthcoming rulemaking for higher technology air bags to protect vulnerable populations.  
<P>
It is for this reason that Public Citizen and the Center for Auto Safety petitioned the NHTSA in November to issue a proposal for dual stage inflation air bag systems.  These systems can be designed and installed in the short term, far sooner than much of the 2lst Century "smart", high tech systems, and the additional cost is very small.
<P>
Air bag suppliers as reported in the NHTSA docket have already developed dual stage systems that inflate with less force in low speed crashes and more in high speed.  In addition,  Mercedes and BMW already offer designs that distinguish not only the force of the crash but whether occupants are wearing belts.  These systems generally require electronic sensors, but many manufacturers have already moved from mechanical to electronic sensors (the electronic, single point sensors can be cheaper than using mechanical sensors).  We urge NHTSA to encourage these near-term technology systems as well as development of more sophisticated systems in its forthcoming rulemaking.  The car buying public should be able to purchase the next generation of safer air bags as rapidly as possible.  (I would note that the Washington Post reported on December 17, 1996 that TRW, a major air bag supplier, purchased a Canadian-based supplier of electronic devices, including sensors.)
<P>
The timing is particularly important to consumers because the auto industry has petitioned the government to permit a depowering of current air bag designs for the next few model years and to allow certification with sled tests rather than full scale crash tests.  Consumer organizations have reluctantly decided not to object to this proposal because we are extremely concerned about the fatal and other serious injuries now occurring and trust that some of them, particularly harm to small adults, can be mitigated with depowering.  Depowering is only a short term partial fix for air bags that need to be redesigned. But we also are deeply concerned there will be a tradeoff for adults in higher speed crashes.  In addition, substitution of sled tests, which are advantageous because they are much cheaper and faster than crash tests, can be manipulated to substantially reduce the protection achieved with air bags.  Permanent depowering of airbags is projected to kill more people than it would save.
<P>
The American Automobile Manufacturers Association agrees that depowering is a temporary measure until better technology is incorporated.  Thus, protective systems that can be incorporated in the next few years, such as dual inflation systems, have great appeal now over much more complex, higher technology systems that may take additional years to test and produce.  
<P>
Fourth, disabling air bags.   Consumer groups have opposed the on/off switch proposed by NHTSA (except for vehicles with no rear seat), as well as disconnecting air bags that NHTSA has indicated it will propose, because in the end we believe more people will be killed and seriously injured than will be helped. For example, Dainius Dalates of Canada DOT and Kennerly Digges, former Deputy Administrator of Research at NHTSA authored a paper for the last Experimental Safety Vehicle conference showing reduction of head injury with air bags for belted occupants in frontal crashes of at least 65% compared to belted only occupants.  And as described above, there are available remedies other than on/off switches that are far superior for investment of industry resources.  As well, other witnesses today will describe information developed by insurance companies and the government that should be made more readily available to consumers about air bag performance in current cars and how to purchase the car that best fits the buyers needs, thus reducing concerns that might lead the owner to want to disconnect the air bag.
<P>
Also, disconnecting or turning off the air bag wrongly implies that children should ride in the front seat.  We believe this sends the wrong message to parents, as children are far better protected in the rear seat in an air bag or non-air bag car.  In addition, for the government to suggest that disconnection is acceptable only further sparks public anxiety, much of which is unfounded.
<P>
Fifth, built-in rear child restraints.   Some manufacturers, such as Volvo and Chrysler, are building child restraint systems into the back seats of their vehicles.  Built-in child restraints assure compatibility between the restraint and the vehicle, are usually easier to operate, make it clear the child belongs in the rear seat, and are useful for owners without young children who occasionally transport children in their vehicles.   NHTSA should develop a performance standard requiring these restraints be in the rear seats of all new cars.
<P>
In summary, Mr. Chairman, the government, motor vehicle-related businesses and consumer organizations all have a common interest in getting the message to citizens across the nation about putting their children in proper restraints in the rear seat and allowing about l0 inches between the belted driver and the steering hub for maximum safety in current air bag equipped vehicles.  
<P>
We also have a common interest in getting the next generation of air bag systems with improved technologies (not necessarily highly complex ones) into the marketplace as rapidly as possible, certainly within the next few years.  With the loss of life on our roads every day almost equivalent to a Value-Jet crash, we must all rise to the challenge of enhancing the proven life-saving advantages of air bags while removing the risks of unnecessary injury.
<P>
Thank you for the opportunity to testify on this important issue. 
<P>
<P>
<P>
<CENTER>
<FONT size="1" color="#0a5397">Ralph Nader, Founder</FONT><BR>
<FONT size="1" color="#0a5397">1600 20th Street NW </FONT>
<FONT size="1" color="red">&#149;</FONT>
<FONT size="1" color="#0a5397">Washington, DC 20009-1001 </FONT>
<FONT size="1" color="red">&#149;</FONT>
<FONT size="1" color="#0a5397">(202) 588-1000 </FONT>
<BR>
<a href="http://www.citizen.org/"><FONT size="1" color="#0a5397">http://www.citizen.org/</FONT></a>

