<TITLE>
Statement By Joan Claybrook
</TITLE>
<BODY bgcolor="white">

<CENTER>
<IMG src="pclogo.gif" width=185><BR>

<FONT size="1" color="#0a5397">Buyers Up </FONT><FONT size="1" color="red">&#149;</FONT><FONT size="1" color="#0a5397"></FONT>
<FONT size="1" color="#0a5397">Congress Watch </FONT><FONT size="1" color="red">&#149;</FONT><FONT size="1" color="#0a5397"></FONT>
<FONT size="1" color="#0a5397">Critical Mass </FONT><FONT size="1" color="red">&#149;</FONT><FONT size="1" color="#0a5397"></FONT>
<FONT size="1" color="#0a5397">Global Trade Watch </FONT><FONT size="1" color="red">&#149;</FONT><FONT size="1" color="#0a5397"></FONT>
<FONT size="1" color="#0a5397">Health Research Group </FONT><FONT size="1" color="red">&#149;</FONT><FONT size="1" color="#0a5397"></FONT>
<FONT size="1" color="#0a5397">Litigation Group </FONT>
<BR>
<FONT size="1" color="#0a5397">Joan Claybrook, President<BR></FONT>
</CENTER>
<P>
<FONT size="3" face="times">
Statement By Joan Claybrook<BR>
President of Public Citizen<BR>
November 22, 1996<BR>
<P>
<P>
	The Department of Transportation actions today are long overdue and should begin the process for improving air bag designs, but unfortunately the authorization for disconnecting air bags could cause mass confusion because it appears to contradict the req
uired label warning that young children should be properly restrained and seated in the rear.
<P>
	For the government to authorize disconnection sends the wrong message to motorists who will interpret this as a recommendation to disconnect. No doubt citizens who have their air bags disconnected will be required to sign liability waivers, surrendering 
their legal rights, and paperwork records will have to be maintained for years to reference in crash investigations, lawsuits and vehicle transfers.
<P>
	The solution lies in long-overdue "smart" technology. This has been delayed because the auto industry chose not to develop smarter, safer air bags despite knowing of the potential dangers for many years. Depowering appears to be the only feasible interim
 solution until more advanced designs go into production.  
<P>
	Among the most promising technological short-term solutions would be dual-inflation air bags that inflate more slowly in low-speed crashes and faster in high-speed crashes. They could be in production within the next two years and would add little to the
 cost -- $10-20 per car. These systems would improve air bag safety for children and small adults.  There must be no compromise on the date for the introduction of smart air bags - there has been too much delay already.
<P>
	The warning labels are clearly needed as soon as possible.  Air bag injuries to children can be eliminated <u>immediately</u> if children are properly restrained in the back seat.  The toddlers who died so tragically -- with one or two possible exception
s -- were all unrestrained or improperly restrained.  The safest place for children 12 and younger is in the back seat, with safety belts buckled.  Infants in rear-facing seats should never be in front seat.  If children are in front seat, they should alw
ays be restrained and the seat should be back as far as possible.
<P>
	All drivers and passengers of any age, weight or size should use safety belts at all times.  Shorter, lighter drivers should be sure to stay 6-10" back from the air bag module in the steering wheel.  These common-sense precautions increase safety immedia
tely, in all kinds of crashes, with or without air bags.
<P>
	Air bags save hundreds of lives and reduce injuries -- particularly brain, head and facial injuries -- to thousands of other crash victims.  Every day on America's roads there is a loss of life equivalent to a Value-Jet crash. The challenge to all involv
ed with auto-safety is to preserve the proven life-saving advantages of air bags while eliminating the risk of injury.
<P>
<P>
<CENTER>
<FONT size="1" color="#0a5397">Ralph Nader, Founder</FONT><BR>
<FONT size="1" color="#0a5397">1600 20th Street NW </FONT>
<FONT size="1" color="red">&#149;</FONT>
<FONT size="1" color="#0a5397">Washington, DC 20009-1001 </FONT>
<FONT size="1" color="red">&#149;</FONT>
<FONT size="1" color="#0a5397">(202) 588-1000 </FONT>
<BR>
<a href="http://www.citizen.org/"><FONT size="1" color="#0a5397">http://www.citizen.org/</FONT></a>

