<HEAD><TITLE>Public Citizen's Greatest Hits</TITLE></HEAD>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/public_citizen/pclogo.gif" ALT="Public Citizen"></CENTER>
<P><H1><CENTER>GREATEST HITS</CENTER></H1>
Day after day, year after year, Public Citizen proves the power
ordinary citizens have to fight the special interests -- and defend
our democracy.  Here are some of the victories we've won together.
<BR>
<UL>
<LI>
1994
<UL>
<LI>Public Citizen wins another Supreme Court case, bringing its
record to 22-10.</LI>
<LI>Public Citizen enlists nearly 100 cosponsors for a single-payer
health care reform bill.</LI>
<LI>Public Citizen successfully challenges the FDA's failure to
restrict use of the drug Parlodel.</LI>
</UL></LI>

<LI>
1993
<UL>
<LI>Public Citizen lobbies successfully to end funding for the
Advanced Breeder Reactor.</LI>
<LI>The Senate and House of Representatives each pass a campaign
finance bill in the first step to election reform.</LI>
</UL></LI>


<LI>
1992
<UL>
<LI>Public Citizen helps defeat an industry-backed bill that would
restrict the use of the courts by consumers injured by defective
products.</LI>
<LI>Public Citizen, after a four-year campaign, wins a nearly complete
ban on the use of silicone gel breast implants.</LI>
<LI>Public Citizen exposes the threat to health and safety standards
posed by Dan Quayle's Council on Competitiveness.</LI>
</UL></LI>

<LI>
1991
<UL>
<LI>Public Citizen wins all three cases it argues in the Supreme
Court.</LI>
<LI>Public Citizen publishes <I>Women's Health Alert</I>, a handbook on
women's health issues.</LI>
<LI>Public Citizen publishes <I>They Love to Fly and It Shows</I>, a study of
lobbyist-funded House travel during 1989-90.</LI>
</UL></LI>


<LI>
1990
<UL>
<LI>Public Citizen publishes <I>6,892 Questionable Doctors</I>, a nationwide
listing of doctors disciplined by state medical boards and federal
agencies.</LI>
<LI>Public Citizen wins a court victory requiring the Nuclear
Regulatory Commission to issue mandatory training requirements for
nuclear plant personnel.</LI>
<LI>Public Citizen publishes an account of the savings and loan
scandal, entitled <I>Who Robbed America?</I></LI>
</UL></LI>

<LI>
1989
<UL>
<LI>A regulation requiring air bags or passive seat belts in all cars
takes effect after a 20-year battle.</LI>
<LI>Ralph Nader and Public Citizen successfully oppose a $45,500
congressional pay raise while fighting for campaign finance reform.</LI>
<LI>Public Citizen helps persuade California voters to shut down the
Rancho Seco nuclear plant.</LI>
</UL></LI>


<LI>
1988
<UL>
<LI>Public Citizen publishes <I>Worst Pills, Best Pills</I>, a guide to
dangerous drugs for the elderly.  By 1995, almost two million
copies are sold.</LI>
<LI>Public Citizen's advocacy for Proposition 103 helps the measure
win in the California polls, and rolls back auto insurance rates.</LI>
</UL></LI>
<LI>
1987
<UL>
<LI>Public Citizen plays an instrumental role in the defeat of Robert
Bork's Supreme Court nomination.</LI>
<LI>Public Citizen helps pass a strong "check hold" bill restricting
the time banks can hold checks.</LI>
<LI>Public Citizen forces the chemical companies who produced Agent
Orange to make all relevant documents public.</LI>
</UL></LI>

<LI>
1986
<UL>
<LI>Public Citizen lawsuit strikes down the Gramm-Rudman-Hollings
deficit reduction law as unconstitutional.</LI>
<LI>Congress passes a law requiring health warnings on the labels of
snuff and chewing tobacco, capping Public Citizen's two-year
campaign.</LI>
</UL></LI>

<LI>
1985
<UL>
<LI>After a four-year battle by Public Citizen, the FDA requires
aspirin labels to warn of the risk of Reye's Syndrome.</LI>
<LI>Public Citizen begins publishing the Health Letter.</LI>
</UL></LI>

<LI>
1984
<UL>
<LI>Public Citizen publishes <I>Retreat From Safety</I>.</LI>
<LI>Public Citizen helps block legislation that would make it easier
for manufacturers to use cancer-causing food additives.</LI>
</UL></LI>

<LI>
1983
<UL>
<LI>Public Citizen wins a landmark separation-of-powers case in the
Supreme Court, stopping Congress from vetoing government
regulations.</LI>
<LI><I>Over the Counter Pills That Don't Work</I> is published.
<LI>Public Citizen and Ralph Nader found Buyers Up, a cooperative
consumer buying group.</LI>
<LI>Public Citizen gets Congress to stop funding the Clinch River
Breeder Reactor, revived by President Reagan.</LI>
</UL></LI>


<LI>
1982
<UL>
<LI>Oraflex, an arthritis drug that caused dozens of deaths and
hundreds of injuries, is withdrawn from the market after Public
Citizen's campaign.</LI>
<LI>Public Citizen stops passage of a regulatory roll-back bill
intended to give OMB's David Stockman extraordinary powers over
government agencies.</LI>
<LI>Public Citizen convinces Congress not to exempt doctors and
lawyers from Federal Trade Commission (FTC) oversight.</LI>
</UL></LI>

<LI>
1981
<UL>
<LI>Public Citizen helps thwart President Reagan's attempt to bury the
Consumer Product Safety Commission in the Commerce Department.</LI>
</UL></LI>

<LI>
1980
<UL>
<LI>Public Citizen publishes <I>Pills that Don't Work</I>, which quickly
climbs onto the best-seller lists.</LI>
<LI>Public Citizen plays a critical roles in passage of the Superfund
law to require cleanup of toxic waste dumps.</LI>
</UL></LI>

<LI>
1979
<UL>
<LI>In response to a 1977 petition by Public Citizen, the EPA bans
DBCP, a pesticide that causes sterility in human males and cancer
in laboratory animals.</LI>
</UL></LI>

<LI>
1978
<UL>
<LI>Cyclamates, widely used as artificial sweeteners, are banned in
response to concerns raised by Public Citizen.</LI>
<LI>Congress passes the National Consumer Cooperative Bank bill,
drafted by Public Citizen, providing $300 million "seed money" for
consumer cooperatives.</LI>
</UL></LI>

<LI>
1977
<UL>
<LI>Public Citizen is instrumental in passing the Toxic Substances
Control Act and antitrust reform legislation giving states the
right to sue price fixers.</LI>
<LI>Public Citizen mobilizes citizens, persuading President Carter to
stop construction of the Clinch River Breeder Reactor.</LI>
</UL></LI>
<LI>
1976
<UL>
<LI>The FDA bans Red Dye No. 2, after Public Citizen's four-year
campaign against the carcinogenic food dye.</LI>
<LI>FDA bans the use of cancer-causing chloroform in cough medicines
and toothpastes, in response to a Public Citizen petition.</LI>
<LI>Consumers win the right to obtain meaningful price information
about prescription drugs as a result of a Public Citizen victory in
the Supreme Court.</LI>
</UL></LI>

<LI>
1975
<UL>
<LI>Public Citizen successfully lobbies for new energy conservation
legislation, including fuel economy requirements for cars.</LI>
<LI>Public Citizen obtains a court order requiring the Labor
Department to reconsider its inadequate rules to protect workers
from 14 carcinogenic chemicals.</LI>
</UL></LI>

<LI>
1974
<UL>
<LI>Critical Mass Energy Project is founded to mobilize opposition to
nuclear power.</LI>
<LI>Public Citizen convinces Congress to pass major improvements to
the Freedom of Information Act, overriding President Ford's veto.</LI>
</UL></LI>

<LI>
1973
<UL>
<LI>Public Citizen wins a court decision that Nixon's firing of
Special Watergate Prosecutor Archibald Cox was illegal.</LI>
<LI>Congress Watch, the legislative lobbying arm of Public Citizen, is
formed.</LI>
</UL></LI>

<LI>
1972
<UL>
<LI>The Litigation Group and the Tax Reform Research Group are
founded.</LI>
</UL></LI>

<LI>
1971
<UL>
<LI>Public Citizen is founded by Ralph Nader</LI>
<LI>The Health Research Group and the Aviation Consumer Action Project
are created.</LI>
<LI>The Citizen Action Group, the organizing arm of Public Citizen,
organizes Student Public Interest Research Groups.</LI>
</UL></LI>
</UL>
</P>
<HR>
<P>
Return to <A HREF="/public_citizen/public_citizen.html"> 
<IMG SRC="/public_citizen/red_ball.gif"> Public Citizen's Home Page</A>
