<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Presidential Candidates Environmental & Energy
Issues Questionnaire</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFCC" LINK="#993333" VLINK="#444444"
ALINK="#444444"> 

<CENTER><STRONG>
Energy America Education Fund<BR>
Newmarket Road, Box 201; Warner, N.H. 03278 (603-431-2499;
603-456-
3641)</STRONG></CENTER>
<P>
<H2><CENTER>
1996 U.S. Presidential Candidates<BR> 
Environmental & Energy Issues Questionnaire
</CENTER></H2>
<P>
<A HREF="/CMEP/candidatespollrelease.html">News Release</A><BR>
<A HREF="/CMEP/candidatespollstatement.html">Critical Mass Press 
Conference Statement</A>
<P>
<STRONG>1.) Do you support abolition of the U.S. Department of
Energy (DOE)?</STRONG><P>

<P><STRONG>Clinton</STRONG>:  No.  The President has already
ordered substantial reductions in the size of the Department to
make it more efficient.  By 2000, the Administration's plan will
have saved taxpayers more than $10 billion.  Essential functions
of
the Department -- such as research and development, efficiency
programs and critical defense programs -- should be preserved. 
Republican proposals to dismantle the Department would either
save
money by shirking essential missions or simply transfer functions
to other departments without saving taxpayers anything.

<P><STRONG>Alexander</STRONG>:  Yes.

<P><STRONG>Buchanan</STRONG>:  Yes.

<P><STRONG>Dole</STRONG>:  Yes.  Bob Dole supports abolition of
the
U.S. Department of Energy because of the need to downsize the
Federal government and because the Department of Energy serves
little purpose in obtaining energy or environmental benefits in
the
public interest.  The Department of Energy is one of four cabinet
agencies which together spend more than $74 billion per year and
whose elimination Bob Dole has called for in his initiative to
streamline the entire Federal bureaucracy.

<P><STRONG>Dornan</STRONG>:  Yes.

<P><STRONG>Forbes</STRONG>:  Yes.

<P><STRONG>Gramm</STRONG>:  Yes.

<P><STRONG>Keyes</STRONG>:  Yes.

<P><STRONG>Lugar</STRONG>:  No.  Not at this time.  However, if
reliable analysis determined that the essential functions of DOE
could be more efficiently allocated to existing departments as
part
of a general reorganization of the Executive Branch, I would
consider supporting such a reorganization.

<P><STRONG>Taylor</STRONG>:  Yes.

<P><STRONG>
2.) Do you support federal "takings" legislation that would
require
payment if federal environmental regulations reduce property
values?</STRONG>

<P><STRONG>Clinton</STRONG>:  No.  The Administration supports
protecting private property.  If the government takes someone's
property, the government should pay.  That's what the
Constitution
says and that is what the President demands of his government. 
But, the so-called "takings" legislation introduced as part of
the
Republicans' Contract with America goes beyond Constitutional
protections: It would cost taxpayers tens of billions of dollars
and weaken safeguards for public health, safety, and the
environment.  The President has said he would veto these types of
bills.

<P><STRONG>Alexander</STRONG>:  Yes.  I support the
constitutional
principle that property should not be taken without just
compensation.  When I was Governor of Tennessee, I was able to
protect wetlands with a bill that specifically prohibited the
taking of property by condemnation or by eminent domain.

<P><STRONG>Buchanan</STRONG>:  Yes.

<P><STRONG>Dole</STRONG>:  Yes.  Bob Dole supports Federal
legislation that protects the private property rights of American
citizens from invasion by the Federal government consistent with
the Fifth Amendment to the U.S. Constitution and has introduced
legislation in the Senate to achieve that objective.

<P><STRONG>Dornan</STRONG>:  Yes.

<P><STRONG>Forbes</STRONG>:  Yes.

<P><STRONG>Gramm</STRONG>:  Yes.

<P><STRONG>Keyes</STRONG>:  Yes.

<P><STRONG>Lugar</STRONG>:  The Constitution already requires
that
landowners be compensated for takings of their private property. 
I am skeptical that Congress should try to improve upon the work
of
the courts in defining a taking or determining what is just
compensation.

<P><STRONG>Taylor</STRONG>:  Yes.

<P><STRONG>
3.) Do you support opening the Arctic National Wildlife Refuge to
oil exploration and drilling?</STRONG>

<P><STRONG>Clinton</STRONG>:  No.  The Arctic Refuge is a rare,
pristine wilderness that should be preserved for future
generations.  There are substantial state and federal lands that
can be developed in Alaska without disturbing the Refuge.  And
since there is more oil in energy efficiency than can be
extracted
from the Arctic Refuge, drilling is as unnecessary as it is
unwise.

<P><STRONG>Alexander</STRONG>:  Yes.  I favor opening ANWR for
oil
and natural gas exploration.  I believe that such a step is
important for increasing our domestic oil production while
decreasing our dependence on foreign oil.  Although I oppose
opening some areas to oil drilling -- off the coast of Florida
would be one area -- I am convinced that the technology now
exists
to begin limited oil and gas exploration in ANWR in a way that
would be safe for the environment.

<P><STRONG>Buchanan</STRONG>:  Yes.

<P><STRONG>Dole</STRONG>:  Yes.  Bob Dole supports allowing oil
and
gas development on the Coastal Plain -- a small portion -- of the
Arctic National Wildlife Refuge because it can be done safely and
responsibly without damage to the environment, and because
careful
development of America's oil and natural gas resources
contributes
to economic growth, creates American jobs, enhances our nation's
energy security and reduces dependence on foreign oil.

<P><STRONG>Dornan</STRONG>:  Yes.

<P><STRONG>Forbes</STRONG>:  Yes.

<P><STRONG>Gramm</STRONG>:  Yes.

<P><STRONG>Keyes</STRONG>:  Yes.

<P><STRONG>Lugar</STRONG>:  Yes.  I would support it on the
assumption that strict regulations and advanced technology will
protect wildlife.

<P><STRONG>Taylor</STRONG>:  Yes.

<P><STRONG>
4.) Do you favor raising the Corporate Average Fuel Economy
standards for new cars to 45 mpg and for new light trucks to 35
mpg
by the year 2005?</STRONG>

<P><STRONG>Clinton</STRONG>:  No.  The Administration strongly
supports improving fuel efficiency, and believes CAFE has been a
useful tool to increase fuel economy in the past.  However, the
fast-paced increase suggested by the question runs a strong risk
of
not being cost-effective and of being counterproductive.  In
September 1993, the President initiated a new partnership with
the
domestic auto industry and labor to develop a new generation of
high-performance, affordable vehicles up to three times more fuel
efficient than today's models.  Early developments are promising.

<P><STRONG>Alexander</STRONG>:  No.

<P><STRONG>Buchanan</STRONG>:  No.

<P><STRONG>Dole</STRONG>:  No.  Bob Dole supports saving energy
in
the transportation sector, but he believes that additional
Federal
regulatory mandates such as raising Corporate Average Fuel
Economy
("CAFE") standards are not the best way to obtain more energy
efficient cars and trucks.  Bob Dole advocates greater use of
alternative fuels like ethanol to reduce emissions and increase
energy security.  Bob Dole also advocates taking a harder look at
market-based mechanisms to get the really inefficient and
polluting
cars off the road.

<P><STRONG>Dornan</STRONG>:  No.

<P><STRONG>Forbes</STRONG>:  No.

<P><STRONG>Gramm</STRONG>:  I am opposed to arbitrary government
mandates that can lead to increased burdensome government
intervention and increased costs to the consumer.

<P><STRONG>Keyes</STRONG>:  No.  CAFE kills 2,000 - 4,000 people
a year by making larger, safer cars less affordable.  It's an
assault on the family car and should be abolished.

<P><STRONG>Lugar</STRONG>:  No, but I support the current CAFE
standards, which have doubled the energy efficiency of our
automobile fleet.

<P><STRONG>Taylor</STRONG>:  Yes.  Increase ethanol/fuel ratio to
30/70 from 15/85.

<P><STRONG>
5.) Do you support the construction of new nuclear power plants
in
the U.S.?</STRONG>

<P><STRONG>Clinton</STRONG>:  New nuclear power plants are not
being built today for two economic reasons:  first, they are
extremely expensive -- more costly than both conservation
measures
and other sources of electricity generation; and second,
nationwide
conservation and utility deregulation have reduced the demand for
huge new plants.  The Administration supports research and
development funding to help develop more cost-effective nuclear
plant designs.  Ultimately, however, the market and the public
must
choose the technology and fuels for future electricity generation
-
- not the government.

<P><STRONG>Alexander</STRONG>:  Yes.

<P><STRONG>Buchanan</STRONG>:  Yes.

<P><STRONG>Dole</STRONG>:  Bob Dole supports a diversified energy
supply system.  If nuclear power is selected as the economic
choice, and otherwise meets all health and safety licensing
requirements, Bob Dole supports the right of companies to choose
nuclear power technology.  However, one of the most pressing
problems facing the nuclear energy industry is the disposal of
nuclear waste.  This problem has not been adequately addressed by
the Clinton Administration and needs to be resolved.

<P><STRONG>Dornan</STRONG>:  Yes.

<P><STRONG>Forbes</STRONG>:  Yes.

<P><STRONG>Gramm</STRONG>:  Federal safety standards governing
the
construction of nuclear facilities should continue.  States and
localities should decide for themselves if they want nuclear
power
plants in their communities.

<P><STRONG>Keyes</STRONG>:  Yes, provided the nuclear plants are
not built with tax dollars.

<P><STRONG>Lugar</STRONG>:  I would not rule out such
construction
if a particular nuclear plant is an economical and safe option. 
Nuclear power could help combat the threat of global warming.

<P><STRONG>Taylor</STRONG>:  Yes.

<P><STRONG>
6.) Do you support cuts of 25 percent in the DOE energy
efficiency
and renewable energy programs?</STRONG>

<P><STRONG>Clinton</STRONG>:  No.  These programs save consumers
money, create jobs, help new technologies gain market share in
the
U.S. and abroad, and reduce the gases that cause global climate
change and other air pollution.  That's why the President has
expanded funding for these programs -- more than 40 percent for
conservation and renewables (measured from the last Bush budget
to
the 1996 Clinton request).  Many of these programs engage the
private sector in voluntary energy-saving efforts that help
improve
productivity -- and generate significant economic and
environmental
benefits for each taxpayer dollar invested.

<P><STRONG>Alexander</STRONG>:  Yes.

<P><STRONG>Buchanan</STRONG>:  Yes.

<P><STRONG>Dole</STRONG>:  Yes.  DOE's energy efficiency and
renewable energy programs, like many other worthy programs in the
Federal government, must bear their share of the budget restraint
necessary to obtain a balanced budget.  Federal funding for
energy
conservation programs and for renewable energy programs increased
27.5% and 42% respectively, from FY'1993 to FY'1995.  These
substantial increases came on top of a doubling of energy
conservation research and development funding and a 65% increase
in
renewable energy funding during the Bush Administration.  The
Congress has approved approximately $800 million in FY'1996
funding
for DOE's energy conservation and renewable energy programs. 
This
seems adequate.

<P><STRONG>Dornan</STRONG>:  Yes.

<P><STRONG>Forbes</STRONG>:  Additional cuts may be needed so I
have not yet established a funding level.

<P><STRONG>Gramm</STRONG>:  As President, I will eliminate the
Department of Energy.

<P><STRONG>Keyes</STRONG>:  Yes.

<P><STRONG>Lugar</STRONG>:  No, but in the context of addressing
our budget predicament, all federal programs, including DOE
programs, must be eligible to take some cuts.

<P><STRONG>Taylor</STRONG>:  Yes.

<P><STRONG>
7.) Do you support ensuring that the government receives a fair
market return for publicly owned minerals extracted by private
mining companies on federal land?</STRONG>

<P><STRONG>Clinton</STRONG>:  Yes.  Mining companies should pay a
fair share.  At a time when Republicans in Congress are cutting
Medicare and Medicaid and raising taxes on working families in
order to balance the budget, it is wrong that mining companies
can
take public minerals worth $1 billion for as little as $275.  I
believe the current laws should be reformed.

<P><STRONG>Alexander</STRONG>:  Yes.

<P><STRONG>Buchanan</STRONG>:  Yes.

<P><STRONG>Dole</STRONG>:  While Bob Dole supports reform of out-
dated mining laws, he opposes efforts that would put miners and
others in related activities out of work, severely impact the
economy in our Western states and actually decrease Federal
revenues.  Fees for mineral extraction on Federal lands should be
set in a way that promotes responsible development of our
nation's
mineral resources to support economic growth and create jobs. 
Such
fees also need to reflect the Federal government's fiscal
responsibilities to the American taxpayers to balance the budget
and manage Federal resources.

<P><STRONG>Dornan</STRONG>:  Yes.

<P><STRONG>Forbes</STRONG>:  I support the principle of a fair
market return but have endorsed no specific plan as of now.

<P><STRONG>Gramm</STRONG>:  I support revising the 1872 mining
law
and increasing the amounts charged to mining companies using
federal lands.

<P><STRONG>Keyes</STRONG>:  Yes, provided market value is
determined by some kind of auction or competitive bidding.

<P><STRONG>Lugar</STRONG>:  Yes, although we should recognize
that
there are differences about what constitutes a fair market rate
that must be resolved.  I would favor an increase of some type in
the fees that mining companies pay for extracting minerals on
public lands.

<P><STRONG>Taylor</STRONG>:  Yes.

<P><STRONG>
8.) Do you support the proposed cuts in funding (40%) for HHS'
Low
Income Home Energy Assistance Program (LIHEAP) and DOE's
Weatherization Assistance Program?</STRONG>

<P><STRONG>Clinton</STRONG>:  No.  In the past two years, we have
witnessed severe weather -- the brutal winter of 1993-94 in the
East, the hot summer of 1995 in the Midwest, and the blizzard of
1996 which we are now facing -- where many poor and elderly
citizens face life-threatening situations.  LIHEAP helps these
citizens pay their bills and offers them an important lifeline. 
Weatherization continues to be a very cost-effective way to help
poor families, who spend about three times the proportion of
their
family budgets on fuel and utility bills than average.

<P><STRONG>Alexander</STRONG>:  Yes.  I support cuts in these
programs to help balance the budget.

<P><STRONG>Buchanan</STRONG>:  No Response.

<P><STRONG>Dole</STRONG>:  Again, Bob Dole supports HHS' Low
Income
Home Energy Assistance program and DOE's weatherization
assistance
program and understands the importance of these programs to the
State of New Hampshire.  The issues are:  (1) how much should be
spent on these programs given other competing priorities; (2) the
need to balance the budget; and (3) who should bear financial
responsibility for these programs, the Federal government or the
states.  In general, he believes the states should have more say
about how to use Federal resources to provide for the welfare of
their citizens.  Whether states choose to use those resources for
low income energy assistance or weatherization should be a
judgment
for states to make, not the Federal government.

<P><STRONG>Dornan</STRONG>:  Yes.

<P><STRONG>Forbes</STRONG>:  I have established no specific
funding
level.

<P><STRONG>Gramm</STRONG>:  I have voted in favor of increased
funding for the Low Income Home Energy Assistance Program and
sought to reduce spending on other programs of lower priority in
order to pay for it.

<P><STRONG>Keyes</STRONG>:  Yes.

<P><STRONG>Lugar</STRONG>:  No.  I strongly support the low
income
home energy assistance and weatherization programs.

<P><STRONG>Taylor</STRONG>:  No.

<P><STRONG>
9.) Do you support the phase-out of new appliance efficiency and
building energy code standards?</STRONG>

<P><STRONG>Clinton</STRONG>:  No.  These standards have saved
consumers billions of dollars in the past 10 years.  Moreover,
new
appliance standards are set by consulting with manufacturers to
ensure that standards are cost-effective and in the best
interests
of both consumers and appliance producers.  Building energy codes
remain the cheapest, most efficient way to increase energy
efficiency in homes and offices, and federal guidance is
necessary
because state and local programs don't always have the resources
to
develop their own codes.

<P><STRONG>Alexander</STRONG>:  No.  They do need to be reformed,
however, to eliminate the most burdensome regulations.  Many
builders have already invested money to conform with existing
codes.

<P><STRONG>Buchanan</STRONG>:  No Response.

<P><STRONG>Dole</STRONG>:  Bob Dole supports providing consumers
with the information they need to choose the level of efficiency
they want to pay for.  He does not support Federal mandates or
regulations that deny consumers choice and affordable appliances
or
cost American jobs.

<P><STRONG>Dornan</STRONG>:  Yes, (as regards to new appliance
efficiency standards; building energy codes are a matter of state
law)

<P><STRONG>Forbes</STRONG>:  Yes.

<P><STRONG>Gramm</STRONG>:  Consumers should determine which
product(s) in the marketplace is superior based on available
information provided by the manufacturer.

<P><STRONG>Keyes</STRONG>:  Yes.

<P><STRONG>Lugar</STRONG>:  No.  I helped persuade President
Reagan
to sign national appliance efficiency standards into law.

<P><STRONG>Taylor</STRONG>:  No.

<P><STRONG>
10.) Do you support cutting U.S. so-called greenhouse gas
emissions
to 1990 levels by the year 2000?</STRONG>

<P><STRONG>Clinton</STRONG>:  Yes.  On Earth Day 1993, shortly
after taking office, President Clinton made a commitment to cut
emissions of greenhouse gases to 1990 levels by the year 2000 --
a
commitment previous Presidents refused to make.

<P><STRONG>Alexander</STRONG>:  No.  Greenhouse gas emissions are
a serious issue, and we should rely on the best science to make
policy.  But this is not exclusively an American problem.  It
should be dealt with in conjunction with other countries.  The
U.S.
should not place its businesses at an economic disadvantage by
acting unilaterally.

<P><STRONG>Buchanan</STRONG>:  No Response.

<P><STRONG>Dole</STRONG>:  Bob Dole supports the commitment made
by
President Bush to prepare a plan with the objective of returning
U.S. greenhouse gas levels in the year 2000 to 1990 levels
through
voluntary measures.

<P><STRONG>Dornan</STRONG>:  Yes.

<P><STRONG>Forbes</STRONG>:  I question the need for restricting
the United States' ability to create jobs for our people based on
global warming theory which is unproven.

<P><STRONG>Gramm</STRONG>:  I support market-driven energy
efficiency and oppose artificial government mandates implemented
by
EPA regulations.

<P><STRONG>Keyes</STRONG>:  No.

<P><STRONG>Lugar</STRONG>:  I supported the 1992 Climate Change
Convention, which called on all nations to stabilize emissions of
greenhouse gases.

<P><STRONG>Taylor</STRONG>:  No Response.

<P><STRONG>
11.) Do you support establishment of an interim storage
high-level
nuclear waste site in Nevada?</STRONG>

<P><STRONG>Clinton</STRONG>:  No.  The Administration opposes
building anywhere a temporary storage facility for high-level
waste
until scientific investigation on a permanent disposal site is
farther along.  The Administration believes that we should focus
on
funding and completing the scientific examination of the
permanent
underground disposal repository at Yucca Mountain, Nevada.  We
should make the decision about where and when to build an interim
site after we know more about Yucca Mountain's suitability as a
permanent repository.

<P><STRONG>Alexander</STRONG>:  Yes.

<P><STRONG>Buchanan</STRONG>:  No Response.

<P><STRONG>Dole</STRONG>:  Bob Dole supports the siting of an
interim storage facility for high-level nuclear waste.  He
believes
that determinations regarding the siting of that facility should
be
left to the legislative process, through the authorizing
committees
of the Congress working with those deeply involved in the high-
level nuclear waste program.

<P><STRONG>Dornan</STRONG>:  Yes.

<P><STRONG>Forbes</STRONG>:  Undecided pending further study.

<P><STRONG>Gramm</STRONG>:  I believe it is appropriate that the
Federal government should be involved with the disposal of
nuclear
waste, and the government will need to work closely with
individual
states to best determine the future of interim and long term
storage issues.

<P><STRONG>Keyes</STRONG>:  Undecided.

<P><STRONG>Lugar</STRONG>:  Yes, if needed to avoid premature
licensing of a permanent storage facility.

<P><STRONG>Taylor</STRONG>:  Yes.

<P><STRONG>
12.) Do you support transfer of federal land for the proposed
Ward
Valley, California low-level nuclear waste facility?</STRONG>

<P><STRONG>Clinton</STRONG>:  Yes, if the proper health and
safety
standards are in place.  Unfortunately, the state of California
(to
whom the site would be transferred) and Republicans in Congress
believe the site should be transferred without any binding
commitments for public safeguards.  The President opposes that
measure, and vetoed it with the rest of the GOP budget (the
reconciliation bill).

<P><STRONG>Alexander</STRONG>:  Yes.  I am not familiar with the
details of the proposal, but I would support it provided the
project is scientifically and environmentally sound.

<P><STRONG>Buchanan</STRONG>:  No Response.

<P><STRONG>Dole</STRONG>:  Yes.  Ward Valley is the site selected
by state officials charged with the responsibility of siting a
low-
level nuclear waste facility.  Independent scientific assessments
have demonstrated no reason why Ward Valley is not a suitable
site
for such a facility.  Bob Dole believes, therefore, that the
Federal government should accommodate the choice that the states
have made.

<P><STRONG>Dornan</STRONG>:  Decision is made at [the] state
[level]; local issue.

<P><STRONG>Forbes</STRONG>:  Undecided pending further study.

<P><STRONG>Gramm</STRONG>:  I believe it is appropriate that the
Federal government should be involved with the disposal of
nuclear
waste, and the government will need to work closely with
individual
states to best determine the future of interim and long term
storage issues.

<P><STRONG>Keyes</STRONG>:  Yes.

<P><STRONG>Lugar</STRONG>:  Yes.  The National Academy of
Sciences
endorsed this concept.

<P><STRONG>Taylor</STRONG>:  No Response.

<P><STRONG>
13.) Do you support reauthorization and strict enforcement of the
Endangered Species Act?</STRONG>

<P><STRONG>Clinton</STRONG>:  Yes.  The President supports a
strong
Endangered Species Act (ESA) that protects wildlife and provides
more flexibility to landowners and more involvement for the
states. 
Without waiting for Congress, the Administration has already
launched reforms of the ESA that will ensure that the vast
majority
of homeowners never again have to worry about ESA restrictions.

<P><STRONG>Alexander</STRONG>:  Some of the extreme applications
of
the Endangered Species Act have become somewhat silly, costing
jobs
and drifting away from the original purpose of the Act.  That was
the case in Tennessee when the allegedly "endangered" snail
darter
almost prevented our state from building a dam.  We later learned
that the snail darter was not endangered at all, which is why we
need a better, more scientific system of determining whether a
species is actually endangered.  I think there is a way of
reforming the Endangered Species Act that is less onerous to
property owners, gives more incentives to property owners to
protect endangered species, but still retains federal protection
of
endangered species and their habitats.

<P><STRONG>Buchanan</STRONG>:  No.

<P><STRONG>Dole</STRONG>:  The Endangered Species Act ("ESA") is
in
need of reform.  It has been a divisive and costly mechanism that
-
- while playing a role in the return of formerly endangered
species
such as the bald eagle -- has effectively placed the judiciary in
charge of commerce and land management in significant portions of
the West and Northwest.  The bitterness and controversy
surrounding
the ESA works <EM>against</EM> the responsible environmental
stewardship that needs to be encouraged on the part of all
Americans.

<P><STRONG>Dornan</STRONG>:  No.

<P><STRONG>Forbes</STRONG>:  No, unless common sense amendments
are
adopted to stop prosecution of farmers who run over endangered
rats
while plowing their fields and similar ridiculous situations.

<P><STRONG>Gramm</STRONG>:  I support a rational, science-based
endangered species law which respects private property and
individual jobs.  I believe the most important environmental
reform
we can adopt is to guarantee the protection of private property.

<P><STRONG>Keyes</STRONG>:  No.  I support the Shadegg bill --
voluntary, incentive-based conservation.

<P><STRONG>Lugar</STRONG>:  Yes, but the scope of the ESA needs
clarification.

<P><STRONG>Taylor</STRONG>:  No.  Enforcement should consider
economic impact and environmental impact.

<P><STRONG>
14.) Do you support application of probabilistic risk assessment
and cost/benefit tests to all new and existing federal
environmental and energy regulation?</STRONG>

<P><STRONG>Clinton</STRONG>:  Yes.  The Administration supports
risk assessment and cost/benefit analysis for new and existing
regulations, when the analysis is commensurate with the
significance of the decision, and would improve the regulatory
system.  The Administration cannot support a risk assessment or
cost/benefit scheme that would cause undue delay or litigation or
would roll back health, safety, and environmental protection.

<P><STRONG>Alexander</STRONG>:  Yes.

<P><STRONG>Buchanan</STRONG>:  Yes.

<P><STRONG>Dole</STRONG>:  Yes.  While we have made enormous
improvements in reducing environmental pollution, Bob Dole
believes
that the current environmental regulatory approach is flawed.  We
need to learn from the last 25 years of Federal environmental
regulation to determine how to best achieve our environmental
goals
for this and future generations.  Americans have spent about $2
trillion on direct compliance with Federal environmental
regulations since 1970.  In a study done for GAO in 1992,
Professor
Thomas Hopkins of the Rochester Institute of Technology projected
that Americans would be spending at least $170 billion a year on
direct compliance with environmental regulations by 1995 -- an
amount that is more than double (in constant dollars) what he
estimated was spent in 1985.  Risk assessment and cost/benefit
tests are not an attempt to "roll back" environmental
protections,
but rather are an effort to ensure that as we move forward to
protect our environment we do so wisely.  We must emphasize sound
science, prioritize our efforts, be careful of pursuing small
risks
at great costs and understand that spending more to chase slight
or
sensational risks means less state, local and individual
resources
are available to meet other health or societal needs.  Bob Dole
believes that we can afford to apply a little common sense to
environmental regulation.  In fact, we cannot afford <EM>not</EM>
to.

<P><STRONG>Dornan</STRONG>:  Yes.

<P><STRONG>Forbes</STRONG>:  Yes.

<P><STRONG>Gramm</STRONG>:  Yes.  I believe that all regulatory
legislation Congress considers should be subject to risk
assessment
or cost-benefit studies.  Business, local governments, families
and
individuals make cost-benefit decisions every day on how to spend
their money and ensure that expenditures are cost-effective.  The
Federal Government, particularly the EPA and other regulatory
agencies that thrive on imposing new rules, should be subject to
similar standards.  They don't follow those standards now because
the money being spent is not their own; it's ours.

<P><STRONG>Keyes</STRONG>:  Yes.

<P><STRONG>Lugar</STRONG>:  Yes, in order to achieve strict
environmental standards at reasonable costs such as we did in
controlling acid rain.

<P><STRONG>Taylor</STRONG>:  Yes.

<P><STRONG>
15.) Do you support the proposed cuts (about 35%) in the EPA
budget?</STRONG>

<P><STRONG>Clinton</STRONG>:  No.  The President is strongly
opposed to cuts of this magnitude, which would put public health
and safety at risk.  He vetoed the Republican EPA appropriations
bill in large part because it would have cut EPA's funding 22
percent from the President's request.  (The vetoed bill had been
improved slightly in the House/Senate conference from the 35% cut
cited in the question, which was the House level.)

<P><STRONG>Alexander</STRONG>:  One of the proposed cuts in EPA
funding would have cut the money for state efforts to keep their
drinking water clean.  That makes no sense to me.  Clean water is
the single most important environmental issue in every community.

We want states and localities to play a greater role in keeping
water clean.  Republicans should be arguing for moving
responsibility to states, not making it more difficult for them.

<P><STRONG>Buchanan</STRONG>:  Yes.

<P><STRONG>Dole</STRONG>:  For fiscal year 1996, EPA will
<EM>not</EM> receive a 35% cut in funding.  Although Bob Dole
supports the current funding level for EPA, EPA must also bear
its
share of the burden of achieving a balanced budget.  EPA has
almost
doubled in size in the past 20 years to over 19,000 employees
(not
counting contract employees), and its budget has grown from $1.6
<EM>billion</EM> to $3.6 billion (in constant dollars), not
counting construction spending, during the same period.  More EPA
staff does not automatically mean a better environment.  It does
mean fewer resources to devote to other needs (e.g., health,
nutrition, housing).

<P><STRONG>Dornan</STRONG>:  Yes.

<P><STRONG>Forbes</STRONG>:  I have established no specific
funding
level.

<P><STRONG>Gramm</STRONG>:  To balance the federal budget, cut
taxes, and defend private property in America, I will look at
every
federal program - including the EPA - to determine if the
benefits
to be derived by spending money on it are worth taking the money
away from hard-working, ordinary Americans to pay for it.  Not a
lot of programs will stand up to that test.

<P><STRONG>Keyes</STRONG>:  Yes (noting the cuts were 20% less
than
the President's budget).  Appropriations riders were the only way
to discipline EPA after the environmental establishment blocked
reauthorization of major environmental bills.

<P><STRONG>Lugar</STRONG>:  No.  I would oppose a 35% cut in
current funding levels, but I voted for a smaller cut in FY'95
[sic] funding levels for EPA.

<P><STRONG>Taylor</STRONG>:  Yes.

<P><STRONG>
16.) Do you support repeal of the 1935 Public Utility Holding
Company Act?</STRONG> 

<P><STRONG>Clinton</STRONG>:  No. PUHCA was enacted to limit
anti-
competitive behavior by utility monopolies, and still serves as
an
important safeguard for consumers.  Significant changes have been
enacted to PUHCA and related laws in recent years, and we should
carefully examine the effect of those reforms before we make
further changes.  However, as the electric utility industry
becomes
more competitive, the Administration will assess the prospects
for
undertaking statutory reforms of PUHCA in view of national
objectives of reliable, clean, and economic electricity
generation.

<P><STRONG>Alexander</STRONG>:  Yes.

<P><STRONG>Buchanan</STRONG>:  No Response.

<P><STRONG>Dole</STRONG>:  Yes.  The 1935 Public Utility Holding
Company Act is an outdated statute that no longer provides
benefits
to consumers or investors and should be repealed.  The Securities
and Exchange Commission under both Republican and Democratic
Administrations in 1981 and again in 1985 has recommended repeal
of
this statute.  Bob Dole has co-sponsored legislation that would
repeal this out-moded statute with appropriate safeguards for
consumers.

<P><STRONG>Dornan</STRONG>:  Yes.

<P><STRONG>Forbes</STRONG>:  Yes.

<P><STRONG>Gramm</STRONG>:  Yes.

<P><STRONG>Keyes</STRONG>:  Yes.

<P><STRONG>Lugar</STRONG>:  Yes, if this would eliminate
duplicative regulation.

<P><STRONG>Taylor</STRONG>:  Yes.

<HR>
<P>
<A HREF="/orgs/public_citizen/CMEP/home.html">Return to the
Critical Mass Home Page</A>
