<html>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<center><img height=75 width-=120
src="/public_citizen/pclogo.gif"></center><p>
<h1><center>Corporate Welfare</h1></center>
<p>
Each year, U.S. taxpayers subsidize U.S. businesses to the tune 
of more than $150 billion. Every five years, the U.S. Treasury loses $1 
billion because mining companies don't pay a fair market value for 
minerals extracted from public lands. Companies such as Hershey 
International and McDonalds receive some $69 million each year in public 
funds for advertising campaigns and other promotions of their products as 
American agricultural exports.  Stopping public funding of new roads in 
the national forests, which are used by timber companies to carry away 
trees they bought from the government for next to nothing, would save 
about $50 million annually.  
<p>
	Each dollar spent on these "aid for dependent corporation" 
welfare programs means one dollar less for environmental programs, 
support for education, assistance to those in need, tax 
breaks for families, or deficit reduction.  During this Congress, Public 
Citizen will help lead a major  push to reduce corporate welfare. Key 
votes will likely occur in the spring, when the 
budget is debated, and then in the summer and fall as specific 
appropriations bills, ladened with corporate pork, are considered.
<p>
<h3>Please Choose From the Following for Information:</h3><p>
<img src="/gtw/images/new.gif"><a href="ralph.html">Statement on 
Corporate Welfare by Ralph Nader, January 30, 1997</a><p>
<img src="/gtw/images/new.gif"><a href="kash.html">"Cut Corporate 
Welfare Now," Statement of Public Citizen President Joan Claybrook, 
January 28, 1996.</a><p>
<a href="cuts.html">The Corporate Welfare Hit List</a><p>
