<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<center><img height=75 width=120 
src="/public_citizen/pclogo.gif"></center><p>
<center><h1>Protecting Your Health, Safety and Environment</h1></center><p>
<center><h3>Regulatory Roll Back</center></h3><p>

	Today, Americans enjoy safer automobiles and consumer products, 
purer food and drinking water, cleaner air, more reliable drugs and 
medical devices, and safer work places than ever before.  These 
safeguards were under attack in the 104th Congress, and we expect a 
similar assault on these important protections in the 105th 
Congress.           
<p>
	Pro-industry Members of Congress want to cripple government 
agencies such as the EPA, the FDA, and OSHA --  each charged with 
protecting the health and safety of the American public.  Anti-regulatory 
extremists have a three-pronged approach to rolling back important health 
and safety standards: 1) Paralyze regulatory agencies by requiring 
needless and excessively bureaucratic procedures -- such as extensive 
cost-benefit analyses and risk assessments -- before a simple standard to 
implement environmental, health and safety laws could be issued.  2) 
Attack actual laws that guarantee health and safety protections.  At 
various times over the last two years, serious attempts to roll back the 
Clean Air Act, the Clean Water Act, the Safe Drinking Water Act, the 
Food, Drugs and Cosmetics Act and the Occupational Safety and Health Act 
all came up for consideration.  3) De-fund important agencies and 
programs that ensure health and safety.
<p>
	Anti-safety leaders and their special interest allies were 
thwarted in the 104th Congress, but they are likely to be back with a 
vengeance in 1997-1998.  One probable bill will neutralize important FDA 
protections.  Another may make a broader attack on all environmental, 
health and safety laws.  Public Citizen is prepared to again take the 
lead to make sure that critical health and safety standards are not 
rolled back.
<p>
<h3>Please choose from the following for more information:</h3><p>
<li><a href="intro.html">Executive Summary of the Public Citizen 1996 
Report,<i> A 
Million for Your Thoughts: The Industry-Funded Campaign Against the FDA 
by Conservative Think Tanks.</i></li></a><p>
<li><a href="release.html">"Drug, Medical Device, Biotech and Tobacco 
Companies Gave at Least $3.5 Million for Deceptive Anti-FDA Campaign," 
Press Release, July 24, 1996.</a></li>
