<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<center><img height=75 width-=120 
src="/public_citizen/pclogo.gif"></center><p>
<h1><center>Civil Justice/Legal Rights</h1></center>
<p>
	For over 100 years, Americans injured by defective products, 
unsafe workplaces and medical malpractice have had the right to seek 
compensation in courts of law before citizen juries. America's civil 
justice system has been responsible for punishing corporations that  
manufacture defective products -- such as the Ford Pinto, school buses, 
asbestos, tobacco and the Dalkon Shield -- and holding HMOs, hospitals 
and doctors accountable for reckless medical care.  Public Citizen 
believes that Americans have a right to a trial by jury when they are 
injured by defective products or negligent health care. 
<p>
	Because it has been a successful deterrent of corporate 
misconduct, in the last 15 years, America's civil justice system has been 
under ferocious attack in Congress and state legislatures by HMOs and 
doctors, insurance companies, oil and chemical polluters, big tobacco and 
auto manufacturers seeking immunity for wrongdoing. Although corporations 
have been successful in securing some limitations on liability in 
individual states, Public Citizen and other consumer groups have stopped 
Congress from enacting federal limits on corporate liability.
<p>	But each year, the attack on the right to trial by jury 
intensifies. Last year, the bill actually passed Congress but was stopped 
from becoming law by President Clinton's veto. In 1997, Public Citizen 
will once again lead the effort to oppose another well-funded corporate 
effort to limit the liability of reckless corporations and doctors. Votes 
will likely take place in the House 
and Senate during the Spring of 1997.  In addition to limitations on 
liability for defective products and medical malpractice, key votes will 
likely occur on limiting the liability of railroads and shipping 
companies. 
<p>
<h3>Please choose from the following for more information:</h3>
<p>

<img src="/gtw/images/new.gif"><a href="nofault.html">"Auto Choice Makes 
Good Drivers Pay for Bad," Press Release, January 30, 1997</a><p>
<a href="auto.html">Fact Sheet on No Fault Auto Insurance</a><p>
