<html><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<center><img height=75 width=120 
src="/public_citizen/pclogo.gif"></center><p>
<center><h1>Health Care Reform</h1></center><p>

	One hundred forty-million Americans now get their health coverage 
through some form of managed care. There has been an explosion of big 
business, profit-making managed care companies that often put profits 
ahead of patient care. Some managed care companies have included "gag 
rules" in their contracts with participating physicians, preventing them 
from fully discussing treatment options with patients.  Many have 
financial incentives which reward doctors for referring fewer patients to 
specialists.  Often decisions on what treatments will be authorized are 
made by persons who have not examined the patients -- they may not even 
be fully qualified medical professionals.  
<p>
	Only a few states have adopted comprehensive measures to stop 
managed care abuses.  Many Americans whose health care comes from 
self-insured, employer-sponsored managed care plans are not protected by 
any state legislation because current federal law forbids states from 
regulating such plans.	
<p>									  
	Public Citizen continues to believe that fundamental health care 
reform that provides quality universal care will only come when the U.S. 
adopts a single-payer system similar to Canada's.  However, to protect 
those Americans who find themselves in managed care from abuses which may 
threaten their health, Public Citizen is working for passage of federal 
legislation to provide comprehensive, effective regulation of managed 
care and for a change in federal law to ensure that states are able to 
protect the rights of all managed care enrollees within their state. 
<p>
<hr>
<a href="/congress/cwhome.html">Return to the Congress Watch Home Page</a>
