<html>
<head>
<title>1995 Annual Report</title>
</head>
<BODY COLOR BGCOLOR ="#ffffff" text="#000000"
   LINK="0000ff" VLINK="dd0000">
<body>
<h1><center><FONT SIZE=+4>P</FONT>UBLIC <FONT SIZE=+4>C</FONT>ITIZEN 
<FONT SIZE=+4>L</FONT>ITIGATION <FONT SIZE=+4>G</FONT>ROUP

<p><I>1995 Annual Report</h1></I> </center>
<p>
<b>1995</b> was a year of great accomplishment for Public Citizen
Litigation Group.  In terms of productivity, 1995 was exceptional.
The sheer number of cases in which the Litigation Group is involved
has grown significantly, largely as a result of our legal staff's
high level of experience.  Indeed, Litigation Group lawyers average
about 15 years in practice, and nearly ten years with the group,
which enables us to handle a high volume of complex cases. <p>

<p>

     1995 was a watershed as well in terms of significant
victories.  Not only did we win an important victory in the Supreme
Court, but we  also saw notable wins on a number of  key fronts,
including class action litigation, industry claims that consumer
rights are cut off or "preempted" by a federal law, and open
government.<p>

<p>

     The Litigation Group was founded in 1972 by Ralph Nader and
Alan Morrison, the Group's senior lawyer and formerly its director.

For the past three years, David Vladeck has directed the Group,
which has a staff of ten lawyers, including one who serves as the
Coordinator for the Supreme Court Assistance Project, which is
discussed in the final section of this report.  <p>

<p>

     In 1995, Litigation Group staff handled cases in virtually
every federal circuit, in a number  of state courts, and  before
severalfederal agencies.  Unlike some other public interest law
firms, we rarely file briefs as an <i>amicus curiae</i> (friend of
the court) in cases primarily handled by other lawyers.  Thus, the
cases discussed in this Report, unless otherwise noted, were
handled by Litigation Group staff lawyers.  In addition, staff
lawyers were actively involved in the legislative process, often
testifying before congressional committees, working with committee
staffs, writing reports on pending legislation, and providing
technical support to Public Citizen's lobbying arm, Congress Watch.

<p>

<p>

     Consistent with the Litigation Group's long track record of
appearances before the United States Supreme Court, our attorneys
argued yet another case before the Court in 1995, bringing the
total number of cases we have argued to 36.  In that case,
<i>Yamaha v. Calhoun</i>, we represented the family of a 12-year
old girl killed while using an allegedly defective jet ski. 
Yamaha, the jet ski's manufacturer, claimed that "general federal
maritime law,"  and not state law, determined how much a victim's
survivors can recover in accidents occurring in the territorial
waters of the United States. That claim, if accepted, would have
limited the family's recovery to funeral expenses and little more. 
Fortunately, in an unanimous ruling that came right after the new
year, the Court agreed with our position and held that state law
governs.  Our victory in <i>Yamaha</i> brings our record to 24
wins, 11 losses and one tie.  Moreover, we have two cases pending
before the Court that will be heard in 1996, which is a testament
to the vitality of our Supreme Court practice.<p>

<p>

     From its founding in 1972, the Litigation Group has focused
its efforts to protect consumers in five major areas: government
and corporate accountability; fighting government and corporate
secrecy; regulation of the professions; separation of powers; and
worker rights.  In recent years, however, our efforts to protect
consumers have expanded dramatically to respond to two disturbing
trends in the law.<p>

<p>

     First is the rising tide of class action settlements that
benefit the manufacturers of unsafe or defective products and the
plaintiffs' lawyers, but deliver little or no value to consumers. 
The class action device can be a powerful pro-consumer tool because
it allows a large number of individuals who have been ripped off to
join forces against large corporations or the government.  But too
often in recent years that tool has been used to fashion sweetheart
settlements for lawyers and defendants that work against the
interests of consumers.  <p>

<p>

     Second, we are also doing battle against the aggressive use by
corporate defendants of the "preemption defense" - a claim that a
federal  law or regulation ousts (preempts) state laws  that allow
the consumer or accident victim to recover damages.  In 1995, we
handled cases involving medical devices, airline safety, automobile
safety, and maritime accidents.  And next year we will argue an
important preemption case involving medical devices before the
Supreme Court.<p>

<p>

     Because our work on class actions and preemption now occupies
center stage at the Litigation Group, we begin this year's annual
report with an overview of the significant cases we have handled in
those fields.  We then summarize our more important cases in each
of the other areas as well, to show the breadth of our work and the
impact we have had, and will continue to have, in those critical
areas.<p>


<table border width=100% cellpadding=5>
<tr><td><a
href="http://www.citizen.org/public_citizen/litigation/annual_rep
/govcorp.html">Government &amp; Corporate
Responsibility</a>
<td><a
href="http://www.citizen.org/public_citizen/litigation/annual_rep
/conprotec.html">General Consumer
Protection</a>
<td><a
href="http://www.citizen.org/public_citizen/litigation/annual_rep
/govsec.html">Government Secrecy</a>
