<BODY>
<H2>
<CENTER>
Critical Mass Publications List
</CENTER>
</H2>
<HR>
<P>
Nonprofit groups and individual consumers are eligible for
discount
prices.  Call Public Citizen's Publications Office (202)
588-1000
for pricing infomation.
</P>
<HR>
<P>
<A Name="NewReleases">
<H3>NEW RELEASES</H3>
</A>
<P>
<UL>
<LI>
<B><A HREF="/orgs/public_citizen/CMEP/nuclearsafety/lemon-summary.html">
Nuclear Lemons 5th Edition: An Assessment of Amercia's Worst
Commercial Nuclear Power Plants</A></B><BR>
- Ranks the worst commercial nuclear 
reactors based on twelve safety and economic indicators.  The rankings 
are based entirely on data garnered from government and industry 
documents.  Charges that the Nuclear Regulatory Agency has failed to 
identify many of the most troubled nuclear reactors in the nation and has 
failed to improve the performance of those reactors it has identified.  
10/96, 76 pages. [Item #CM-L8581]
<P>
<LI>
Nuclear Lemons (5th Edition): Reactor-by-Reactor Data Supplement - Gives 
a breakdown of each reactor's performance based on the criteria used in 
Nuclear Lemons. Includes complete data used to rank plants, along with 
other useful site-specific information. 10/96, 110 pages.
[Item#CM-L8581-S]. Both Report and Supplement. 
[Item#CM-L8581-B] 
<P>
<LI>
Power for the People - A public interest blueprint for restructuring the 
electric utility industry.  Shows how sustainable and affordable energy 
can be promoted through the increased use of renewable energy and 
efficiency technologies, guaranteed universal service, and vigorous 
consumer protections that couple market forces with minimum standards.  
Includes comparison of restructuring proposals by industry groups.  7/96, 
21 pages. [Item #CM-L8271]
<P>
<LI>
Renewable Energy Sourcebook: A Primer for Action (Section II): Wind and 
Ocean Energy - A comprehensive review of Department of Energy research 
and development programs for wind energy and ocean thermal energy 
technologies provides the backdrop for an examination of government 
policies intended to bring renewable energy technologies to the utility 
grid.  Finds that federal research and development must continue and must 
be accompanied by strategic efforts to deploy new technologies in 
cooperation with the private sector.  6/96, 25 pages. [Item 
#CM-L828X]
<P>
<LI>
Terminate the Advanced Light Water Reactor - Public Citizen's testimony 
to the House Subcommittee on Energy and Environment on the Department of 
Energy's FY97 budget request for advanced light water reactors (ALWR).  
Public Citizen opposes continued funding of the ALWR program on the 
grounds that  program authorization expires at the end of FY96 and 
utility interest in building new nuclear reactors is lacking.  ALWR is a 
corporate welfare program for Westinghouse and General Electric.  5/96, 8 
pages. [Item #CM-L041]
<P>
<LI>
Support Renewables; Abort Nuclear Pork - Public Citizen's testimony to 
the House Energy and Water Subcommittee on the FY97 Energy and Water 
Appropriations bill. Public Citizen supports increased funding for 
renewable energy technologies and cuts in nuclear energy programs 
including ALWR, pyroprocessing, fusion energy and the Yucca Mountain 
permanent radioactive waste repository program. 2/96, 6 pg. [Item 
#CM-L042]
</UL>
<P>
<H3><A Name="NukeSafety">
NUCLEAR POWER PLANT SAFETY AND NUCLEAR ECONOMICS
</A></H3>
<P><UL>
<LI>
A Roll of the Dice: NRCs Efforts to Renew Nuclear Reactor Licenses - 
Compares operations and maintenance costs to cost of replacement power 
for each U.S. reactor; finds that 57 reactors operate above the cost of 
replacement power.  4/95, 46 pages. [Item #CM-L039]
<P>
<LI>
Abuse of Discretion: NRCs Non-Enforcement Policy - Reveals that for the 
last decade the Nuclear Regulatory Commission has been allowing 
violations of its own regulations at 110 nuclear power plants in 34 
states.  Includes a reactor-by-reactor list of non-enforcement decisions. 
11/94, 71 pg. [Item #CM-L036]
<P>
<LI>
Payment Due: A Reactor-by-Reactor Assessment of the Nuclear Industrys 
$25+ Billion Decommissioning Bill - Examines the cost to decommission 
each of the U.S.s commercial nuclear reactors, the funds already set 
aside, the amount still needed, the type of funding mechanisms being used 
and the U.S.s experience with decommissioning to date. 10/90, 90 pages. 
[Item #CM-L015]
<P>
<LI>
Payment Due: Supplement - Reactor-by-Reactor Data Sheets - Provides data 
used in the first volume of the study for each commercial nuclear plant.  
10/90, 117 pages. [Item #CM-L016]   Both the 
study and supplement - [Item #CM-L016a]
<P>
<LI>
Westinghouse: Leaks and Lawsuits - Examines the steam generator leaks 
that have plagued Westinghouse nuclear reactors. Reveals Westinghouses 
efforts to cover up the safety problem through secret settlements of 
utility lawsuits. 6/94 16 pg.  [Item #CM-L034]
<P>
<LI>
Hear No Evil, See No Evil, Speak No Evil: What The NRC Won't Tell You 
About Americas Nuclear Reactors - Examines secret industry documents that 
detail safety hazards at Americas nuclear reactors.  Compares reports 
written by the Institute of Nuclear Power Operations to the Nuclear 
Regulatory Commissions public assessments of the same plants, showing 
that the NRC fails to address almost two-thirds of the problems 
identified by the nuclear industry.   12/93, 28 pages. [Item 
#CM-L019]
<P>
<LI>
Poisoned Power by Dr. John Gofman - Examines nuclear plants emphasizing 
the problems of radiation, waste,  nuclear safety, environmental impacts, 
and alternatives. 79, 352 pg. [Item#CM-L005]
<P>
</UL>
<H3>
<A Name="Renewable">
RENEWABLE ENERGY
</A></H3>
<UL>
<P>
<LI>
Renewable Energy Sourcebook: A Primer for Action (Section I) - A 
state-by-state study of renewable energy use, resource potential, 
policies, programs, and utility activities.  Each state profile contains 
data for oil, coal, nuclear, natural gas, municipal solid waste, biomass, 
direct-use geothermal, geothermal electric, geothermal heat pumps, solar 
thermal electric, solar hot water, photovoltaics, and wind.  States are 
nationally ranked and contain detailed graphs and charts.  4/95, approx. 
300 pages. [Item#CM-L040]  Single 
State Renewable Energy Profiles are also available
(please specify state). 
 [Item#CM-L040a]
<P>
<LI>
Power Surge - Provides a pioneering review of the status and near-term 
potential of renewable energy technologies which already provide 8% of 
U.S. energy needs at costs competitive with oil, coal and nuclear.  
Includes detailed policy recommendations for doubling that contribution 
by the year 2000 to combat global warming.  1989, 100 pages. 
[Item #CM-L012]
</UL><P>

<H3>
<A Name="NukeWaste">
NUCLEAR WASTE
</A></H3>
<P><UL>
<LI>
Nuclear Legacy: An Overview of the Places, Problems and Politics of 
Radioactive Waste in the United States - Provides a comprehensive, 
state-by-state analysis of the amounts, radioactivity levels and types of 
radioactive waste from nuclear power plants and other nuclear facilities. 
 Reviews the health impacts and the failure of government disposal 
efforts along with transportation problems.  1989, 170 pages.  
[Item #CM-L029]
<P>
<LI>
High-level Radioactive Waste: Moving It Around Will Not Solve the 
Problem 
- Public Citizens testimony to the U.S. Senate Committee on Energy and 
Natural Resources on proposals to amend the Nuclear Waste Policy Act.  
Public Citizen opposes efforts to weaken environmental standards and 
force an unnecessary nuclear waste dump upon the state of Nevada.  A dump 
in Nevada would open the door to transportation of highly toxic nuclear 
waste on an unprecedented scale.  3/95, 10 pages.  [Item #CM-L038]
<P></UL>
<H3>
<A Name="Directories">
DIRECTORIES
</A></H3>
<P><UL>
<LI>
The Renewable Source:  A National Directory of Resources, Contacts, and 
Companies - A state-by-state listing of 2200 advocacy, business, 
government, research, trade, and utility organizations working with 
renewable energy systems and policies.  All entries include a contact 
name, address and phone number.  Most have short descriptions and fax 
numbers.  Some even include internet addresses.  Entries are indexed by 
contact person, organization, category and technology. 8/94, 234 pages. 
[Item #CM-L032]  Available on IBM (DBF or ASCII) or Mac (tab 
delimited text) diskette.  [Item #CM-L032a] for PC-compatible. 
[Item #CM-L032b] for Macintosh.
<P>
<LI>
National Directory Of Safe Energy Organizations (8th Edition) - Contains 
over 1100 records of citizens groups working in nuclear power, 
radioactive wastes, energy efficiency, and renewable energy issues. All 
entries include names of primary contact people, and addresses.  Most 
include phone and fax numbers.  Several also offer internet addresses.  
Entries categorized by state and organization name. 9/94, 80 pg. 
[Item #CM-L033]  Available on IBM (DBF or ASCII) or Mac (tab delimited 
text) diskette.  [Item #CM-L033a] for PC-compatible, [Item 
#CM-L033b] for Mac.
<P></UL>
<H3>
<A Name="Motor">
MOTOR VEHICLES & FUEL
</A></H3>
<UL><P>
<LI>
The Green Buyers Car Book:  Environmental Ratings of 1994 Cars and Light 
Trucks - The first-ever environmental ratings of motor vehicles.  Ranks 
over 900 cars and light trucks on their contributions to smog, global 
warming, oil spills, ozone depletion, and solid waste.  Describes how 
vehicles contribute to these ecological problems, and recommends ways of 
reducing environmental damage they cause. 8/94, 200 pg. [Item 
#CM-L030]
<P>
<LI>
The Green Buyers Car Guide:  Environmental Ratings of 1994 Cars and 
Light 
Trucks - A condensed version of the Green Buyers Car Book.  Includes 
overall environmental ratings of over 900 models, along with brief 
descriptions of the environmental hazards caused by motor vehicles. 8/94, 
52 pages.  [Item #CM-L031]
<P>
<LI>
Fueling the Public - Explains how the oil industry is misleading the 
public into wasting billions of dollars yearly on unneeded premium 
gasoline and gasoline with mislabeled octane.  Shows how federal agencies 
have not protected consumers from these problems.  8/92, 60 pages. 
 [Item #CM-L014]
<P>
<LI>
Twenty Years After The Embargo: The Costs of U.S. Oil Dependence and How 
They Can Be Reduced - Explains how U.S. dependence on imported oil is 
greater now than it was during the 1973 oil embargo.  Demonstrates that 
this dependence has serious economic and environmental consequences and 
outlines effective solutions for reducing oil consumption and making the 
U.S. more energy independent. 10/93, 44 pages. [Item #CM-L008]
</UL>
<P> 
Orders must be prepaid.  Please include $4.00 for 
shipping and handling for the first item, plus $1.00 for each additional
item.
