Date: Mon, 10 Feb 1997 23:39:44 GMT
Server: NCSA/1.5.2
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<HTML><BODY>
<H3>
KEEP NUCLEAR WASTE OFF THE ROAD;  OPPOSE H.R. 1020
</H3><P>
     Is nuclear waste coming to your community?  If the nuclear
industry gets its way, citizens in 43 states could host thousands
of tons of high-level nuclear waste on a journey to Nevada.
<P>     Since 1987, Yucca Mountain in Nevada has been targeted as
the final home for the nation's irradiated nuclear fuel.  The
Department of Energy's program to study the site has been beset
by poor management and cost overruns and continues in the face of
vigorous state opposition and mounting evidence that the site may
be unsuitable. A nuclear waste repository, once expected by 1998
will not be available until 2010, at the earliest.
<P>     Nuclear utilities have generated approximately 30,000 metric
tons of high-level nuclear waste.  Having produced so much of
some of the deadliest materials ever created, they are now
appealing to the government to take out their garbage for them.
<P>     The House of Representatives will soon consider legislation to
do just that.  The industry-backed 
Nuclear Waste Policy Act of 1995, H.R. 1020, would force the construction
of an unneeded and unwanted "interim" storage facility in Nevada,
overriding current law that forbids placing such a facility in
Nevada.   This prohibition is important to ensuring the integrity
of site suitability studies at Yucca Mountain lest any
"temporary" site become a de facto permanent repository.  The
interim site would not, however, have the performance
expectations of a repository.
<P>     There is no substantive rationale for moving high-level
nuclear waste to a centralized interim site.  No risk assessment
or cost-benefit analysis has been conducted that justifies the
hazards and expense of such a project.  While the nuclear
industry claims that centralized storage reduces high-level waste
sites from 109 to one, every operating reactor will remain a
high-level waste site so long as it continues to split atoms. 
Nuclear utilities want to move the waste out of their backyards
purely for political and public relations reasons. 
<P>
H.R. 1020 would also:    
<P>               
-eliminate repository site suitability standards<BR> 
-establish a repository radiation exposure standard that poses a
lifetime risk of one cancer death for every 285 exposed individuals<BR> 
-carve holes in the National Environmental Policy Act<BR>
-forbid the Environmental Protection Agency from issuing<BR>
radiation release standards<BR>
-allow the preemption of Nevada state law<BR>
-establish unforgiving deadlines that may compromise program
safety<BR>
-order the DOE to begin interim storage construction without
Nuclear Regulatory Commission approval<P>

     If H.R. 1020 passes, transportation of high-level
radioactive waste will commence on a scale unprecedented in human
history.  Over 95 percent of the nation's waste radioactivity is
contained within these materials.  The increased number of
shipments, coupled with the length of the journey (most reactors
are east of the Mississippi River) will raise the likelihood of
transportation accidents involving radioactive waste.  Cask
safety standards fail to incorporate the full range of trauma to
which a cask may be exposed in an accident, and regulations do
not require testing of full-scale models to ensure compliance.  
<P>
What you can do:
<P>
Write or call Representative and urge her or him to:
<P>   
     -oppose H.R. 1020 and any other bill that would weaken
environmental standards or force construction of an unneeded
"interim" storage facility
<P>     
     -support legislation to institute a comprehensive
independent review of the nation's nuclear waste policy. 
<P>
For more information, contact Michael Grynberg at (202)546-4996; email 
grynberg@citizen.org
</BODY></HTML>
