</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="#FFFFFF">

<P>
<H3>
NUCLEAR REGULATORY COMMISSION - 10 CFR Part 50
</H3>
<P><BR>
<H2><U><B><center>COMMENTS OF IPALCO ENTERPRISES, INC., CITIZENS ACTION 
COALITION OF INDIANA, INC., AND PUBLIC CITIZEN, INC.</center></B></U></H2>

<BR>
<H4><A HREF="ipalco-newrel.html">News 
Release</A></H4> <HR>
<BR>
<P>
<H3>I. <U>Identification of Commentors and Their Interest in this
Matter</U>.<H3>
<P>
<H4>
IPALCO Enterprises, Inc. (&quot;IPALCO&quot;), the Citizens Action
Coalition of Indiana, Inc. (&quot;CAC&quot;) and Public Citizen,
Inc. (&quot;Public Citizen&quot;), jointly submit these comments
on the Nuclear Regulatory Commission's (&quot;NRC&quot; or 
&quot;Commission&quot;)
proposed policy statement regarding the impact of competition
and electric utility industry restructuring on its power reactor
licensees.
<P>
IPALCO is a multi-state energy company providing a variety of
energy products and services. IPALCO's principal subsidiary, Indianapolis
Power &amp; Light Company, provides retail and wholesale electric,
steam and other energy services primarily in the area in and around
Indianapolis, Indiana. CAC is an Indiana not-for-profit corporation
which represents the interest of consumers in utility matters
and is also actively involved in environmental protection issues
in Indiana and throughout the United States. Public Citizen is
a non-profit research, lobbying and litigation organization based
in Washington, D.C., which advocates for consumer protection and
for government and corporate accountability, and is supported
by members throughout the United States. None of the commentors
herein are power reactor licensees or have any proprietary interest
in power reactor licensees of the NRC.
<P>
IPALCO, CAC and Public Citizen have been actively involved in
the ongoing national debate and proceedings with reference to
electric utility industry restructuring
<A HREF="#footnote1"><SUP>1</SUP></A>. They support national
efforts to bring full, fair and sustainable competition to the
electric utility industry in a manner which will be beneficial
to all energy consumers while protecting and promoting public
health, safety and the environment. <BR>
<P></H4>
<H3>II. <U>Summary Position of Commentors</U>.</H3>
<P><H4>
The Commission's Draft Policy Statement (&quot;DPS&quot;) is a
necessary and timely effort. The Commission is commended for its
willingness to confront the serious and potentially dramatic effects
on its licensees of the transition to a more competitive electric
utility industry. The Commission's concerns as expressed in the
DPS are legitimate, and prompt regulatory action will be required
to ensure adequate protection of the public health, safety and
environment.
<P>
The NRC should acknowledge certain principles and consider specific
proposals. First, the current &quot;fund as you go&quot; exemption
for regulated public utility licensees' decommissioning funding
is untenable. In a restructured and competitive industry, adequate
funding should be assured in advance. Second, the Commission should
immediately require, by rule or order, that all funds received
by any licensee for so-called &quot;stranded cost&quot; recoveries
are first applied to fully fund that licensee's external decommissioning
trust fund. Third, licensee decommissioning funds collected to
date that remain in so-called &quot;internal funds&quot; of the
licensee-utility should be immediately converted into independent,
external trust funds. Fourth, incremental decommissioning cost
estimates should be required to be fully analyzed and revised
as appropriate, particularly in the context of revising procedures
to facilitate early retirement of uneconomic licensee reactors.
Finally, the NRC should request of Congress additional inspection
and compliance resources for the daunting tasks associated with
regulating its licensees in an increasingly competitive industry.
<P>
As good policy, the Commission's actions should not be directed
toward frustrating the electric industry's movement toward competition,
nor should the Commission allow its regulatory regime to promote
special protections, subsidies or other competitive advantages
to its licensees which are injurious to competition, consumers
and competitors. The Commission will increasingly become involved
in the ongoing national debate on restructuring. In this debate,
the Commission must take a principled policy position. Licensees
with questionable financial ability to sustain safe operations
in a competitive environment should be promptly shut-down and
decommissioning completed. They should not be propped-up by direct
or indirect subsidies.
<P></H4>
<H3>III. <U>The Economics of Restructuring and Nuclear Power</U>.</H3>
<P><H4>
Much discussion has already occurred concerning the effects industry
restructuring may have on the segment of the electric utility
business owning nuclear generating stations. The percentage of
generation in the United States provided from nuclear power has
oscillated between 21% and 22% since 1990. While nuclear power
thus represents a substantial source of electrical energy today,
a significant percentage of existing nuclear power plants could
be replaced by much lower cost alternatives in a relatively short
period of time. Indeed, recent proceedings by the Federal Energy
Regulatory Commission (&quot;FERC&quot;) which address the so-called
&quot;stranded cost&quot; problem emphasize this economic reality
<A HREF=#footnote2><SUP>2</SUP></A>.
<P>
The extent to which existing investment in nuclear power plants
exceeds the current cost to replace their output using modern
technology is substantial. Such potentially stranded costs represent
the lion's share of the total electric utility industry stranded
costs estimated to range from $50 to $300 billion <A HREF=#footnote3>
<SUP>3</SUP></A>. Even Commission
licensees assert that &quot;the financial integrity of some utilities
may be jeopardized&quot; <A HREF=#footnote4><SUP>4</SUP></A>
 by the failure to fully recover stranded
costs.
<P>
Regardless of the uncertainty created by stranded sunk capital
costs, many licensees will be required to compete on the basis
of forward operating costs <A HREF=#footnote5><SUP>5</SUP></A>
 in a competitive environment. Despite
recent relative improvements in some licensees' operating costs,
many licensees may not be competitively viable on this basis alone.
For example, if 2.4&#162; per kWh proves to be the competitive
benchmark for production costs, <A HREF=#footnote6><SUP>6</SUP></A>
 then 34 of 109 utility-owned commercial
power reactors would not be economically viable based on their
production costs during 1993 through 1995. <A HREF=#footnote7>
<SUP>7</SUP></A> By comparison, if the
competitive benchmark is only 2.0&#162; per kWh, then 55 reactors,
or approximately one-half of the total, would not be economically
viable given their reported production costs between 1993 and
1995. Perhaps most notable of all, 30 of the 55 reactors that
fail the test for financial viability at 2&#162; per kWh had capacity
factors greater than 70% during the relevant period. <A HREF=#footnote8>
<SUP>8</SUP></A> Even the
most zealous advocates of nuclear power appear to concede that
many licensees will be competitively viable power sellers only
if full stranded cost recovery and substantial license extensions
occur. <A HREF=#footnote9><SUP>9</SUP></A>
<P>
A recent Moody's report places 47 of 65 nuclear utilities evaluated
into the &quot;significant risk&quot; category and states:
<P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>Many nuclear operating utilities are among the group least likely
to avoid a deterioration in credit quality as competition unfolds.
Notwithstanding the progress that many of these utilities have
made in lowering non-fuel operating and maintenance expense, interest,
and property taxes, the cash costs tied to nuclear power production
remain high and may not be recoverable in the rates dictated by
an open market. . . .[O]n average, non-fuel operating and maintenance
costs (fixed charges) associated with the generation of nuclear
power (expressed in dollars per kilowatt) are greater than those
relating to fossil fueled or hydro power by wide multiples. Likewise,
. . . sunk costs, which are non-cash in nature and relate to recovery
of past capital expenditures, are substantially greater on a dollar
per kilowatt basis for nuclear plants than for other types, reflecting
the high initial costs of constructing nuclear capacity.
<A HREF=#footnote10><SUP>10</SUP></A></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
Since April 1993, Moody's has downgraded the bond ratings of 24
nuclear utilities, some more than once. <A HREF=#footnote11><SUP>11</SUP></A>
<P>
As the industry is restructured, the continued viability of many
nuclear plants becomes increasingly questionable. Under the existing
monopoly system, captive customers subsidize the high capital
costs or high operating costs, or both, of such plants through
electricity prices that far exceed the current long-run marginal
cost of producing power. Some proposals to restructure the electric
utility industry, including Order 888, explicitly acknowledge
and seek to preserve these subsidies in the name of &quot;stranded
cost&quot; protection. Other proposals do not.
<P>
If national retail competition occurs without stranded cost subsidies,
one group of existing nuclear power plants, those with low sunk
capital costs, low operating costs and limited incremental capital
requirements, will either be largely unaffected or increasingly
profitable. A second group of nuclear power plants, those with
low operating costs, but high sunk capital costs, will continue
operating, albeit with an accounting write-down of the value of
such plants and less financial assurance of the ability to perform
necessary tasks affecting the public health, safety and environment
like decommissioning.
<P>
A third group of nuclear power plants will, of necessity, cease
operations. This group includes those plants with operating costs
that will exceed the market price of power for a sustained period
of time and plants which, despite low operating costs, confront
the need for major, incremental capital expenditures for projects
like re-sleeving cracked steam tubes and replacing steam generators.
In this regard, Moody's reported:
<P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>In the August 1995 Special Comment <I>Stranded Costs Will 
Threaten
Credit Quality of U.S. Electrics</I>, Moody's first reported the
belief that there are at least 10 nuclear plants (out of 110 in
the U.S.) that might be closed for economic reasons if the generation
of electric power is completely deregulated. The propensity for
certain nuclear plants to require expensive capital additions
to comply with the standards of their Nuclear Regulatory Commission
(NRC) operating license increases the likelihood that the number
of early shutdowns might be even greater than those 10 originally
identified. <A HREF=#footnote12><SUP>12</SUP></A></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
As these plants cease operation, they cease producing spent fuel
and other waste streams that require storage, transportation and
disposal. Once these non-viable plants cease operation, a national
plan for the prompt decommissioning of these plants must be confronted.
<P></H4>
<H3>IV. <U>Specific Issues to be Addressed and Regulatory Action 
Required</U>.</H3>
<P><H4>
The plain fact that many licensees' investments in nuclear power
plants are uneconomic and sunk costs will not be recoverable in
a competitive environment has numerous implications. Many of the
most immediate and significant issues concern the inevitable 
&quot;back-end&quot;
costs of the nuclear cycle associated with decommissioning and
waste disposal. Indeed, numerous licensees argued at the FERC
that proposed stranded cost recovery provisions were <I>inadequate</I>
to assure decommission funding. <A HREF=#footnote13><SUP>13</SUP></A>
 Notably, none of the utility proposals
presented, which continue the huge cash flows that both the current
monopoly system and stranded cost protection produce for these
plants, suggest that stranded cost &quot;lost revenues&quot; that
are recovered through these regulatory schemes should be <I>dedicated</I>
to the necessary tasks of decommissioning and waste disposal.
Other issues which need to be addressed relate primarily to assuring
adequate resources are available to the Commission during a period
of necessary increased activity.
<P>
Certain specific proposals should be considered by the Commission.
First, as the DPS acknowledges, since monopoly protection will
no longer assure licensees of recovering all costs or maintaining
financial viability, the current requirements for financial assurance
by a licensee, particularly with reference to funding decommissioning,
require revision. The current &quot;fund as you go&quot; exemption
for regulated public utility licensees' decommissioning funding
is untenable because monopoly protection is neither desirable
nor likely to continue until all licenses expire and plants are
decommissioned.
<P>
The Commission's decommissioning requirements are designed to
ensure protection of the public health, safety and environment
by (1) requiring licensees to maintain adequate funds to safely
remove their plants from service and decontaminate and decommission
the radiological portions of their facilities, and (2) ensuring
that residual radioactivity at the site resulting from a plant's
operation meets stringent radiological criteria. Specifically,
10 C.F.R. &#167;50.33 requires holders of operating licenses to
provide reasonable assurance that they have sufficient funds available
to decommission their plants. In addition, 10 C.F.R. &#167;50.75
requires the submission of a decommissioning report containing
a certification that a specified level of funding will be provided.
<P>
Citing pro-nuclear industry sources, the average per unit decommissioning
cost estimate (in 1994 dollars) is in the range of $300-$400 million.
<A HREF=#footnote14><SUP>14</SUP></A>
For the nuclear power plants, this yields a future liability on
the order of $35 to $40 billion, across the industry. Because
funding for this future liability is currently accumulated over
the life of the generating plants, the amount that has been collected
to date by the industry is only approximately $6 billion. 
<A HREF=#footnote15><SUP>15</SUP></A> Clearly,
in a restructured and competitive industry, adequate funding must
be assured in advance. There is no continued justification for
the &quot;fund as you go&quot; approach.
<P>
Second, prompted by Order 888 and competitive pressures, many
licensees are now seeking from utility regulators the ability
to recover their stranded sunk capital costs during the transition
to full competition. Such stranded cost recovery schemes go by
various names, including &quot;transition costs,&quot; &quot;wires
charges&quot; and &quot;exit fees.&quot; The use of cash flows
received by licensees from such stranded cost recovery schemes
is currently unrestrained. In essence, a licensee can get the
money and leave town with it, or more appropriately leave the
country, primarily by investing in foreign ventures. During the
last two years at least five nuclear electric utilities that have
been identified as having significant &quot;stranded costs,&quot;
have participated in overseas merger or acquisition transactions
involving approximately $7.5 billion. <A HREF=#footnote16><SUP>16
</SUP></A> The Commission should immediately
require of all licensees that all funds received by any licensee
from such stranded cost recovery first be applied to fully fund
the licensee's external decommissioning trust fund.
<P>
Third, a significant fraction of some licensee decommissioning
funds collected to date remain in so-called &quot;internal funds&quot;
of the licensee-utility. <A HREF=#footnote17><SUP>17</SUP></A>
The future availability of actual funds
for decommissioning from such internal funds is inherently dependent
on the continued financial viability of the licensee in an increasingly
uncertain competitive environment. In requiring full prefunding,
the Commission should also require all such internal funds be
immediately converted to independent, external trust funds.
<P>
Fourth, decommissioning cost estimates may require revision in
numerous respects. For example, the cost estimates used to establish
the level of funding needed should not assume any ongoing administrative
and general support from the licensees. To assure adequate decommissioning
funding regardless of the then-financial status of a competitive
licensee, the amount of decommissioning costs to be prefunded
in the external trust should be the cost of an independent third
party to perform all necessary decommissioning tasks, including
administrative and general support.
<P>
Similarly, because of the increased likelihood of early licensee
retirement of nuclear power plants in a competitive environment,
and to assure that the lack of cost-effective and fair procedures
for early retirement do not frustrate or delay otherwise economically
rational decisions to retire a plant, the Commission should promptly
review its procedural and substantive requirements for early licensee
termination and decommissioning. Among the many considerations
in this regard would be investigation and data gathering on a
decommissioning cost estimate credit associated with a voluntary
commitment to early retirement. Such a &quot;credit,&quot; or
reduction in the decommissioning prefunding requirement, should
be equal to the estimated incremental decommissioning costs that
will be avoided by a commitment to early retirement.
<A HREF=#footnote18><SUP>18</SUP></A>
<P>
It is important to recognize that some decommissioning costs are
&quot;fixed,&quot; in the sense that an obligation to incur them
at a future date is determined by an initial decision to operate
the plant. Generally, the total radioactivity inventory of a nuclear
power plant builds up very quickly during the first few years
of operation, and then tends to level off.
<P>
On the other hand, there will be some incremental costs associated
with any changes in scope of decommissioning activities, caused
by continued operation, even after the first few years. 
<A HREF=#footnote19><SUP>19</SUP></A> For example,
the total radioactivity is dominated by that built up in the reactor
vessel and internals, and that is dominated by Cobalt 60, which
has a relatively short half-life (5 years). <A HREF=#footnote20>
<SUP>20</SUP></A> The more problematic
isotopes may be those such as Nickel 59 (half-life of 80,000 years)
and Niobium 94 (half-life of 20,000 years). <A HREF=#footnote21><SUP>
21</SUP></A> These levels of radioactivity
build up linearly with plant operation. In reality, whenever deferred
dismantlement is a likely scenario, the longer-life isotopes will
play a more prominent role in the overall inventory at the time
of dismantlement. Also, if continued operation results in unexpected
contamination of certain components and structures, the additional
tasks associated with packaging and burial will increase decommissioning
costs.
<P>
Another area in which decommissioning costs may be incrementally
increased by plant operation relates to equipment additions and
replacement. As previously discussed, the costs of such incremental
capital additions to nuclear plants have been considerable. The
cost of decommissioning the added equipment has generally been
ignored. In one case, the cost for decommissioning just three
years of added equipment at one plant was estimated at about $10
million in 1985 dollars. <A HREF=#footnote22><SUP>22</SUP></A>
 Over a full plant operating license period,
the amount of equipment added and replaced can be considerable.
Steam generator replacement, for example, can add considerably
to decommissioning costs. In sum, the issue of incremental decommissioning
costs must be fully analyzed.
<P>
Finally, the NRC should be aware that the pressures of a competitive
environment on uneconomic licensees could motivate underfunding
necessary operating requirements, deferring maintenance, reducing
staffing below acceptable levels, <A HREF=#footnote23><SUP>23</SUP>
</A>  or engaging in corporate reorganization
or mergers to &quot;isolate&quot; nuclear costs. <A HREF=#footnote24>
<SUP>24</SUP></A> Given the unique
public health, safety and environmental effects of the licensees'
operations, the NRC should evaluate its own internal needs for
additional inspection and compliance resources, and seek additional
resources needed for the daunting tasks ahead.
<P></H4>
<H3>V. <U>Avoiding Anti-Competitive Effects in Licensee Regulation</U>.</H3>
<P><H4>
A broad concern involves Commission policy regarding the inherent
unsustainability of continued subsidization of its licensees during
industry restructuring. The commercial nuclear power industry
in the U.S. is one of the most heavily subsidized industrial segments
in the world. <A HREF=#footnote25><SUP>25</SUP></A>
 Whether it is long-standing legislative subsidies
like the Price-Anderson Act of 1957 or the new regulatory 
&quot;super-subsidies,&quot;
such as stranded cost surcharges and transition exit fees, the
advent of full, fair and sustainable competition will of necessity
require stripping away all of these subsidies. As Commission licensees
attempt to &quot;have thebest of both worlds&quot; -- the massive
subsidies of the current monopoly system and the anti-competitive
advantages those same subsidies would confer in an unregulated
marketplace -- the Commission will increasingly become involved
in the ongoing national debate on restructuring. Already some
licensees are urging economic regulators and policymakers to provide
continuing subsidies because &quot;the nuclear industry developed
as it did, in large part, as a result of government policies and
regulation.&quot; <A HREF=#footnote26><SUP>26</SUP></A>
 In this debate, the Commission must take a principled
policy position. Licensees with questionable financial ability
to sustain safe operations in a competitive environment should
be promptly shut-down and decommissioning completed. They should
not be propped-up by direct or indirect subsidies. To the extent
the DPS suggests otherwise in Section IV (A), it should be revised.
<P>
The Commission's actions should not be directed toward frustrating
the electric industries' movement toward competition, nor should
the Commission allow its regulatory regime to promote special
protections, subsidies or other competitive advantages to its
licensees which are injurious to competition, consumers and competitors.
The Commission should assure, to the maximum extent practicable,
that all costs associated with the operation and retirement of
its licensees' facilities, which cannot be recovered by competitively-priced
electric service, are borne by the licensees and that the U.S.
taxpayers and energy consumers are held harmless for such costs.</H4>
<BR>
