Industry Views on Issues Raised by the Public Interest Blueprint<p>

<center>_________________________________________________________
_______<p>
<i>A Public Interest Blueprint for Electricity
Restructuring</b></i><p>

</center>
<p>

Competition in the electric power industry could either usher in
a new era of cleaner, more affordable energy
services or prove to be the biggest consumer shakedown of our
time.  Americans consider electricity service to be a
basic commodity, making the stakes high and the consequences
potentially very severe.<b>   <p>

<p>

</b>With this nation on the verge of a historic transformation in
the way it generates, transmits and sells electricity, the
interests of average consumers must be fully represented in
efforts to write the new rules that will govern
competition.<b>  Power for the People</b> outlines a
comprehensive vision for restructuring the electric utility
industry to
benefit consumers and the environment while encouraging free and
fair competition.  Designed for implementation at
the state level, the blueprint proposes a variety of policy
mechanisms on issues that affect all Americans.<p>

<p>

Proposals to introduce competition into electricity markets pose
new challenges to regulators and elected officials. 
Bad public policy choices could seriously harm consumers in their
pocketbooks and in the quality of their
environment.  Specifically, possible outcomes of restructuring
include:<p>

<p>

     *    higher bills for small business and residential
consumers while large consumers receive discounts.<p>

     *    degraded environmental quality through increased use of
dirty plants and fossil fuels.<p>

     *    elimination of energy efficiency programs.<p>

     *    little or no development of renewable energy
technologies.<p>

     *    discrimination against low-income and rural
customers.<p>

     *    companies taking advantage of consumers through abusive
marketing and business practices.<p>

     *    unregulated monopoly utilities able to stifle
competition and increase profits.  <p>

     *    bailing out inefficient, high-cost utilities to reward
shareholders for bad business decisions.<p>

<p>

In order to prevent these outcomes from occurring and ensure that
benefits accrue to all classes of consumers, the
blueprint proposes that states do the following:<p>

<p>

     *    grant no recovery of costs for uneconomical utility
assets except in special circumstances.<p>

     *    break up vertically integrated utility monopolies by
requiring divestiture of assets.<p>

     *    create an independent energy agency to administer and
oversee energy efficiency, low-income, universal<p>

          service and research &amp; development programs.<p>

     *    aggressively promote an array of energy efficiency
programs funded by a system benefits charge.<p>

     *    guarantee universal service and bill assistance to
low-income and rural consumers.<p>

     *    increase the use of cleaner energy by requiring all
electric service providers to certify that a percentage          
     of their energy comes from renewable technologies.<p>

     *    enact standards on fossil fuel plants ensuring that the
emissions of hazardous pollutants decreases.<p>

<p>

These issues must be addressed prior to the introduction of
competition and cannot be solved simply by hoping that
the free market will provide equitable solutions.  All markets
exist within a regulatory and policy framework that
encourages certain types of business behavior.  If a new utility
structure provides the wrong incentives to
participants, the outcome could reward wasteful energy
consumption, promote the use of dirty generation sources,
allow one company to dominate a given market, and make it more
difficult for low-income and rural consumers to
meet their basic energy needs.  State legislatures and regulatory
commissions must aggressively engage these issues
and devise rules that facilitate competition and serve the public
interest.<p>

<p>

Consumer and environmental groups seek the creation of a safe,
affordable and sustainable energy system.  To that
end, <b>Power for the People</b> offers a vision and roadmap for
progressing towards a competitive market that includes
minimum standards, structural mechanisms for delivering basic
services, protections against market
power abuses
and assurances that small customers will be the first to see any
benefits.<p>

__________________________________________________<p>

<center><b>PUBLIC INTEREST BLUEPRINT FOR ELECTRICITY
RESTRUCTURING<p>

<i><a name="Principles and Summary">Principles and
Summary</a></i><p>

</center>
<p>

<p>

CONSUMER PROTECTION<p>

</b>The entrance of many new companies into electricity markets
creates the potential for fraud, deceptive marketing
and abuse of market power.  Consumers
must be protected against unfair business practices and be
assured that
sellers of electricity are not discriminatory or dishonest. 
Informed consumer choices will only be possible if
there is full disclosure of each company's resource portfolio and
environmental impacts.  States must also
aggressively monitor compliance with all consumer protection
laws.  If not already in existence, an independent
Citizen Utility Board should be established to advocate on behalf
of small business and residential electricity
consumers. <p>

<p>

<b>COST SHIFTING</b><p>

Utility restructuring should not result in a widening gap between
the rates paid by small and large consumers of
electricity.  Unless the benefits of competition are delivered
equally to all customer classes, a disproportionate cost
burden will fall to average citizens and ratepayers.  Under no
circumstance should any consumer on the utility
system be allowed to escape responsibility for supporting
reasonable low-income, renewable energy, R&amp;D and
energy efficiency programs.  <p>

<p>

<b>CREATION OF AN INDEPENDENT ENERGY AGENCY</b><p>

Ensuring independent oversight and administration of energy
efficiency, renewable energy, low-income and R&amp;D
programs will require the creation of an independent non-profit
or government agency.  This agency will
coordinate and adopt measures to ensure that all monies collected
from the electricity system are disbursed through
competitive bidding, effectively spent and directed to
high-priority programs that serve the public interest.  Since
allowing an existing utility to administer public funds for
energy services creates an inherent conflict of interest,
this agency must not be owned, operated or directed by an
existing utility or any other company conducting
business within the state's electricity sector.<p>

<p>

<b>DIVESTITURE OF UTILITY ASSETS</b><p>

Past monopoly status must not confer competitive advantages to
utilities or their subsidiaries.  Fair and free
competition will be impossible if one entity maintains monopoly
ownership over all aspects of the utility system. 
Requiring a distribution of assets among independent companies
will enhance competition and protect consumers
from the potential abuses of monopoly control.  In order to
protect against such abuses, utilities must separate their
generation, transmission and distribution assets into distinct
and unaffiliated corporate entities.<p>

<p>

<b>ENERGY EFFICIENCY<p>

</b>The aggressive pursuit of energy efficiency must not be
compromised by the switch to competitive electricity
markets.  Energy efficiency provides significant economic savings
and pollution prevention benefits that are not
sufficiently valued.  To ensure that efficiency receives priority
in a competitive system, funds should be collected
through a nonbypassable system
benefits charge and disbursed by the Independent Energy
Agency.  Total funding
must support an increase in activity over pre-competition
efficiency efforts.  In addition, state-guaranteed access to
below-market loans for efficiency improvements would help
consumers afford capital investments that yield energy
and financial savings over time.<p>

<p>

<b><p>

ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION<p>

</b>Restructuring poses serious threats to environmental quality
that must be addressed prior to the implementation of
changes.  Competition must produce improvements in environmental
quality.  States should consider a range of
mechanisms to achieve net reductions in air, liquid and solid
waste emissions, including a requirement that all
generators meet federal and state environmental standards applied
to new plants or demonstrate that equivalent
emissions reductions have been achieved at other plants within
the state.  Furthermore, all fossil and nuclear
generators should be subject to fees based on emissions and waste
generation.  <p>

<p>

<b>RENEWABLE ENERGY</b><p>

Increased reliance on renewable energy must be a priority for any
restructured system given the considerable
environmental and economic benefits that accrue from its use. 
Since the value of renewables is not accurately
reflected in conventional pricing, states must adopt strong
structural measures that harness competitive forces and
guarantee a minimum level of resource diversity.  A renewables portfolio
standard, applied to all retail suppliers
of electricity, should be used to increase resource diversity
from current levels.  The pro-competitive nature of a
portfolio standard will result in low-cost renewables that
benefit all consumers and the environment.  Issues
relating to distributed generation, system reliability, off-grid
customers, renewables project financing and self-generation must
also be addressed.<p>

<p>

<b>RESEARCH &amp; DEVELOPMENT</b><p>

As utilities, industry and the federal government cut back on
research and development efforts, states must ensure
that adequate support is available to develop and deploy new
technologies that increase transmission and
distribution efficiency, enable distributed generation and reduce
or prevent pollution.  A system
benefits charge
should fund R&amp;D efforts administered by the Independent
Energy Agency.<p>

<p>

<b>RETAIL COMPETITION<p>

</b>This blueprint does not constitute an endorsement of retail
competition.  Unresolved issues could dramatically
affect the benefits retail competition offers to small business
and residential consumers.  If, however, a state
chooses to enact retail competition, it must mitigate the most
harmful potential consequences to consumers by
ensuring that methods of meaningful customer access and
aggregation are available.  In addition, small business
and residential consumers should be able to take advantage of
retail competition at the same time as large
consumers without any barriers to full participation.<p>

<p>

<b>STRANDED COSTS<p>

</b>The transition to a competitive market must offer concrete
savings to all consumers.  Granting full utility recovery
of stranded costs would saddle ratepayers with an unprecedented
burden that precludes many from realizing any
near-term benefits from restructuring.  Utility profits have
historically reflected the assumed risk of investments in
assets that could be rendered superfluous over time.  Relieving
utilities of liability for their bad decisions would
penalize efficient utilities and consumers.  The full burden of
covering the costs for uneconomical assets should fall
upon utility shareholders unless there is conclusive proof that
state regulators, over strenuous utility objections,
required a specific investment or that the decision to build a
stranded asset was, in hindsight, the least-cost option
available to the utility.  Furthermore, cost recovery should not
include anticipated profits, lost
revenues, expenses
or liabilities associated with future operations.  Any recovery
must also be balanced against all undervalued assets
in the utility system.<p>

<p>

<b>UNIVERSAL SERVICE</b><p>

Competition must bring benefits to all consumers.  Rural and
low-income consumers have the most to lose from
restructuring unless strong protections are enacted that ensure
universal service, access to competing suppliers, bill
assistance, reasonable payment policies, emergency service and
affordable rates.  Furthermore, degraded service
and redlining must be prohibited.  Funding for energy assistance
and universal service must be adequately supported through a nonbypassable 
system charge and low-income consumers should be guaranteed sufficient
weatherization and energy efficiency services.  <p>

______________________________________________________________<p>
To order this entire Blueprint please call (202) 588-1000 and ask for the 
publications department. <P>
For more information contact:<br><p>

Charlie Higley at (202) 546-4996
