<HTML><BODY><PRE>
S. 1936 Vote Results

On Wednesday, the Senate voted 63-37 to pass S. 1936, the Nuclear
Waste Policy Act of 1996.  In passing the measure, nuclear
industry supporters lost three votes from an earlier motion to
break a filibuster against the bill.  The 37 votes against the
bill demonstrates that Congress will sustain President Clinton's
promised veto against the legislation.  A list of how Senators
voted is printed at the end of this message.

What Now?

The bill's supporters now turn to the House of Representatives,
which may or may not elect to consider nuclear waste legislation
this year.  On the whole, the prospects are looking grim for the
industry lobbyists.  If the House adopts the Senate bill as is,
President Clinton's veto will be sustained easily, finishing the
bill once and for all.  If, on the other hand, the House passes a
differing version, the bill will have to go to a House-Senate
conference and be passed by both bodies again before being sent
to the President.  The remaining time on the legislative
calendar, however, is quite short, and the conference process
would give Senators Bryan and Reid the opportunity to launch two
additional filibusters against the bill. 

What you can do.

While there is cause for optimism, we should not breathe
completely easily yet.  The nuclear lobby will no doubt try to
place pressure on both the President and the House over the
August recess, and we need to exert a countervailing force. 
Please call the White House and thank President Clinton for
promising a veto of S. 1936 and tell him to hold firm against
industry pressure.  Then call your Representative and ask him or
her to oppose H.R. 1020, S. 1936's House counterpart, and any
similar legislation.  Also, be sure to thank your Senator(s) who
opposed the bill.

The White House Switchboard number is (202)456-1111; the Capitol
Switchboard number, (202)224-3121.  Direct line and fax numbers
as well as email addresses for Representatives and Senators can
be found on Critical Mass' voting index
(http://www.essential.org/CMEP).

Many thanks to everyone who has worked against the nuclear waste
bills this year.  Your efforts have made a difference.

Finally, as noted in an earlier posting, I am about to leave
Public Citizen for the dubious pleasures of law school.  While
the Senate vote made my exit a little later than planned, this is
my last posting to the CMEP list.  I will maintain my current
email address for some time, but future inquiries on Public
Citizen's work on nuclear waste policy should be directed to Bill
Magavern (magavern@citizen.org).

