************************** JOB ANNOUNCEMENT #1 *****************************

                   RESEARCHER/ADMINISTRATIVE ASSISTANT
              PUBLIC CITIZEN'S CRITICAL MASS ENERGY PROJECT
              *********************************************

Since its founding in 1974, Public Citizen's Critical Mass Energy Project
has been a powerful voice in the movement to decrease reliance on nuclear
and fossil fuels and to promote safe, economical and environmentally sound
energy technologies.  From a Capitol Hill office, Critical Mass prepares
and disseminates reports, lobbies Congress, and acts as a watchdog of key
federal and state energy agencies.  In addition, Critical Mass works
closely with other citizens groups and individuals across the country,
empowering them to participate in important decisions affecting their
health, safety and standard of living. 

RESPONSIBILITIES:
1) Research, write and organize on energy policy.
2) Handle administrative duties for five-person team.
3) Prepare and distribute public education materials and action
   alerts.

REQUIREMENTS:
1) Commitment to the protection of the environment and consumers.
2) Strong research and writing skills.
3) Strong computer skills, including Internet experience.
4) Knowledge of energy issues and the legislative process
   preferred. 
5) General office skills.

SALARY/BENEFITS:
1) Salary in high teens, depending on prior work experience.
2) Opportunity for advancement.
3) Complete medical and dental benefits.
4) Three weeks paid vacation (four weeks after two years); ten
   holidays. 
5) Pension after three years.


TO APPLY:  Send letter, resume and 1-2 page writing sample (no
calls, please) by September 1 to:

                          Bill Magavern, Director
               Public Citizen's Critical Mass Energy Project
                         215 Pennsylvania Ave. SE
                           Washington, DC  20003

Public Citizen is an equal opportunity employer.



************************** JOB ANNOUNCEMENT #2 *****************************

                   NUCLEAR WASTE CITIZENS COALITION
                     ANTI-REPROCESSING COORDINATOR
                   ********************************

The Nuclear Waste Citizens Coalition consists of national and grassroots
organizations focused on various aspects of the nuclear waste problem. 
Our broad coalition includes anti-nuclear power groups, groups opposed to
reprocessing, groups from contaminated Department of Energy weapons sites,
residents of sites targeted for nuclear waste dumps, peace activists, and
national environmental groups.  We are allied to prevent implementation of
flawed nuclear waste programs that would transfer both commercial and
military-related high-level nuclear wastes from one state to another with
little respect for human health and safety and no regard for democratic
principles. 


JOB DESCRIPTION:
1) Work closely with and provide public education resources for a
   nationwide network of citizens organizations, public officials, and 
   researchers;
2) Coordinate activies in Washington, D.C.pertaining to national-level
   developments regarding reprocessing of military or commercial
   nuclear spent fuel or wastes;
3) Coordinate with the Anti-Reprocessing Work Group, the NWCC's D.C.
   Coordinator, and grassroots conference calls;
4) Promote an Independent Review of nuclear waste and reprocessing 
   issues; 
5) Do some media and fundraising work.

REQUIREMENTS:
1) Demonstrated ability to work with grassroots organizations;
2) Experience in coordination and analysis on national issues;
3) Ability to assimilate technical information;
4) Excellent strategy and communication skills;
5) Computer networking, fundraising and international experience
   will be valued.

COMPENSATION:  Flat fee for this self-employed contractor position,
depending on experience, $30,000 to $38,700 per year (contractor pays own
health, SSI, etc.). 

TO APPLY:  Send a letter of interest, resume, writing sample and three
references to: 

Hiring Committee
Nuclear Waste Citizens Coalition
110 Maryland Avenue, NE, Suite 307
Washington, DC 20002

