<HTML><BODY><PRE>
Senate Breaks First Filibuster; Waste Bill Receives Enough No
Votes to Sustain Clinton Veto

The first vote on S. 1936, the Nuclear Waste Policy Act, was like
the proverbial glass of water: half empty or half full, depending
on one's perspective.

Unfortunately, supporters broke the filibuster on the motion to
proceed to the bill (the question of whether the Senate would
consider the legislation) by a 65-34 vote.  The 34 votes,
however, will be enough to sustain the veto of the legislation
promised by President Clinton if cast on final passage.

The next cloture vote, which will be on whether to vote on the
bill itself, is more important.  At the moment, this vote is
expected early next week.

Because this vote was only on the question of whether to consider
the bill, we can hope to pick up a few more opponents of the bill
on the next vote.  Equally, if not more, important is ensuring
that the "No" votes remain firm.  The nuclear utilities will only
increase their pressure in the next few days.  We need, as
always, calls from the grassroots to provide a counterweight to
the industry dollars.

If your Senator supported the filibuster and opposed the bill,
please call and thank him or her for the vote and ask her or him
to continue to vote against the bill.  If your Senator voted for
S. 1936, call to express your disappointment and your expectation
that they will support the Bryan-Reid filibuster on the next
cloture vote and oppose the bill as a whole. 

The Capitol Switchboard number is (202)224-3121.  Direct
line and fax numbers as well as email addresses for Senators can
be found on Critical Mass' voting index
(http://www.essential.org/CMEP).

A record of the vote and Public Citizen's press release follows. 
Keep in mind that this was a vote on whether to debate the bill;
many of those supporting S. 1936 at this stage may not do so in
the future.  In other words we can still get them to our side. 

No on breaking the filibuster (the anti-S. 1936 vote)

Akaka
Baucus
Biden
Bingaman
Boxer
Bryan
Bumpers
Byrd
Campbell
Coats
Conrad
Daschle
