Public Citizen's press release


For Immediate Release         
July 16, 1996
Contact:  Michael Grynberg    (202)546-4996
          Bill Magavern  (202)546-4996

Senate Moves Closer to Passing Anti-Environmental Nuclear Waste
Bill

     The Senate opened a debate on whether to do the nuclear
industry's bidding and ram hazardous waste down the throat of an
unwilling host, voting to break the first of two filibusters on
S. 1936, the Nuclear Waste Policy Act of 1996.

     Industry lobbyists have mounted a well-financed campaign to
slash environmental standards, preempt state law, and force some
of the deadliest materials ever created upon Nevada before
studies are complete on whether Yucca Mountain in the state is a
suitable site for a permanent repository for these materials.

     "It's easy to be an environmentalist when you're worried
about burning rain forests half a world away," Michael Grynberg,
Energy Policy Analyst with Public Citizen, said.  "The true test
is voting your principles when corporate interests in your state
want the opposite.  Today, too many Senators failed that test."  
          
     S. 1936 contains broad preemptions of federal and state
environmental laws.  The measure also forbids the Environmental
Protection Agency from issuing standards to protect citizens from
radiation releases from a repository.  Instead the bill sets a
lax exposure standard that permits four times the radiation of
current storage guidelines and is associated with one excess
cancer death for every 286 exposed individuals. 

     "The nuclear industry seems to be punishing Nevada for its
wise choice to avoid the costs and perils of nuclear power," Bill
Magavern, Director of Public Citizen's Critical Mass Energy
Project, said.  "Apparently, the industry thinks Nevadans can
take more radiation than the rest of us."

     S. 1936 would also require the taxpayer to assume title to
and liability for the deadly garbage that the nuclear industry
chose to create.  By limiting the user fee earmarked for the
nation's disposal program, S. 1936 leaves taxpayers facing a
liability that could reach billions.

     "No one has presented a valid reason to start shipping waste
to Nevada now," Grynberg said, citing the non-partisan Nuclear
Waste Technical Review Board's recommendation to wait on
centralized "interim" storage.  "Using citizen safety and
taxpayer dollars to subsidize the nuclear industry is corporate
welfare of the worst kind." 

For more information contact Michael Grynberg
(grynberg@citizen.org).
</PRE></BODY></HTML>
