<PRE>
May 28, 1996


The Honorable Robert Livingston
Committee on Appropriations
U.S. House of Representatives
2406 Rayburn House Office Building
Washington, DC 20515

Re:  Transit and Amtrak funding

Dear Mr. Chairman:

Public Citizen, a consumer advocacy organization with over
100,000 members, urges you to maintain funding for transit and
Amtrak at the highest possible levels.

Decreased funding for mass transit has a debilitating effect on
the American public.  More than 30 million people rely on public
transportation each day to get to and from work, school, daycare
centers, shopping centers and a host of other destinations vital
to the maintenance of their quality of life.  Public
transportation brings mobility to those citizens who, for
example, cannot afford an automobile, have a disability which
prevents them from driving, are elderly or are under driving age. 
Transit effectively brings the otherwise marginalized into the
mainstream; without it millions of people would be economically
and socially stranded. 

Besides the threat that decreased funding poses to the
individual, two vital national concerns -- environmental quality
and energy security -- are also at stake.  Public transportation
benefits our environment and public health by reducing pollution
in the air we breathe and the water we drink.  It also lessens
our reliance on imported fuel, making America less vulnerable to
oil embargoes and price shocks.  It is a stalwart and necessary
component in our country's energy efficiency effort.

Mass transit and passenger rail provide a valuable public
service.  Fiscal year 1996 budget cuts to these two programs --
accounting for nearly 50% of transportation spending cuts -- were
devastating; more cuts would be disastrous.  This downward trend
must be reversed.  Public Citizen urges you to increase transit
funding and maintain Amtrak operating assistance.


Sincerely,

Bill Magavern, Director
Critical Mass Energy Project
</PRE>
