<HTML>
<BODY>






                              May 9, 1996
<P>
Dear Representative:
<P>
     You may soon vote upon H.R. 558, the Texas Low-Level
Radioactive Waste Disposal Compact.  Last September, the House
voted down the measure by a convincing 243-176 tally.  On behalf
of our nation-wide membership, I urge you to oppose the measure
should it return to the floor.
<P>
     During the prolonged debate on the North American Free Trade
Agreement, considerable attention was paid to environmental
conditions on the U.S.-Mexican border.  While promises of
improving conditions in the region have not been fulfilled by
NAFTA's passage, approval of the Texas compact would create the
potential for a new environmental catastrophe in the area.
<P>
     If the Texas compact passes, a nuclear waste dump will be
constructed in Hudspeth County in a location about 16 miles away
from the Rio Grande river.  The site is seismically active and
could threaten the Rio Grande by permitting the burial of
radioactive waste, mostly generated by the nuclear power
industry, in trenches that only require 100 years of
institutional control.  Many of these "low-level" wastes,
however, will remain toxic far beyond 100 years, thus endangering
future generations.  Building the dump in the border region, an
area which has experienced more than its share of environmental
damage, also violates the 1983 La Paz Agreement with Mexico, in
which the U.S. and Mexico agreed to reduce and eliminate sources
of pollution on their shared border.
<P>
     Many of the Texas compact and dump's problems, such as the
classification of long-lived radionuclides as "low-level" waste,
hamper the nation's nuclear waste policy as a whole.  Rather than
targeting a low-income community on the Mexican border for the
nuclear industry's garbage, Congress should reject H.R. 558 and
implement instead a comprehensive independent review of the
country's nuclear waste policies and practices.  Such a review is
overdue and offers the best opportunity to replace a politically
driven program with a policy based on sound science and citizen
participation.
<P>
                              Sincerely,

<P>
<P>
                              Bill Magavern<BR>
                              Director<BR>
                              Critical Mass Energy Project
</BODY></HTML>␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀
</DOC>
