<HTML><BODY><PRE>
Senate Energy and Natural Resources Committee Passes Interim
Storage, Ward Valley Bills; Ward Valley to Hit Senate Floor as
Early as Next Wednesday

On Wednesday the Senate Energy and Natural Resources Committee
passed both S. 1271, the Nuclear Waste Policy Act of 1996, and S.
1596, the Ward Valley Land Transfer Act.

Ward Valley

S. 1596 was passed by a voice vote and could be voted on by the
full Senate as early as next Wednesday.  Calls are needed to
Senators now in opposition to this anti-environment bill.

-- Tritium testing, recommended by a National Academy of Sciences
panel, is needed to determine whether radioactive wastes dumped
at Ward Valley would leak into the water table and into the
Colorado River, a source of drinking water for millions of
people;
   
-- U.S. Ecology, the dump contractor, should clearly not be
allowed to operate a radioactive waste facility. The company
admits to engaging in illegal dumping at its Nevada site, and has
also left behind heavily contaminated waste dumps at Sheffield,
Illinois, and Maxey Flats, Kentucky;
   
-- As a steward of federal land, the U.S. government should not
give California a site for radioactive waste without conducting a
planned supplemental environmental impact statement covering all
threats to public health and safety, in addition to the impacts
on Native American tribes.

The Capitol Switchboard number is (202)224-3121.  Direct line
numbers and email addresses for committee members can be found on
Critical Mass' voting index (http://www.essential.org/CMEP).


S. 1271

The committee passed S. 1271 on a 12-6 vote.  All of the
committee's Republicans and Senator Howell Heflin voted in favor,
while Senators Daniel Akaka (D-HI), Jeff Bingaman (D-NM), Dale
Bumpers (D-AR), Byron Dorgan (D-ND), Wendell Ford (D-KY), and
Paul Wellstone (D-MN) opposed the measure.  Senator Bill Bradley
(D-NJ) passed as did Bennett Johnston (D-LA), who was upset over
the committee's rejection of an amendment he offered to make S.
1271 more politically palatable.

Senator Wellstone offered amendments designed to lessen the
liability risk S. 1271 poses to the taxpayer, ensure the adequacy
of the nuclear waste fund, and prevent the construction of new
nuclear reactors without disposal capacity for their irradiated
fuel.  None of the amendments were approved. 

Senator Bumpers tried and failed to strip language from the bill
that would open the door to renewed reprocessing of irradiated
fuel.  The clause allows utilities to send their waste to
"qualified entities" who would "package, ship, and receive a
contract holder's spent nuclear fuel for interim storage and
conditioning."  After the fuel and any high-level reprocessing
wastes are packaged, the materials would become title of the
taxpayer.

The White House has assured Nevada senators Bryan and Reid that
President Clinton opposes the bill, which has not been scheduled
for the Senate floor.

For a list of how committee members voted on each amendment, send
an email to Michael Grynberg (grynberg@citizen.org).

Critical Mass' Press Release on today's votes follows.
 



For Immediate Release    Contact:  Michael Grynberg
                                   Bill Magavern (202)546-4996

Senate Energy and Natural Resources Committee Celebrates "Hug a
Nuclear Lobbyist Day;" Passes Legislation to Slash Standards,
Force Nuclear Dumps

     The Senate Energy and Natural Resources Committee held a
party for the nuclear industry today, passing legislation to
slash environmental standards and force the opening of nuclear
waste dumps in Nevada and California before the completion of key
scientific studies.  

     "Today the committee celebrated 'Hug a Nuclear Lobbyist
Day,'" Michael Grynberg, Energy Policy Analyst with Public
Citizen's Critical Mass Energy Project, said.  "Their votes
represent another display of the callous disregard for the
environment for which the 104th Congress is justly notorious."

     The Committee passed S. 1271, the Nuclear Waste Policy Act
of 1996, as a substitute bill offered by original sponsor Larry
Craig (R-ID) and committee Chairman Frank Murkowski (R-AK).  
Like its earlier incarnation, the bill slashes environmental
standards and designates the Nevada Test Site as the site of an
"interim" nuclear waste dump before studies are completed of
nearby Yucca Mountain's suitability as a permanent repository for
high-level nuclear waste.  S. 1271 would override current law
that protects the integrity of ongoing studies by prohibiting
interim storage construction in Nevada.

     S. 1271 would also prohibit the Environmental Protection
Agency from issuing regulations to protect the public from
radiation releases from a repository, carve holes in the National
Environmental Policy Act, open the door to renewed reprocessing
of irradiated fuel, and set a repository radiation release
standard that poses a lifetime risk of one cancer death for every
286 exposed individuals.

     "Once again, members of the committee have shown that when
it comes to protecting the public from environmental hazards,
they still just don't get it," Bill Magavern, Director of
Critical Mass, said.  "Voters don't want the EPA to look the
other way when the nuclear industry takes the reins of the
nation's nuclear waste policy."

     Worst of all, Magavern added, is the fact that there is
currently no safety reason for centralized storage, as the
Nuclear Regulatory Commission has concluded that irradiated
reactor fuel can be stored at reactors for 100 years. 
Centralization would not reduce the number of high-level waste
sites, as every operating reactor is a de facto waste site so
long as it splits atoms.  Shipping waste to an unnecessary
"interim" facility, from which it would likely have to be shipped
again, only exposes citizens to the risks of radioactive waste
transportation. 

     If a nuclear dump opens in Nevada, transportation of nuclear
waste would proceed on a scale unprecedented in human history. 
Over 95 percent of the nation's waste radioactivity would be
shipped, affecting 43 states.  Many of these trips would be quite
long, as most of the nation's commercial nuclear reactors are
east of the Mississippi River. 
 
     Serious safety concerns surround nuclear transportation. 
With a greater number of shipments, the likelihood of accidents
involving a cask of irradiated nuclear fuel increases.  Adequate
steps have not been taken to ensure cask integrity in the event
of such a mishap.  Cask safety standards fail to incorporate the
full range of trauma to which a container may be exposed in an
accident.  Furthermore, regulations do not even require
compliance testing on full-scale models.

     "If citizens are to accept the risks of nuclear waste
transportation, these risks must be in the service of a carefully
considered program designed with public safety, not the
convenience of utility executives, as the single top priority,"
Grynberg said.  "Now is not the time to make private liabilities
public property.  Until a real solution to the problem of nuclear
waste can be devised, irradiated fuel should remain the
responsibility of those who chose to generate it."   

     The committee also passed legislation that would pave the
way for a "low-level" radioactive waste dump at Ward Valley,
California.  S. 1596, sponsored by Murkowski and longtime nuclear
industry advocate J. Bennett Johnston (D-LA), would order the
transfer of the federal land for the proposed dump before
critical studies of the site can occur.  

     Because of concerns that Ward Valley waste could contaminate
the Colorado River with radioactive pollutants, the Clinton
Administration plans studies recommended by a National Academy of
Sciences (NAS) panel and a Supplemental Environmental Impact
Statement before transferring the land.  S. 1596 would short-
circuit the process by transferring the land once the pro-dump
California state government merely declares its intent to conduct
the NAS-recommended studies.  The bill would also exempt the
transfer from federal environmental and land laws.

     "The committee gave Bennett Johnston's campaign for a post-
Senate career with the nuclear industry a boost," Magavern said,
"but the people who drink from the Colorado River would probably
have preferred that committee members wrote a letter of reference
instead."

     The Ward Valley dump would be operated by U.S. Ecology, a
company that has admitted to engaging in illegal dumping at its
Nevada site, and has also left behind heavily contaminated waste
dumps at Sheffield, Illinois and Maxey Flats, Kentucky.
   
                              ##

Public Citizen is a nonprofit, nonpartisan consumer advocacy and
research organization.  Critical Mass is its energy policy arm.
</PRE></BODY></HTML>
