<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Nuclear Power and Reactor Safety Congressional
Testimony
</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000ff" VLINK="#dd0000"
ALINK="#ff0000">
<BODY>
<H3>
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=+2>N</FONT>UCLEAR <FONT SIZE=+2>P</FONT>OWER AND <FONT
SIZE=+2>R</FONT>EACTOR <FONT SIZE=+2>S</FONT>AFETY
</CENTER>
</H3>
<P>
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=+1>Congressional Testimony</FONT>
</CENTER>
<P>
<UL>
<LI><A 
HREF="/orgs/public_citizen/CMEP/nuclearsafety/usec.html">ENRICHMENT FOR
WHOM?</A>
<BR>February 24, 1995 -- Public Citizen's testimony to the House
Commerce Committee's Subcommittee on Energy and Power on the
privatization of the U.S. Enrichment Corporation.  Public Citizen
supports privatization of the government-owned uranium-enrichment
enterprise if the privatization meets two basic tests.  Taxpayers
must receive the maximum value for the assets being sold and must
not be stuck with any lingering future liabilities.</LI>
<P>
<LI><A HREF="june3093testimony.html">
PUBLIC PARTICIPATION AND JUDICIAL REVIEW IN NUCLEAR
REGULATION</A>
<BR>June 30, 1993 -- Public Citizen's testimony to the Senate
Environment and Public Works Subcommittee on Clean Air and
Nuclear Regulation on the Nuclear Enforcement Accountability Act
of 1993, the Nuclear Regulatory Commission's performance and
related issues.</LI>
</UL>
<HR>
