<HR>
<UL>
<LI><B><I>
Enrichment for Whom?</I></B><BR>
Public Citizen's Testimony to the House Commerce Committee on 
Privatization of the U.S. Enrichment Corporation.  Public Citizen
supports privatization of the government-owned uranium enrichment
enterprise if the privatization meets two basic tests. Taxpayers
must receive the maximum value for the assets being sold and must
not be stuck with any lingering future liabilities.
<BR>2/95, 10 pages.  [Item #CM-L037]
</LI>
<P>
<LI><B><I>
Department of Energy Budget for Fiscal Year 1995</I></B>
<BR>Public Citizen's
testimony to the U.S. House of Representatives, Appropriations
Subcommittee on Energy and Waste Development, on renewable
energy,
nuclear power, and radioactive waste programs. 
<BR>3/94, 6 pages. [Item #CM-001]
</LI>
<P>
<LI><B><I>
A Sustainable Energy Blueprint and Budget</I></B>
<BR>A set of policy
recommendations presented to the Clinton administration by 100
environmental, consumer and business groups calling for steps to
reduce U.S. dependence on fossil fuels and increase reliance on
efficiency and renewable energy. 
<BR>1/93, Blueprint is 36 pages,
Budget-updated for FY95 is 45 pages.  [Item #CM-002]
</LI>
</UL>
