<H3>
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=+2>E</FONT>NERGY <FONT SIZE=+2>E</FONT>FFICIENCY
</CENTER></H3>
<P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=+1>
Publications</FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<A HREF="/orgs/public_citizen/CMEP/pubs.html">Click here for
Critical Mass' full publications list</A>
<P>
Nonprofit groups and individual consumers are eligible for
discount
prices.  Call Public Citizen's Publications Office (202) 588-1000
for pricing infomation.
</P>
<HR>
<UL>
<LI><B><I>
A Sustainable Energy Blueprint and Budget</I></B>
<BR>A set of policy
recommendations presented to the Clinton administration by 100
environmental, consumer and business groups calling for steps to
reduce U.S. dependence on fossil fuels and increase reliance on
efficiency and renewable energy. 
<BR>1/93, Blueprint is 36 pages,
Budget-updated for FY95 is 45 pages.  [Item #CM-002]
</LI><P>
<LI><B><I>
New Department of Energy Initiative is Not The Answer to U.S. Oil
Dependence</I></B>
<BR>Explains how the Clinton Administration's new Domestic
Oil and Gas Initiative will waste millions of taxpayer dollars
and
do nothing to save the U.S. oil industry.  Shows that energy
efficiency and clean fuel policies will do much more to reduce
U.S.
oil import dependency and create new jobs. 
<BR>12/93, 4 pages.  [Item #CM-007]
</LI><P><LI><B><I>
Twenty Years After The Embargo: The Costs of U.S. Oil Dependence
and How They Can Be Reduced</I></B>
<BR>Explains how U.S. dependence on
imported oil is greater now than it was during the 1973 oil
embargo.  Demonstrates that this dependence has serious economic
and environmental consequences and outlines effective solutions
for
reducing oil consumption and making the U.S. more energy
independent. 
<BR>10/93, 44 pages. [Item #CM-008]
</LI><P><LI><B><I>
<A HREF="/orgs/public_citizen/CMEP/efficiency/EnergyAuditII.html">Energy
Audit
II: A State-by-State Profile of Energy Consumption and
Conservation</A></I></B>
<BR>Details energy use in all fifty states, ranking each
according to its dependence on non-renewable resources, use of
renewable energy, energy intensity and residential consumption. 
Examines how states can implement policies to increase energy
efficiency and the use of clean energy resources.  
<BR>11/92, 45 pages.*  [Item #CM-009]
</LI>
</UL>
<P>
*Denotes that earlier editions are available.  Please write for
further information.
</P>
<P>
Orders must be prepaid.  Please include $2.90 for shipping and
handling for the first item, plus $1.00 for each additional item.
</P>
<P>
Send to:
<BR>Public Citizen Publications 
<BR>1600 20th Street, NW 
<BR>Washington, D.C. 20009
<BR>The telephone number is (202) 588-1000. 
<BR>Please allow 4-6 weeks for delivery.
