<HTML>
<BODY>
<CENTER>
<H2>
Majority Report to the President<BR>
by the<BR>
Policy Dialogue Advisory Committee
<P> 
To Recommend Options for 
Reducing Greenhouse Gas Emissions
from Personal Motor Vehicles
<P>
</H2>
<STRONG>
Table of Contents
</STRONG>
</CENTER>
<P>
Chapter I:  <A HREF="#introduction">Introduction</A><BR>
A.  <A HREF="#IA">Overview of the Policy Dialogue Advisory
Committee Process</A><BR>
B.  <A HREF="#IB">Background on GHG Emissions from Personal Motor
Vehicles</A><BR>
C.  <A HREF="#IC">What's Possible?  Recommended Scenarios for
2005, 2015, 2025</A>
<P>
Chapter II:  <A HREF="#recommendations">Recommendations</A><BR>
A.  <A HREF="#IIA">Policy Evaluation Process</A><BR>
B.  <A HREF="#IIB">General Recommendations</A><BR>
<P>
Chapter III:  <A HREF="#pathways">Pathways to Greenhouse Gas
Reductions:
Analysis and Strategies</A><BR>
A.  <A HREF="#IIIA">Fuel Economy Policies and Reductions</A><BR>
1. <A HREF="#IIIA1">Background</A><BR>
2. <A HREF="#IIIA2">Vision</A><BR>
3. <A HREF="#IIIA3">Descriptions of Recommended Policies</A><BR>
<UL>
<LI>a. <A HREF="#IIIA3a">Increase CAFE Requirements under Current
Law</A><BR>
<LI>b. <A HREF="#IIIA3b">Feebates for Higher Fuel Economy</A><BR>
<LI>c. <A HREF="#IIIA3c">Maintain Support for Partnership for New
Generation Vehicle</A><BR>
<LI>d. <A HREF="#IIIA3d">Consumer Incentives to Purchase Highly
Fuel Efficient Vehicles</A><BR>
<LI>e. <A HREF="#IIIA3e">Replacement Tire Feebate for Low Rolling
Resistance Tires</A><BR>
</UL>
<P>
B.  <A HREF="#IIIB">Alternative Fuels and Vehicle Policies and
Reductions</A><BR>
1. <A HREF="#IIIB1">Vision</A><BR>
2. <A HREF="#IIIB2">Policy Overview</A><BR>
3. <A HREF="#IIIB3">Descriptions of Recommended Policies</A><BR>
<UL>
<LI>a. <A HREF="#IIIB3a">Enhanced Research and Development for
Liquid Biofuels and Incentives for other Low-GHG Emitting
Fuel</A><BR>
<LI>b. <A HREF="#IIIB3b">Incentives for Natural Gas Vehicles and
Infrastructure</A><BR>
<LI>c. <A HREF="#IIIB3c">Support for Electric Vehicles</A><BR>
</UL>
<P>
C.  <A HREF="#IIIC">Vehicle Miles Traveled (VMT) Policies and
Reductions</A><BR>
1. <A HREF="#IIIC1">Background</A><BR>
2. <A HREF="#IIIC2">History</A><BR>
3. <A HREF="#IIIC3">Policy Overview</A><BR>
4. <A HREF="#IIIC4">Descriptions of Recommended Policies</A><BR>
<UL>
<LI>a. <A HREF="#IIIC4a">Integrated Land-use Strategies</A><BR>
<LI>b. <A HREF="#IIIC4b">Fixed Route and On-Demand
Transit</A><BR>
<LI>c. <A HREF="#IIIC4c">Workplace Parking Subsidy Reform</A><BR>
<LI>d. <A HREF="#IIIC4d">Shifting the Cost of Driving</A><BR>
</UL>
<P>
Chapter 4:  Appendices (Unavailable in this on-line version)<BR>
A.  VMT Growth Modeling<BR>
B.  Literature on the effects of Non-pricing Demand measure, Land
Use measures<BR>
C.  Briefings on Factors Affecting Fuel Economy, Vehicle Miles
Traveled, and Alternative Fuel Technologies<BR>
D.  Fact-Finding Field Visit Reports<BR>
E.  Alternative Fuels & Vehicle Infrastructure Survey<BR>
F.  VMT Modeling Runs for 2005 and 2015<BR>
G.  Bibliography<BR>
<P>
<CENTER>
<STRONG>
Executive Summary
</STRONG>
</CENTER>
<P>
     This report represents the view of a majority of the Policy
Dialogue Advisory Committee to Assist in the Development of
Measures to Significantly Reduce Greenhouse Gas Emissions from
Personal Motor Vehicles.  President Clinton charged the Committee
with developing recommendations for three sets of policies that
would, if adopted, most cost-effectively return greenhouse gas
emissions from cars and light trucks to 1990 levels by the years
2005, 2015, and 2025, respectively, with no upturn thereafter.
<P>
     Essentially the Committee had two goals: to articulate,
evaluate and recommend a package of policies capable of returning
transportation sector greenhouse gas emissions to 1990 levels,
and to develop consensus among a diverse membership.
<P>
The Committee at large was not able to reach a consensus.  This
majority report is submitted so that the President will be able
to take advantage of the considerable work done by the Committee
as the President crafts federal policies to reduce greenhouse gas
emissions.
<P>
     The Committee as a whole approached its work by examining
the three factors that determine greenhouse gas emissions from
personal motor vehicles: fuel economy, vehicle miles traveled
(VMT) and alternative fuels.  The Committee reached agreement on
a number of policies in the areas of reducing VMT and promoting
the use of alternative fuels, subject to their being included in
a balanced package that achieves the emission targets set by the 
President.  In addition, an analytical framework for evaluating
and scoring policies was accepted by all members for the purpose
of the Committee's work. Finally, there was widespread agreement
that the gap between emission reductions anticipated for the
agreed-upon policies and the targets in the Committee's charge
should be approached through some combination of increasing the
cost of driving (e.g. by a gas tax) and policies that directly 
increase fuel economy (e.g. by fuel economy standards supported
by feebates).
<P>
     The Committee could not reach consensus on a report because
it was unable to reconcile the following positions:
Environmentalists favored fuel economy standards, which the auto
industry opposed.  The automobile industry proposed gas taxes to
which the oil industry representatives objected. Finally, a
consensus report stating the Committee's disagreement was
unacceptable to the auto industry if it mentioned direct measures
to increase fuel economy in a quantified way.
<P>
     The Committee members signing this report believe that a
package cannot be complete and is unlikely to be cost-effective
or equitable without including direct policies for addressing
fuel economy and the cost of travel.  
<P>
     This report therefore recommends a balanced set of policies
that would:
<P>
     1)  reduce vehicle emissions by increasing the efficiency of
the vehicle fleet;<BR>
     2)  reduce emissions by introducing cleaner burning fuels;
and<BR>
3)  reduce driving by improving the attractiveness of
alternatives to driving, and by sending accurate price signals
about the cost of driving.
<P>
     In particular, we make the following recommendation (numbers
in parenthesis represent millions of metric tonnes of carbon
equivalent for 2005, 2015, and 2025 in the case that returns
emissions to 1990 levels by 2005):
<P>
<STRONG>
Recommended Policy Set<P>

FUEL ECONOMY MEASURES:<BR>
</STRONG>
<UL>
<LI>increasing the Corporate Average Fuel Economy (CAFE)
Standards starting in 1998 to achieve 45 mpg and provide market
incentives plus research and development support.  This will
result in the most significant portion of the greenhouse gas
reductions (36, 117,175 MMT). 
<LI>introducing feebates for low rolling resistance tires (3,4,5
MMT).
<P>
</UL>
<STRONG>
ALTERNATIVE FUELS MEASURES:<BR>
</STRONG>
<LI>supporting the use of electric vehicles and further research
and development plus a tax credit (.4, 4.5, 9.9 MMT)
<LI>supporting natural gas vehicles and infrastructure (1.1, 5.5,
7.7 MMT)
<LI>supporting liquid biofuels research and development, in
particular ethanol produced from cellulosic biomass, providing
production incentives for low-emitting fuels (5.1, 38, 100 
MMT)</UL>
<P>
<STRONG>
VEHICLE MILES TRAVELED MEASURES:<BR>
</STRONG>
<UL>
<LI>encouraging the equitable shift of state and local road
subsidies to cost-of-driving (VMT fees) (30, 32, 30 MMT)
<LI>encouraging land use changes away from auto dependency by
improving fixed-route and on-demand transit services plus bicycle
and pedestrian access (5.3, 13, 23 MMT).
<LI>reforming workplace parking subsidy programs (5.7, 11, 22
MMT).
<P>
The longer lead time available by 2015 permits a slower ramp-up
of fuel economy standards and a lower VMT fee.  Both the 2005 and
the 2015 policy packages provide an ongoing downward emissions
trend, so that either would suffice to meet the Committee's 
goal for 2025 as well.
<P>
          We favor adoption of policies having continuity over
time.  The relative importance, however, of the various policies
is different at different times.  For example, alternative fuels
are a relatively small contributor in 2005, but can become a
large contributor in 2015 and 2025 provided that aggressive and
sustained development efforts are initiated now.
<P>
          Meeting the Committee's charge will not be easy to
accomplish, but it will be necessary to meet the United States'
obligation under the Framework Convention on Climate Change
agreed to in Rio in 1992.  In addition to achieving reductions in
emissions from the transportation sector, we believe that these
recommendations will also reduce air pollution including urban
smog, save consumers money, create jobs and cut U.S. reliance on
imported oil.
<P>
     By signing this report members agree that this is a
compromise proposal that represents a viable way to meet the
President's goals.  Among those signing this report are 
those who would have preferred less stringent or more
market-based mechanisms and those who would have preferred
tougher purely regulatory approaches.  We recognize that in the 
interest of compromise, we have crafted this package.  We are all
joining together to submit this set of options that we all
believe can accomplish the President's goal, although any 
specific mechanism alone may not be one which an organization may
support.
<P>
     This is a critical time with respect to greenhouse gas
emissions. 
<P>
<STRONG>
The undersigned members of the Committee endorse this report:<P>
