<P>
<CENTER>
<H2>
Majority Report to the President 
by the Policy Dialogue Advisory Committee
<P>
To Recommend Options for 
Reducing Greenhouse Gas Emissions
From Personal Motor Vehicles
</H2>
</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<STRONG>
<FONT SIZE=+2>CHAPTER I:  <A
NAME="introduction">INTRODUCTION</A></FONT>
</STRONG>
</CENTER>
Much of the anticipated growth in greenhouse gas emissions after
2000 will be in the transportation sector.  Even with actions
taken under this plan, we expect that overall use of automobiles
and trucks will increase as vehicles are driven greater
distances.  In order to continue emission reduction trends beyond
the turn of the century, additional cost-effective measures will
be needed to reduce greenhouse gas emissions of individual
vehicles and to increase America's transportation options, so
that personal mobility can be enhanced while private vehicles
can be driven less.<A HREF="#note1">[1]</A>
<P>
     In September, 1994, President Clinton convened a Federal
Advisory Committee Policy Dialogue to assist in the development
of measures to significantly reduce greenhouse gas (GHG)
emissions from personal motor vehicles.  The charge to
the Advisory Committee was to develop three sets of policies that
would, if adopted, most cost-effectively return greenhouse gas
emissions from cars and light trucks to 1990 levels by the years
2005, 2015, and 2025, respectively, with no upturn thereafter. 
The President gave the Committee this ambitious charge with full
knowledge that the debate over how the US should respond to the 
threat of global climate change, particularly in the
transportation sector, had stalled numerous times in recent
years. 
<P>
     Over the course of one year, members of the Policy Dialogue
Advisory Committee met eleven times to discuss how to return
greenhouse gas emissions from light duty vehicles to 1990 levels
in each of the three target years in the most cost-effective
manner.  These members recognize that achieving the goal is not
easy.  Yet, the work of the full Committee has demonstrated that,
while addressing reduction of GHG emissions from the transport 
sector is difficult, there are sets of feasible and
cost-effective alternatives to return GHG emissions from light
duty vehicles to 1990 levels in each of the three target years -
2005, 2015 and 2025.  In response to its charge, this group of
Committee members has developed a blueprint for how to achieve
the President's goals and as an "insurance plan" that could be 
used to address climate change in the future.
<P>
<STRONG>The Policy Dialogue Advisory Committee
</STRONG>
<P>
     When President Clinton appointed the thirty members of the
Policy Dialogue Advisory Committee, he and his staff sought
representatives of state, local and regional government agencies,
automobile manufacturers and related parties like suppliers and
insurers, the transportation fuels industry, labor, and public
interest groups who could constructively address the Committee's
charge. Over 170 individuals were nominated by various groups for
appointment to the committee.  The President appointed
individuals who met the following qualifications:<P>
<UL>
<LI>knowledge of and familiarity with the range of issues to be
addressed by the Committee; 
<LI>leadership experience within his or her constituency;
<LI>willingness and ability to participate in the Advisory
Committee, including technical 
and administrative support to do so;
<LI>ability to be constructive and to take a creative approach,
including willingness to 
move beyond past positions; and 
<LI>contribution to overall balance and diversity on the
Committee.
</UL>
<P>
The Committee included the following membership:<BR>
1.  Isaac Barpal, Allied-Signal (represented by George
Lester)<BR>
2.  Daniel Becker, Sierra Club<BR>
3.  Scott Bernstein, Center for Neighborhood Technology<BR>
4.  Ron Blum, United Auto Workers<BR>
5.  Ronald R. Boltz, Chrysler Corporation<BR>
6.  Patsy Brownson, National Association of Fleet Administrators
& Cox Enterprises<BR>
7.  Joan Claybrook, Public Citizen<BR>
8.  John DeCicco, American Council for an Energy Efficient
Economy<BR>
9.  Clarence Ditlow, Center for Auto Safety<BR>
10. Hank Dittmar, Surface Transportation Policy Project<BR>
11. George Dixon, Greater Cleveland Regional Transit
Authority<BR>
12. Patrick Dougherty, Missouri House of Representatives<BR>
13. George Eads, General Motors Corporation<BR>
14. David Freeman, formerly, New York Power Authority<BR>
15. George Giek, American Automobile Association<BR>
16. Sonia Hamel, Massachusetts Executive Office of Environmental
Affairs<BR>
17. Ben Knight, Honda Research & Development North America<BR>
18. Allen Kozinski, Amoco<BR>
19. Daniel Lashof, Natural Resources Defense Council<BR>
20. Valerie Lemmie, City Manager for Petersburg, Virginia<BR>
21. James M. Lents, South Coast Air Quality Management District,
California<BR>
22. Lee R. Lynd, Independence Biofuel, Inc., and Dartmouth
College<BR>
23. John McTague, Ford Motor Company<BR>
24. Francis J. Murray, National Association of State Energy
Officials<BR>
25. Brian O'Neill, Insurance Institute for Highway Safety<BR>
26. Wayne Shackleford, Georgia Department of Transportation<BR>
27. Ann Shen Smith, Southern California Gas Company<BR>
28. Joseph P. Swift, Sun Company<BR>
29. Margaret Walls, Resources for the Future<BR>
30. Karl-Heinz Ziwica, BMW of North America<BR>
<P>
Interagency Steering Committee Liaisons:<BR>
Frank E. Kruesi, Assistant Secretary for Transportation Policy,
Department of Transportation<BR>
Mary D. Nichols, Assistant Administrator for Air and Radiation,
Environmental Protection Agency<BR>
Susan F. Tierney, Assistant Secretary for Policy, Planning, and
Program Evaluation, Department of Energy<BR>
<P>
<STRONG><A NAME="IA">A. Overview of the Policy Dialogue Advisory
Committee Process</A></STRONG>
<P>
     At its first meeting, several elements of the Committee's
functioning were determined.  The Committee discussed and agreed
on procedural groundrules, including a provision that it would
make decisions by consensus, defined as all can live with the
decision made.  
<P>
     Also early on, the Committee began its interaction with the
Analytic Support Group (ASG), comprised of government technical
experts, who, at the Committee's request, provided information
about the extent of the climate change problem and the
contribution of the personal transportation sector to total CO2
emissions.  The ASG provided the Committee with considerable
assistance over its year of deliberations, including running
analyses on the baseline computer model that allowed calculations
of the greenhouse gas emission reductions from specific policies
and sets of policies.
<P>
The Committee undertook the following tasks as it addressed its
charge:
<P>
*analyzing and developing agreements about the underlying
assumptions that were used as inputs to the model that estimated
the baseline for CO 2 emissions;<BR> 
*obtaining briefings from experts on fuel economy technology, the
Partnership for a New Generation Vehicle, members of the National
Research Council Committee on potential fuel economy
improvements, experts on alternative fuels and their relative
greenhouse gas emissions, on current generation electric
vehicles, and demographic and transportation planning experts on
driving behaviors and patterns;<BR> 
*visiting California's South Coast Air Quality Management
District and the city of Pasadena, where the focus was on
alternative fuel vehicles, reducing single-occupant-
vehicle driving, and land use planning that incorporates
transportation demand management;<BR>
*commissioning of three ad-hoc policy groups of Committee members
to develop recommendations to the plenary group on three areas:
1) policies for improving fuel economy, 2) policies to introduce
and support low greenhouse gas fuels, and 3)policies to reduce
vehicle miles of travel (VMT);<BR>
*developing a consensus set of evaluation criteria for over 65
potential policies;<BR>
*preparing a proposal and analysis, with the Analytic Support
Group, of many potential policies; and<BR>
*seeking agreement on a set of general recommendations and
acceptable policy sets that could, if adopted, return CO 2
emissions from personal motor vehicles to 1990 levels by 2005,
2015 and 2025.
<P>
     While the majority submitting this report agree on a set of
options for achieving the President's goals for reducing CO 2
emissions from personal motor vehicles, some Committee 
members disagreed about including fuel economy standards as a
strategy.  There was consensus within the Committee on a partial
set of policies, however these policies missed achieving the
President's goals by a significant margin.  Some other ideas
which were discussed, in the end were not recommended because
their costs were considered either too high or too
disproportionally distributed, therefore, making them
infeasible.
<P>
<STRONG>B.  <A NAME="IB">Background on Achieving GHG Emissions
Reductions from Personal Motor Vehicles</A></STRONG>
<P>
     The Annual Energy Outlook (AEO) for 1995 identified 1990
carbon emissions from the transportation sector at 32.3% of total
carbon emissions, and projected an increase of 27% by 2010 (See
table below).  Within the transportation sector, 1990 emissions
from light duty vehicles were 53.1% of total energy use, with all
but 18% of that in the personal transportation category.  Thus,
reducing carbon emissions from the transportation sector could
make a significant contribution to reducing greenhouse gases
during the first quarter of the next century.
<P>
<STRONG>
Percentage of Energy Use for the Transportation Sector
</STRONG>
<P>
<PRE>
Sector         Percent of Total              Percent of Total 
               Transportation 1990           Transportation 2010

Highway             74.5                          70.7
LDVs                53.1                          53.6
     Autos          47.3                          32.4
     Trucks         5.8                           21.1
     Bus            0.4                           0.6
     Heavy Trucks   21.0                          16.5
Non-Highway         21.8                          29.3
Air                 9.9                           13.6
Other               11.7                          13.5 
     (water, rail, pipeline, lube)
Military            3.3                           2.3
(Source: AEO-95)
</PRE>
<P>
<STRONG>
Carbon Emissions (MMT) and (Share) by End-Use Sector
</STRONG><P><PRE>
Sector              1990 (%)                 2010 (%)
                                             Reference

Residential         91.6   (6.8)        94.4   (5.8)
Commercial          59.2   (4.4)        59.5   (3.7)
Industrial          279.3 (20.9)        335.1 (20.7) 
Electric Utilities  476.7 (35.6)        583.7 (36.0)
Transportation      432.2 (32.2)        548.1 (33.8) 
Total Emissions1    338.0               1620.8           
(Source: AEO-95)
</PRE>
<P>
Total greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions from personal transportation
are completely determined by three factors: 
<P>
*    total vehicle miles traveled (VMT),<BR>
*    the rate of fuel use for each of these miles (fuel economy,
or MPG), and<BR>
*    the GHG content of the fuels used, which depends, in turn,
on the rate of utilization of non-carbon-based alternative fuels
and vehicles (AF's, AFVs). 
<P>
     To develop a plausible unrestrained path for future GHG
emissions from personal transportation, it was necessary to
specify trends for each of these components.  From the 
calculation of these trends it was possible to develop estimates
of reductions in GHG emissions from personal motor vehicles
needed to bring emissions back to 1990 levels.
<P>
     Developing trends for growth VMT, MPG, and AFs and AFVs
required judgments about a variety of other influences.  For
example, the rate of growth of VMT will depend on 
future income growth, changes in the fuel and other costs of
driving, growth or leveling off of female labor force
participation, mobility of retirees, changes in land use and
availability of other modes.  Fuel economy trends depend on fuel
prices, changes in consumer preferences for vehicle attributes,
changes in costs of supplying fuel economy technology, and other 
factors potentially affecting vehicle turnover (e.g., the
performance of vehicle I&M programs).  The use of AFs and AFVs
depends on the degree of success in developing technological
options with competitive costs and performance characteristics,
the time needed to develop necessary infrastructure, and the GHG
characteristics of the fuel and vehicle technologies.
<P>
     The Analytic Support Group (ASG) of the interagency Steering
Committee developed information used by the Committee to specify
a plausible unrestrained path for GHG emissions - the baseline -
and an accounting model to compare the amount of greenhouse gas 
reductions that would result from any specific policy against the
baseline. The Analytic Support Group used existing estimates in
the literature as inputs to the baseline.  The Policy 
Dialogue Advisory Committee reviewed the ASG assumptions and
refined several parameters.  For fuel economy predictions, the
Committee agreed to construct the baseline under the assumption
of both moderately increasing and constant (real) oil prices over
the next 30 years.  For predictions about the use of alternative
fuels, alternative fuel vehicles (AFVs) were assumed to rise to a
3% market penetration by 2025, consistent with current regulatory
mandates for fleet use.
<P>
     To model VMT trends, the ASG relied in part on an
econometric model developed at the Volpe Transportation Center
that can predict growth in VMT given assumptions about 
growth in population, income, and demographic factors.  The ASG
also surveyed the available literature on VMT growth and its
causes, and together with a subcommittee of the Advisory
Committee, backtested the model for the period 1980 to
1990.  After considerable analysis and debate the Committee
elected to set a baseline VMT growth rate of 2% per year 
to 2005, and then to use the prediction from the Volpe model
(expected to be 1.7% annually)through 2025.
<P>
     The other crucial set of assumptions the Committee needed
involved predicting and estimating the response of VMT and MPG to
changes in the cost of fuel or in the total cost of 
driving.  After much debate and examination of the literature,
the Committee developed a set of elasticities that were agreed
upon only for the specific purpose of the Committee's work.  
They included:
<P>
*The elasticity of demand for new car fuel economy in response to
fuel prices should be 0.4.
<P>
*The VMT elasticity with respect to fuel price should be .21 and
VMT elasticity with respect to the fuel cost per mile should be
.35.**  The Committee recognized that these elasticities,
particularly VMT with respect to fuel cost per mile
(the so-called rebound effect) could be inaccurate and agreed to
do sensitivity analyses to reflect differing estimates.
<P>
*To reflect the uncertainties of market responses to price
increases, the Committee decided to build into the model
assumptions of a threshold of $.25 fuel price increase before the
full fuel economy elasticity is in effect.  During the period
before full elasticity effect, the Committee decided to build in
an elasticity factor of .25.
<P>
     These agreed upon assumptions and projections were critical
to the Committee deliberations and to analysis of policy impacts. 
The baseline calculations are referred to repeatedly throughout
this report.  For analytical purposes, the constant oil price
projection was the usual assumption used.
<P>
**This elasticity tends to fall into the middle of a wide range
of estimates derived from a number of methodologies for a longer-
term response.  The Committee did not specifically address the
applicability of this elasticity to a shorter time frame,
including its utility for the 2005 timeframe.
<P>
<STRONG>C.  <A NAME="IC">What's Possible: Recommended Scenarios
for 2005, 2015, and 2025</A></STRONG>
<P>
     Determining what policies to recommend for what target years
required the Committee to understand the technological
achievements that were possible, as well as the 
long-term time horizon for behavioral and demographic changes. 
The policy sets presented in Chapter 2 are based on some of the
following projections of changes that are possible, in 
the Committee's view, over the next 30 years.
<P>
BY THE YEAR 2005, we will see:
<P>
<STRONG>Alternative Fuels and Vehicles
</STRONG>
<P>
<UL>
<LI>Alternative fuels and vehicles will be part of the car-buying
picture.
<LI>Electric vehicles are standardly used in niche markets and in
urban areas.  Continuous improvements in the performance, range,
and recharge time of battery-powered electric vehicles will have
resulted from Zero Emission Vehicle mandates in California, 
Massachusetts, and New York, and from other Clean Air Act
requirements.
<LI>Natural gas and liquid propane gas will increasingly be used
for public and private fleets, especially in areas with Clean Air
Act mandates.  Natural gas powered vans and light trucks will be
widely available on the personal motor vehicle market.
<LI>Technology to improve the production of ethanol from
cellulosic biomass may be improved to produce a shorter
fermentation process, setting the stage for cellulosic 
ethanol to replace corn-ethanol as a low-greenhouse-gas fuel.
<LI>Farmers will be growing biomass crops for ethanol production
on land formerly targeted for erosion prevention.
</UL>
<P>
<STRONG>
Fuel Economy Improvements
</STRONG>
<P>
<UL>
<LI>Conventional internal combustion engines fueled by gasoline
but with improved fuel efficiency will continue to be the
predominant choice for personal motor vehicles.
<LI>Increased CAFE standards will cause auto makers to introduce
new technology into motor vehicles to improve new car, van and
light truck fuel efficiency.
<LI>New technologies such as improved transmissions from 5-speed
automatics to continuously variable, lean burn engines, light
weight/high strength materials, and accessories with reduced
friction losses will become common place in the market.
<LI>Existing technologies such as multi-valve engines and
multi-port fuel injection which have significant penetration in
the passenger car market today will reach similar market 
penetration levels in light trucks and vans where they have
limited penetration today.
<LI>Incentive programs (like rebates, vehicle retirement, and
feebate programs) to induce consumers to purchase vehicles with
good fuel economy will be in place to help this market creation
along
<LI>Low-rolling resistance tires will be commonly sought by
consumers as lower cost in the long run, aided by incentive
programs like rebates and vouchers. 
<LI>The highly fuel efficient standard-size prototypes with up to
80-mpg fuel economy that result from the Partnership for a New
Generation Vehicles (PNGV) in 2003 will give impetus for even
more dramatic changes in future fuel economy beyond 2005.
<LI>Increased CAFE standards will cause the auto makers to
realize the PNGV goal of integrating technology developed from
the PNGV program into the new vehicle fleet as the technology is
developed.
<LI>VMT fees and feebates will work to increase consumer demand
for the more fuel efficient motor vehicles needed to meet
increased CAFE standards. 
</UL>
<P>
<STRONG>
VMT Reduction
</STRONG>
<UL>
<LI>An equitable shift of state and local road subsidies to
cost-of-driving fees will reduce the amount of miles traveled.
<LI>About 80% of cars driven to work are parked in free,
employer-provided parking, but a new Workplace Parking Subsidy
Reform gives employees the option to exchange the value of free
parking for taxable income.  This starts to make alternative
modes of commuting more attractive.
<LI>1995 proposals to create livable communities will begin to
bear fruit in development plans for suburbs and urban areas;
pricing strategies to discourage single-occupant-
vehicle use will be options in several large cities.  
<LI>Infill strategies to prevent deterioration of cities will be
commonly proposed in urban revitalization plans.
<LI>Mixed use developments with walkable and bikeable travel
patterns will be proposed, with pilot projects for smaller
communities well under way.
<LI>Reliable mass transit paired with affordable and reliable
on-demand transportation outside of urban cores will be accepted
increasingly by communities.  
<LI>CO2 emissions from residence-to-work travel will be reduced
by employer/employee designed programs to provide financial
incentives to those traveling to work in coordinated group travel
in vans and ride-share programs.
</UL>
<P> 
<STRONG>
BY THE YEAR 2015,</STRONG> many of the policy directions noted
above will be much further along.
<UL>
<P> 
<LI>CAFE standards will contribute the biggest reductions in
greenhouse gas emissions as turnover of the vehicle fleet subject
to tighter CAFE standards begun in 1998 model year and increased
thereafter takes effect.
<LI>Spurred by CAFE standards, feebates and "green machine
challenges", the PNGV vehicles introduced in 2003, or other
highly fuel-efficient vehicles, will have achieved a 
significant market share as high as 15%.
<LI>World oil prices may begin to rise due to increasing demand
on the oil supply, creating additional demand for higher fuel
economy vehicles and alternative fuels. 
<LI>VMT pricing mechanisms will be in place in almost half of the
major congested areas in the U.S. 
<LI>Several leaders will have emerged in the competition to
produce the most reliable and cost-effective alternative fuels,
and the need for transition strategies, like incentives to 
fuel producers and consumers, may diminish.
<LI>Advanced technology vehicles may be in many fleets, including
those of car rental companies, and the groundwork and experience
will be there for consumer familiarity and demand for these
vehicles.  
<LI>Citizens may accept shared electric (or other alternatively
fueled) "town-cars" for transportation within congested cities. 
<LI>Livable communities will continue to be a goal, and some of
the innovative plans of 1990 and 2005 will begin to bear fruit,
as will road use and VMT pricing strategies, to reduce VMT.  
<LI>Alternatives to single occupancy travel will continue to
grow, with most improvement from the availability of on-demand
transit (taxi's, super shuttles, etc.) in non-urban areas.
</UL>
<P>
<STRONG>
IN 2025,</STRONG> many of the long term strategies for changing
the consumption of carbon in transportation may have run a full
cycle, with evident results:
<P>
<UL>
<LI>CAFE standards and alternate fuels will each contribute over
one-third of the net greenhouse gas emissions reductions achieved
begun in 1998 model year and increased thereafter takes effect.
<LI>Alternative fuels and vehicles could become competitive on a
life-cycle cost basis with gasoline and diesel vehicles.  
<LI>Very high mileage vehicles with the typical family sedan
getting up to 80-mpg and smaller vehicles getting over 100-mpg
will be common place; break through technologies such as hybrid
engines and implementation of known technologies such as direct 
injection will penetrate the market.
<LI>These vehicles will be sought by consumers as oil prices
increase globally, and as technology produces affordable
products.  
<LI>The technology to produce ethanol from cellulosic biomass may
be advanced to the point that it is a sustainable energy source
for the transportation sector.
<LI>U.S. manufacturers could build on research and development
earlier in the century to become leading exporters of new
alternative fuels technology.  
<LI>Half of the houses in existence in 2025 will have been
constructed after 1995.  If this new housing is developed
according to plans that emphasize alternative mobility options, 
VMT could decline.
</UL>
<P>
<CENTER>
<STRONG><FONT SIZE=+2>
CHAPTER II:  <A NAME="recommendations">RECOMMENDATIONS</A></FONT>
</STRONG>
</CENTER>
<STRONG>
<A NAME="IIA">Policy Evaluation Process</A>
</STRONG>
<P>
     The Committee agreed on how it would use the criteria
specified in its charge from the President to evaluate various
policies for inclusion in final recommendations.  The 
Committee decided to define the policy options and do rough
estimate of GHG emission reductions available from each option. 
Based on the GHG reduction potential, the Committee then decided
which policy options to evaluate in greater detail and which
policy descriptions needed to be refined.
<P>
Next the Committee evaluated policy options on the following
criteria:
<P>
<UL>
<LI>amount of GHG reduction
<LI>costs and their distribution
<LI>cost effectiveness (costs of obtaining a specific GHG
emission reduction divided by the amount of the reduction)
<LI>time horizon for implementing the policy and realizing the
reductions
<LI>sustainability of reductions (i.e. no upturn thereafter), and
reliability (i.e. policy will produce projected reductions), 
<LI>other impacts including:<BR>
                    - safety<BR>
                    - other environmental effects<BR>
                    - social (including effects on mobility,
jobs, consumer requirements and satisfaction, intergenerational,
urban/suburban/rural, geography etc.) and their distribution<BR>
                    - other GHG reduction policy implications<BR>
<LI>feasibility of adoption
<LI>ease of implementation
</UL>
<P>
     In applying these evaluation criteria the Committee came to
several important 
conclusions.  They were:
<P>
<UL>
<LI>CO2 emission reduction efforts should be particularly
supported when they are achievable in the context of reaching
other important national objectives, like reducing air pollution
and improving the quality of life in congested communities.  
Efforts undertaken to address climate change impacts from
personal motor vehicles overlap significantly with efforts being
proposed or undertaken to address other national and local
challenges.  For example, alternative fuel vehicles are needed in
certain parts of the county to address air pollution problems;
these vehicles and fuels can also reduce CO2 emissions. 
Committee members realize the value of and agreed upon a goal of
specifically including greenhouse gas emission reduction goals in
efforts that will be underway for other reasons.
<P>
<LI>Policies recommended by the Committee must meet the criteria
set out in the President's charge.  The Committee took its charge
seriously and set about to find policies with the greatest
reliability, cost-effectiveness, and feasibility of adoption.  
</UL>
<P>
<STRONG><A NAME="IIB">
General Recommendations</A></STRONG>
<P>
     Two packages of policies are recommended by this report, one
for returning car and light truck greenhouse gas emissions to the
1990 level by 2005 and the other for achieving return by 2015. 
Both packages provide an ongoing downward emissions trend, so
that either would suffice to meet the Committee's goal for 2025
as well.  The following table lists the packages for 2005 showing
estimated emissions reductions in each of the three years 
specified for discussion (2005, 2015, 2025).  Policy descriptions
are given in the following sections of this report. The longer
lead time available by 2015 permits a slower ramp-up of 
fuel economy standards and a lower VMT fee.  In fact, the 2015
package reduces emissions to 24 MMT (7%) below the 1990 level - a
modest safety margin. The VMT fee was chosen so as to keep the
variable cost of driving constant as fuel economy increased
through fuel economy standards;  dispensing with the VMT fee
would still suffice to return emissions by 2015, but the safety
margin would be only 1%.  The 2005 package just meets the return 
requirements.  Results are shown relative to the flat oil price
baseline; a rising world oil price could make the targets easier
to achieve.
<P>
     The Committee approached its work in constructing packages
by examining the three major factors - vehicle miles traveled
(VMT), fuel economy, and fuel type (e.g., lower carbon 
content) - which determine greenhouse gas emissions in the
personal transportation sector.  The Committee members issuing
this report believe that a balanced approach to controlling 
car and light truck greenhouse gas emissions entails using a
variety of measures, affecting all of these three factors.  The
most difficult measures on which to achieve consensus were those 
for directly improving vehicle fuel economy (such as stronger
fuel economy standards) and those for directly increasing the
variable cost of driving (such as a gasoline tax or VMT fee).  
The members issuing this report acknowledge that Committee
members from the directly affected industries objected to such
policies during the Committee discussions.  However, we 
feel that a package cannot be complete and is unlikely to be
cost-effective or equitable without including direct policies for
addressing fuel economy and the cost of travel.
<P>
     Most policies can vary in their degree of stringency.  For
example, a gasoline tax could, in principle, extend much higher
than current U.S. levels (European levels range up to 
$3 per gallon).  Similarly, VMT fees could span a range: a 0.5
per mile fee would increase the cost of driving by just under
10%, whereas a 6 per mile fee would double it.  Fuel 
economy standards could be set at various levels, as could
subsidies for various alternative fuels.  Given the uncertainties
(and sometimes serious disputes) about the emissions reductions,
costs and benefits, and distributional effects of any given
policy, the members issuing this report felt that a balanced
package should not rely solely on a more stringent version of a
single policy when a less stringent version would suffice if
combined with other policies.  Thus, while in theory, emissions
could be returned by a sufficiently high gasoline 
or carbon tax alone, we do not believe that such an approach
would be cost - effective, equitable, or even reliable (let alone
politically realistic).  There are no "silver bullets" for 
meeting the challenge of controlling greenhouse gas emissions.  A
package is more robust if it includes a range of measures that
reliably alter each major factor that influences emissions 
from cars and light trucks.
<P>
     The policies constituting each package are categorized here
under their major factors of influence: VMT reduction, fuel
economy improvement, and alternative fuels use.  However,
policies directed toward any one factor can affect the other
factors.  Thus, the policies constituting a package interact, so
that the integrated emissions reduction achieved by a package of
measures can be different (higher or lower) than a simple
summation of the reductions estimated for each measure scored in
isolation.  The emissions reductions for each package were scored
using an integrated accounting model, developed by the Analytic 
Support Group for the purposes of the Committee, which accounts
for policy interactions.
<P>
     Policies were scored using "compromise" assumptions
regarding the responsiveness of the vehicle market and vehicle
travel to changes in the price of fuel or the variable cost per 
mile of travel.[1]  These assumptions were developed only for the
purposes of the Committee's work and do not reflect a consensus
that they provide an accurate or "best judgement" degree 
of market responsiveness.  Sensitivity analyses were performed
using assumptions reflecting the lower degree of market
responsiveness which some Committee members (including many 
issuing this report) feel are more accurate.[2]  Under such
assumptions, either higher fuel economy standards or a higher VMT
fee would be required for the 2005 package.  On the other hand,
such assumptions still imply a 10% safety margin for returning
emissions to the 1990 level by 2015 and, in fact, suggest that
emissions could be returned to the 1990 level by 2010 with a 1
mpg/year (combined fleet) fuel economy increase and a VMT fee of
only 0.2 per mile.
<P>
<STRONG><CENTER>
Policy Package for Returning U.S. Car and Light Truck Emissions
to the 1990 level by 2005</CENTER></STRONG>
<P>
<PRE>
