     [1]  See the Committee's interim report (Resolve. March
1995, p. 3)  The assumptions are: a fuel price elasticity of VMT
equal to 0.21; a cost-per-mile elasticity of VMT equal to 0.35; a
fuel price elasticity of new fleet MPG equal to 0.4 when the fuel
price exceeds a threshold of $0.25 gal. but equaling 0.25 below
this threshold.
     [2]  The most pertinent change is lowering the cost-per-mile
elasticity of VMT to -0.1.  The other key assumption is a lower
fuel price elasticity of new fleet MPG of 0.3, with a threshold
of $0.50/gal before the full effect is felt (so that this
elasticity ramps up from 0 to 0.3 as fuel price rises from zero
to $0.50/gal above the current real gasoline price).  
     [3]  Effects of PNGV are not scored separately, but assumed
to help in reaching fuel economy targets.  The fuel economy
standards continue to ramp-up at 1.5 mpg/yr (1.7 for cars and
1.25 for light trucks) through 2025, when the new light duty
fleet average would reach 66mpg, which is less than the 75mpg
that might be achieved if the whole fleet reached the PNGV
tripled fuel economy level by then.
     [4]  From revised analytic support group results of 9/15/95,
using response modeled by a ramp-up of a monthly average parking 
opportunity cost from $30 in 2005 to $80 in 2025. 
     [5]  The VMT fee is assumed to ramp up to 1.22/mile by 2005
and remain fixed thereafter.  The cost of driving would then
begin to fall because of the ongoing fuel economy increase.
</PRE>
<P>
<CENTER><STRONG><FONT SIZE=+2>Chapter III: <A
NAME="pathways">Pathways to
Greenhouse Gas Reductions Analysis and Strategies</A></FONT>
</CENTER>
<P>
A.  <A NAME="IIIA">Fuel Economy Policies and Reductions</A>
<P>
<A NAME="IIIA1">Background</A>
</STRONG>
<P>
     In examining the role higher vehicle efficiency can play in
reducing greenhouse gas emissions from personal transportation,
it is useful to look back at its role over the past two decades,
following the 1973 oil embargo that made MPG a household acronym.
The average on-road fuel economy of the fleet of US cars and
light trucks improved 60% during this time period, cutting fuel
use per mile by more than one-third.  Despite dire predictions
that new car CAFE standards requiring a 100% increase in average
new car fuel efficient from 13.8 to 27.5 MPG would eliminate all
large cars and force a fleet of sub-sub-compacts, new car fuel 
economy more than doubled by 1985 without any restriction on
consumer choice.  Despite the additional VMT growth that higher
vehicle efficiency induced, nationwide gasoline consumption is
roughly one-quarter lower (and petroleum use over 2 million
barrels per day lower) than it would be if fuel economy had not
improved. CAFE standards were the primary factor in this
increase, particularly since gasoline price has decreased since
1982 with today's real gasoline prices being lower than any time
in the 1960's or 1970's.
<P>
     Now, 20 years later, the dust from two oil crises has
settled and gasoline prices are at historic lows.  Today's cars
and light trucks are cleaner, safer, more durable, more reliable,
more powerful and more comfortable as well as more fuel efficient
than those in the showrooms of 1973.  Today's new car fuel
economy is more than twice that of 1974 models while vehicle
fatality rates have declined to less than half what they were in
1974.  That's technological progress.  While today's vehicles are
also more expensive than those of 1974, the cost for fuel economy
improvements are more than offset by the savings in gasoline
costs to the consumer.
<P>
<STRONG><A NAME="IIIA2">Vision</A></STRONG>
<P>
     Looking ahead 10, 20, or 30 years, continued progress in
fuel economy can significantly reduce greenhouse gas emissions. 
Between now and 2015, improvements in fuel economy can produce
greater greenhouse gas reductions than any other policy.  Of the 
83 million metric tons (MMT) of reductions needed to return
greenhouse gas emissions to 1990 levels by 2005, fuel economy
improvements can provide 36 MMT.  Of the 163 million metric tons
(MMT) of reductions needed to return greenhouse gas emissions to
1990 levels by 2015, fuel economy improvements can provide 88
MMT.  By 2025 fuel economy improvements can reduce greenhouse gas
emissions by 138 MMT while alternative fuel policies will total
117 MMT of reductions.  Technology improvements can be
implemented fleetwide over the next 10 years with similar
proportional improvements to the fuel consumption of all
vehicles.
<P>
     Obtaining such improvements in fuel economy will come from
increased CAFE standards with feebates to stimulate market demand
for more fuel efficient vehicles.  To the extent that gasoline
prices rise from higher petroleum prices or VMT fees, they will
help stimulate consumer demand for more fuel efficient vehicles. 
However, the Committee considered and rejected gasoline taxes as
a way to improve fuel economy for two reasons.  First, some
members of the Committee believed that it was politically
infeasible to raise gasoline taxes in any significant amount in
the near future.  Second, some members of the Committee did not
believe that any foreseeable level of gasoline taxes would match
the fuel economy levels produced by higher CAFE standards with
feebates.  
<P>
     In an effort to reach a compromise with the auto industry,
some members proposed using a market mechanism (such as the
gasoline taxes proposed by the auto industry) to be tried with a
mandatory trigger for increased CAFE standards if taxes or other
market mechanisms failed or could not be implemented.
<P>
     These reporting members of the Committee believed the best
method to improve new vehicle fleet economy is through increased
fuel economy standards which could be paired with feebates and
incentives such as a "green machine challenge".  New vehicle
fleet economy is made up of: the fuel efficiency of individual
vehicles, the mix of vehicles in the fleet, the mix of technology
in the vehicles in the fleet, and customers' choice of vehicle 
attributes.  Manufacturers can best impact the fuel efficiency of
new vehicles by incorporating new fuel efficiency technology into
their new models.  While the manufacturers' can influence vehicle
mix through vehicle and option pricing, this has less effect on
new fleet fuel economy than does improving the technology offered
on the different models in the fleet.  Analysis of the best in
class models demonstrates this.  If all the cars in each weight
class were as efficient as the most efficient vehicle in that
class, the fuel economy of America's fleet would be 33 mpg
instead of 28.2 mpg.  Offering consumers better technology such
as airbags and multi-valve engines which improve safety and both 
fuel economy and performance increases sales and profits.
<P>
     The new vehicle fleet for each of the three return year
scenarios (2005, 2015 and 2025) will offer at least the same
level of consumer attributes and performance as the present 
vehicle fleet.  Just as there were no restrictions on consumer
choice from 1975 to 1985 when average new car CAFE doubled, there
will be no restrictions on consumer choice between 1995 and 2005,
2015 or 2025.  The emphasis will be on developing and utilizing
new technology to maintain vehicle size and performance while
improving efficiency.  An example of this vision is the evolution
of the Honda Civic from 1975 to 1995.  In 1975, the Honda Civic
had a curb weight of 1650 pounds with a wheel base of 87 inches
and a CAFE rating of 35 MPG.  By 1995, the Civic increased
dramatically in size, weight and fuel economy.  The 1995 Civic VX
had a 103 inch wheelbase, a curb weight of 2540 pounds and a CAFE
rating of 57 MPG.  Despite a 50% increase in weight and a 16 inch
longer wheelbase, the Civic's fuel economy improved by 63%.
<P>
     Policies that increase the variable cost of driving
(especially in proportion to the amount of greenhouse gases
emitted by the vehicle) will increase the entire on-road fleet
fuel economy as well as the fuel economy of new vehicles.  Such
policies reduce the current demand for travel as well and change
the vehicle and attribute mix by increasing consumer demand for
vehicles with higher fuel economy.  Furthermore, these policies
will pull advanced fuel economy technologies into the market by
ensuring that consumers will value them.  Taken together, these
results can significantly reduce greenhouse gas emissions from 
personal transportation vehicles. 
<P>
     We expect progress in fuel efficiency; technological
advances are a hallmark of our industrialized society.  It is the
nature of innovation to provide either similar amenities at 
lower cost or greater amenities without higher costs.  Prototypes
of high fuel economy vehicles exist.  Bringing the improvements
these prototypes embody to market without greatly increasing
vehicle price, and while still meeting government standards and
customer expectations, is the challenge.  The path of
technological progress, while promising, is unpredictable but can
be pushed by government intervention as has so often been 
demonstrated in the past.
<P>
     Technological improvements are integral to achieving
greenhouse gas reduction goals.  Since attainment of the
statutory 27.5 MPG CAFE standards in 1985, ongoing fuel 
efficiency (combustion) improvements have been approximately 1%
per year, but have not recently resulted in commensurate
increases in fuel economy (miles per gallon).  Manufacturers have
utilized improvements in efficiency of engines, transmissions and
accessories to offer more options, size and performance.  The
success of CAFE is perhaps best seen in the 1982 to 1985 time
frame when average new car fuel economy increased by about 5 MPG
while real gasoline prices decreased by over 25%.  CAFE standards
never failed to raise fuel economy levels but they can only
increase fuel economy up to the level of that standard.  Since
1985, there has been no failure of CAFE, just a failure of
regulators and legislators to raise CAFE standards.  While
continuing fuelefficiency improvements will likely occur, the
extent to which they will lead to higher fuel economy is doubtful
without regulatory measures such as CAFE and indirect measures
such as feebates.  Adding VMT-fees or other pricing mechanism
will increase the effectiveness of regulatory measures.
<P>
     Our ability to envision further technological advances in
vehicle efficiency reflects our hope that the country will not
have to abandon the flexibilities and benefits of personal 
mobility.  Higher fuel economy, coupled with policies affecting
vehicle miles traveled and alternative fuels, means that energy
can be saved and greenhouse gas emissions reduced without
sacrificing vehicle ownership or the mobility and utility
valued by the broad majority of Americans, who currently own
passenger cars and light trucks and prize the personal 
freedom they so obtain.
<P>
     What will it take to achieve a degree of fuel economy
improvement enough to meet a national climate action commitment? 
The mechanisms to achieve a substantial measure of fuel economy
improvement will have at its core increased CAFE standards
accompanied by feebates and special market creation programs to
promote purchases of efficient vehicles, committed research and
development efforts to support technological improvements, and 
gradual but expected continuing increases in the price of
driving.  The last need not be accomplished by a net tax
increase, but rather by a VMT-fee increasing the marginal cost of
driving by "incrementalizing" some of a variety of currently
fixed fuel- or driving related costs.
<P>
     Policies addressing on-road fleet fuel economy must be
integrated with those impacting vehicle miles traveled and
alternative fuels.  Indeed, CAFE increases which 
improve the efficiency of cars help promote alternative fuel
vehicles (AFVs) by increasing their driving range and making AFVs
more attractive to consumers.  While significant near-
term fuel efficiency gains can come from existing technology,
large and dramatic efficiency gains of up to three times present
fuel efficiency as envisioned by the Partership for a New 
Generation Vehicle (PNGV) program can come only from successful
research into breakthrough technologies which is then required in
the market by CAFE standards accompanied by feebates and special
market creation programs. Without regulatory requirements to
capture the technological innovations being developed by the many
private and public R&D programs, the 80 to 100 MPG prototypes
will remain just for show and not for go on the roads of the
world.
<P>
<STRONG><A NAME="IIIA3">Descriptions of Recommended
Policies</A></STRONG>
<P>
<STRONG><A NAME="IIIA3a">Increase CAFE Requirements Under Current
Law</A></STRONG>
<P>
<STRONG>
Policy
</STRONG>
<P>
The administration must consider the following criteria when
setting fuel economy standards for cars and light trucks.  The
levels must:
<P>
     1)  be technologically feasible,<BR>
     2)  be economically practicable,<BR>
     3)  account for the need of the nation to save energy,
and<BR>
     4)  consider the impacts of other regulations affecting
automobile fuel economy (e.g. safety and emission requirements).
<P>
The following is an example of the potential GHG reductions that
could be achieved from a CAFE increase.  A 60% overall increase
over ten years starting in 1998 so that new cars reach 45 mpg and
new light trucks reach 34 mpg by the year 2007.  These targets
correspond to standards increasing annually by 1.5 mpg per year
(an average rate for the combined car and light truck fleet). 
For the year 2015, a lesser rate of CAFE standards increase would
meet the target greenhouse gas reductions necessary.  This rate
would correspond to a 40% increase over 10 years or an average
increase of 1.0 mpg per year.
<P>
Corporate Average Fuel Economy (mpg)
<P>
<PRE>
Baseline                           2005      2015      2025
Cars                               28.2      28.2      28.2
Light Truck                        20.9      20.9      20.9

Example Change
Cars                               41.7      58.7      75.6
Light Trucks                       30.9      43.5      56.0
____________________________________________________________
Estimated Impact on Emissions

     If the sales-weighted fuel economy of all cars and light
trucks sold in the U.S. equaled the CAFE levels identified in the
above example, the following reduction in greenhouse gas 
emissions would result:
____________________________________________________________
Reduction in Greenhouse Gas Emissions Resulting from Increased
CAFE Standards (mmMTCe)

                                   2005      2015      2025

Reductions from Policy             36        117       175
Target Reduction Levels            83        163       258

_____________________________________________________________

     The fuel economy levels in this scenario are lower than the
maximum feasible levels obtainable because the set of policy
options chosen sought to use the maximum gains possible from VMT
reductions and alternative fuels with fuel economy increases
being set at the levels necessary to reach the President's goal.
</PRE>
<P>
<STRONG><A NAME="IIIA3b">Feebates for Higher Fuel
Economy</A></STRONG>
<P>
<STRONG>Policy
</STRONG>
<P>
Federal legislation could require rebates proportional to the
extent to which a vehicle's fuel consumption is lower than
average and would assess fees to the extent to which fuel
consumption is higher than average.  For addressing greenhouse
gas emissions, feebates could be based on relative CO2  emissions
per mile.
<P>
     Several approaches can be taken to designing rational
feebate structure that balance the various concerns related to
improvements in fuel economy. For purposes of targeting 
greenhouse gas emissions, all approaches can start with vehicles'
CO2 emissions per mile (gCO2/km), computed from MPG ratings using
full fuel cycle emissions factors.  Three rather distinct
approaches are as follows:
<P>
     (1) Base feebates on crash worthiness and domestic content. 
Such a design would calculate a feebate using two factors.  One
is gCO2/km adjusted by crash worthiness as measured by a dynamic
impact test score.  The other is gCO2/km multiplied by domestic
content.
<P>
     (2) Base feebates on vehicle size with separate treatment of
cars and light trucks.  This design uses the same formula for all
vehicles, based on gCO2/km divided by vehicle footprint.  A
vehicle's feebate would be computed as a weighted sum of the 
size-adjusted term plus one based only on gCO2/km.
<P>  
     (3) Base feebates strictly on gCO2/km, but compute a
vehicle's feebate relative only to other vehicles made by the
same manufacturer fleet.  This approach may or may not 
separately treat cars and light trucks.
<P>
     The relative magnitude of feebates, whatever their
structure, needed to induce a given level of fuel economy
improvement is highly uncertain.  The response depends on a 
parameter called the "feebate rate", which gives the change in a
vehicle fee or rebate corresponding to a change in its fuel
consumption or CO2 emission rate.  This parameter underlies all
feebate structures, which may modify the rate depending on which
other attributes are incorporated into the feebate.  A published
analysis is available for feebate rates of approximately $6 per
gCO2/km and $12 per gCO2/km.  Scoring of feebate proposals for 
likely greenhouse gas emissions assumes use of the $12 per
gCO2/km rate.
<P>
     The greenhouse gas reductions of feebates are integrated
into the CAFE policy.
<P>
<STRONG><A NAME="IIIA3c">Maintain Support for 
Partnership for New Generation Vehicle</A></STRONG>
<P>
<STRONG>Policy
</STRONG>
<P>
Maintain federal support for the Partnership for a New Generation
of Vehicles (PNGV) by continuing congressional authorization and
appropriation of program funding required to achieve a high
probability of success.  
<P>
     This program's goals are:  (1) to produce production
prototype passenger sedans by 2004 with a fuel economy of up to
80 miles per gallon that maintain the size, utility and 
performance standards of today's vehicles - the 1994 Chrysler
Concorde, Ford Taurus, and Chevrolet Lumina, and (2) incorporate
any new technology developed before 2004 into new vehicles as the
technology is developed.
<P>
     The feasibility of realizing any greenhouse gas reductions
from PNGV depends upon increased CAFE, feebates and other direct
measures necessary to force auto manufacturers to utilize the
technology developed through the program.  Without technology
forcing mechanisms, the innovations developed through PNGV will
not likely be introduced into the market place or will be
utilized to increase performance rather than fuel economy.
<P>
<STRONG>
Estimated Impact on Emissions
</STRONG>
<P>
While the outcome of this research project is in no way certain,
successful development of PNGV production prototypes and the
manufacturing technology required to produce them at competitive
cost would demonstrate the feasibility of producing 80-mpg family
sedans.  For the purpose of estimating emission reductions, we
have modeled three scenarios which vary according to the degress
of their success in achieving all program goals and show what
greenhouse gas reductions could be obtained if there were a shift
to production of PNGV sedans.
<P>
     Scenario 1:  All program goals are met.  Production
prototypes introduced in 2004 and vehicle production commences in
2006.  Production increases to satisfy growing consumer demand
but is limited by the capability to shift vehicle production
capacity to PNGV sedans without increasing costs or prematurely
idling the capacity to produce conventional vehicles.  The
maximum long run market share for PNGV sedans is assumed to be
85%.  Average PNGV fuel economy is 80 mpg (passenger cars) and 60
mpg (light trucks).
<P>
     Scenario 2:  A longer lead time is assumed from production
prototype introduction (2004) to mass production (2009).  This
longer lead time reflects current industry lead times.  PNGV
penetration rates grow less rapidly based on a more conservative 
estimate of the capability to shift vehicle production capacity
to PNGV sedans without increasing PNGV costs or prematurely
idling the capacity to produce conventional vehicles.  In
addition, PNGV sedans do not achieve as high a final market share
(60%  instead of 85%).  PNGV fuel economies are the same as in 
Scenario 1.
<P>
     Scenario 3:  This scenario assumes that the fuel economy
goals of PNGV sedans are only partially met. Instead of tripling
passenger car fuel economy (80 mpg), passenger car fuel economy
is only doubled (60 mpg) and light truck mpg only increases to 30
mpg.  In addition, PNGV production does not begin until 2012 and
the final market share of PNGV sedans only reaches 50%.
<P>
<PRE>
PNGV Sales as a Percent of Total Vehicle Sales

          Scenario 1               Scenario 2          Scenario 3

2006           1%                       0%                  0%
2010           11%                      1%                  0%
2015           58%                      21%                 5%
2020           75%                      50%                 36%
2025           80%                      55%                 45%
2030           85%                      60%                 50%
________________________________________________________________

Setting CAFE standards to require the market penetration of PNGV
or equivalent technology vehicles shown in these three scenarios
would result in a reduction of 2025 greenhouse gas emissions as
shown below, measured in million metric tons of carbon equivalent
(mmMTCe).
_________________________________________________________________
Greenhouse Gas Reductions from Continued PNGV Funding
 (mmMTCe) 

          Scenario 1               Scenario 2          Scenario 3

2010           5                        0                   0
2015           46                       11                  2
2020           124                      60                  22
2025           202                      120                 63
2030           272                      177                 105
</PRE>
<P>
     The graph above shows the greenhouse gas emissions (mmMTCe)
for each scenario and illustrates the contribution that PNGV or
equivalent technology can achieve to help reach greenhouse gas
stabilization goals.  The base case (top line) and each scenario
assume constant fuel prices.  All emissions are measured on the
full-fuel-cycle basis.  
<P>
<STRONG>
Costs
</STRONG>
<P>  For Scenarios 1 and 2, the eleven-year cost of the
government's share of PNGV is projected to be $4.6 billion, which
will be matched by the industry partners.  The cost savings 
of scenario 3 have not been estimated. <P>
[GREENHOUSE GAS EMISSIONS GRAPH-unavailable for Internet display]
<P>
The FY 1995 budget for PNGV is $267 million spread over the eight
participating federal agencies. The majority of the federal
support for PNGV is through the Department of Energy (DOE); the
most significant piece is in DOE's Office of Energy Efficiency
and Renewable Energy (EE).  The FY 1996 request for PNGV is $383
million, with $250 million in DOE and $176 million in EE. The
currently anticipated FY 1996 House and Senate appropriations
bills will provide slightly more than half of the
administration's request for PNGV.  The implications of reduced
funding on PNGV's timetable are currently being developed.
<P>
<STRONG><A NAME="IIIA3d">
Consumer Incentives to Purchase Highly Fuel Efficient
Vehicles:</A></STRONG>
<P>
<STRONG>
A Federally Coordinated "Green Machine" Challenge Policy
</STRONG>
<P>
A "Green Machine" Challenge would be a program to foster an
initial market for advanced, ultra-efficient ("next generation")
light-duty vehicles.  This program would represent a set of
"market pull" mechanisms that would complement the "technology
push" policies such as PNGV, and specifically would encourage the
market adoption of technologies and vehicle prototypes developed
as part of the PNGV program.  A green machine challenge might
entail a variety of program elements, such as strategic
procurement of advanced vehicles by government fleets, 
voluntary purchase commitments by private fleets or individuals,
a national advanced vehicle product development competition,
financial incentives for manufacturers or consumers, and
marketing and consumer information efforts.
<P>
<STRONG>
Example Policy
</STRONG>
<P>
     The example policy described here would involve establishing
purchase commitments (possibly backed up by deposits or
downpayments) from government, private fleets, and private
individuals to purchase qualifying vehicles beginning in
2003.  A purchase goal of 50,000 vehicles per year would be set. 
Qualifying vehicles would meet phased "step forward" targets,
defined as follows:
<P>
     In 2003, vehicles having a 100% fuel economy improvement
(compared to 1995 vehicles of similar size, range, and
performance) and meeting LEV emission levels and all applicable
safety standards;
<P>
     In 2008, vehicles having a 200% fuel economy improvement
(compared to 1995 vehicles of similar size, range, and
performance) and meeting ULEV emission levels and all applicable
safety standards.
<P>
<STRONG>  
Estimated Impact on Emissions 
</STRONG>
<P>
     This program is intended to complement the PNGV policy and
is not scored separately at this time. See the PNGV policy
description for combined scoring estimates.
<P>
<STRONG><A NAME="IIIA3e">
Replacement Tire Feebate for Low Rolling Resistance
Tires</A></STRONG>
<P>
Recent technological improvements in tire manufacturing have
facilitated the development of lower rolling-resistance tires,
which can meaningfully increase fuel economy while not
sacrificing safety or performance.  However, low rolling-
resistance tires are more expensive than other tires.  Therefore,
while newer cars are originally equipped with such tires,
consumers often replace the tires, when worn, with higher
rolling-resistant tires, thereby lowering fuel efficiency and
increasing greenhouse gas emissions.  The purpose of this policy
is to encourage owners of both new and older cars to increase
their purchases of low rolling-resistance tires and to discourage
purchases of higher rolling-resistance tires.
<P>
<STRONG>
Policy 
</STRONG>
<P>
Tire feebates will provide a rebate for purchases of tires that
have rolling resistance below a set point, and fees for rolling
resistance levels above the set point.  The zero point is set at
the average rolling resistance of tires of a given size class
that are used on new cars in the immediately preceding model
year.  (Size classes should be large enough to avoid excessive
complexity while small enough to be an incentive to improve
rolling resistance within a class rather than just switch to a
smaller tire.)  The feebate should be structured so that the
price of a tire with 20% greater rolling resistance than the zero
point is approximately 20% higher than the price of the zero
point tire.
<P>
     There is currently a manufacturers excise tax imposed on
tires, based on tire weight, but it only applies to tires
weighing more than 40 pounds, and it expires on September 30, 
1999.  However, it was imposed on all tires, before 1984.  The
feebate would operate as additions and credits to the existing
tax, with the incidence at the consumer level, but payment by
manufacturers.
<P>
<STRONG>
Estimated Impact on Emissions 
<P>
Assumption:</STRONG>
<P>  Feebate applied to aftermarket tire sales for all cars and
half of light trucks beginning in 1997.
<P>
<STRONG>
Baseline:  Climate Change Action Plan Label Option</STRONG><P>
<UL>
     <LI>Labels apply to cars and half of light trucks (virtually
all personal vehicles)
     <LI>Low rolling resistance (LRR) tires increase from 2.5% of
aftermarket share to 20% by 2010
     <LI>Aftermarket tires last four years (50,000 miles)
     <LI>66% of total LDV miles driven are on aftermarket tires
</UL>
<P>
<STRONG>
Tire Feebate
</STRONG>
<P>
Grade A tires are low rolling resistance, Grade C are current
average tire<BR>
<UL>
     <LI>Grade A tires increase fuel economy by 4% as compared to
Grade C
     <LI>Grade A costs $10/tire more than Grade C ($40 per
vehicle)
     <LI>Feebate sets the cost of Grade A tires equal to the cost
of Grade C tires
     <LI>Grade A tires reach 50% market share by 2000, remain
there through 2025
<P>
<STRONG>GHG Emissions</STRONG><BR>
     <LI>30% increase in use over CCAP labeling case
     <LI>4% increase in fuel economy (FE) x 30% of aftermarket x
66% of vehicles = 0.8% reduction in fuel use, GHG
</UL>
<P>
Yields the following reductions in FFC GHG emissions:
<P>
<PRE>
                              2000 2005 2010 2015 2020 2025

GHG Reductions(mmMTCe)        3    3    4    4    4    5
</PRE>
<P>
<STRONG>
Costs
</STRONG>
<P>
     No costs to government (revenue neutral feebate that covers
its own administrative costs).  Net increase in tire costs in
2010:
<P>
Tire costs:    30% of vehicles x 200 million vehicles x
$40/vehicle = $2.4 billion<BR>
Fuel savings:  30% of vehicles x 200 million vehicles x 4% FE
increase per vehicle x 2,500 gallons/vehicle (50,000 miles @ 20
MPG over four year tire life) x $1.15 = $7 billion.
<P>
NET COST: - $4.6 billion (that is to say, it has a net benefit)
<P>
<STRONG>
<FONT SIZE=+2>B.  <A NAME="IIIB">Alternative Fuels and Vehicle
Policies and
Reductions</A></FONT>
</STRONG>
<P>

     In the decades ahead, alternative fuels combined with new
vehicle technology can provide transportation of today's quality
while greatly reducing greenhouse gases (GHG).  In addition to
such emission reductions per se, alternative fuel and vehicle
technologies represent significant opportunities to realize
reduction of criteria pollutant emissions, decrease oil imports,
and to benefit employment generally and the rural economy in
particular.  Finally, as both the world's largest vehicle
manufacturer and the home of the world's most aggressive effort 
to develop and deploy alternative fuels, the U.S. has an
opportunity to lead the world in developing highly-exportable new
technologies for production of new fuels and vehicles.
<P>
     Realization of these benefits will require a sustained R&D
effort which will span at least a decade along with policies that
promote use of alternative fuels and vehicles.  Industrial
participation in this effort is vital to its success, as is
public support.  The government has a legitimate and important
role to play as well.  How can we advocate an active governmental
role in the current political climate?  We believe that the
appropriate role for government is to be responsive to the public
interest by taking actions that would not be undertaken by the
private sector because the time-to-market is too long, the risks
are too high, or because environmental and other benefits to
society are not reflected by market forces.  In particular, the
time horizon for development of new fuels and vehicles is often
long relative to that for private-sector decision making, thus
the need for such fuels and vehicles must thus be anticipated
long before it becomes acute.  Finally, governmental action is
the only option we have to incorporate environmental goals such
as reducing GHG emissions into market-based decision-making since
the market by itself does not value these goals.
<P>
<STRONG><A NAME="IIIB1">Vision:  Alternative Vehicles of the
Future</A></STRONG>
<P>
     The surest way to reduce carbon levels from motor vehicles
dramatically is to develop the pollution prevention technologies
already invented - eliminating the carbon at birth, so to speak. 
This approach to technology development may also propel the
American automobile industry into a strengthened role in a world
that will be eager to buy these cleaner cars.
<P>
     A new family of vehicles can be mass produced and fueled at
total cost per mile traveled comparable to the cost of internal
combustion engines fueled with gasoline.  Nevertheless, it is
likely that until the stock of these new vehicles accumulate and
before the technologies mature, these "cleaner" cars will have a
higher cost than conventional models.  For that reason,
alternative fueled vehicles will likely have a small impact by
2005, and a moderate impact by 2015.  However, with the technical
options already in hand and a sizable engineering and
commercialization effort, a significant portion of travel in 2025
can be virtually carbon free. 
<P>
     Public education must be a vital and sustained element of
this historic, fundamental shift of the nation's largest industry
and consumers favorite possession.  Industry and government must
be together in an education effort as to why this shift is
important.  The education effort should stress the health
benefits of driving vehicles that don't pollute.  The advantages
of not being subject to oil shocks and being able to improve our
balance of payments could all be part of the message as well as
the public policy goals.  Indeed, we are taking a major step
toward strengthening the American automobile industry on a
sustainable basis.
<P>
<STRONG>
Fuels of the Future
</STRONG>
<P>
     Transportation sector options involving alternative fuels
and vehicles are characterized by conversion of an energy source
to a fuel, and utilization of a fuel in a vehicle to provide
mobility.  These processes involve a set of common
infrastructural elements, both off-vehicle (energy
production/extraction, energy conversion, fuel distribution, and
fuel delivery) and on-vehicle (fuel storage, fuel conversion, and
the engine).
<P>
Alternative fuels/vehicles can be divided into the following
categories:<BR><UL> 
     <LI>liquid fuels used in internal combustion engines
     <LI>non-liquid fuels in internal combustion engines (e.g.
natural gas)
     <LI>battery-powered electric vehicles
     <LI>fuel cell power sources.
</UL>
<P>
     Alternative transportation fuels have the technical
potential to almost eliminate greenhouse gas emissions from the
personal transportation sector as low-emission fuels can reduce
vehicular greenhouse gas emissions by 90% or more.  In addition,
these reductions can be achieved in vehicles that are not very
different than we use today.
<P>
<STRONG>
Greenhouse Gas Emissions and Alternative Fuels
</STRONG>
<P>
     This section summarizes the work of Mark DeLuchi, which
provides comparative data for greenhouse gas emissions associated
with various alternative fuel options.  DeLuchi's study
encompasses a variety of greenhouse gasses (CO2, CH4, N2O, NMHC,
NOx) as well as elements of the fuel production/utilization cycle
(vehicle end use, compression or liquefaction, fuel distribution,
fuel production, feedstock transport, feedstock recovery, leaks
and flares, and vehicle assembly and materials).  The table below
presents relative CO2 production for  24 different alternative
fuel scenarios evaluated relative to a base case reflecting the
current status quo.  
<P>
     Of options involving liquid fuels in internal combustion
engines (group  2A), fossil fuel-based options offer at best
modest improvements over gasoline (> the 74% of base case
emissions for LPG).  By contrast woody biomass-based options
offer significant improvements, with emissions relative to the
base case of  25% for methanol, and 2% for ethanol.  Ethanol
production from corn however results in emissions higher than the
gasoline base-case in the DeLuchi study.<A HREF="#note2">[2]</A> 
<P>
     Options involving non-liquid fuels in internal combustion
engines (group 2B) and their respective emission percentages
relative to the base case are natural gas (76%), natural 
gas from wood (29%), liquified hydrogen produced from nuclear
power (82%), hydrides produced from nuclear power (33%), and
solar-derived hydrogen (7%).
<P>
     The greenhouse impact of options using battery-powered
electric vehicles (group 3) depends primarily on the source of
electricity and also on vehicle efficiency.  Thus, use of 
electricity generated from coal increases emissions relative to
the status quo, natural gas-derived electricity is intermediate
at 66% of the base case, and nuclear- and solar- derived 
electricity have much reduced emissions at 7 and 1% of the base
case respectively.  Greenhouse gas emissions for grid-supplied
electricity vary substantially (e.g. emissions 60 to 99% of
base-case emissions) depending on whether the power mix is
assumed to be marginal or average, whether charging is assumed to
be city only or city-highway.  Taking into account these factors
as well as pursuant communication from Dr. DeLuchi, the Committee
used a value of 80% of base-case greenhouse gas emissions for
electric vehicles powered by grid-supplied electricity. 
<P>
     Emission impacts of fuel cell-powered options (group 4) also
vary depending on the energy source, with relative emissions for
methanol derived from coal, natural gas, and wood at 102%, 56%,
and 15% respectively, nuclear hydrides as 15%, and solar hydrogen
at 2%.  For a given fuel, fuel cell-powered vehicles result in
lower emissions than internal combustion engines. 
<P>
<STRONG><CENTER>
Alternative Fuel Options and Greenhouse Gas Emissions
</STRONG></CENTER>
<P>
<PRE>
Fuel/Source                        Greenhouse Gases (%)
                                   Relative to Gasoline

1. Conventional Fuels 
(internal combustion engines)
     Standard Gas (cf RFG)              98.9
     Reformulated Gas                   100
     Diesel (cf RFG)                    84.5

2. Internal Combustion Engines
A. Liquid Fuels
     Methanol/NG                        95.0
     LPG/NG+oil                         74.0
     Methanol/coal                      166.8
     Ethanol/corn                       112.4
     Ethanol/wood                       2.2
     Methanol/wood                      24.9
B. Non-Liquid Fuels
     Natural Gas                        76.2
     Natural Gas/wood                   28.5
     Liq. H2/nuclear                    82.4
     Hydrides/nuclear                   32.7
     H2/solar                           6.5

3. Battery-Powered Electric Vehicles (LDV only)
     Marginal power mix                 98.2
     Coal-powered only                  106.7
     NG-powered only                    65.8
     Nuclear-powered only               6.6
     Solar-powered only                 1.2
  
4. Fuel-cell Powered
    Methanol/NG                         56.2
    Methanol/coal                       102.2
    Methanol/wood                       15.1
    Hydrides/nuclear                    14.9
    H2/solar                            2.4
</PRE>
<P>
     The values presented above represent DeLuchi's current best
estimates. Uncertainties associated with these estimates arise
from several sources.  The following uncertainty categories were
outlined in correspondence with DeLuchi:
<P>
          <em>Technological uncertainty</em>  - e.g. the design
and performance of fuel cells or emission control strategies are
as yet unknown.  These uncertainties are particularly important
for projected performance of technologies that are not yet
mature, which include the majority of scenarios in Table 1.
<P>
          <em>Contextual uncertainty</em>  - e.g. GHG equivalency
factors or emissions of N 2O from fertilized soils.  These
uncertainties are associated with parameters that describe the
natural and anthropic systems in which fuel and vehicle
technologies function.
<P>
          <em>Discretionary uncertainty,</em> - e.g. how will
electric vehicles be driven, what fertilizer loadings will be
used in biomass production, what compression ratios will be used.
These uncertainties reflect how we choose to use technologies
rather than our inability to precisely predict GHG impacts of
known choices.
<P>
     In his presentation to the Committee and subsequent
communications, Dr. DeLuchi stated that:<P>
<UL>
<LI>There can be a very large range between worst-case and
best-case scenarios when these uncertainties are compounded.
<LI>Best estimates are more probable, and in many cases much more
probable, than the most and least favorable estimates;
<LI>The relative ranking indicated by the best estimates is very
robust even in the presence of uncertainty;
<LI>The use of solar or nuclear electricity (either directly in
electric vehicles or in hydrogen-powered fuel cell vehicles) and
the use of fuels derived from lignocellulosic biomass will
greatly reduce and in some cases nearly eliminate emissions of 
greenhouse gases;
<LI>Alternative fueled vehicles offer larger reductions in
greenhouse gas emissions than do either reduction of VMT or
increased vehicle efficiency;
<LI>For the purpose of comparing alternative fuels with
one-another, and of considering the mitigation potential of
alternative fuels together with the potential of fuel economy
improvements and VMT reductions, his advice to the Committee was
to use the best estimates.
</UL>
<P>
The table below presents the alternative fuel options considered
by DeLuchi rank ordered according to best-estimate greenhouse gas
reductions while noting the energy source for each.  It may be
seen that there is a strong correlation between emission
reduction potential and the energy source, with most alternatives
involving solar, biomass, and nuclear energy superior to
alternatives involving natural gas, natural gas generally
superior to oil, and oil generally superior to coal. There is
essentially no correlation between emission reduction potential
and engine type (data not shown), suggesting that the choice of
energy source is a more important variable in determining
greenhouse gas emissions than is engine type. 
<P>
     The available information suggests that there are some
potential "homeruns" with respect to reduction of greenhouse gas
emissions via the use of alternative fuels.  Options in 
this category include those based on solar, nuclear, and
biomass-based energy sources.  The potential of solar and nuclear
options is perhaps intuitive because the associated electrically-
or fuel cell-powered vehicles do not emit carbon.  This is not
the case for many of the biomass-based options, which have per
mile vehicle emissions comparable to conventional fuels. 
Instead, the attractiveness of biomass-based fuels stems from the
CO2-consuming character of photosynthesis, and the resulting
possibility of a sustainable carbon cycle with no net
contribution to the atmospheric CO2 pool.
<P>
     There appears to be a substantial consensus within the
technical community regarding the strong potential of cellulosic
biomass-based fuel options for greenhouse gas mitigation.  
Although ethanol production from corn is also reliant on
photosynthesis, greenhouse gas emissions for corn ethanol are
markedly greater than for cellulosic ethanol because of: 1) 
higher agricultural energy inputs for production of corn relative
to wood; 2) the presence of lignin in biomass, a nonfermentable
component which when burned can provide all process energy as
well as exported electricity for a typical wood feedstock.
<P>
<PRE>
Relative Emission Ranking and Energy Source

          Solar     Woody     Nuclear   Natural   Oil  Coal
                    Biomass             Gas

