</PRE>
<P>
<STRONG>
Overview of Technical Barriers and Non-Greenhouse Impacts
</STRONG>
<P>
     Beyond the greenhouse mitigation potential of various fuel
options per se, additional important issues for evaluation
include: 1) the degree of infrastructure change and/or 
technology development required to implement various
alternatives, and 2) non-greenhouse gas impacts and benefits. 
The table below presents a summary of information pursuant to 
these issues.
<P>
     When GHG reductions are evaluated as a function of the
extent of infrastructure change or development needed, the most
attractive alternatives for near-term impact have large emission
reductions and relatively fewer required infrastructural changes
or development.  Options in this category include wood-derived
ethanol used in internal combustion engines, battery-powered
electric vehicles with low GHG electricity, wood-derived methanol
used in internal combustion engines, battery-powered electric
vehicles with solar electricity, wood-derived methanol used in
fuel cells, wood-derived natural gas used in internal combustion
engines, and solar-derived hydrogen used in internal combustion 
engines.   
<P>
     The Committee's evaluation of infrastructural barriers was
based largely on a survey, in which experts were asked to rate
infrastructural change/technology development with respect to
seven infrastructural elements.  Details of the survey are
presented in Appendix E. 
<P>
     Established fuels (natural gas, LPG and electricity) are
fossil-based, offer GHG reductions up to about 25% relative to
the status quo, and energy source development is not a 
key barrier.  Fuel delivery (from the retail distribution center
to the vehicle) is an issue for all three, and all three have
significant barriers to be overcome in the vehicle area as well. 
The required research intensity is low for LPG, medium for
natural gas, and high for electricity, with the latter rating
primarily attributable to vehicular issues.
<P>
     The non-established fuels (ethanol or methanol produced from
cellulosic biomass, solar electricity, and solar hydrogen) are
non-fossil based, offer greenhouse gas reductions of 75 to 99%
relative to the status quo, and all have energy source
development as a key barrier.  The principal barriers to using
alcohols from cellulosic biomass involve source development 
and especially conversion processes, with infrastructure and
vehicles less significant as constraining factors.  Both low GHG
electricity and hydrogen face significant barriers to
implementation in the areas of source development/conversion,
infrastructure, and vehicles.
<P>
     Several additional barriers to the implementation of
alternative fuels were also considered by the committee.  These
included higher vehicle costs (compared to conventional 
vehicles), limitations on range, uncertainty about resale value,
warranty issues for converted vehicles, lack of familiarity to
sales and service personnel, and lack of standardization for 
infrastructure (including fuel specifications, refueling
infrastructure and units of measure for energy density.) 
Policies to address some of these barriers are described later
in this section.
<P>
     All of the fuel options listed in the table offer the
potential for significant reductions of criteria pollutants.  For
several cases (LPG, natural gas, and the alcohols), the magnitude
of priority pollutants benefits is strongly dependent upon the
manner in which the fuel is used, with greater benefits for more
advanced vehicles that can be anticipated at higher levels 
of market penetration.  In addition, development of domestic
industries for production of non-established fuels represents an
opportunity to create jobs,increase exports, and decrease 
oil imports.
<P>
     The figure below presents GHG emission reductions for
various alternative fuel/vehicle combinations as a function of
the extent of infrastructural change or technology development
needed.  Infrastructural change/technology development is
quantified as presented, based on the following scale:
<P><PRE>
     0, Essentially no changes
     1, Minor qualitative modification to existing
          infrastructure/major expansion
     2, Significant modification to existing infrastructure
     3, Substantially new technology, minor development work
          required
     4, Substantially new technology, major development work
          required; major constraint to implementing 
          alternative  
</PRE>
<P>
     The most attractive alternatives for near-term impact have
large emission reductions (a high value on the Y-axis) coupled
with relatively little required in the way of infrastructural
change (a low value on the x-axis).  Options exhibiting these
features include wood derived ethanol used in internal combustion
engines, battery-powered electric vehicles with low greenhouse
gas electricity, wood-derived methanol used in fuel cells,
wood-derived natural gas used in internal combustion engines, and
solar-derived hydrogen used in internal combustion engines.
<P>
[GRAPH ON INFRASTRUCTURAL IMPACT (not available for Internet
viewing)]
<P>
<STRONG>
<A NAME="IIIB2">Alternative Fuels and Vehicles Policy
Overview</A></STRONG>
<P>
     In the course of its deliberations, the Committee sought to
consider the broad range of alternative fuel and vehicle
alternatives, looking at 24 different alternatives. The 
group also considered policies that were fuel-neutral and
performance-based to as great an extent as possible. 
Notwithstanding a predisposition to be fuel-neutral, 
three fuel-specific policies resulted from a year of intensive
effort.  This result reflects in part the limited range of
alternatives that are likely to offer significant GHG reductions
in the timeframes required by the charge.
<P>
     An important element of the recommendations in the
alternative fuels and vehicles area involves fuel-neutral price
supports available to all liquid and gaseous alternative fuels 
on a GHG emission reduction-proportional basis.  This policy
element is contained within the policy "Enhanced Research and
Development for Liquid Biofuels and Incentives for other 
Low-GHG Fuels" because cellulosic ethanol is the chief
anticipated beneficiary of this policy, and because some
Committee members felt strongly that the establishment of fuel-
neutral price supports should be linked both fiscally and
politically to the current ethanol tax incentive.
<P>
     The Committee considered a comprehensive R&D initiative
encompassing all fuels offering greenhouse gas benefits. 
Although attractive in concept, this was rejected primarily 
because:
<P>
          1)  Different fuels have very different needs in terms
of overall resources and how these resources should be allocated
(e.g. between commercialization and R&D).
<P>       
          2)  In the world outside of our deliberations,
significant components of the rationale for supporting various
fuels will arise due to considerations other than greenhouse
gases.  Since these considerations are different for the 
different fuels, it is difficult to present a common rationale
for an integrated policy, and thus to gain political support -
this dynamic was played out in the Ad Hoc group and would also
exist in broader debates outside of this report.
<P>  
     In light of the potential for expanded use of electric
vehicles, the Committee considered making recommendations with
respect to policies to decrease GHG emissions from the utility
sector.  A decision was made not to make such recommendations,
because utilities play such a small role in transportation today,
because this matter is being examined in other fora, and because
of a sense that the Committee's composition was not well-suited
to consider this issue.  Notwithstanding, the Committee
recognizes significant desirable features of using low
GHG-emitting electricity (or hydrogen derived therefrom) as an
energy carrier for transportation.  We thus strongly urge that
the potential of substantial electricity demand from the
transportation sector be considered in other fora addressing the
utility sector, and that this potential add impetus to the need
for developing low GHG-emitting sources of electricity.
<P>
     It should be noted that electric vehicles are considered in
this report in the Fuel Economy Section as well as the
Alternative Fuels and Vehicles Section.  This is largely 
because the Partnership for New Generation Vehicles (PNGV) is
defined in terms of increased efficiency, and is a negotiated
agreement not easily subject to modification.  The Electric
Vehicle Policy in this section augments the PNGV by providing
commercialization incentives in the form of an extended electric
vehicle tax credit, and by providing for increased R&D on battery
powered vehicles, including fuel cell/battery hybrids.  As 
discussed elsewhere in this report, the PNGV encompasses a
broader range of vehicle alternatives.
<P>
     The Committee's projections indicate that increased fuel
economy and alternative fuel utilization are the major
contributors to realizing target emission reductions in 2015 and 
2025.  It is thus relevant to consider the interaction between
these.  Many combinations of efficiency-improving technology and
fuel substitution are compatible in the sense that they can both
be implemented on the same vehicle.  For example, ethanol or
natural gas can be used in a high-efficiency ICE vehicle or in
many advanced vehicles that are potential outcomes of the PNGV,
and a significant fraction of potential PNGV vehicles are powered
by electricity.  It is desirable that technologies to increase
fuel economy and fuel substitution technologies be developed in
an interactive fashion to maximize overall effectiveness in 
terms of reducing greenhouse gases as well as other benefits.
<P>
References
