<P>  
<STRONG><FONT SIZE=+2><A NAME="IIIB3">Descriptions of Recommended
Policies</A></FONT></STRONG>
<P>
<STRONG><A NAME="IIIB3a">Enhanced Research & Development for 
Liquid Biofuels and Incentives for other Low-GHG Emitting
Fuel</A>
<P>
Policy
</STRONG>
<P>
Increase R&D funding and provide incentives to encourage
production of low greenhouse gas-emitting fuels. 
<P>
     The R&D program targets reducing the cost of
cellulosic-based ethanol via improved biochemical conversion
technology as well as improved cellulosic energy crops and 
procedures for their cultivation.  The program could be broadened
to include biomass-derived methanol if new information were to
suggest that R&D-driven improvements could result in production
costs and greenhouse gas savings on the order of those projected
here for ethanol.  R&D funding would increase from about $25
million per year currently to $50 million in FY 1997, $75 million
in FY 1998, and $100 million per year for FY 1999 to 2005. 
Production incentives would be achieved by establishing an annual
pool of $1 billion available to producers of alternative fuels in
proportion to full-cycle greenhouse gas emissions (based on 
a facility-by-facility audit), with the pool phased-out over the
period 2015 to 2025.  This pool would include the current ethanol
tax incentive, which would be capped at its current overall 
level of $600 million per year and would be phased-out linearly
over the period 2000 to 2010.  Currently, the ethanol tax
incentive is authorized through 2000.  An amount of funds 
corresponding to the difference between $1.1 billion and the
amount of the current ethanol tax incentive in that year would be
allocated to alternative fuel producers on a basis proportional
to reduced greenhouse gas emissions.  Corn ethanol would qualify
either for the remainder of the current ethanol tax incentive or
the greenhouse gas emissions-based incentive, whichever is
greater, but not both.  The incentive to producers would be
through tax waivers and/or direct payment, with the total capped
at $180 per MTCE reduced (or about 54 cents per gallon based on
DeLuchi's wood/ethanol scenario).
<P>
     This policy fosters development of low greenhouse gas
emitting fuels, while also attaching a market value to reduced
greenhouse gas emissions.  A R&D program devoted to liquid
biofuels is consistent with their predicted greenhouse gas
benefits.  Both the possibility of including methanol as well as
ethanol and the availability of incentives to all fuels are 
intended to provide flexibility in pursuing the goal of reduced
emissions.  The production incentive component is designed to
give a large cost advantage to low greenhouse gas emitting fuels
at low levels of production when the technology is least mature,
with per-gallon and per-tonne MTCE subsidies decreasing as
volumesincrease.  Thus, the impact on the Treasury is capped, and
expanded production of alternativefuels will only proceed as the 
fuels become more cost-competitive.  The cost of the policy is
independent of actual ethanol and gasoline prices, both of which
are uncertain.  The magnitude of the subsidy is chosen so 
as to eliminate the cost differential between ethanol and
gasoline, assuming successful R&D to reduce costs and a gasoline
price in between the flat and rising price scenarios.  If the 
actual ethanol-gasoline price differential were larger than
assumed, rates of ethanol market penetration would be slowed
and/or profits for ethanol producers would be smaller, with the 
opposite result if the actual price differential were smaller
than assumed.  The fastest way to get a cellulosic ethanol
industry established, and to begin torealize greenhouse gas
benefits therefrom, is by a transition from corn to cellulosic
feedstocks in existing facilities.  The timing of the phase-out
of the current tax incentive is chosen to give the current
ethanol industry, and the farmers it supports, time to make such
a transition.
<P>
<STRONG>
Estimated Impact on Emissions
</STRONG>
<P>
     Reduced greenhouse gas emissions resulting from this policy
are driven by the assumed amount of ethanol produced.  Based on
work by Committee member Lee Lynd, ethanol production has been
estimated to be 2 billion gallons in 2005, 15 billion gallons in 
2015, and 40 billion gallons in 2025.  Ethanol is assumed to be
blended with gasoline either directly or as ETBE at levels rising
to 17% ethanol by volume. Around 2015, projected ethanol
production will exceed the level at which it can be blended into
gasoline without vehicle modifications and ethanol will begin to
be used as a near-neat fuel (greater than or equal to 85% ethanol
by volume).  The transition from low-level blends to neat fuels
is expected to be market driven with little if any Federal
intervention.  The policy is scored assuming that R&D results in
lower ethanol production costs (50 to 70 cents per gallon 
ethanol), consistent with analyses of R&D-driven improvements by
Lynd et al and by DOE.  Some other analyses have projected higher
prices, however these were generally based on a lower R&D
intensity and/or more near-term application than
considered by the group.   The greenhouse gas impact was derived
from the ethanol production volume assumption and DeLuchi's
estimates of greenhouse gas emissions savings (97 percent
reduction compared to reformulated gasoline).  As an
illustration, the following table presents projected values used 
in scoring this policy for a flat oil-price scenario and R&D
success as projected by Lynd et al.
<P>
<PRE>

                                        2005      2015      2025
                                        ------------------------
Ethanol production (billion gallons)    2         15        40
Ethanol Subsidy (cents per gallon)      50        6.6       0   
GHG Emission Reduction (FFC, mmMTCE)    5.1       38        100
</PRE>
<P>
     Cumulative GHG reduction is about 930 mmMTCE.  Below is a
graph of base case carbon emissions and the impact of this policy
on projected emissions in the sector.  All emissions are measured
on a full-fuel-cycle basis.
<P>
<STRONG>
Cost and Cost Effectiveness
</STRONG>
<P>
     For purposes of scoring this policy, it is assumed that $25
million per year is in the base case in terms of ethanol R&D
costs and that $600 million per year is in the base case for 
ethanol incentive (i.e., the subsidy is scored as costing $400
million per year except between 2021 and 2025, when the incentive
pool falls below $400 million).  Total additional R&D 
spending is $600 million and the total additional incentive is
$8.8 billion.
<P>
<PRE>
                         2005 

Cost ($ billion)         $0.5      $0.4 
Cumulative Undiscounted
Federal Cost ($ billion) $2.6      $6.6 
$/Tonne                  $98       $11 
Cumulative$/
Cumulative Tonne*        $204      $31

*  All preceding expenses up to and including the specified year
divided by all tons saved up to and including that year.
</PRE>
<P>
<STRONG><A NAME="IIIB3b">Incentives for Natural Gas Vehicles and
Infrastructure</A>
<P>
Policy
</STRONG>
<P>
Subsidize incremental vehicle cost, CNG station construction
costs, and fuel costs to achieve critical mass and economies of
scale in the natural gas vehicle (NGV) industry.  
<P>
     This policy consists of four primary components to encourage
large-scale introduction of NGVs in the consumer car and light
truck fleet:
<P>
1)research, development, & demonstration (R,D,&D) support on
reducing the costs of Vehicle Refueling Appliances (VRAs),<BR>
2)federal vehicle subsidies to reduce incremental natural gas
vehicle costs to $500;<BR>
3)federal subsidies to service stations to reduce CNG station
installation costs to $1500/scfm; and<BR>
4)continuation of the Federal CNG excise tax incentive.  
<P>
     VRAs allow households with natural gas access and
appropriate facilities to refuel conveniently from home or from a
commercial site.  This policy provides for $10 million ($2 
million a year for five years) in R,D,&D money to reduce costs to
$1000 installed.  
<P>
     Current NGV incremental vehicle cost is roughly $3500.  This
policy provides for subsidies to reduce the incremental cost to
$500.  This subsidy will be phased-out as NGV incremental costs
approach $500 per vehicle.  It is estimated that at production
levels of 50,000 vehicles, the NGV incremental cost will drop to
$1000 and that at production levels of 200,000 vehicles, the NGV
incremental cost will drop to $500.
<P>
     Current CNG station construction costs for a 100 scfm is
$3000/scfm.  This policy provides for $31 million in subsides to
reduce out-of-pocket costs to station owners to $1500/scfm.  This
subsidy will not be  necessary as production volumes reduce costs
to the $1500/scfm target.
<P>
     This policy also includes the continuation of the Federal
highway motor fuel excise tax incentive equivalent to 12.9 cents
per GGE (gasoline is taxed at the rate of 18.4 cents per 
gallon compared to 5.5 cents per GGE for compressed natural gas).
<P>
<STRONG>
Estimated Impact on Emissions
</STRONG>
<P>
     The driving assumption for estimating greenhouse gas
emissions impacts of this policy is NGV market penetration.  For
purposes of scoring this policy, it is assumed that annual NGV
production/sales reaches 70,000 in 2000 and rapidly
increases to over 1 million vehicles in 2003, eventually
capturing a 10% market share of consumer car and light truck 
sales  [or 6.7% of the total car and light truck market including
fleet sales.  The incremental sales from this policy are assumed
to be in the consumer market only, however].  This rate of 
market penetration is made possible because this policy reduces
some of the major barriers to NGVs by providing incentives for
CNG refueling stations, low-costs VRAs to provide 
refueling at home/on-site, and low-cost fuel.  Though NGV buyers
will pay a $500 premium, their expected payback ranges between
3.3 and 4.9 years.  The greenhouse gas impact was derived from
the CNG usage rate implied by the market penetration assumption
and DeLuchi's estimate of greenhouse gas savings (20 percent
reduction compared to reformulated gasoline on a full-fuel-cycle
basis).  Following is a table of NGV market penetration, stock
penetration, CNG usage, and greenhouse gas impact:
<P>
<STRONG><CENTER>
Estimated Impact of Natural Gas Vehicle Policy
</CENTER></STRONG>
<P>
<PRE>
                         2000      2005      2015      2025 
NGV Market Penetration
     (percent)*          0.5%      6.7%      6.7%      6.7%
Non-Fleet NGV Stock
     (million)           0.1       2.7       12.0      16.5
CNG Use (billion GGE)    --        0.3       5.9       9.7
GHJG Emission Red. 
     (FFC, mmMTCE/yr)    0.1       1.1       5.5       7.7

* Market penetration is based on total sales, though this policy
is scored assuming that all additional NGVs sold due to the
policy are purchased by non-fleet consumers.
</PRE>
<P>
     Cumulative GHG reduction is about 105 mmMTCE.  Below is a
graph of base case carbon emissions and the impact of this policy
on projectedemissions in the sector.  All emissions are measured
on a full-fuel-cycle basis and compared to the constant gasoline
price baseline.
<P>
[Graph not available for Internet viewing]
<P>
     In keeping with the Charter of this Committee, this
assessment focuses upon the personal consumer vehicle.  It is
generally recognized that the use of NGVs in commercial 
fleets can result in even greater benefits.  Therefore, before
this policy option is implemented alone, additional analysis
should be undertaken to ascertain the emissions reduction
potential for larger fleet applications.
<P>
Cost and Cost Effectiveness
<P>
     For purposes of scoring this policy, it is assumed that 1)
VRA R,D,&D is $2 million per year from 1996 to 2000; 2) Stations
are subsidized by nearly $31 million (total) between 
1998 and 2000; 3) Vehicles are subsidized by about $340 million
(total) between 1997 and 2000; and 4) that the Federal excise tax
incentive is continued indefinitely for a cumulative total of
about $17.0 billion.  The table below illustrates costs for this
policy, as well as costs per tonne of greenhouse gas reduction. 
In addition to scoring the cost-effectiveness of this policy in
terms of cost per greenhouse gas reduction, it is possible to
score this policy also taking criteria pollution reduction into
account. Depending on the assumed level of criteria emission
reduction from NGVs, the overall cost-effectiveness of this
policy ranges from $120 to $140 per tonne of greenhouse gas
emission reduction when the value of criteria pollution reduction
is taken into account.<A HREF="#note3">[3]</A>
<P>
<STRONG><CENTER>Estimated Cost of NGV Policy
</CENTER></STRONG>
<P>
<PRE>
                              2005      2015      2025
Cost $ billion                $0.2      $0.9      $1.3
