</PRE>
<P>
<STRONG>
<A NAME="IIIB3c">Support for Electric Vehicles</A>
<P>
Policy
</STRONG>
<P>
Increase electric vehicle (EV) R&D and extend EV tax credit to
accelerate EV introduction into the light-duty vehicle fleet.  
<P>
     For purposes of this policy, EVs are electric drive vehicles
powered by electricity stored by batteries and/or generated by
fuel cells (thus differentiating itself from the likely R&D
outcome of PNGV, hybrid vehicles, that may or may not utilize
electric drive solely).  The two components of this policy are to
double Federal funding for EV R&D from $100 million currently to
$200 million (from the period 1996 to 2005) and to extend the
current EV tax credit, that is set to expire in 2005, ten more
years.
<P>
     Electric vehicles (EVs), including battery and hybrid fuel
cell/battery powered vehicles, represent an opportunity to reduce
greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions significantly because of their
ability to utilize carbon-free fuels and their intrinsic higher
efficiency compared to gasoline vehicles.  They also represent an
important opportunity to reduce urban smog and improve air
quality generally by offering an effective means to reduce mobile
source emissions of criteria pollutants including carbon monoxide
and the ozone precursors: volatile organic compounds, and
nitrogen oxides.  There is potential for even greater 
greenhouse gas emission reductions with electric vehicles as the
greenhouse gas emissions of the electricity used to charge
batteries, and to produce hydrogen for fuel cells, are reduced 
through time through the commercialization of solar energy, wind
power, and biomass as well as the possibility of other low
greenhouse gas sources. These lower greenhouse gas electricity
sources could replace current higher greenhouse gas sources in
the electricity generation grid.
<P><STRONG>
Estimated Impact on Emissions</STRONG>
<P>
     The driving assumption for estimating greenhouse gas
emissions impacts of this policy is EV market penetration.  For
purposes of scoring this policy, it is assumed that EV 
market penetration reaches 2% nationally in 2005, 5% in 2010, and
10% in 2015 and thereafter.  The distribution of vehicle use
would not need to be even throughout the nation.  That is to say,
urbanized areas with high levels of air pollution could take the
lead in the introduction of EVs and the GHG benefits would happen
simultaneously with air pollution benefits making the policy yet
more cost-effective.  This rate of market penetration is made 
guaranteed by providing additional resources for EV R&D and
providing tax credit incentives for consumers to purchase EVs. 
The GHG impact estimates were derived from the gasoline
displacement implied by the market penetration assumption
(assuming an EV displaces one gasoline-powered vehicle totally)
and DeLuchi's estimate of greenhouse gas savings (20 percent
reduction compared to reformulated gasoline on a full-fuel-cycle
basis).  Following is a table of EV market share, stock
penetration, and GHG impact:
<P>
<CENTER><STRONG>
The Benefits of Electric Vehicles for Greenhouse Gas Reductions
</STRONG></CENTER>
<P>
<PRE>
                                   2005      2015      2025

EV Market Penetration (percent)    2%        10%       10%
EV Stock (million vehicles)        0.8       9.7       21.4
GHG Emission Red. (FFC, mmMTCE)    0.4       4.5       9.9
</PRE>
<P>
     Cumulative GHG reduction is about 100 mmMTCE.  Below is a
graph of base case carbon emissions and the impact of this policy
on projected emissions in the sector.  All emissions are measured
on a full-fuel-cycle basis and compared to the constant gasoline
price scenario.
<P>
[Graph unavailable for Internet Viewing]
<P>
<STRONG>
Cost and Cost Effectiveness
</STRONG>
<P>
     For purposes of scoring this policy, it is assumed that $100
million per year is in the base case in terms of EV R&D costs and
that the EV tax credit through 2004  is in the base case.  This
policy incurs a cost of $100 million per year from 1996 to 2005
to account for increasing EV R&D and this policy incurs a cost of
$1 billion per year from 2005 to 2014 to account for extending
the EV tax credit an additional 10 years (the tax credit is
capped at $1 billion per year).  Total additional R&D spending is
$1 billion and total additional tax subsidy is $10 billion.  In
addition to scoring the cost-effectiveness of this policy in
terms of cost per greenhouse gas reduction, it is possible to
score this policy also taking criteria pollution reduction into
account.  Depending on the assumed level of criteria emission 
reduction from EVs, the overall cost-effectiveness of this policy
ranges <STRONG>from (-$10) to (-$40)</STRONG> 
per tonne of greenhouse gas emission reduction when the value of
criteria pollution reduction is taken into account.<A
HREF="#note4">[4]</A>  That is, this policy actually results
in no net cost and <STRONG>a net benefit.</STRONG>
