<P><STRONG><FONT SIZE=+2><A NAME="IIIC">
C.  Vehicle Miles Traveled Policies and Reductions</A></FONT>
</STRONG>
<P>
<A NAME="IIIC1">
Background
</A>
<P>
     Throughout the latter part of the nineteen eighties,
Americans drove more and farther than ever before.  Driving
increased even though we were nearing a saturation point in the
number of Americans with drivers licenses.  Reducing the number
of miles Americans travel is one important strategy for reducing
the consumption of carbon-based fuels, and therefore reducing 
the carbon dioxide emissions that contribute to global climate
change.
<P>
<A NAME="IIIC2">History</A>
<P>
     Beginning with the adoption of a model uniform zoning code
by the Department of Commerce in the 1930s, a series of direct
and indirect government actions paved the way for a new type of
community organization that has dominated our development
patterns in this century.  This new development pattern was
characterized by single use zoning which physically separated
work activities, shopping, and living places from one another. 
The cities and suburbs where most Americans live are thus
structured around the automobile - zoning codes, financing 
systems and tax laws encourage developers to build single family
homes on large lots which are physically separated from daily
activities.  Originally these laws were meant to protect us from 
industrial odors, but now they separate us from a loaf of bread,
from the hardware store and from the elementary school. 
Auto-oriented suburbs introduced new street patterns organized
around cul-de-sacs extending from arterial streets and by road
design standards intended to allow cars to operate at high rates
of speed in residential areas without pedestrian interference.
<P>
     After World War II, a series of governmental decisions
combined with the workings of the market to reorient our economy
around new development. Manufacturing plants that had 
geared up for war time production of weapons, tanks and jeeps,
shifted to automobiles and household consumer projects.  People
who had left the farm or the city to join the war effort 
settled in the West and Southwest, using VA loans to purchase new
single family homes in new suburbs.  By and large, these suburbs
were located on cheap land rendered valuable by federally 
financed infrastructure, particularly the Interstate Highway
System.  Many of these subsidy arrangements and financing
structures continue to this day, only they are now so imbedded
that we call them the working of the free market.
<P>
     As a result, efforts to reduce auto use are swimming
upstream.  In the 1980s  savings and loan deregulation fueled a
new explosion in suburban development along outer beltways all
over America.  Vehicle Miles Traveled (VMT) grew at over 4
percent a year from 1983 to 1990.  According to the National
Personal Transportation Survey, the length of average auto
commutes in urban areas grew by 25.6 percent during that same
period.  Public concern over congestion and sprawl is growing, as
evidenced by a May Newsweek cover story about the decline of the 
suburbs and recent reports about commute-induced stress in the
Washington Post. 
<P>
<A NAME="IIIC3">Policy Overview</A>
<P>
     At the present time, most Americans have no choice but to
drive for most of their trips.  Walking or bicycling is difficult
because streets lack sidewalks or shopping, schools and libraries
are accessible only by motor vehicle.  Public transit is often
not within reach, and when it is, it often is more expensive than
driving and less frequent than one would need.   
<P>
     The goal should be a multifaceted approach that makes the
choice not to drive easier to make, rather than an approach which
seeks to prevent us from driving.   In large part, this effort 
to reduce driving is also an effort to make communities places
people will like to live in and share in, rather than continuing
to create transient places in which we build equity.  
<P>
     The goal cannot be achieved by pouring greater and greater
sums into building more conventional rail and bus systems. 
Rather, we recommend an approach that simultaneously 
provides options to driving while creating market signals which
favor living in communities where alternatives are available and
using those alternatives.
<P>
     Such a multifaceted approach to reducing VMT is outlined
below.  Because changing the way all of us think about getting to
work or picking up groceries, buying a home, and even what 
kind of community we want to live is a significant task, VMT
reductions will be particularly difficult to achieve.   The
policies we advocate will be important to achieving the
President's goal in 2005.  While VMT policies will have a greater
role in reducing greenhouse gas emissions in later years, it is
essential that changes in this area begin now.
<P><FONT SIZE=+2>
<A NAME="IIIC4">Descriptions of Recommended Policies</A></FONT>
<P>
<STRONG><A NAME="IIIC4a">Integrated Land-use Strategies</A>
<P>
Land-Use and Communities:  Creating High Access Livable Places
(HALP)</STRONG>
<P>
     The goal of the policies focused on land use is a deliberate
and gradual removal of government regulations and government
supported market subsidies which favor decentralization 
and single-use auto-dependent development.  In place of these
subsidies would be a set of policies which allow, and even
encourage, resource efficient, mixed use walkable communities.  
Single family suburban development may continue to be the choice
of many-due to schools, employment patterns, race and class
issues among others.  It is necessary, however, to create 
affordable choices of other kinds of communities, and eliminate
market distortions which prevent such communities from
developing. Even suburban communities can be configured to be
much more efficient with mixed use community centers and improved
pedestrian and transit accessibility.  Given that non-work trips
constitute a majority of all trips, improving access to 
shopping, schools, and services from both the suburban residence
and the workplace can help to reduce these trips.
<P>
     Along with more efficient suburban growth patterns, many
people may prefer a more urban lifestyle, including young adults,
"empty nesters", some ethnic groups and perhaps the elderly. 
Policies should ensure that well developed livable communities
are available in urban areas as well and this may entail both
redevelopment and renovation of existing neighborhoods 
and new development in former industrial areas and around
existing or new transit stations and downtown living.  A similar
opportunity exists for the redevelopment of older inner ring
suburbs as they age.  Tremendous private and public capital is at
risk of being stranded as post war suburbs age - in older
shopping centers, strip malls, offices and housing subdivisions. 
Suburban jurisdictions and investors alike need to be given a way
to hang onto the value of these investments and the creation of
High Access Livable Places may be the solution.  Over time our 
goal is a doubling of density in core parts of major cities.  In
many ways this is a modest goal, as a doubling of density in most
of these areas leads only to moderate density development.  Such 
development intensities can, however, support neighborhood
serving retail and transit.
<P><STRONG>
HALP Policies 
</STRONG>
<P>
1.   Development of model zoning codes and parking requirements
in concert with developers, architects, planners, city managers
and other local government and public interest groups.  
<P>
     The model codes would allow mixed use development,  grid
street patterns, sidewalks, mixed income and mixed housing stock
communities.  A similar effort would be undertaken to reduce
parking requirements for transit oriented mixed use livable
places.  These codes would be promulgated as models and
distributed widely by federal agencies including the Departments
of Commerce, Housing and Urban Development, Transportation,
Interior, Energy and Health and Human Services.
<P>
     Model zoning codes promulgated by the Department of Commerce
during the 1930's were widely adopted by counties and cities all
over America. These codes mandated the development of
functionally segregated suburban and exurban communities.  An
ongoing effort of the American Planning Association and the
efforts of a group of architects, planners and developers under
the banner of the New Urbanism both seek to provide alternative
models for both infill and new development.  A new model zoning
code, if coupled with altered parking requirements and traffic
and street standards, could do much to encourage and allow the 
development of mixed use and pedestrian and transit oriented
communities. During its site visit, the Committee met with
developers in Pasadena, California who identified incompatible
local government regulation as a key obstacle to undertaking less
auto intensive development patterns.
<P>
     The federal government's role would be to fund the
collaborative development of model planning, zoning parking and
local street guidelines and then to use federal agencies to 
promulgate these guidelines as new standards for communities
which wish to develop in a more sustainable way.  At the same
time an effort should be initiated to undertake research and 
develop tools which enable cities, counties and regions to
research and understand the long range fiscal implications of
sprawl oriented development on fiscal capacity, tax base,
provision of infrastructure (roads, transit, water, sewer,
telecommunications and power) and the provision of 
services (police, fire, libraries, social services and school). 
The research would result in user friendly products for local
officials to use in planning as well as in considering
development proposals.  The government expenditures on these
programs was estimated by transportation planners on the
Committee to be about $20-25 million.
<P>
2.   Development of programs to encourage the redevelopment of
inner-city properties, especially "brownfield " abandoned
industrial sites and transit and pedestrian oriented 
mixed use communities.  
<P>
     The program would link existing "Clean Sites" programs with
transit oriented development strategies. This option builds on an
existing effort under the "Clean Sites" program to clean up
polluted inner city sites to allow infill development to occur on
these sites.  The project would recognize that clean up is only
one barrier to economic development of abandoned industrial sites
and that other barriers exists, including availability of labor,
relationship to the surrounding community and access to the
transportation network. Many of these barrier require 
an integrated land use and transportation planning solution.  The
project would engage local planners, community developers and
transportation providers in the development of a planning 
process for these "clean sites" that would ensure mixed use,
transit and pedestrian oriented development that provides a high
level of intermodal access.  The federal government's role 
would be both to ensure that these considerations are being
explored and to provide seed funding for the development of these
plans through the Department of Transportation.  A government 
program cost of $2-3 million per affected community is estimated
by the transportation planners on the Committee for the conduct
of a public collaborative planning effort.
<P>
3.   A government led public/private mixed use financing
initiative to identify and end barriers to financing of higher
density, mixed use transit oriented development.  
<P>
     Government regulations and lending requirements were cited
by builders and developers in Los Angeles as preventing the
development of mixed use projects that were very marketable. 
Developers identified a number of problems in amassing the
capital to build higher density, mixed use developments oriented
toward transit and pedestrian travel.  The first problem of 
incompatible local government regulation is discussed above.  The
second problem is the difficulty of obtaining financing for mixed
use projects which combine, for instance, townhomes, 
apartments, retail and some office on the same site, or even for
single family residences with accessory apartments on site. 
Government programs for low income housing finance often do 
not allow mixed uses to occur and the same problem occurs in
securing private capital.  Developers stress that the problem is
not the lack of a consumer demand, but rather the lack of 
recognition of that demand on the part of sources of public and
private capital, particularly in secondary markets.  This project
would attempt to resolve the problem by gathering together 
developers, architects and planners, local government officials
and development finance interests including banks, pension and
insurance investors, public corporations such as Fannie Mae which
provide secondary markets and community development corporations
in an effort to identify and end barriers to obtaining financing
for these kind of projects.  The initial government cost is 
estimated at $1-2 million for both the planning effort and the
research which is likely to be suggested at the conclusion of the
effort.
<P>
4.   Development of a program for location efficient mortgages,
which recognizes the reduced household expenses that derive from
living in dense, transit rich communities and would utilize these
savings in mortgage qualification of prospective homeowners in
these communities.  Further study and development of this concept
with the Administration and the housing finance community is a
necessary first step. 
<P>
     This policy build upon research conducted by John Holtzclaw
and David Goldstein for the Natural Resources Defense Council
which found correlation between reduced driving and 
density and transit access.  The insight which emerged from this
research was that this VMT reduction also results in lower
expenses for driving, which in turn leads to a higher proportion
of household income not devoted to transportation.  These savings
can be calculated as part of the PITI, which is the formula for
calculating the amount of a mortgage a household can support.  
Thus the savings in these neighborhoods can result in the
issuance of Location Efficient Mortgages and in the purchase of
prepaid transit passes to secure the savings.  This strategy has 
been included in the PCSD recommendations and in the President's
Home Ownership Initiative and Fannie Mae has agreed to
participate in a demonstration.  The next step is a rigorous
analysis of market potential in three cities - Los Angeles, San
Francisco, and Chicago - to answer questions on existing research
and to engage the banking and mortgage lending community in 
working out the instruments for LEM.  The government cost of this
initial effort is estimated by transportation planners on the
Committee to be under $2 million.  An option for permanent 
funding is secondary mortgage.
<P>
5.   Development and enforcement of a policy to require
government facilities and services to be located in areas that
are accessible by public transit and accessible to the 
population served.
<P>
     Government facilities contribute to the development of a
culture where there is a lack of alternatives to driving when
they are located in ex-urban areas accessible by automobile. 
Such location decisions force workers and people who need
services to drive, and encourage related development to occur
near the site.  Government facilities can contribute to the
solution rather than the problem by choosing locations
inaccessible communities, with mixed use opportunities 
nearby, by  locating on transit lines and by providing on-site
amenities that lessen the need to travel during the day such as
day care and worker-serving retail.  It is particularly critical
for social service facilities to be accessible, as studies show
that very low income people spend a disproportionately high
portion of their income and time on travel.  This time and
expense spent traveling to services is an expense to government,
as well as time not devoted to looking for work or working. The
transportation planners on the Committee estimated that this
proposal could have moderate costs, because sites in higher
density, transit accessible communities may be more expensive
than 'greenfield sites."
<P>
6.   Reinvention of integrated community development and
infrastructure grant programs at HUD, HHS, DOT, Energy,
Agriculture and other agencies to ensure that the various grants
can be combined to allow co-location of service and coordinated 
development of mixed use projects. 
<P>
     The Administration's Empowerment Zone/Empowerment Community
Program (EZ/EC) included proposal's to streamline and coordinate
grant administration and delivery mechanisms for a variety of
grants and loans that can be used to revitalize communities. 
Both institutions and rules and regulations generally inhibit the
coordination of federal funding streams at the local 
level. These efforts generally involve coordinating social
service and community development funding, but should be extended
to incorporate infrastructure funding and other government 
programs.  The EZ/EC model needs to be implemented and should
also be extended in other areas to allow an integrated approach
to community revitalization and infill, so that for example, 
FTA and FHWA funding for transit and road infrastructure can be
co-mingled with housing and other community development
subsidies. This would allow developers to "write down" the 
development cost for an inner city development so that it is
competitive with lower cost "greenfield" development.  This
approach merely tries to provide the same cost advantage that 
free interstate access and subsidized power and sewer have
offered to exurban locations.   Another example would be the
coordinated delivery of grants to subsidize transit, which now 
originate at FTA and at a plethora of other agencies for
specialized services for the elderly, the disabled, youth and
other population groups, resulting in uncoordinated services. 
The principal government costs of this proposal will be in staff
time in redesigning regulations and rules.  The policy should
result in more bang for the buck.
<P>
7.   Extension of the regional and statewide planning structure
developed under ISTEA to other programs which influence and guide
growth and development -- HUD's new block grants, HHS service
grants, etc.  All should be linked to a regional structure for 
metropolitan planning so that housing, business development and
service delivery can be regionally designed and delivered as part
of regional growth strategies.  ISTEA's regional 
structure should be maintained and the Administration needs to
support the flexibility, planning, public involvement and program
emphases of ISTEA and extend them to other government programs.
<P>
     The ISTEA legislation charges metropolitan planning
organizations with conducting a public, region-wide planning and
programming process in close consultation with state governments. 
For the first time, significant authority is vested in bodies
which cover entire metropolitan regions.  Although these agencies
are experiencing growing pains, the shift to regional decision
making about investment of public capital and coordinated
planning and away from disconnected decision making by local
bodies reflects essential economic reality.   Unfortunately few
other government programs have a metropolitan context,
incorporating center city, older suburb and emerging suburb or
"edge city."  HUD's emerging emphasis on regionalism needs to be
supported, strengthened and explicitly merged with planning
contexts inherently in ISTEA.  Similarly, HHS grants, Department
of Commerce programs, and urban and edge programs at Agriculture,
Interior, Education and Justice need to be given a metropolitan 
context through these collaborative ventures between states and
local governments at the regional level.  Only through creating a
regional investment context and forcing the difficult debates can
economic development needs be balanced with the equity and
environmental imperatives for encouraging higher density, choice
oriented development.  
<P>
     The regional bodies would be charged with making investment
decisions about public capital and public services, rather than
usurping local control over zoning.  The government cost 
of this proposal is estimated by transportation planners on the
Committee to be relatively small.  ISTEA's regional governments
consume a 1% takedown for administration of planning and 
programming.  There would likely be savings from the elimination
of duplicative and competitive investment and services that could
far outweigh the costs.
<P>
8.   This policy involves the development of a bicycle and
pedestrian infrastructure in communities throughout America
through continuation of ISTEA funding programs and through the
development of zoning codes which stress accessibility.  A key
part of it is the revision of design standards as per current
National Highway System legislation to provide for access to
other modes on highway projects.  Another component might be the
education of the public and local government on the importance of
sidewalks in creating safe and livable places.  This policy would
make bike paths available on all major roads in urban areas with
over 1 million people (top 38 Metropolitan Statistical Areas
(MSAs)).
<P>
     Most suburban communities developed after World War II lack
pedestrian or bicycle accessibility.  Where sidewalks exist, they
are discontinuous and often connect residential areas 
internally without connecting shopping or service oriented
developments.  This policy proposes a federally assisted program
to reclaim safe communities through making sidewalk retrofit an 
eligible category for federal highway funds in the Surface
Transportation Program.  In addition, FHWA law would be amended
to be clear that pedestrian and bicycle access is eligible on all
new federally assisted projects.  An additional 2.5 cents is
scheduled to be returned to the Highway Trust Fund and the Mass
Transit Account this next year and the increased eligibility 
could be incorporated into and made a priority for the
Administration's proposal for the reauthorization of ISTEA. 
Public support for sidewalk and bicycle projects is high, both
for transportation of adults and to ensure safety and
accessibility for children, who are increasingly 
impacted by high speed auto traffic.  This proposal would simply
add eligibility and priority for a new spending category in the
Federal Aid Highway program.  Existing programs and eligibility 
for bike and trail construction in ISTEA should be preserved.
<P>
     Bicycle lanes are assumed to boost bike trip mode share. 
0.7% of all trips are currently made by bike.  The bike commute
rate is more than 3 times greater in areas where the ratio of 
bike lanes to arterial miles exceeds 0.35 than where it is below
0.35 (Goldsmith, 1993), and it is assumed that only 8 of the top
38 MSAs currently have bike lane to arterial miles ratios greater
than 0.35.  The effect of this policy is assumed to increase bike
mode share to 2.1% of all trips.  Every 1% increase in bike mode
share is assumed to reduce VMT by .2% (the average bike trip 
is much shorter than the average auto trip) (Goldsmith, 1993).<A
HREF="#note5">[5]</A>
<P>
<STRONG><A NAME="IIIC4b">Fixed Route and On-Demand Transit</A>
<P>
Policy</STRONG>
<P>
This policy would make transit service - either fixed or flexible
route - available in all communities with populations above
200,000, only as land use and other infrastructural changes can
produce ridership for these services.
<P>
     "Supply push" transit strategies by themselves have shown
limited success in increasing ridership.  Our survey of the
literature on the impact of improving fixed-route public transit
and reducing wait time suggests that these two policies together
would reduce national VMT only minimally.  For this reason, these
policies should be phased-in as land use changes occur, as the
land use changes will produce most changes in transit ridership.
<P>
     Under this policy, fixed route public transit would be
available at 20 minute intervals within 0.25 miles of every
residence in urban core areas of cities with over 1 million
people.  This transit would be subsidized to be comparable to the
cost of driving.  On-demand transit service would be available
and competitively priced in all communities with populations 
above 200,000 with 1 hour advance reservation.  Transit services
would include subscription services, dial-a-ride, jitney
operations, expressway shuttles, or taxis.  These services would 
have access to and utilize the latest information technology
available.
<P>
<STRONG>
Estimated Impact on GHG Emissions from HALP Strategies
</STRONG>
     In an effort to evaluate the greenhouse gas reducing impacts
of combined land use and fixed route and on-demand transit
policies, a qualitative and quantitative approach was 
used.  A survey of all studies of any of these changes that have
already occurred around the US was undertaken, and projections of
reductions in VMT were made based on reported results to date.

<P>     Projected reductions in VMT were then used to calculate
GHG reductions, with some discounting to take doublecounting of
VMT reduction effects into consideration.
<P>
     It is presumed that reductions in these policies will be
phased in over time, as impacts from land use and lifestyle
changes are slower than those from "shock" impacts like sudden 
pricing changes or oil shortages.  Primarily these impacts are to
be seen from creating the density to allow walkable, mixed use
environments.  In an effort to prevent double counting 
we have not calculated an additional impact from creating a
pedestrian environment, assuming that the VMT/density
relationship would account for both.
<P>
     The effect of transit on VMT is inextricably linked to the
cluster of land use policies.  Improved transit service is
integral to the success of the land use policy cluster.  Moving
people out of their cars is accomplished both by supplying more
alternatives and by boosting demand for alternatives.  In this
case, better transit provision is the supply side of the 
equation, and policies to increase land use density are the
demand side.
<P>
     Transit ridership changes would flow from three factors:  1)
service expansions would increase coverage, 2) waiting time would
be reduced, and 3) prices would be comparable to driving.  Each
would have an impact on VMT and thus an impact on emissions.  The
emissions reduction would be offset by increased emissions from
transit service expansions, and the estimate is discounted
accordingly.  
<P>
     An integrated analysis of the greenhouse gas reductions from
land use changes, bicycle and pedestrian access, and improved
fixed-route and on-demand transit shows the following reductions:
<P>
<STRONG><CENTER>
Estimated Impact from Policy on GHG Emissions
</STRONG></CENTER>
<P>
<PRE>
YEAR                2005      2015      2025

Reductions(MMT)     5.3       12.7      22.7
</PRE>
<P>
<STRONG><A NAME="IIIC4c">Workplace Parking Subsidy
Reform</A></STRONG>
<P>
     Currently, a major federal subsidy for driving alone is the
employee tax exemption for employer-provided workplace parking. 
Employees do not have to pay taxes on such parking benefits of up
to $160 per month.  Technically, the subsidy is a tax-exempt
fringe benefit.  Employer-provided transit benefits are tax-
exempt only up to $60 per month.  No tax-exempt benefit at all is
available to cover other commuting costs incurred by workers who
walk, bike, or rideshare (such as shared vehicle costs, other
than workplace parking, in a carpool).  Neither can employers
offer taxable cash instead of the parking benefit.  Thus, the tax
code's current preferential treatment for workplace parking is an
incentive for commuters to drive to work alone rather than
carpool or use alternative commuting modes.
<P>
     Short of completely eliminating the workplace parking
subsidy, it could be substantially reformed by equalizing the
federal tax benefit for any commuting mode and making the benefit
contingent on an employers' offering a taxable cash allowance
instead of the benefit.  A unified tax exemption capped at $100
per month for any employer-provided commuter benefit, not just
parking, would create a level playing field among commuting modes
without added cost to the U.S. Treasury.  Commuting modes covered
would include transit, car or van pools, walking, bicycling, and
telecommuting, as well as parking.  Employers offering a parking
benefit would also be required to offer the value of the benefit
as taxable cash in lieu of a tax-exempt parking or other direct
receiptable commuting expense benefit.  A weaker version of this
policy was proposed in the 1993 Climate Change Action Plan. 
Maximum benefits and greater fairness are obtained by a broader
policy that fully levels the tax benefit playing field among
workplace commute modes for all employees and also makes any such
employer-provided parking benefit contingent upon employees also
being offered taxable cash equivalent to the fair local market
value of the parking subsidy.  It is this last provision that
will provide the greatest incentive for commuters to shift away
from solo driving.  In order to insure equity for low income
workers, families which qualify for the earned income tax credit
would be exempted from the tax implications of this policy.
<P>
     Because of the limited experience with changing the economic
signals faced by commuters, emissions reductions estimates for
this policy are quite uncertain.  In the October 1993 Climate
Change Action Plan, greenhouse gas emission reductions of 6.6 MMT
in 2000 were estimated for the version of this policy that was
somewhat more restrictive in scope, but was assumed to be applied
in combination with other measures to reduce VMT.  Other impact
estimates for even the broader version recommended here are much
lower (less than 1 MMT).  Here we use estimates developed by the
Analytic Support Group (ASG) by assuming a parking ramp-up of the
"opportunity cost" created by a less stringent version of this
reform.  The ASG also provided even higher estimates, but these
were found to be highly implausible by some Committee.  The
working estimates adopted here are emissions reductions of 6 MMT
in 2005, 11 MMT in 2015, and 22 MMT in 2025.  These estimates are
based on an assumption that the policy would suffice to create a
well-functioning "market" among workplace commute modes and
technical parameters of: (1) the policy affects only the
metropolitan share (61%) of overall commuting VMT; (2) 50% of
cars in metropolitan areas are receiving an employer-provided 
parking benefit; (3) a parking price elasticity of -0.16; (4) a
base marginal driving cost of $0.09 per mile, which includes fuel
plus tires and vehicle maintenance; and (5) the monthly 
"opportunity cost" of workplace parking ramps-up to $30 by 2005,
$50 by 2015, and $80 by 2025.
<P>
<STRONG><A NAME="IIIC4d">Shifting The Cost of Driving</A>
<P>
Background
</STRONG>
<P>
     Federal Highway Statistics show that, in 1993, $87 billion
was spent by federal, state and local governments to build and
maintain roads.  A direct comparison of variable user fees 
collected (gas taxes and tolls) and expenditures reveals a
shortfall of $36 billion.  Of the $24 billion raised in gas taxes
at the federal level, however, only $13 billion is available for
road and highway expenditures (the remaining $11 billion is
dedicated to deficit reduction, mass transit, and the leaking
underground storage tank fund).  When the variable user fee
revenue which actually funds road and highway expenditures is
compared to annual outlays, the shortfall becomes $47 billion.    
<P>
     Further, up to $20 billion of road-related expenditures are
currently financed through property taxes and general
appropriations (i.e., income and sales taxes), and bond issue 
proceeds plus investment income at the state and local level add
nearly $13 billion.
<P>
<STRONG>
Proposed Policy
</STRONG>
<P>
     This policy begins to shift the costs of road building and
maintenance which road users do not now directly cover and it
turns these costs into a Vehicle Miles Traveled (VMT) 
fee.  This measure is revenue neutral and will not have any net
new costs to consumers.  Given the other policies proposed in
this report, a VMT charge of 1.22 cents per mile would 
close the gap and return to 1990 GHG levels by 2005.  This
approach would effectively convert some of the fixed costs of
driving (which are currently sustained by a range of non-
driving related taxes and fees) to marginal costs.  In addition,
this policy would reduce the demand for driving and increase
demand for more fuel efficient vehicles.  This policy could 
be further enhanced by creating a formula which incentivizes fuel
economy, i.e. VMT multiplied times the class of fuel efficiency
rating would establish the fee.
<P>
     Equity is our prime concern when developing a plan to
implement this proposal to shift state and local road subsidies
to cost-of-driving fees.  Equity concerns include the need 
to protect low income individuals, the need for provision for
alternatives to driving and the need for fair distribution of
revenues among state and local government to replace general 
funds currently spent on roads.  Therefore, it is essential to
involve fully state and local government representatives, as well
as low-income and community organizations, in the deliberations
that will be needed to develop a workable, effective, and
equitable proposal for this policy.
<P><STRONG>
GHG Emissions Reductions
</STRONG>
<P>
     To achieve the goal in 2005 the average cost-of-driving
shift would require a 1.22 cents per mile VMT fee, which is
equivalent to a $.28/gallon increase in fuel price by 2005.  
This VMT fee would ramp up to 1.22 cents by 2005 and remain fixed
thereafter.  The following estimates are based on running the GHG
accounting model developed for the Committee's use.
<P>
<PRE>
                         TARGET YEAR 2005
                    (average 1.22 cent/mile fee)

YEAR                2005      2015      2025
REDUCTIONS          30.0      32.0      30
</PRE>
<P>
<STRONG>

Cost of Policy</STRONG>
<P>
     Estimates of the social cost of VMT fees are not readily
available.  However, as with any incentive-based policy the fees
can be expected to be relatively cost-effective, though not 
as cost-effective as policies that target fuel economy as well as
VMT.  The fees also will produce auxiliary benefits from
reductions in urban air pollution.  The fees also will increase 
the efficiency of road use by making more of the road-related
cost of travel directly apparent.
<P>
Notes:
<P>
<A NAME="note1">1</A> President Clinton's Climate Change Action
Plan, October 1993.<BR>
<A NAME="note2">2</A> There is significant diversity of opinion
with respect to greenhouse gas emissions for corn ethanol. 
Marland and Turhollow (4) estimate a 20 to 40%  reduction in net
CO2 emissions, while the USDA (5) estimates a roughly 30% 
reduction in CO2 emissions and little or no net increase in N2O
emissions.  Evaluation is somewhat more complicated for 
corn ethanol than for many other options because of the matter of
properly allocating energy inputs for animal feed 
coproduction.<BR>
<A NAME="note3">3</A> We used emission avoided-cost values of
$3,050 per ton for VOCs, $2,750 per ton for NOX, and $300 per ton
for CO.<BR>
<A NAME="note4">4</A> We used emission avoided-cost values of
$3,050 per ton for VOCs, $2,750 per ton for NOX, and $300 per ton
for CO (as used in DOE's National Energy Strategy).<BR>
<A NAME="note5">5</A>  Case Study No. 1: Reasons Why Bicycling
and Walking Are and Are Not Being Used More Extensively as Travel
Modes, for FHWA, 1993, as cited in the September 1993 Comsis
document entitled Implementing Effective Travel Demand 
Management Measures: Inventory of Measures and Synthesis of
Experience.
<P>
