<html>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<pre>

	SUSTAINABLE ENERGY COALITION
	315 Circle Avenue, #2; Takoma Park, MD 20912-4836
	301-270-2258; fax: 301-891-2866


	AMERICA SPEAKS OUT ON ENERGY:
	A SURVEY OF 1996 POST-ELECTION VIEWS

	Released:  December 1996

	survey results gathered in November 1996 by
	Research/Strategy/Management, Inc.
	Project Directors: Dr. Ronald H. Hinckley, Dr. Vincent J. Breglio
	9344 Lanham-Severn Road, Suite 102, Lanham, MD 20706
	(301-306-0844; fax: 301-306-0711)


Introduction:

This survey presents the results of a national survey of 1,200 registered 
voters on sustainable energy issues.  The study was conducted November 9 
- 14, 1996 immediately following the election and included questions on 
how respondents voted for President and Congress.  The margin of error is 
+/-2.9 percent.  The fifteen questions summarized here address:

	* 	the public's funding/budget cutting priorities for the 
		U.S. Department of Energy's (DOE) research and development 
		programs;
	* 	public support for the U.S. Environmental Protection 
		Agency's Green Lights, Energy Star, and other voluntary "green
		programs;"
	*	future funding of the federal government's nuclear \
		pyroprocessing program;
	*	priorities among competing energy sources for federal tax 
		support;
	*    	support for federal tax incentives to promote renewable liquid
 		fuels, notably ethanol-	blended gasoline;
	*	whether the government should set stronger energy efficiency
		standards for appliances;
	*	the seriousness of the threat of global climate change caused
		by emissions from the combustion of fossil fuels;
	*	whether the United States should sign an international 
		agreement to set mandatory limits on the emission of 
		greenhouse gases;
	*	views on options for federal electric utility 
		restructuring legislation including:
			- mandating that electricity generators include 
			  renewables in their energy mix;
			- using a Renewable Portfolio Standard to promote 
			  increased use of renewables;
			- requiring utilities to invest in energy 
			  efficiency programs;
			- disposing of so-called "stranded nuclear 
			  assets;" and
			- establishing comparable environmental standards 
			  for all utility fossil-fueled plants.                            

DOE Research and Development Funding and Cutting Priorities:

Respondents were reminded about the budget cuts facing federal 
departments and agencies as Congress and the Administration try to reduce 
the deficit.  With this as a back drop, they were asked about five energy 
research and development (R&D) programs:  renewable energy (i.e., solar, 
wind, geothermal, biomass, and hydroelectric power); nuclear power; 
technologies to improve energy efficiency and conservation; fossil fuels 
such as oil, gasoline, and coal; and natural gas.  People were asked 
which of these programs should receive the highest priority for funding 
in DOE's research and development budget and which should be subject to 
funding cuts first.

Renewable energy programs receive the most public support for R&D funding 
priorities (34%) followed by energy efficiency and conservation (22%) for 
a combined total of 56%.  By comparison, only 10% cite natural gas as 
their first priority for federal R&D funding, followed by other fossil 
fuels (10%) and nuclear power (9%).  About 15% of the respondents did not 
select one of the offered responses.  Thus, nearly two-thirds (66%) of 
those who expressed a preference among the proffered choices (56% out of 
85%), select either DOE's renewable energy or energy efficiency R&D programs.

Support for renewable energy and energy efficiency programs cut across 
political party lines with 51.4% of Republicans, 62% of Democrats, 54% of 
Independents, and 57% of Reform Party members choosing these technologies 
as their top priorities.

When the topic shifts to budgetary cuts, the public focuses on two of 
these programs: nuclear power and fossil fuels.  Nearly a third of the 
respondents (31%) select nuclear power as the first R&D program that 
should be subject to budget cuts followed by fossil fuels (21%) for a 
combined total of 52%.  By comparison, 13% select renewable energy 
programs as the first that should be subject to budget cuts, followed by 
natural gas (6%) and energy efficiency (5%).  About a quarter of 
respondents (25%) did not express a preference among the proffered 
choices (which may indicate that a large segment of the public is not 
conversant with sustainable energy issues).  Thus, over two-thirds (69%) 
of respondents offering a preference among the proffered choices (52% out 
of 75%) recommend cutting funding for either nuclear power or fossil fuel 
programs.  

Again, these views were bipartisan and consistent regardless of the 
respondent's political affiliation with 48% of Republicans, 53% of 
Democrats, 53% of Independents, and 61% of Reform Party members choosing 
nuclear power and fossil fuels as their top priorities for making energy 
R&D budget cuts.

The public's funding and budget cutting priorities found in this survey 
are virtually the same as responses to identical questions asked in a 
December 1995 survey of 1,000 registered voters conducted by 
Research/Strategy/Management (R/S/M) for the Sustainable Energy 
Coalition.  In addition, the same ordering of priorities was found in a 
December 1994 R/S/M survey also conducted for the Sustainable Energy 
Coalition.  


U.S. Environmental Protection Agency's "Green Programs":

Respondents were informed of the "Green Lights," "Energy Star" and other 
voluntary EPA programs that encourage private industry to invest in 
cost-effective, energy-efficient improvements in their facilities.  They 
were asked whether funding for these programs should be increased, 
decreased, or maintained at current funding levels.

A plurality (45%) favor maintaining funding at the current level and 24% 
favored increased funding.  Thus, over two-thirds (69%) of respondents 
favor either maintaining or increasing funding levels for these programs 
while just slightly more than a quarter (27%) recommended cutting 
funding.  Only 4% of the respondents did not offer an opinion.

Again, support for these programs is bipartisan.  Nearly three-quarters 
(75%) of Democrats favor maintaining or increasing funding for these 
programs as do 62% of Republicans, 70% of Independents, and 66% of Reform 
Party members.

A similar question in a December 1995 R/S/M survey conducted for the 
Sustainable Energy Coalition found only 50% of respondents in favor of 
retaining funding for EPA's "green programs" while 41% favored cutting 
funding to help balance the federal budget.


Nuclear Pyroprocessing:

Respondents were presented with a lengthy question that outlined the 
arguments in favor of, and in opposition to, the federal government's 
nuclear pyroprocessing program which separates plutonium and uranium from 
the nuclear waste generated by the now-terminated "breeder" nuclear 
reactor system.  They were then asked whether Congress should continue to 
fund this activity.

A plurality of respondents (44%) were either strongly or somewhat opposed 
to Congress funding this program.  By comparison, 17% strongly felt 
Congress should fund this program and 23% somewhat believed this 
(combined total of 41%).

Nearly a sixth (15%) of the respondents did not offer an opinion possibly 
reflecting the complexity of the issue and the lack of familiarity with 
nuclear pyroprocessing by many voters.

Thus, among those respondents offering an opinion (44% out of 85%), a 
majority (52%) expressed some measure of opposition to continued funding 
of the program.

Opposition to continued funding was particularly strong among respondents 
identifying themselves as Republicans or Independents which may prove a 
factor in how the Republican Congress addresses the issue during the 
coming year.  Among those who voted for the Republican candidate in the 
recent congressional elections, 54% of those offering an opinion (or 47% 
out of 86%) are somewhat or strongly opposed to continued funding for the 
nuclear pyroprocessing program compared to only 16% strongly in support 
and 30% somewhat in support (combined total of 46%).  

Among Republican respondents offering an opinion, 54% (or 45% out of 84%) 
were opposed to continued funding as well as 54% of Independents (or 48% 
out of 88%) and 53% of Reform Party members (or 43% out of 80%).  
Democrats were evenly split on the issue (43% opposed and 43.0% in support).


Tax Incentives for Energy Development:

Respondents were asked which energy sources should receive federal tax 
incentives to attract private sector efforts to develop and promote 
them.  The question specifically focused on five energy resource 
categories:  renewable energy (i.e., solar, wind, geothermal, biomass, 
hydroelectric), energy efficiency and conservation, natural gas, other 
fossil fuels (i.e., coal, oil, gasoline), and nuclear power.

The responses closely parallel voters' priorities for federal funding of 
energy R&D programs.  More than a third (35%) of respondents chose 
renewable energy as their top priority for federal tax incentives 
followed by 17% for energy efficiency for a combined total of 52%.  By 
comparison, only 9% supported tax incentives for fossil fuels, 8% for 
natural gas, and 7% for nuclear power.  Nearly a quarter of the 
respondents either offered no opinion (16%) or felt that none of these 
technologies should be given tax incentives (9%).  

Thus, among those stating a preference, nearly two-thirds (62%) supported 
tax incentives for either renewable energy or energy efficiency efforts 
(i.e., 52% out of 84%).

Again, support for renewable energy and energy efficiency cuts across all 
party lines.  Among Republicans stating a preference, 63% favored 
sustainable energy technologies (48% out of 76%);  this was also true for 
73% of Democrats (54% out of 75%), for 74% of Independents (56% out of 
76%), and 75% of Reform Party members (57% out of 75%).

A majority of voters (57%) felt that tax reform should be a very high or 
top priority for the 1997 congressional agenda and 73% of respondents 
indicated that cutting taxes made a real, or at least some, difference in 
how they voted for Congress.  Nonetheless, support for sustainable energy 
tax incentives remains strong and may be increasing.  In response to an 
identical question asked by R/S/M in a December 1995 survey conducted for 
the Sustainable Energy Coalition, 61% of those expressing a preference 
(49% out of 80%) stated their support for renewable energy and energy 
efficiency tax incentives compared to 69% in November 1996. 


Ethanol and Renewable Liquid Fuels:

Respondents were informed that the United States currently imports more 
than half of its oil from foreign countries and that dependency will 
increase over the next 10 years.  They were then asked whether the U.S. 
should continue to give tax breaks or subsidies to oil companies as a way 
to ensure a steady supply of oil or instead redirect these tax breaks to 
encourage the increased use of domestically produced renewable fuels from 
biomass.  They were also asked whether they support or oppose continuing 
the 5.4 cent/gallon federal tax exemption for ethanol-blended gasoline.

By an overwhelming majority (83%), voters stated their preference for 
redirecting tax breaks to renewable fuels while only 10% felt they should 
continue to be given to oil companies.  This pattern was reflected by 
virtually identical margins across all party lines.  A small number of 
voters (4%) felt there should be no tax breaks given at all and 4% 
offered no opinion.  

Support for renewable fuels was particularly strong in the Midwest (85%) 
where ethanol-blended fuels are commonplace and in the Northeast (86%) 
which is particularly dependent on more costly home heating oil.  In 
addition, women favored a shift (87% compared to 78% for men).  

By margins almost as large, voters strongly or somewhat support (71%) 
continuing the federal tax exemption for ethanol-blended gasoline while 
only 20% oppose it strongly or somewhat.  Party affiliation appears to 
have no impact on the level of support with 70% of Republicans, 73% of 
Democrats, 68% of Independents, and 73% of Reform Party members strongly 
or somewhat supporting the tax exemption.  Perhaps not surprisingly, 
strong support (74%) was found among voters in the Midwest.  



Appliance Energy Efficiency Standards:

Respondents were asked whether the government should continue to 
strengthen efficiency standards for new refrigerators, clothes washers, 
hot water heaters, and fluorescent lighting equipment.  They were told 
the alternative was not to strengthen them any further because current 
standards are good enough and more efficient products would be more 
expensive to purchase.

Nearly two-thirds of voters (65%) strongly, or at least somewhat, favor 
strengthening appliance efficiency standards while only 29% somewhat or 
strongly oppose new standards.  While the strongest support comes from 
Democratic voters (78%), even a majority of Republicans (53%) expressed 
their support.  In addition, 62% of Independents and 69% of Reform Party 
members favor strengthening the standards.

Last year, the Republican Congress had imposed a one-year moratorium on 
the issuance of new appliance efficiency standards.  Yet, among those who 
voted in November 1996 for the Republican candidate for Congress, 56% 
favored strengthening the standards while only 40% expressed some degree 
of opposition.  Support also extends across all geographic regions with 
support particularly strong in the Northeast (72%), followed by the 
Midwest (65%), West Coast (65%), and South (62%).

Significantly, voter support for the government continuing to strengthen 
appliance efficiency standards comes at a time when a majority (56% vs. 
35%) feel -- when asked about the role of government in the economy -- 
that the government is generally doing too many things.

In response to a similar question asked in December 1995 by R/S/M in a 
survey conducted for the Sustainable Energy Coalition, only 48% of voters 
favored having the government continue to strengthen appliance efficiency 
standards while 46% preferred letting the market place determine new 
standards.


Climate Change:

Respondents were asked how serious they thought the threat of global 
climate change was from burning fossil fuels such as coal, oil, and gasoline.

Over seventy percent of voters (71%) view global climate change as a very 
serious (34%) or somewhat serious (37%) threat.  On the other hand, 17% 
of voters believe climate change to be not too serious a threat and only 
9% consider it to not be a threat at all.  

A very small number of respondents (3%) expressed no opinion on the issue 
-- the smallest percentage of undecided voters responding to the 15 
questions in this survey.  This suggests that global climate change is an 
issue with which most voters have some familiarity and a solid opinion.

For example, despite an aggressive public relations campaign during the 
past year by industry groups challenging whether the combustion of fossil 
fuels can lead to global climate change, public concern about this issue 
has not diminished.  In response to an identical question in a December 
1995 survey by R/S/M conducted for the Sustainable Energy Coalition, 71% 
of voters stated that they viewed global climate change to a serious 
threat -- virtually unchanged from the 71% who held this view in November 
1996.    

Concern about global climate change extends across all political party 
affiliations with Democrats (82%) and Reform Party members (83%) most 
likely to view it as a very serious or somewhat serious threat.  This 
view is shared by 72% of Independents and 56% of Republicans.  

Among voters who cast their ballots for President Clinton in November 
1996, four out of five voters (80%) agreed that global climate change was 
somewhat or very serious.  This may be significant as the Administration 
assesses how aggressively it wants to pursue domestic options to address 
climate change as well as an international agreement to control 
greenhouse gas emissions.

Even among respondents who voted for a Republican candidate in the recent 
congressional elections, 54% said that climate change was a serious 
threat while only 26% felt it was not too serious and 16% felt it was not 
a threat at all.  Again, this may be significant because it may be a 
Republican Congress that will have to ultimately approve any 
international treaty to limit greenhouse gas emissions and subsequent 
implementing legislation.

Of particular note, women were significantly more likely to view climate 
change as a serious threat (77% compared to 62% for men).  And, perhaps 
less surprisingly, among voters who believe that the environment should 
be a congressional priority in 1997, 85% view global climate change as a 
serious threat.


International Climate Change Agreement:

Respondents were told that the United States is considering signing an 
international agreement by the end of 1997 that would set a legally 
binding deadline for reducing a specified amount of greenhouse gases, 
such as carbon dioxide.  After being presented with some of the arguments 
in favor of, and opposed to, signing such an agreement, voters were asked 
whether or not they favored the United States signing such an agreement.

A plurality, approximately half (50%), of voters are either strongly 
(25%) or somewhat (24%) in favor of signing such a treaty.  A fifth of 
voters (20%) are somewhat opposed while only 21% strongly oppose signing 
a treaty (for a combined total of 41%).  Nearly a tenth (10%) of 
respondents did not offer an opinion.  Thus, among those offering an 
opinion, 55% said they strongly or somewhat favor signing a treaty (i.e., 
50% out of 90%).

Support is strongest among Democratic (63%), Reform Party (62%), and 
Independent (51%) voters.  Among Republicans, 35% strongly or somewhat 
favor signing an agreement while 26% are somewhat opposed and 32% are 
strongly opposed.

However, the level of support rises to nearly two-thirds (66%) among 
voters who cast their ballot in the November 1996 election for President 
Clinton whose Administration will be taking the lead on negotiating a 
treaty throughout the coming year.  Furthermore, voters who cite the 
environment as a factor that influenced their vote for president favor 
signing an agreement by 71%.  Likewise, among those who view the 
environment as a priority for Congress in 1997, more than two-thirds 
(67%) favor signing an agreement.


Electric Utility Restructuring - Renewable Energy:

Respondents were told that Congress is considering options to change the 
way the electric utility industry operates to increase customer choice 
somewhat akin to how one selects a long-distance telephone carrier.  
However, as with any significant change of this type, there are 
trade-offs involved including the possibility that renewable energy 
sources would be a competitive disadvantage and their use would decline.  

Respondents were then asked two questions.  The first was whether 
Congress should adopt policies to require electricity companies to use 
renewable energy or alternatively leave the decision to the companies 
themselves.  The second was whether favored a specific policy, also known 
as a Renewable Portfolio Standard (RPS), whereby electricity suppliers 
would be required to produce some of their electricity, for example about 
5 percent, from renewables even if this might raise the average 
consumer's electricity bill up to $1.00 per month.

A clear majority (53%) of voters favor Congress requiring electricity 
companies to use renewable energy while 44% would leave the choice up to 
the companies' discretion; 4% of voters expressed no opinion.  The 
strongest support for a congressional mandate was expressed by members of 
the Reform Party (78%) followed by Democrats (62%) and Independents (57%) 
for a combined average of 62%.  Only Republicans favored leaving the 
matter to the discretion of the electricity companies (57%) rather than 
resorting to a congressional mandate (39%).

While at least a plurality of voters in all geographic regions of the 
country agree that Congress should adopt policies to require electric 
companies to use renewable energy, support was particularly strong in the 
Midwest (60%).  Moreover, among voters who view the environment as a 
priority for Congress in 1997, nearly two-thirds (64%) favor a 
congressional mandate.

Voters overall expressed even stronger support for a Renewable Portfolio 
Standard (RPS) with 57% favoring Congress adopting such a requirement 
either strongly (27%) or somewhat (30%).  Only a fifth of voters (21%) 
strongly oppose the RPS proposal while another 17% are somewhat opposed 
(for a combined total of 38%).  

RPS supporters outnumber opponents regardless of political party 
affiliation.  Nearly three-quarters of Reform Party members (74%) favor 
an RPS requirement as do 65% of Democrats, 53% of Independents.  Among 
Republican voters, 48% support the RPS approach compared to 47% who 
oppose it somewhat or strongly.  Moreover, a majority (51%) of voters who 
supported the Republican candidate for Congress in the November 1996 
election favor an RPS requirement while 45% oppose it.  Two-thirds of 
voters (67%) who supported the Democratic candidate for Congress favor 
the RPS requirement.  

The public's support for Congress requiring electricity companies to use 
renewables is all the more notable given that a majority of voters (56%) 
believe the government is trying to do too many things with the economy 
that should be left to business and individuals compared to only 35% who 
believe the government should do more.


Electric Utility Restructuring - Energy Efficiency:

Respondents were advised that changes in how the utility industry 
operates could lead to cutbacks or the elimination of programs, such as 
home energy audits and rebates on energy efficient products, that help to 
improve consumers' energy efficiency.  They were asked whether they favor 
requiring utilities to invest in energy efficiency programs or leaving 
the decision to the utilities to offer energy efficiency programs.

By a large majority (69%), voters favor requiring utilities to invest in 
energy efficiency programs either strongly (37%) or at least somewhat 
(32%).  Only 10% of voters strongly oppose such a requirement while 16% 
are somewhat opposed (for a combined total of 26%).

Support for mandatory utility investments in energy efficiency extends 
across all party lines with 78% of Reform Party members, 76% of 
Democrats, 72% of Independents, and 60% of Republicans.  Even among 
voters who define themselves as being "somewhat conservative," a strong 
majority (55%) favors this approach.

Voters who believe the environment should be a top congressional priority 
in 1997 are overwhelmingly (84%) in support of this requirement as well 
as those who list the environment as a reason that influenced their 
recent vote for president (78%).
 

Electric Utility Restructuring - Stranded Nuclear Assets:

Respondents were then informed that another consequence of changing how 
electric utilities operate is that some of the existing nuclear power 
plants may not be economically competitive but will still have 
construction and operating debts to pay off.  They were asked who should 
be most responsible for paying these debts: utilities and shareholders, 
consumers, or the general public through taxes.

By a lopsided margin (70%), voters felt that utilities and their 
shareholders should be most responsible for paying the debt on existing 
nuclear power plants that may not be able to compete in a restructured 
utility market.  Only 14% thought that the consumers served by these 
utilities should pay while 8% indicated that the general public should 
pay through their taxes.  A small number (3%) of respondents offered that 
the debt should be equally shared by all three groups while 6% did not 
offer an opinion.

Since this is an issue that is likely to be before the Republican 
Congress in 1997, it is notable that two-thirds (67%) of those who voted 
for the Republican candidate in the recent congressional elections felt 
that utilities and shareholders should bear responsibility for nuclear 
plant debts.

Similarly, this view prevailed strongly across all party lines with 76% 
of Reform Party members, 71% of Democrats, 69% of Independents, and 68% 
of Republicans agreeing that nuclear plant debts should be borne by 
utilities and their shareholders.


Electric Utility Restructuring - Environmental Impacts:

Finally, respondents were told that some people fear that under utility 
deregulation, fossil fuel power plants which are subject to weaker 
environmental standards because of their age and location could gain a 
competitive advantage and increase their output and resulting emissions.  
They were then asked whether they believe the standards for the 
less-regulated plants are good enough and should not be made higher 
because that could reduce the economic benefits of competition.  As an 
alternative, they were asked whether strong environmental standards 
should be applied equally to all power plants.

A majority of voters (53%) strongly favor strong environmental standards 
that would apply equally to all power plants while another 27% somewhat 
favor such standards for a combined total of 80%.  Only 15% of voters 
somewhat or strongly oppose such standards.

This view is shared by people of all political stripe:  Reform Party 
(85%), Democratic (85%), Independents (80%), and Republicans (74%).  Even 
voters who define themselves as very conservative favor this view by 68%.

