<BODY>
Key to understanding the votes listed in Public Citizen's
Critical Mass Energy Project Congressional database:
<P>
In all cases "+" represents the safe and sustainable energy
policy vote or position; "-" represents opposition to the safe
and sustainable position; "A" indicates the Representative did
not vote; "N" indicates that the Representative was not yet
serving in Congress when the vote was taken.
<HR>
<P>
<STRONG><A NAME="hr1020cosp">HR1020 Cosponsorship</A></STRONG> --
Cosponsorship in
the 104th
Congress of H.R. 1020,
the "Nuclear Waste Policy Act of 1995."  Cosponsorship is 
marked with a (-).  Because Representatives who did not cosponsor the 
legislation may not oppose it, a (+) is not given for this bill.<P>
<EM>Reason for listing:</EM><BR>
H.R. 1020 would slash
environmental standards, preempt state law, and force the opening
of an unnecessary "interim" storage facility for high-level
nuclear
waste in Nevada, resulting in the unprecedented transportation of
high-level waste throughout the nation despite the absence of a
long-term plan for disposition.  
<P>
<STRONG><A NAME="texasllw">Texas Low-Level Waste
Compact</A></STRONG> --
Vote to
suspend House rules
and pass H.R. 558, the
"Texas Low-Level Radioactive Waste Disposal Compact."  On
September 19, 1995, the compact failed by a vote of 176-243.  A
NO vote is marked with a (+), a YES vote with a 
(-).  "A" indicates the Representative did
not vote; "N" indicates that the Representative was not yet
serving in Congress when the vote was taken.
<P>
<EM>Reason for listing:</EM><BR>
Passage of
the Compact would allow the placement of a nuclear waste dump in
a seismically active area in Texas near the Mexican border.  The
dump's location appears to target a poor, minority community
and threatens the Rio Grande river.
<P>
<STRONG><A NAME="effstand95">New Energy Efficiency
Standards</A></STRONG> --
Vote
on an
amendment by
Rep. Parker (R-MS) to the
1996 Interior Appropriations bill (H.R. 1977) to eliminate $12.7
million in funding for DOE's Codes and Standards Program and
prohibit this office from conducting any new rulemakings on
appliance efficiency standards and building codes.  On July 18,
1995, the amendment passed by a 262-164 vote.  A NO vote is
marked with a (+), a YES vote with a (-).  "A" indicates the 
Representative did not vote; "N" indicates that the Representative was 
not yet serving in Congress when the vote was taken.
<P> 
<EM>Reason  for 
listing:</EM><BR> 
Appliance efficiency standards adopted to date will save
consumers $132 billion net over the life of the products covered
and avoid the need for 58,000 Megawatts (MW) of new capacity, or
the equivalent of more than 100 nuclear or coal-fired plants. 
Freezing ongoing and future rulemakings could cost consumers
over $100 billion in lost energy savings over the next
30 years and create the need for an additional 37,300 MW of new
capacity, or the equivalent of 75 coal or nuclear plants by the
year 2015.
<P>
<STRONG><A NAME="renew95">Restore Renewable Energy
Funding</A></STRONG> --
Vote on
an amendment by Reps.
Klug (R-WI), Schaefer
(R-CO), Fazio (D-CA), Markey (D-MA) and Thurman (D-FL) to the
1996 Energy & Water Appropriations bill to restore $44.7 million
to renewable energy programs authorized by the Energy Policy Act
of 1992.   On July 12, 1995, the amendment passed by a 214-208
vote.  A YES vote is marked with a (+), a NO vote with a (-).
"A" indicates the Representative did not vote; "N" indicates that the 
Representative was not yet serving in Congress when the vote was taken.
<P>
<EM>Reason for listing:</EM><BR>
Even after passage of the amendment, the House Energy and Water
Appropriations bill cut spending on renewable energy
programs by 32%, from $393.6 million in 1995 to $266.5 million in
1996.  Nuclear fission would only be reduced by 18%, from
$288.3 million in 1995 to $235.7 million in 1996.  The level of
these cuts contrasts with the results of a recent public opinion
survey performed by Republican pollster Vince Breglio.  The poll
of 1,000 registered voters found that when asked which two energy
programs should receive cuts first, 61% chose nuclear energy, 59%
said oil and coal, 23% said natural gas, 16% identified renewable
energy and 16% chose energy efficiency.  When asked which two
programs should receive the highest priority for continued
funding, 64% cited renewable energy, 49% chose energy efficiency,
35% said natural gas, 21% picked nuclear power and 19% identified
oil and coal.
<P>
<STRONG><A NAME="alwr95">End the Advanced Light Water Reactor
Program</A></STRONG>
-- Vote on
an amendment by Rep. Obey
(D-WI) to the 1996
Energy & Water Appropriations bill to eliminate $40 million in
funding for the Advanced Light Water Reactor program.  On July
12, 1995, the amendment failed by a 191-227 vote.  A YES vote is
marked with a (+), a NO vote with a (-).  "A" indicates the 
Representative did not vote; "N" indicates that the Representative was 
not yet serving in Congress when the vote was taken.
<P>
<EM>Reason for listing:</EM><BR>
The Advanced Light Water Reactor program has provided over $275 
million since 1992 to corporate
giants like General Electric and Westinghouse for the development
of evolutionary light water reactors designed primarily for
export.  In a poll of
electric utility executives taken in 1994, nearly 72% of
respondents said that their company would never consider ordering
another nuclear power plant, yet Congress insists on pouring more
money into nuclear technology.
<P>
<STRONG><A NAME="nuctech95">Cut Nuclear Fuel Reprocessing R&D
</A></STRONG>-- Vote
on an amendment
by Rep.
Obey (D-WI) to the 1996
Energy & Water Appropriations bill to eliminate $18 million in
funding for the Nuclear Technology R&D program.  On July 12,
1995, the amendment failed by a 156-265 vote.  A YES vote is
marked with a (+), a NO vote with a (-).  "A" indicates the 
Representative did not vote; "N" indicates that the Representative was 
not yet serving in Congress when the vote was taken.
<P>
<EM>Reason for listing:</EM><BR>
The Nuclear Technology R&D program, an effort to develop
"pyroprocessing" technology to reprocess spent nuclear fuel, is
what remains of the Advanced Liquid Metal Reactor program that
was terminated by Congress in 1994 and could be used to revive
breeder reactor research in the future.  The reprocessing
technology will increase DOE's radioactive waste inventory and
has no support from DOE's own office of Environmental Management.
 A National Academy of Sciences study on plutonium disposition
raises serious questions about the utility of continuing this
program and states that "[pyroprocessing] has several
disadvantages that the panel believes effectively rule it out as
a serious competitor for the near-term plutonium disposition
mission."
<P>
<STRONG><A NAME="gtmhr95">Terminate the Gas Reactor
(1995)</A></STRONG> --
Vote on
an
amendment by Reps.
Klug (R-WI), Foley
(R-FL), Obey (D-WI) and Luther (D-MN) to the 1996 Energy & Water
Appropriations bill (H.R. 1905) to eliminate $20 million in
funding for the Gas-Turbine Modular Helium Reactor (GT-MHR).  On
July 11,
1995, the amendment was passed by a 306-121 vote.  A YES vote is
marked with a (+), a NO vote with a (-).  "A" indicates the 
Representative did not vote; "N" indicates that the Representative was 
not yet serving in Congress when the vote was taken.
<P>
<EM>Reason for listing:</EM><BR>
The federal government has already spent over $900 million
on gas-cooled reactor technology, despite a
complete lack of interest from electric utilities.  The National 
Academy of Sciences, in a 1992 report,
recommended that the government stop supporting the program and
concluded in a 1994 report that the technology would not be a
feasible way of disposing of excess weapons plutonium.  The 
GT-MHR also made the top ten list of wasteful and
environmentally destructive programs in the 
"Green Scissors" report published by an alliance of
environmental, taxpayer and consumer organizations including
Friends of the Earth, Public Citizen and the National Taxpayers
Union. Terminating the GT-MHR will save $20 million in FY'96 and
$2.6 billion in coming years.
<P>
<STRONG><A NAME="tripleplay">Oppose the "Tripleplay"
Reactor</A></STRONG> --
Vote
on an amendment by
Reps. Markey (D-MA), Dellums (D-CA), Vucanovich (R-NV), and
Ensign (R-NV) to the 1996 Defense Authorization bill to strip $50
million in funding for the construction of a "triple play"
reactor to generate electricity, produce tritium and fission
weapons-grade plutonium.  The reactor would be built by Asea
Brown Boveri/Combustion Engineering at the Savannah River site. 
On June 15, 1995, the amendment passed by a 214-208 vote.  A YES
vote is marked with a (+), a NO vote with a (-).  "A" indicates the 
Representative did not vote; "N" indicates that the Representative was 
not yet serving in Congress when the vote was taken.
<P>
<EM>Reason for listing:</EM><BR>
The amendment both saves taxpayer dollars, by cutting the funding
for a tritium source to  
$50 million, and preserves the public's right to be part of the 
process by withholding that  
funding until the PEIS for Tritium has been completed and there 
have been Congressional hearings on the subject.
<P>
<STRONG><A NAME="almr94">Terminate the Advanced Liquid Metal
Reactor
(1994)</A></STRONG> -- Vote on a
motion by Rep. Sharp (D-IN) to instruct the
Energy & Water Appropriations conferees to retain the House
position in favor of terminating the Advanced Liquid Metal
Reactor.  On
August 1, 1994, the amendment passed after another motion,
offered by Rep. Myers (R-IN), designed to block consideration of
the ALMR motion, was defeated by a 171-209 vote.  A NO vote on
the previous question is marked with a (+), a YES vote with a
(-).  "A" indicates the Representative did
not vote; "N" indicates that the Representative was not yet
serving in Congress when the vote was taken.
<P>
<EM>Reason for listing</EM><BR>
The National Academy of
Sciences, the Office of Technology Assessment and the General
Accounting Office have all released studies which rejected the
feasibility of the ALMR.  Both
President Clinton and Secretary of Energy Hazel O'Leary asked 
Congress to terminate the ALMR program because it undermines U.S.
policy on nuclear weapons proliferation. 
<P>
<STRONG><A NAME="coal94">Cut Coal Subsidies (1994)</A></STRONG> --
Vote on an
amendment by Reps. Klug
(R-WI), Kleczka
(D-WI) and Ramstad (R-MN) to the 1995 Interior Appropriations
bill (H.R. 4602) to cut $27 million in funding for coal research &
development.  On June 23, 1994, the amendment was rejected by a
182-242 vote.  A YES vote is marked with a (+), a NO vote with a
(-).  "A" indicates the Representative did not vote; "N" indicates that 
the Representative was not yet
serving in Congress when the vote was taken.
<P>
<EM>Reason for listing:</EM><BR>
Despite the pollution created by mining and burning coal, the DOE
has spent vast
sums on R&D for Coal.  When the DOE recommended reducing these
funds, the House Interior Appropriations Subcommittee voted
instead to increase Coal R&D funding while cutting the Clinton
Administration's request for energy efficiency programs.
<P>
<STRONG><A NAME="gtmhr94">Terminate the Gas Reactor
(1994)</A></STRONG> --
Vote on an amendment by Reps.
Byrne (D-VA) and Klug
(R-WI) to the 1995 Energy & Water Appropriations bill (H.R. 4506)
to eliminate $12 million in funding for the Gas-Turbine Modular
Helium Reactor (GT-MHR).  On June 14, 1994, the amendment was
rejected by
a 188-241 vote.  A YES vote is marked with a (+), a NO vote with
a (-).  "A" indicates the Representative did
not vote; "N" indicates that the Representative was not yet
serving in Congress when the vote was taken.
<P>
<EM>Reason for listing:</EM><BR>
The federal government has already spent over $900 million
on gas-cooled reactor technology, despite a
complete lack of interest from electric utilities.  The National 
Academy of Sciences, in a 1992 report,
recommended that the government stop supporting the program.  The
GT-MHR also made the top ten list of wasteful and
environmentally destructive programs in the 
"Green Scissors" report published by an alliance of
environmental, taxpayer and consumer organizations including
Friends of the Earth, Public Citizen and the National Taxpayers
Union. Terminating the GT-MHR will save $20 million in FY'96 and
$2.6 billion in coming years.
<P>
<STRONG><A NAME="almr93">Terminate the Advanced Liquid Metal
Reactor
(1993)</A></STRONG> -- Vote on an
amendment by Reps.
Sharp (D-IN),
Coppersmith, (D-AZ) and Zimmer (R-NJ) amendment to the 1995
Energy and Water Appropriations bill (H.R. 4506).  This amendment
called for terminating work on the Advanced Liquid Metal Reactor,
a breeder reactor project operated at the Idaho National
Engineering Laboratory with support from Argonne National
Laboratory.  On July 24, 1993, the amendment passed by a 272-146
vote.  A YES vote is marked with a (+), a NO vote with a (-).  "A" 
indicates the Representative did
not vote; "N" indicates that the Representative was not yet
serving in Congress when the vote was taken.
<P>
<EM>Reason for listing</EM><BR>
The National Academy of
Sciences, the Office of Technology Assessment and the General
Accounting Office have all released studies which rejected the
feasibility of the ALMR.  Both
President Clinton and Secretary of Energy Hazel O'Leary asked 
Congress to terminate the ALMR program because it undermines U.S.
policy on nuclear weapons proliferation. 
<P>
<STRONG><A NAME="coal93">Cut Coal Subsidies (1993)</A></STRONG> --
Vote on an
amendment by Rep.
Walker (R-PA) to the 1994
Interior Appropriations bill (H.R. 2520) to cut $50 million in
funding for coal research & development, distributing $25 million
to energy efficiency programs and $25 million to deficit
reduction.  On July 15, 1993, the amendment passed by a 276-144
vote.  A YES vote is marked with a (+), a NO vote with a (-).  "A" 
indicates the Representative did not vote; "N" indicates that the 
Representative was not yet serving in Congress when the vote was taken.
<P>
<EM>Reason for listing:</EM><BR>
Budget priorities should be shifted towards conservation and
renewables and away from polluting sources of power like coal. 
President Clinton sought reduced funding for coal R&D, only to
have the House Interior Appropriations Subcommittee increase
funds.
<P>
<STRONG><A NAME="hcr188cosp">Sustainable Energy Resolution
Cosponsorship</A></STRONG> -- Cosponsorship of
the
"Sharp Resolution", named for
Rep. Phil Sharp (D-IN) during the 103rd Congress.  This
nonbinding  resolution called for a shift of $1 billion into
DOE's renewable energy and energy efficiency programs over a two
year period.  There was no vote on this resolution.  Cosponsors
receive a (+), all others get a (-).  "N" indicates that the 
Representative was not in Congress when the resolution was 
proposed.  Ninety-five members who
cosponsored the bill during the 103rd session (1993-1994) remain
in Congress.
<P>
<EM>Reason for listing:</EM><BR>
Renewable energy and efficiency programs have received about 18%
of all federal energy R&D funding since 1950 (in real terms)
while nuclear fission, fusion, and fossil energy programs
benefitted from the bulk of R&D monies and generous tax breaks. 
Public opinion polls show strong support for renewable energy and
efficiency programs while respondents consistently call for
cutting nuclear and fossil programs first.  Shifting $1 billion
away from other DOE programs into sustainable energy R&D would
help to quicken the deployment of emerging technologies that
provide a wide array of economic and environmental benefits.
<P>
<STRONG><A NAME="nuclic92">Public Hearings on Reactor
Safety</A></STRONG> --
Vote
on an amendment by Reps.
Clement (D-TN) and
Barton (R-TX) to the Energy Policy Act of 1992 that would
implement "one-step" licensing for new nuclear power plants.  On
May 20, 1992, the amendment passed by a 254-160
vote.  A NO vote is marked with a (+), a YES vote with a (-).  "A" 
indicates the Representative did not vote; "N" indicates that the 
Representative was not yet serving in Congress when the vote was taken.
<P><EM>Reason 
for listing:</EM><BR>
This change would take away citizens' right to a public hearing
on new safety issues after reactor construction is
authorized.
<P>
