<DOCOLDNO>IA077-000522-B014-331</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.citizen.org:80/CMEP/votingindex/senatevotedescriptions.html 198.4.52.38 19970211002904 text/html 7644
HTTP/1.0 200 Document follows
Date: Tue, 11 Feb 1997 00:30:11 GMT
Server: NCSA/1.5.2
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
EE<HTML>
<BODY>
Key to understanding the votes listed in Public Citizen's
Critical Mass Energy Project Congressional database:
<P>
In all cases "+" represents the safe and sustainable energy
policy vote or position; "-" represents opposition to the safe
and sustainable position; "A" indicates the Senator did
not vote; "N" indicates that the Senator was not yet
serving in the Senate when the vote was taken.
<HR>
<P>
<A NAME="anwr95">Preserve the Arctic National Wildlife Refuge</A>
<P>
<STRONG>Description of Vote:</STRONG> -- Amendment by Senator
William Roth (R-DE) to the Budget Reconciliation bill to strip
provisions allowing oil and gas exploration and drilling in the
Arctic National Wildlife Refuge.  The amendment, offered on
October 27, 1995, was defeated on a 48-51 vote.  A YES vote is
marked with a (+), a NO vote with a (-).  "A" indicates the
Senator did not vote; "N" indicates that the Senator was not yet
serving in the Senate when the vote was taken.
<P>
<EM>Reason for listing:</EM><BR>
The Arctic National Wildlife Refuge (ANWR), located in Alaska's
northeast corner, is the only place in the United States where
the full range of sub-Arctic and Arctic ecosystems are protected
in one unbroken continuum.  ANWR's coastal plain is important to
Beafort Sea polar bears; millions of migratory sea birds, song
birds and waterfowl from six continents; and the 152,000 member
Porcupine River caribou herd.  Biologists predict significant
impacts on populations of caribou, muskoxen, polar bears, brown
bears, wolves, wolverines, and numerous species of migratory
birds if oil and gas drilling on the coastal plain goes forward. 
The oil industry, which already has access to over 90% of the
Arctic coastline, plans to export oil extracted from ANWR to East
Asian nations, which will do nothing to alleviate America's
dependence on imported oil.  Instead of opening up pristine
wildlife areas for oil drilling, Congress should cut oil
consumption by increasing fuel economy standards for automobiles
and light trucks.
<P>
<STRONG><A NAME="gtmhr95">Terminate the Gas Reactor
(1995)</A></STRONG> --
Vote on an amendment by Sens. Bumpers (D-AR), Inhofe (R-OK), and
Kerry (D-MA) to the 1996 Energy & Water
Appropriations bill (H.R. 1905) to eliminate funding for the
Gas-Turbine Modular Helium Reactor (GT-MHR).  On
August 1,
1995, the amendment was passed by a 62-38 vote.  A YES vote is
marked with a (+), a NO vote with a (-).  "A" indicates the
Senator did not vote; "N" indicates that the Senator was not yet
serving in the Senate when the vote was taken.
<P>
<EM>Reason for listing</EM><BR>
The federal government has already spent over $900 million
on gas-cooled reactor technology, despite a
complete lack of interest from electric utilities.  The National 
Academy of Sciences, in a 1992 report,
recommended that the government stop supporting the program and
concluded in a 1994 report that the technology would not be a
feasible way of disposing of excess weapons plutonium.  The 
GT-MHR also made the top ten list of wasteful and
environmentally destructive programs in the 
"Green Scissors" report published by an alliance of
environmental, taxpayer and consumer organizations including
Friends of the Earth, Public Citizen and the National Taxpayers
Union. Terminating the GT-MHR will save $20 million in FY'96 and
$2.6 billion in coming years.
<P>
<STRONG><A NAME="almr94">Terminate the Advanced Liquid Metal
Reactor
(1994)</A></STRONG> -- Vote on a
motion by Sen. Johnston (D-LA) to table (kill) an amendment by
Sens. Bumpers (D-AR), Gregg (R-NH), and Kerry (D-MA) to the FY
1995 Energy and Water Appropriations bill that would terminate
the Advanced Liquid Metal Reactor.  On June 30, 1994, the motion
passed 52-46.  A NO vote is marked with a (+), a YES vote with a
(-).  "A" indicates the Senator did not vote; "N" indicates that
the Senator was not yet serving in the Senate when the vote was
taken.<P>
<EM>Reason for listing</EM><BR>
The National Academy of
Sciences, the Office of Technology Assessment and the General
Accounting Office have all released studies which rejected the
feasibility of the ALMR.  Both
President Clinton and Secretary of Energy Hazel O'Leary asked 
Congress to terminate the ALMR program because it undermines U.S.
policy on nuclear weapons proliferation. 
<P>
<STRONG><A NAME="hark_jeff">Restore Renewable Energy
Funding</A></STRONG> --
Vote on motion by Sen. Johnston (D-LA) to table (kill) an
amendment to the FY 1995 Energy and Water Appropriations bill by
Sens. Harkin (D-IA) and Jeffords (R-VT) that would have added $33
million to renewable energy programs by decreasing spending for
nuclear weapons.  On June 30, 1994, Johnston's motion passed 53-
45.  A NO vote is marked with a (+), a YES vote with a (-).  "A"
indicates the Senator did not vote; "N" indicates that the
Senator was not yet serving in the Senate when the vote was
taken.
<P>
<EM>Reason for listing:</EM><BR>
Renewable energy and efficiency programs have received about 18%
of all federal energy R&D funding since 1950 (in real terms)
while nuclear fission, fusion, and fossil energy programs
benefitted from the bulk of R&D monies and generous tax breaks. 
Public opinion polls show strong support for renewable energy
programs while respondents consistently call for
cutting nuclear and fossil programs first.  Shifting funds
into sustainable energy R&D would help to quicken the deployment
of emerging technologies that provide a wide array of economic
and environmental benefits.
<P>
<STRONG><A NAME="gtmhr93">Terminate the Gas Reactor
(1993)</A></STRONG> -- Vote on a motion by Sen. Johnston (D-LA)
to table (kill) an amendment by Sen. Bradley (D-NJ) to the FY
1994 Energy and Water Appropriations bill to strip $22 million
from the Gas Turbine Modular Helium Reactor (GT-MHR).  On
September 30, 1993 the Johnston motion failed 41-58.  A NO vote
is marked with a (+), a YES vote is marked with a (-).  "A"
indicates the Senator did not vote; "N" indicates that the
Senator was not yet serving in the Senate when the vote was
taken.<P>
<EM>Reason for listing:</EM><BR>
The federal government has already spent over $900 million
on gas-cooled reactor technology, despite a
complete lack of interest from electric utilities.  The National 
Academy of Sciences, in a 1992 report,
recommended that the government stop supporting such technology.
<P>
<STRONG><A NAME="nukelic">Allow Hearings on Reactor
Safety</A></STRONG> -- Vote on a motion by Sen. Johnston (D-LA)
to table (kill) an amendment by Sens. Graham (D-FL) and Fowler
(D-GA) that would have preserved citizens' rights to hearings on
nuclear reactor safety issues that arose after reactor
construction.  The motion passed 52-43 on February 6, 1992. A NO
vote is marked with a (+), a YES vote with a (-).  "A" indicates
the Senator did not vote; "N" indicates that the Senator was not
yet serving in the Senate when the vote was taken.
<P><EM>Reason for listing:</EM><BR>
Because the larger energy bill allowed for "one-step" licensing
of nuclear reactors, failure to adopt the amendment resulted in
eliminating citizens' rights to public hearings
on new safety issues after reactor construction is
authorized.
<P>
<HR>
