<body BGCOLOR="#ffffff">

<h1><b>Industry Views on Issues Raised by the Public Interest Blueprint
</b></h1>
<P><P>
Numerous organizations have a stake in the outcome of
electric industry restructuring. The following comparison of
other viewpoints on Blueprint issues was compiled by 
requesting "vision" documents from a variety of players in the
restructuring debate.  Many of these groups have not issued
comprehensive blueprints for state-level industry restructuring. 
In the absence of such documents, comparisons are made based on
available published materials, in many cases outlines of desired
federal legislation.
<p>

<b>CONSUMER PROTECTION</b><p>

<p>

<b>American Public Power Association</b><p>

<i>APPA's Views on Competition and Restructuring in the Electric
Utility Industry</i><p>

<p>

"In light of the ongoing industry consolidation, the fundamental
consumer protections embodied in PUHCA
must be preserved in any restructuring effort to guard against
potential market power abuses by giant holding
companies."  Confidential rate schedules should be disallowed.
<p>

<p>

<b>Electric Generation Association</b><p>

<i>Electric Generation Association's Vision of a Fully
Competitive Electric Industry</i><p>

<p>

"The LDC can help accomplish a state's social goals in regard to
electricity production and service." <p>

<p>

Electricity Consumers Resource Council (ELCON)<p>

<i>Blueprint for Customer Choice</i><p>

<p>

Consumers can choose a "primary service provider," while states
retain authority over local distribution and to
"impose, on a competitively neutral basis... requirements
necessary to preserve and advance universal service,
protect the public safety and welfare, ensure the continued
reliability of basic electric services, and safeguard
the rights of consumers."  Rules should be established to assure
the competitive availability of meters and
other load control equipment.  Proprietary information about
customers cannot be exclusively controlled, and
customer privacy must be protected.  "Customer proprietary
information that is individually identifiable, and
other proprietary information, may be shared with a subsidiary or
affiliated entity, or another provider of basic
electric services, only with the written consent of the person to
which such information relates or from whom
it was obtained."<p>

<p>

<b>IPALCO</b><p>

<i>A White Paper for Restructuring the Electric Utility Industry
-- The Real Problem and the
Real Solution: Customer Choice Through Universal Access</i><p>

<p>

"The existing federal or state sanctions for consumer deception
and anti-competitive conduct can be focused
on those who do not deal openly and fairly with customers and
competitors.  Moreover, the nature of
competition, giving a choice among suppliers to customers, is the
ultimate form of consumer protection."  The
need for consumer protection is one of the justifications for
continued state and local jurisdiction over
distribution access.<p>

<p>

<b>COST SHIFTING</b><p>

<p>

<b>Electric Generation Association</b><p>

<i>Electric Generation Association's Vision of a Fully
Competitive Electric Industry</i><p>

<p>

"Safeguards against abuse of market power should exist for all
industry participants."<p>

<p>

<b>Electricity Consumers Resource Council (ELCON)</b><p>

<i>Blueprint for Customer Choice</i><p>

<p>

"[T]he potential for any cost shifting is greatest the longer
industry restructuring is delayed or averted."<p>

<p>

<b>IPALCO</b><p>

<i>A White Paper for Restructuring the Electric Utility Industry
-- The Real Problem and the
Real Solution: Customer Choice Through Universal Access</i><p>

<p>

Expresses confidence in the long-term benefits of competition. 
While some artificially low rates may rise,
giving all buyers access at the same time would prevent customer
strandings.  "That large purchasers will have
more bargaining power than small purchasers is a simple fact of
life also present under current regulation. 
Allowing entry by aggregators and resellers will provide ample
opportunity for small consumers to receive a
large percentage of the benefits of bulk power
purchasing.....True competition is the surest way to assure
long-term low prices for all customers."<p>

<p>

<b>DIVESTITURE OF UTILITY ASSETS</b><p>

<p>

<b>Electric Generation Association</b><p>

<i>Electric Generation Association's Vision of a Fully
Competitive Electric Industry</i><p>

<p>

"To ensure fairness and to guard against self-dealing, EGA urges
that existing vertically-integrated utilities be
required, at a minimum, to functionally unbundle their generation
resources from their transmission and
distribution activities.  With appropriate safeguards to ensure
against market abuses, the generation
marketplace can include affiliate transactions."  Independent
System Operators should run the grid with
common access and pricing rules.<p>

<p>

<b>Electricity Consumers Resource Council (ELCON)</b><p>

<i>Blueprint for Customer Choice</i><p>

<p>

Retail services should be "unbundled" and offered competitively
without government oversight.  "There
should be no restrictions on the ownership of transmission and
distribution facilities.  Over time, ownership of
these assets should gravitate to those who value them most
highly, <i>i.e</i>., the users of transmission services. 
This could provide private user-owners a powerful incentive to
self-regulate the use of the grid."  Once
competition arrives, "grid owners will actively solicit (and not
impede) new business."  By the same token,
"there should be no restrictions on the ownership of a
corporation that exists to buy power at wholesale and
resell at retail," beyond enforcement of anti-trust laws.<p>

<p>

<b>IPALCO</b><p>

<i>A White Paper for Restructuring the Electric Utility Industry
-- The Real Problem and the
Real Solution: Customer Choice Through Universal Access</i><p>

<p>

Congress would create self-sustaining Independent System
Operators (ISOs) to run the grids.  The ISO could
be a private non-profit or a federal enterprise.  Transmission
owners would lease their facilities to the ISO
who assumes reliability responsibility.  The ISO issues access
charges based on all long-run marginal costs. 
Congress would spell out compensation for transmission owners
based on replacement value, not diminished
revenues. <p>

<p>

<b>National Independent Energy Producers</b><p>

<i>Fundamental Principles of Electricity Industry
Restructuring</i><p>

<p>

"[T]ariffs must require that utilities: (1) charge themselves for
their own uses of their transmission systems on
terms comparable to those that are applied to third party users;
and (2) provide any and all ancillary services
that will be required to conduct transactions on fair and
comparable terms."  Divestiture of generation from
transmission and distribution is the best way to address market
power issues.  "Alternative means of dealing
with market power (other than divestiture) are: functional
separation of generation from transmission and
distribution, with strong regulatory controls on affiliate
transactions, or a requirement that certain standards of
competition have been met."<p>

<p>

<b>ENERGY EFFICIENCY</b><p>

<p>

<b>Electric Generation Association</b><p>

<i>Electric Generation Association's Vision of a Fully
Competitive Electric Industry</i><p>

<p>

"Universal basic service, demand side management, lifeline rates,
low-income assistance and other social
programs can be established and maintained by state regulatory
commissions using non-bypassable
distribution charges."<p>

<p>

<b>Electricity Consumers Resource Council (ELCON)</b><p>

<i>Blueprint for Customer Choice</i><p>

<p>

"Market structures that encourage the marketing of energy
efficiency products and services that promote
overall economic efficiency should be encouraged."<p>

<p>

<b>ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION</b> <p>

<p>

<b>Electric Generation Association</b><p>

<i>Electric Generation Association's Vision of a Fully
Competitive Electric Industry</i><p>

<p>

"Environmental and siting laws and regulations should be applied
in a consistent and non-discriminatory
manner to all industry participants."<p>

<p>

<b>Electricity Consumers Resource Council (ELCON)</b><p>

<i>Blueprint for Customer Choice</i><p>

<p>

"Competing suppliers should be allowed to bundle these products
and services with basic electric services and
financing.  These services include various 'green' pricing
options, in which customers may elect to pay a
premium for renewable energy or other resources or services that
help achieve environmental benefits beyond
federal statutory requirements."<p>

<p>

<b>RENEWABLE ENERGY</b><p>

<p>

<b>American Public Power Association</b><p>

<i>APPA's Views on Competition and Restructuring in the Electric
Utility Industry</i><p>

<p>

PURPA should remain law until "questions of market power for
existing generators can be resolved and
assurances can be given that a competitive market will not only
develop, but be sustained over time."<p>

<p>

<b>Electric Generation Association</b><p>

<i>Electric Generation Association's Vision of a Fully
Competitive Electric Industry</i><p>

<p>

PURPA would be eliminated, but "states will continue to use their
traditional authority to ensure resource and
fuel diversity, using mechanisms such as tax incentives and
siting authority that do not unfairly skew power
costs."<p>

<p>

<b>Electricity Consumers Resource Council (ELCON)</b><p>

<i>Blueprint for Customer Choice</i><p>

<p>

"Competing suppliers should be allowed to bundle these products
and services with basic electric services and
financing.  These services include various 'green' pricing
options, in which customers may elect to pay a
premium for renewable energy or other resources or services that
help achieve environmental benefits beyond
federal statutory requirements."<p>

<p>

<b>IPALCO</b><p>

<i>A White Paper for Restructuring the Electric Utility Industry
-- The Real Problem and the
Real Solution: Customer Choice Through Universal Access</i><p>

<p>

PURPA could "become a curious anachronism once consumers are free
to buy electricity directly from
generation sources." <p>

<p>

<b>National Independent Energy Producers</b><p>

<i>Fundamental Principles of Electricity Industry
Restructuring</i><p>

<p>

"There should be no federal prohibition on or preemption of state
decisions to favor certain fuel sources or
technologies.  States should remain free to design source
portfolios that meet fuel diversity and other
legitimate state needs.  There should be competitive procurement
to meet such requirements."<p>

<p>

<b>RETAIL COMPETITION</b><p>

<p>

<b>American Public Power Association</b><p>

<i>APPA's Views on Competition and Restructuring in the Electric
Utility Industry</i><p>

<p>

"Retail wheeling alone is not sufficient to guarantee least cost
electric service to retail customers, and it may
actually impede the development of effective competition.  Retail
wheeling should not be mandated until non-discriminatory, open
transmission access is ensured, fully competitive, regional bulk
power markets are
developed, and issues related to the obligation of a utility to
provide service to customers are resolved." 
Localities must retain the right to form a municipal utility.<p>

<p>

<b>Edison Electric Institute</b><p>

<i>A Study on the Treatment of, and Jurisdiction Over, Electric
Utility Costs During
Transition to a More Competitive Industry</i><p>

<p>

"If a state permits consumers to have the option of direct retail
access to electricity suppliers of their choice, it
should condition the availability of such access on the
consumer's payment of its fair share of the system costs
previously incurred for its benefit."  States have prime
responsibility for retail cost recovery, but "FERC
should play a 'backstop' role, to step in only when a state does
not or cannot provide for recovery of stranded
costs."<p>

<p>

<b>Electric Generation Association</b><p>

<i>Electric Generation Association's Vision of a Fully
Competitive Electric Industry</i><p>

<p>

Federal legislation should set policies that would require
competitive markets by January 1, 2003.  "FERC
should be authorized to certify the existence of a competitive
market, in which a utility must show that its
market power has been mitigated through unbundling, sale or
divestiture of generation resources or by other
means.  Such steps would be a prerequisite, for example, for
acceptance of market-based rates or elimination
of PURPA's mandatory purchase requirements."  There should be no
ownership restrictions, such as PUHCA,
and federal or state-owned power should be privatized.<p>

<p>

<b>Electricity Consumers Resource Council (ELCON)</b><p>

<i>Blueprint for Customer Choice</i><p>

<p>

Federal legislation should require every utility to file a
restructuring plan within 18 months.  "[W]holesale-only
competition is an oxymoron.....All consumers should be allowed to
purchase electrical services from
multiple suppliers."  Rate of return regulation would end, and no
state statute or regulation would be permitted
to effectively prevent the entry of any potential market
participant.<p>

<p>

<b>IPALCO</b><p>

<i>A White Paper for Restructuring the Electric Utility Industry
-- The Real Problem and the
Real Solution: Customer Choice Through Universal Access</i><p>

<p>

Competition cannot begin on a state-by-state basis.  Federal
legislation should require states provide the
following conditions: 1. all power suppliers must be allowed
equal access to distribution facilities subject only
to "certification based on technical, managerial and financial
ability to provide power;" 2. aggregators and
resellers of power must also have access; 3. distribution
providers must coordinate with transmission system
operator; 4. distribution providers must provide
non-discriminatory access to ancillary services (meter
reading, connection/disconnection, billing, etc) at
FERC-determined charges based on long-run marginal
costs.  While states can determine when to allow competition for
distribution providers, they should do so. 
Access charges should be imposed on the power user, not seller. 
All remnants of original-cost ratemaking are
to be eliminated.<p>

<p>

<b>National Independent Energy Producers</b><p>

<i>Fundamental Principles of Electricity Industry
Restructuring</i><p>

<p>

"[D]irect access of wholesale and retail customers to electric
suppliers of their choice should be the ultimate
goal of industry restructuring.  This goal should be advanced
expeditiously."  No mandatory pools or similar
devices are needed for the market to operate.  Once full
competition exists, utilites should lose protection from
anti-trust claims. <p>

<p>

<b>STRANDED COSTS</b><p>

<p>

<b>American Public Power Association</b><p>

<i>APPA's Views on Competition and Restructuring in the Electric
Utility Industry</i><p>

<p>

"[R]ecovery of such costs may be appropriate if retail wheeling
is allowed.  Rules for retail services have
traditionally been the prerogative of the states, and any change
in these rules and associated cost
consequences, should be addressed at the state level."<p>

<p>

<b>Edison Electric Institute</b><p>

<i>A Study on the Treatment of, and Jurisdiction Over, Electric
Utility Costs During
Transition to a More Competitive Industry</i><p>

<p>

"Efficient competition potentially benefiting all customers will
not be achieved if some customers are able to
avoid paying their fair share of costs approved, ordered or
deferred by regulators under traditional regulation. 
If such cost avoidance is allowed, it would promote unfair
competition among power suppliers, uneconomic
bypass, distorted pricing and inappropriate cost
shifting....Utilities should take all reasonable actions
available
to mitigate stranded costs.  Further, state and federal
regulatory commissions can assist by providing utilities
with adequate financial incentives to mitigate stranded costs,
including appropriate 'incentive' or
'performance-based' regulation."<p>

<p>

<b>Electric Generation Association</b><p>

<i>Electric Generation Association's Vision of a Fully
Competitive Electric Industry</i><p>

<p>

Prior contracts and regulatory committments should be honored. 
Contract-based costs should be paid by exit
fees; retail strandings, by access fees.  "EGA supports the full
recovery of all net legitimate, verifiable,
prudently incurred, non-mitigatable and public utility commission
(PUC) approved stranded costs.  Such
recovery includes both existing utility assets and power purchase
contracts." No recovery of post EPAct costs.<p>

<p>

<b>Electricity Consumers Resource Council (ELCON)</b><p>

<i>Blueprint for Customer Choice</i><p>

<p>

"[F]ull recovery would hinder the development of a truly
competitive market by creating a 'safe harbor' for
these largely, uneconomic costs."  State commissions should issue
rules on retail cost recovery but these rules
cannot excessively hamper competition.  "Efficient competition is
wholly inconsistent with the continued
employment of <i>any</i> uneconomic asset."<p>

<p>

<b>IPALCO</b><p>

<i>A White Paper for Restructuring the Electric Utility Industry
-- The Real Problem and the
Real Solution: Customer Choice Through Universal Access</i><p>

<p>

Stranded costs are neither new nor unique to electricity.  If
"lost revenue" recovery is permitted, inefficient
utilities may dump excess power, allowing predatory pricing
against low-cost producers.   "[R]eal competition
will prevail only if the recovery of so-called stranded costs --
the balance of past utility company expenditures
that are no longer economic -- is limited.  For customers and new
entrants into the energy business, a broad
policy of stranded cost recovery is a threat to achieving lower
energy prices, as well as a huge barrier to
competition."<p>

<p>

<b>National Independent Energy Producers</b><p>

<i>Fundamental Principles of Electricity Industry
Restructuring</i><p>

<p>

Because honoring past committments is important for future
markets and capital access, utilities should
recover "legitimate and verifiable" stranded investment and PURPA
contract payments.  "Stranded utility
investment should be calculated using market mechanisms and be
subject to full mitigation requirements." 
Stranded costs would be recovered by a non-bypassable access
fee.<p>

<p>

<b>UNIVERSAL SERVICE</b><p>

<p>

<b>Edison Electric Institute</b><p>

<i>A Study on the Treatment of, and Jurisdiction Over, Electric
Utility Costs During
Transition to a More Competitive Industry</i><p>

<p>

"If the exclusive utility franchise is modified, the utility's
obligation to provide service to all who request it,
on a nondiscriminatory basis, must also be modified."<p>

<p>

<b>Electric Generation Association</b><p>

<i>Electric Generation Association's Vision of a Fully
Competitive Electric Industry</i><p>

<p>

"EGA believes that if and when an LDC [local distribution
company] is acting as a supplier of last resort, it
must purchase power supplies from the spot market or through
competitive procurement.  The LDC can help
accomplish a state's social goals in regard to electricity
production and service."<p>

<p>

"Universal basic service, demand side management, lifeline rates,
low-income assistance and other social
programs can be established and maintained by state regulatory
commissions using non-bypassable
distribution charges."<p>

<p>

<b>Electricity Consumers Resource Council (ELCON)</b><p>

<i>Blueprint for Customer Choice</i><p>

<p>

"Where competitive markets are demonstrably inadequate to
safeguard important public policy goals, such as
the continued universal availability of essential electrical
services at reasonable and affordable
prices...Congress should establish workable regulatory procedures
to advance these goals... Eligible customers
would receive a package of services called, 'essential electrical
services' which may be a subset of basic
electrical services."  A Federal-State Joint Board on Universal
Service should be formed to work with FERC
on rules for universal service.  All service providers should
contribute to a universal service fund, which
would be used to pay entities designated by states as "essential
service providers" in necessary areas.  States
may expand their definition of universal service beyond the
FERC's.<p>


</body>
</html>
</DOC>
