<html>
<head>
<title>Joan Statement</title>
<meta name="Author" content="Common Machine#2">
<meta name="CreatedBy" content="WP Internet Publisher 6.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<center><img height=75 width=120 
src="/public_citizen/pclogo.gif"></center><p>
 
<u>For Immediate Release:					</u><b><p>

</b>Tuesday, January 28, 1997					<p>

<p>

<b><center><h2>Statement of Joan Claybrook</h2></center>
<p>

<center><h3>President, Public Citizen</h3></center>
<p>

<p>

<center><h1>CUT CORPORATE WELFARE NOW</h1></b></center>
<p>

<p>

	"Last year there was a major bipartisan effort to change our campaign finance laws -- to
get special interest money out of elections.  Today we are here to announce a related
effort to get special interest pork out of the federal budget.  <p>

<p>

	"Our political system is awash in corporate money and our federal budget is awash in
corporate handouts.  The political money is only a fraction of the handout money.  But it
is the key that opens the door to the Treasury.<p>

<p>

	"This is an unprecedented coalition gathered here to protect taxpayers.  Its broad diversity
illustrates the broad public opposition to unjustified government handouts.<p>

<p>

	"All of our organizations have different priorities. Some want a balanced budget. Others
want much more spending for vital domestic programs.  Some want to cut entitlements.
Others want higher taxes on the wealthy.  Whatever our disagreements, we are united on
one issue - stop corporate welfare.<p>

<p>

	"Last year, many of us were on different sides when Congress' overhauled Aid to
Families with Dependent Children -- AFDC.  However, this year we are on the same side
in this effort to eliminate another AFDC program -- Aid for Dependent Corporations.<p>

<p>

	"This initial "hit list" of corporate handouts is just the beginning of a much longer list of
outrageous government giveaways.  Some of these corporate subsidies not only waste
public funds. They also directly threaten public safety. <p>

<p>

	"Public Citizen is especially concerned about the Energy Department's plutonium
pyroprocessing program, which will cost the taxpayers some $250 million over five years. 
Reprocessing plutonium is not a good method of nuclear waste disposal. It simply creates
even more hazardous radioactive waste that is not suitable for the long-term waste storage
facilities under consideration. Pyroprocessing is the latest attempt by nuclear proponents
to justify pumping billions of dollars into nuclear energy to save an all but dead industry.<p>

<p>

	"We thank Representative Kasich for his leadership on this issue.  We look forward to
working with him, and with this wide array of advocacy groups, in this important effort to
stop corporate welfare."<p>
<center>###</center><p>
<a href="ralph.html">Ralph Nader's Statement on Corporate Welfare</a><P>

<p>
<hr>
<a href="/congress/cwhome.html">Return to the Congress Watch Home Page</a>
<p>


</body>
</html>
