<DOCNO>WT22-B36-148</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA077-000522-B019-125</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.citizen.org:80/congress/corwel/cuts.html 198.4.52.38 19970211003813 text/html 12802
HTTP/1.0 200 Document follows
Date: Tue, 11 Feb 1997 00:39:41 GMT
Server: NCSA/1.5.2
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
<title>Corporate Welfare Hit List</title>
<meta name="Author" content="Common Machine#2">
<meta name="CreatedBy" content="WP Internet Publisher 6.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<h1><center>Corporate Welfare Hit List</h1>
<p>

</center>
<h3>Rural Utilities Service (RUS) (Department of Agriculture)</h3>
The RUS provides subsidized loans to one type of electric supplier (electric coops), which serve
a small portion of the population (10%). The loans are provided at interest rates that are below
the Treasury's cost of borrowing and well below what investor-owned utilities pay. Today, there
is no need for the government to do this.<p>

Its predecessor, the Rural Electrification Administration (REA), was established during the
Depression to bring electricity to rural areas when other utilities would not serve them. This goal
has been accomplished. In fact, many rural utilities are facing increased competition from
investor-owned utilities.<p>

Subsidized financing has wasted money. <i> The Wall Street Journal</i> indicated that the
administration has begun "a multimillion government bailout of several rural electric suppliers
that otherwise might not survive in the new era of utility deregulation." they invested heavily in
nuclear power plants.<p>

According to the Congressional Budgeting Office (CBO), "Because the cost of interest accounts
for only a small percentage of the typical customer's's bill, eliminating the remaining federal
subsidy would have little effect of the utility rates that most borrowers charge their customers."<p>

<i><b>Proposal:</i></b> Terminate all financial support for electric and telephone loans. (Estimated savings:
<b>$190 million </b>over five years)<p>

<h3>Market Access Program (MAP)</h3>
The MAP, formerly known as the Market Production Program, assists exporters of fruits, nuts,
vegetables, meat poultry, eggs, seafood and wine. Payments are made to help offset the costs of
advertising by trade associations, commodity groups and some firms.<p>

Between 1991 and 1994, the Department of Agriculture (USDA) allocated about 35% of the
program's funding for brand-name products. The major recipients were Sunkist, Dole Fresh Fruit
Company, Ocean Spray Cranberries, and M&amp;M Mars. The 1996 farm bill targets assistance for
brand promotions to small businesses; large companies; however, still benefit from payments to
trade associations and cooperatives.<p>

According to GAO, there is little evidence that the program is actually promoting additional
advertising. It may simply be replacing private funds.<p>

<i><b>Proposal:</i></b> Terminate the Market Access Program (Estimated Savings: <b>$347</b> million over five
years)<p>

<h3></h3>
<h3>Animas La Plata</h3>
Animas La Plata is am enormous public works project located in southwest Colorado that will
provide federally subsidized water to farmers to grow low-value crops, such as alfalfa. The
project would divert much of the water from the Animas river, and pump it over 1,00 feet uphill.<p>

According to the Department of the Interior, the cost-benefit ratio of the project is 3 to 1.
Environmentally this project threatens endangered species of fish, would destroy game habitats
and cause violations of the Clean Air Act downstream in New Mexico.<p>

<i><b>Proposal:</b></i> Terminate, or modify, the project. (Estimated Savings: <b>$432 million</b> over the life of
the project if canceled (Federal share only))<p>

<h3>Pyroprocessing Program</h3>
Plutonium Pyroprocessing separates the spent fuel from nuclear reactors into plutonium, uranium
and other elements, thereby creating new fuel for reactors.<p>

Several large companies - Westinghouse, General Electric, and British Nuclear Fuels - are
interested in, and will benefit from, technology to reprocess commercial nuclear fuel. This
program is a continuation of a key technology developed for the breeder reactor program that was
terminated in 1994.<p>

<i><b>Proposal:</i></b> Terminate funding for the program (Estimated Savings: <b>$100 million</b> over four years.<p>

<h3>Appalachian Regional Commission (ARC) Roads Program</h3>
The ARC was established in 1965 to promote long-term economic development in the 13
Appalachian states. It supports a variety of programs, including the Appalachian Development
Highway System. Although the program has certainly benefited construction companies, there is
little evidence that it has actually provided long-term development.<p>

It duplicates activities funded by other agencies, such as the Department of Transportation's's
federal highway program. According to a Special Report by Citizens Against Government Waste,
"Most of the roads are simply linked well-to-do urban centers to other well-to-do urban
centers..."<p>

<b><i>Proposal:</i></b> Terminate the roads portion of the ARC. (Estimated Savings: <b>$500 million</b> over five
years)<p>

<h3>Fossil Energy Research and Development (including Oil, Coal and
Gas Research)</h3>
A principle category of applied research that the Department of Energy pursues is targeted to
mature industries involving oil companies (Exxon, Chevron, and Texaco), coal companies, and
natural gas companies. Development of applies energy technologies is better left to the private
sector. Companies in industries that are most likely to use the technology developed in such
programs - often electrical utilities - and their equipment are better able than DOE researchers to
understand the commercial value of technology.<p>

These firms already spend a great deal of money to develop new technologies. According to
CNO, this research has not been particularly effective. "The major new technologies for
enhanced oil recovery, for example, have come from private industry, not DOE. In other
instances, DOE continues to develop technologies in which the market has no clear interest."<p>

<i><b>Proposal:</i></b> Terminate funding for fossil energy research and development (Estimated Savings:
<b>1.37 billion</b> over five years)<p>

<h3>Timber Roads in the National Forests (USDA's Forest Service)</h3>
Serious problems exist concerning every aspect of the Forest Service, including road
construction. Virtually all of the actual construction is done by  timber companies to gain access
to timber sales. These roads are also used for subsidized recreational access.<p>

Preliminary reports from GAO indicate that both timber companies and recreational users are
being subsidized for the use of these roads. If private firms are going to profit from the use of
private lands, they should pay all associated costs, including the costs of road construction.<p>

<b><i>Proposal:</i></b> The users of roads in the National Forests, whether for logging or for recreation,
should pay full costs for those roads.<p>

Note: We do not know the exact amount of savings. Conservatively, we believe the savings
would exceed over $100 million over five years. We are awaiting a GAO request by
Representative Kasich to give us an exact number.<p>

<h3>Clean Coal Technology</h3>
The Clean Coal Technology Program (CCTP) was created in 1984 to assist private industry in
developing commercial technologies that would use coal in environmentally sound ways.<p>

Most of the projects funded by the CCTP will demonstrate technologies to retro fit coal-burning
electricity generating plants. The program benefits electric utilities and large industrial users of
coal.<p>

Since the passage of the Clean Air Act Amendments in 1990, the private sector has faced a clear
legislative mandate for lowering coal emissions. Electric utilities and large industrial users of
coal now have a clear economic motive for selecting among current practices and the lowest-cost
options for reducing emissions.<p>

<i><b>Proposal: </b></i>Rescind funding from prior years and terminate the CCTP (Estimated Savings:<b>$500
million </b>over five years)<p>

<h3>Overseas Private Investing Corporation (OPIC)</h3>
OPIC provides loans, loan guarantees, and political risk insurance to U.S. companies that invest
in risky, developing countries. The major beneficiaries of this program are large corporations and
politically connected individuals. If their investments are profitable, they benefit. If, however,
loans are not repaid or insurance claims are files, taxpayers are exposed to financial risks. In
addition, OPIC-financed projects have frequently harmed the environments of host companies.<p>

Since OPIC does not add to the supply of available capital, it, at best, can shift investments from
one country to another, riskier countries. This distorts investment decisions and wastes American
capital - capital that could be used in the United States.<p>

<b><i>Proposal:</b></i> Allow OPIC to mange its existing portfolio but preclude them from providing new
insurance or new loans. (Estimated Savings: <b>$281 million</b> over five years)<p>

<h3>General Agreements to Borrow (Part of the IMF)</h3>
The International Monetary Fund (IMF) was created as part of the Bretton Woods agreement and
has gradually transformed its mission from managing exchange rates to promoting international
development. The General Agreements to Borrow (GAB), which are part of the IMF, are
intended to prevent any future "international monetary crisis" caused by developing countries
that are unable to pay their bills. Often, this money is owed to large American banks.<p>

We are bailing these banks out despite the fact that the developing countries have enough money
to pay for bloated bureaucracies, operate money-losing state-sponsored industries and spend too
much on their militaries. Furthermore, new IMF funding to developing countries frequently ends
up substituting IMF debt for reschedulable bank debt.<p>

The IMF will do considerable harm to developing countries by continuing to make loans to their
governments. Bailing these governments out only encourages them to continue policies that are
detrimental to their citizens.<p>

To ensure that it gets repaid, the IMF imposes "conditionality" omits loans - policy changes that
borrowing countries must undertake to receive a loan. Frequently, the IMF has forced developing
nations to enact unsound economic policies that have led to tax increases, currency devaluations
and resource exploitation.<p>

Like the World Bank, the IMF operates outside of the public scrutiny, releasing almost no
information to the public, thereby avoiding any accountability for its programs.<p>

<i><b>Proposal: </b></i>Oppose increased U.S. participation in the GAB. (Estimated Savings: <b>$3.5 billion</b>
over five years.<p>

<h3>IMF Enhanced Structural Adjustment Facility (ESAF)</h3>
The ESAF is the IMF's low interest loan program for the poorest developing countries. The
ESAF was created in 1987 to enable the IMF to provide assistance at below market interest rates
to low-income developing countries that cannot pay their bills to banks and other corporations.<p>

Borrowers must be prepared to "adopt multi-year economic and structural reform programs."
Many of the concerns about the IMF also apply to ESAF. In addition, despite 10 years of ESAF
lending, poverty continues to increase in many ESAF countries.<p>

<b><i>Proposal:</b></i> Oppose increased U.S. participation in the ESAF. (Estimated Savings: <b>$150 million</b>
over five years.<p>

<p>

<h3>Highway Demonstration Projects</h3>
These are specific construction projects that Members of Congress have requested. They can
range in scope from paving a gravel road to building a multilane highway. ISTEA included 539
demonstration projects with an accompanying cost of $6.2 billion.<p>

This amount indicates a five-fold increase compared to the 1987 Transportation's bill.<p>

According to the GAO, highway demonstration projects provide limited benefits.<p>

1.They are frequently not consistent with key transportation priorities, do not appear on any state
or regional transportation plans, and do not receive much scrutiny.<p>

2. They often have problems that cause them to languish in the development stage. These
problems have ranged from threatened intrusion on wetlands to citizen opposition. One proposed
highway construction project GAO reviewed would have cut through a low income housing
project undergoing renovation with federal funds.<p>

3. They tend to draw funds from other major federal aid highway programs, such as a Interstate
Maintenance.<p>

<i><b>Proposal:</i></b> End all highway demonstration projects. (Estimated Savings: <b>$4.0 billion</b> over five
years)<p>

<h1>Total Estimated Savings: $11.5 billion</h1>
<p>
<hr>
<a href="/congress/cwhome.html">Return to the Congress Watch Home Page</a>
</body>
</html>
