<CENTER><img src = "/images/pclogo.gif" alt = "PUBLIC CITIZEN"></CENTER>
<p>
<p>
<h1><b><center>A MILLION FOR YOUR THOUGHTS:
The Industry-Funded Campaign Against
the FDA by Conservative Think Tanks</h1></center></b>
<p>
<p>
<h2><b>Executive Summary</h2></b>
<p>
For the past several years, a group of conservative think tanks with close ties to congressional Republicans has waged an aggressive public relations and lobbying campaign against the federal Food and Drug Administration. The campaign relies on misinforma
tion and distortion of the FDA's record. Between 1992 and 1995, seven of the think tanks received at least $3.5 million dollars in contributions from the industries with the most to gain from the anti-FDA campaign -- pharmaceutical, medical device, biotec
hnology and tobacco manufacturers.
<p>
The think tanks allege both that the FDA keeps Americans waiting for lifesaving therapies available to consumers in other countries, and that health and safety agencies in those countries approve drugs and devices more quickly than the FDA with no impact 
on safety. In fact, according to the U.S. General Accounting Office, the FDA approves drugs -- particularly drugs that offer a significant improvement in therapy -- as fast or faster than its counterparts in the United Kingdom, Japan and Germany. At the s
ame time, the FDA has done a much better job keeping dangerous, even lethal drugs off the U.S. market.
<p>
Despite this record, the anti-FDA campaign is close to bearing bitter fruit. Legislation is pending before the House and Senate that would dramatically weaken the FDA's ability to protect the public from unsafe or ineffective drugs, medical devices, blood
 products, food and food additives.
<p>
Public Citizen examined IRS tax forms, annual reports, fundraising materials and other publications from eight think tanks and dozens of corporations and corporate foundations. Weak disclosure requirements allow corporations to keep much of their contribu
tions hidden, but the documents reveal deep financial and institutional connections between the industries seeking to roll back FDA protections and the think tanks attacking the FDA.
<p><UL>
<LI> Seven think tanks -- the American Enterprise Institute, the Cato Institute, the Competitive Enterprise Institute, the Heritage Foundation, the Hudson Institute, the Progress and Freedom Foundation and the Washington Legal Foundation -- received at le
ast $3.5 million between 1992 and 1995 from drug, medical device, biotechnology and tobacco manufacturers and their corporate foundations.
<p>
<LI> Little specific funding information for the 1992-95 period is available for the eighth think tank -- Citizens for a Sound Economy (CSE). However, CSE received $191,800 from Philip Morris in 1991 and the Chairman of CSE's board is a lobbyist for Amgen
, Inc., a major pharmaceutical and biotech company. CSE has reportedly spent $2 million since the beginning of 1995 on anti-FDA advertising, organizing and lobbying.
<p>
<LI> In addition to lending an aura of academic independence to industry-sponsored legislative proposals, the think tanks also wield significant political influence. Nominally nonpartisan, the organizations carrying out the public relations campaign again
st the FDA have very close links to the Republican Party:
<p>
     <b>Progress and Freedom Foundation (PFF):</b> An integral part of House Speaker Newt Gingrich's political network. The House leadership delayed introducing FDA legislation until PFF finished its proposed blueprint.
<p>
     <b>Hudson Institute:</b> Former Vice President Dan Quayle heads Hudson's Competitiveness Center. The center carries on the work of the Bush Administration's Council on Competitiveness by advocating the weakening of public health and safety laws espec
ially the Food, Drug and Cosmetics Act.
<p>
     <b>Citizens for a Sound Economy (CSE):</b> Former Bush Administration White House Counsel C. Boyden Gray -- now a lobbyist for Amgen, Inc. -- chairs the Board of Trustees for CSE, Inc. CSE has reportedly spent $2 million to roll back the FDA's author
ity to protect public health.
<p>
     <b>Washington Legal Foundation (WLF):</b> The House Commerce Committee, chaired by Rep. Tom Bliley (R-VA), is considering FDA rollback legislation. Bliley's staff counsel is Alan Slobodin, former president of WLF. WLF has placed misleading newspaper 
advertisements attacking the FDA's record and filed suit to force FDA to allow manufacturers to promote products for unapproved uses.
<p>
     <b>Heritage Foundation: </b>Now the think tank most frequently cited by major newspapers.  Several top Republican officials hold fellowships at Heritage, including Reagan-era Attorney General Edwin Meese and former Education Secretary and drug czar W
illiam Bennett. Heritage helped create the "Contract With America," which included a broad regulatory rollback bill that would have destroyed the FDA along with other public health and safety agencies.
<p>










<h3><b><center>MINIMUM CONTRIBUTIONS RECEIVED BY ANTI-FDA THINK TANKS FROM PHARMACEUTICAL, MEDICAL DEVICE, BIOTECHNOLOGY AND TOBACCO COMPANIES AND CORPORATE FOUNDATIONS, 1992-1995</h3></b></center>
<p>
American Enterprise Institute      $1,714,000<BR>
Cato Institute                              152,500<BR>
Competitive Enterprise Institute              50,000 <BR>
Heritage Foundation                    300,000<BR>
Hudson Institute                       693,800<BR>
Progress and Freedom Foundation             580,000<BR>
Washington Legal Foundation              56,000<BR>
<P>
<b>TOTAL                                $3,546,300</b>



