<p>
<p>


<U>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE</U>   
July 24, 1996                                      
<p>                              
<p><b><center><h2>
               DRUG, MEDICAL DEVICE, BIOTECH AND TOBACCO COMPANIES
    GAVE AT LEAST $3.5 MILLION FOR DECEPTIVE ANTI-FDA CAMPAIGN
</h2></b></center><p>
<p>
Washington, D.C., July 24, 1996 -- Public Citizen today released a new report showing that industries seeking to sharply limit the Food and Drug Administration's public health mission gave millions of dollars to conservative think tanks that have mounted 


a vitriolic anti-FDA public relations campaign.  The report details how these industry-funded think tanks generated and circulated a series of myths being used to justify pending legislation that would weaken the FDA's ability to protect the public from u


nsafe or ineffective drugs, medical devices, blood products and food additives. 
<p>
"The FDA rollback legislation would take consumers and patients back to the days of Thalidomide and the Dalkon Shield," said Joan Claybrook, President of Public Citizen.  "This report shows how the misleading case for this dangerous legislation has been m


anufactured by industries that stand to make huge additional profits.  By relying on industry-funded misinformation in crafting FDA legislation, Congress may well threaten the lives and well-being of millions of Americans."
<p>
<i>A Million for Your Thoughts: The Industry-Funded Campaign by Conservative Think Tanks Against the FDA</i> documents $3.5 million in contributions from pharmaceutical, medical device, biotechnology and tobacco companies and their corporate foundations t


o eight conservative think tanks since 1992.  Because limited disclosure requirements allow corporations to hide most of their gifts, actual funding is assumed to be much higher.
<p>
The think tanks -- American Enterprise Institute, Cato Institute, Citizens for a Sound Economy, Competitive Enterprise Institute, Heritage Foundation, Hudson Institute, Progress and Freedom Foundation, and Washington Legal Foundation -- also have close ti


es to the Republican Party.  Indeed, the House leadership delayed introducing its version of the FDA legislation until the Progress and Freedom Foundation, which has close ties to House Speaker Newt Gingrich, finished its blueprint for rollback.
<p>
Over the past two years the think tanks have mounted a costly public relations campaign against the FDA.  "Since corporations are not required to disclose their direct contributions, $3.5 million is certainly a gross underestimate," said John Canham-Clyne


, Research Director of Public Citizen's legislative arm, Congress Watch.  "But if you consider the impact these think tanks have had on the proposed FDA legislation, it's clear the industry donors got their money's worth."
<p>
<p>                              
<p>
Copies of <i>A Million for Your Thoughts: The Industry-Funded Campaign by Conservative Think Tanks Against the FDA</i> are available free to accredited news media from Public Citizen. 

