<html>
<head>
<title>No Fault</title>
<meta name="Author" content="Common Machine#2">
<meta name="CreatedBy" content="WP Internet Publisher 6.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<center><img height=75 width=120 
src="/public_citizen/pclogo.gif"></center><p>
<b>For Immediate Release				<p>

January 30, 1997					</b>	<p>

<p>

<center><h1>Auto Choice Makes Good Drivers Pay for Bad</h1><p>


<h2>
Nader Calls Insurance Companies Profiteers of the 1990s</h2><p>

<p>

</center>
"No fault" auto insurance systems have proved a financial, legal and philosophical disaster for motorists
across the United States, consumer advocates say, pointing to voluminous data on premiums and
litigation in no fault states. A "no fault"/"auto choice" conference in Washington, D.C. promoted by
insurance industry funded organizations and consultants, is the opening gambit in a public relations
campaign to rescue the failed no fault concept through federal legislation that would preempt state auto
insurance laws.<p>

<p>

Auto insurance companies are making huge profits while trying to limit recoveries by drivers. Based on
National Association of Insurance Commissioners' data, <u>Auto Insurance Report</u> has found that the profit
margins for auto insurance are rising. In 1989, the rate of return on net worth for auto insurers was 4.7%.
In 1995, the rate of return was 11.6%. In New York, the insurers made a profit of $841 million in 1995.
Consumer advocate Ralph Nader said, "To arbitrarily limit payments to innocent drivers while making
billions of dollars in profits is unconscionable. The insurance companies, seeking to impose limits on
wounded motorists, want no limits on their profiteering."<p>

<p>

No fault/auto choice would strip Americans of their right to legal representation if they are injured in an
auto accident and to have a citizen jury decide who should pay. No-fault means it's always your fault
because when an accident occurs each side submits a claim to his or her own insurer.<p>

<p>

Studies show that no fault increases premiums; does not reduce litigation costs; is extremely unpopular
with motorists; arbitrarily imposes harmful limits on full compensation, transferring the burden to
victims and ultimately taxpayers; contradicts traditional notions of responsibility and accountability; and
stacks the deck in the insurance companies' favor. (See attached fact sheet.)<p>

<p>

"No fault is an unfair and exceptionally costly system that defies the American tradition of justice and
fair play and forces good drivers to pay for bad drivers," says Nader. "It is ironic that members of
Congress would take a system that has collapsed in state after state, and been rejected by the people of
other states, and attempt to impose it on the entire nation through federal legislation."<p>

<p>

"To lower insurance premiums, the solution is first to improve auto and highway safety, " Nader said,
"second, to help reduce auto theft, and third, to promptly institute consumer protections against the
notorious price-gouging, waste and inefficiencies of the insurance industry, driven by its cost-plus
approach."<p>

<p>

"No fault is an experiment that has utterly failed," said Joan Claybrook, President of Public Citizen and
former Director of the National Highway Transportation and Safety Administration (NHTSA). "Auto
choice makes good drivers pay for bad drivers. It is a testament to the massive power and pervasive
influence of the insurance industry that no fault remains in effect in some states, where beleaguered
motorists want to escape its costly tyranny."<p>

<b><p>

<center>So-called "Consumer Choice" No Fault is a Fraud</b> </center>
<p>

<p>

With no fault facing extinction, insurance companies, which prosper under no fault, crafted the
"consumer's choice" plan as a palliative. Under the "choice" proposal, motorists ostensibly get to choose
whether they want "no fault" coverage or "traditional liability" coverage. But the promise of a "choice"
is an illusion; when a bad driver who causes an accident "chooses" fault-free insurance, that decision
overrides a good driver's choice to hold the bad driver accountable through the tort system. Thus,
"choice" really offers consumers no choice at all -- they are still subject to no fault.<p>

<p>

This proposal also tramples on states' rights, by imposing a Washington-Knows-Best auto insurance
scheme on the states. At present, the majority of states apportion fault in auto cases; their laws would be
run over by auto choice.<p>

<p>

<center><b>Industry Gears up for Federal Effort</b><p>

<p>

</center>
The insurance industry is gearing up a major political and public relations campaign to keep no fault
alive. One component of this campaign is a no fault/auto choice conference which begins today in
Washington, D.C. The conference is sponsored by the Auto Accident Compensation Project (AACP)
and a new group called The Committee for Comprehensive Automobile Restitution and Rate Reductions
(CAR). AACP is funded by the insurance industry; CAR is an unknown group. Many of the attendees
are consultants who have worked with the insurance industry to support no fault and oppose regulation
of the insurance industry. For example, corporate consultant Andrew Tobias worked closely with State
Farm and other insurance companies to unsuccessfully support industry-drafted no fault legislation in
Hawaii and California. University of Virginia Law Professor Jeffery O'Connell also campaigns on
behalf of insurance companies for various measures that restrict injured people's right to sue. In
California, for example, O'Connell was paid $67,000 by the insurance industry to unsuccessfully
support no fault legislation and to oppose the successful Proposition 103 rate regulation and roll back
law. And the latest "choice" no fault proposal is promoted by Michael Horowitz of the Hudson Institute,
which, like Horowitz's former employer, the Manhattan Institute, is funded by insurers and other big
corporations.<p>

<p>

"Unable to win support for no fault at the state level, the insurance industry wants the U.S. Congress to
adopt a no fault insurance system that has failed in every state it has been tried," said Harvey Rosenfield,
who authored California's insurance reform initiatives. "This shows how desperate the insurance
industry is to save no fault. This 'Auto Insurance Reform' conference, despite the effort to cloak it in an
academic guise, has been convened to buttress the insurance industry's no fault agenda. The
conference's failure to even discuss rate regulation and accountability reform, bitterly opposed by the
industry, but which has saved Californians billions of dollars in the last eight years, shows that it is the
insurance industry which is pulling this conference's strings. It is the insurance companies' interest in
fat profits and no accountability which is being protected by these lobbyists masquerading as reform
advocates," Rosenfield added.
<p>
<a href="auto.html">Fact Sheet on No Fault Auto Insurance</a><p>
