<html>
<head>
<title>Insurance</title>
<meta name="Author" content="Common Machine#2">
<meta name="CreatedBy" content="WP Internet Publisher 6.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<img height=75 width=125 src="/public_citizen/pclogo.gif"></center><p>
<h1><center> <b>FACT SHEET ON NO FAULT AUTO INSURANCE</center></h1></b><p>

<p>

<b>1.	No fault increases premiums.</b> Insurance companies, which make most of their profits from the
investments of premiums, prefer no-fault because it generates higher revenues. <u>Paying the reckless</u> as
well as the innocent driver leads to far higher costs; restrictions on tort rights do not offset these higher
costs. On average, according to data from the National Association of Insurance Commissioners,
premiums in mandatory no fault states rose 45.6% between 1989 and 1994, a third higher than the
average in liability states (33.7% increase). In 1994, six of the top ten most expensive auto insurance
states (including D.C.) had no fault systems.<p>

<p>

	States that repeal no fault obtain immediate rate <u>decreases</u>. Of the ten states where auto insurance was
the most expensive in 1989, eight were no fault states. Since then, three of those states -- Pennsylvania,
New Jersey and Connecticut -- have repealed their mandatory no fault systems (no fault remains
optional in Pennsylvania and New Jersey). Georgia repealed its no fault system in 1991; its average
premium dropped 4.8% between 1989 and 1994 -- the greatest decrease in the nation. Connecticut
repealed its no fault system effective January 1, 1994; rates dropped 9.7% that year.<p>

<p>

<b>2.	No fault does not reduce litigation costs. </b>One of the great myths of no fault -- that it dramatically
reduces litigation -- is belied by the facts. In no fault states, suits by motorists against their own
insurance company for failure to pay no fault benefits have skyrocketed. An article in the Insurance
Council Journal, a publication for insurance defense attorneys, concluded: "Whatever the advantages of
no fault, a reduction in court cases and court costs would not appear to be one of them." (July, 1986,
Page 389). During the period 1977-89, of the 1,119 appellate opinions in Michigan dealing with no-fault, a whopping 73% (826) were first party cases in which insurers wound up having to sue their own
insurance company to receive benefits. Sinas, George T., "No-Fault: a Perspective From Michigan," June 30, 1990. P. 15. Traditional no fault systems also spawn enormous litigation over
whether a particular individual has met the threshold over which claims for pain and suffering may be
requested. Another 22% of the reported cases (241) in Michigan concerned the bodily injury threshold
requirement, where the question was whether a suit could be appropriately filed against a third party
because the injuries were serious enough.Id. Moreover, litigation over property damage  -- the vast
majority of car accidents involve property damage -- continues under traditional no fault systems which
retain the liability system for property claims.<p>

<p>

<b>3.	No Fault is extremely unpopular with motorists.</b> No state has adopted a no fault law since 1976. Four
states have repealed their mandatory no fault systems since 1989. Voters have rejected no fault proposals
by landslide margins twice in California (1988 and 1996). In recent years, motorists in Hawaii and
Massachusetts have petitioned their legislature to get rid of no fault.<p>

<b><p>

4.	No fault arbitrarily imposes harmful limits on full compensation, transferring the cost of
irresponsibility to victims and ultimately taxpayers. </b>No fault places cruel, arbitrary and unjustified
restrictions on the compensation victims of auto accidents may receive by eliminating non-economic
damages, commonly known as pain and suffering damages. Under auto choice, motorists who suffer
gross disfigurement, blindness or permanent loss of health most likely would go uncompensated for such
losses. Consumers could buy insurance to cover pain and suffering damages, but it would be so
expensive that most people would forgo this false "choice."  Eliminating pain and suffering damages is
particularly unfair to women, children, seniors and people of modest means, because they tend to receive
most of their compensation in the form of pain and suffering. For example, pregnant women who are hit
by a driver and become permanently sterilized would only be entitled to limited compensation for
medical costs, but not pain and suffering. (And if the person was a homemaker, she would receive
virtually nothing other than payment of medical bills, since she would not be entitled to wages.)<p>

<p>

<b>5.	No fault makes good drivers pay for bad drivers. </b>Under the "choice" proposal, motorists ostensibly
get to choose whether they want "no fault" coverage or "traditional liability" coverage. But the promise
of a "choice" is an illusion; when a bad driver who causes an accident "chooses" fault-free insurance,
that decision overrides a good driver's choice to hold the bad driver accountable through the tort system.
Thus, "choice" really offers consumers no choice at all -- they are still subject to no fault.<p>

<p>

<b>6.	No fault leads to more accidents.</b> Studies suggests that no fault leads to more
accidents. In their 1987 book <i>The Economic Structure of Tort Law</i>,
conservative theorists William M. Landes and Richard A. Posner found that
tort law leads to lower accident rates because if the incentive to take care is
reduced, people will be less careful, and the cumulatively significant result
will be more fatal accidents. Another  recent study concludes that no fault
encourages drunk driving. ("Effects of Tort Liability and Insurance on Heavy
Drinking and Driving," Sloan, at al., Journal of Law and Economics (April,
1995)). Indeed a review of such studies, published in the UCLA Law Review,
concluded that auto fatalities and drunk driving increase in states that adopt no
fault because individual drivers are no longer responsible -- or made to pay --
for their reckless driving (Gary T. Schwartz, "Reality in the Economic
Analysis of Tort Law: Does Tort Law Really Deter?" 42 UCLA Law Review
377 (1994)).<p>

<p>

<b>7.	No fault's benefits are too limited, forcing motorists to buy more
insurance. </b> Since paying both parties to a vehicle collision is an inherently
more expensive system, no fault plans often mandate extremely limited
benefits, leaving victims with little protection. Most motorists must buy
additional coverage, including, in states that allow litigation, liability coverage
to protect themselves against lawsuits by other motorists whose no fault
benefits are inadequate. While proponents of no fault often hold out the
promise of generous benefits as a quid-pro-quo for surrendering legal rights,
the high cost of no fault inevitability leads to industry pressure to reduce
benefits, leaving motorists holding policies that offer dwindling protection.<p>

<p>

<b>8.	No fault stacks the deck in the insurance companies' favor.</b> All no fault
proposals, in practice,  leave the injured person to face clever insurance
adjusters without the leverage of adequate legal remedies -- undermining the
power that consumers have when demanding an insurance company to fully
and promptly pay claims. The elimination of compensation for accident
victims' pain and suffering removes the incentive for scrupulous lawyers to
accept auto accident cases, since their fees would then have to be paid out of
the victim's recovery of medical costs and lost wages. One of the unstated but
obvious purposes of no fault proposals is to discourage lawyers from
representing accident victims, no matter how serious their cases. Without the
ready availability of such representation, insurers will have little reason to
eschew abusive settlement practices. Since insurers have a financial incentive
to deny claims -- they earn most of their profits from the investment of
premiums -- the threat of a financial penalty is often the only leverage a
policyholder can wield to force an insurance company to comply with its legal
obligations.<p>

<p>

<b>9. 	Regulating excessive insurance company profits and overhead is the best
way to lower auto insurance premiums.</b> California voters ordered such
measures eight years ago. As a result, the average auto insurance premium in
California dropped 4.5% between 1989 and 1994, saving motorists $12
billion. (During the same period, premiums increased an average of 37%
throughout the rest of the nation.) An additional $1 billion in premium refunds
have been paid. California, which used to have the fastest growing premiums
in the nation, now ranks 47th.
<p>
<a href="nofault.html">"Auto Choice Makes Good Drivers Pay for Bad," 
Press Release</a><p><hr>
<a href="/congress/cwhome.html">Return to the Congress Watch Home Page</a>
</body>
</html>
</DOC>
