<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Description of SCAP</TITLE>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#8b0000"  
vlink="#8b0000"alink="#8b0000>  
<CENTER><h3><FONT SIZE=+2>T</FONT>HE <FONT SIZE=+2>S</FONT>UPREME
<FONT SIZE=+2>C</FONT>OURT <FONT SIZE=+2>A</FONT>SSITANCE <FONT
SIZE=+2>P</FONT>ROJECT</h3<P>

<img src="/public_citizen/litigation/graphics/barred.gif"
align="middle"></center>  
<P>
<b>The Supreme Court Assistance Project</b> was founded to try to
rectify what the Litigation Group perceived to be a gross imbalance
in the practice before the Supreme Court.  Typically, business
clients are exceptionally well-represented before the Court, often
by experienced Supreme Court practitioners, backed by all of the
resources large corporations can offer.  More often than not, on
the other side are small firm practitioners or legal service
attorneys with little or no Supreme Court experience.  Our theory
is to help equalize this imbalance by lending our experience and
expertise in Supreme Court Practice to the underdog, while at the
same time not attempting to take over the case.<p>

Through SCAP, the Litigation Group provides assistance to small
firm practitioners, legal service lawyers, and other lawyers with
little or no experience in Supreme Court litigation.  Because many
attorneys arguing in front of the Supreme Court have little or no
experience in practicing before the Supreme Court, our expertise
and knowledge is a valuable resource to litigants. SCAP attempts to
ensure that the litigants assisted present the Supreme Court with
the strongest possible arguments prior to its decision.  SCAP
focuses on identifying cases with the potential for broad public
impact.<p>

SCAP provides assistance to attorneys who were not successful in
the lower court and are considering requesting that the Supreme
Court review the case through a petition for certiorari.  The
Supreme Court agrees to hear less than 5% of the cases in which
petitions for certiorari are filed, and in approximately two-thirds
of the cases in which review is granted there is a reversal.<p>

SCAP also provides pre-certiorari assistance to attorneys who were
successful in the lower court to preserve their victory by helping
them write briefs arguing that the Supreme Court should not grant
the other side's petition for certiorari.  These cases often
involve claims of government misconduct, union workers, prisoners
or civil rights plaintiffs who have won damage awards based on some
violation of their rights.  SCAP also focuses on seemingly
technical legal issues <i>(such as jurisdiction, procedure, and
statutory construction)</i> which have the potential to establish
roadblocks that could limit the procedural rights of
many parties.<p>

If the Supreme Court agrees to hear a case, SCAP assists attorneys
in writing briefs and preparing for oral argument, including
organizing moot courts.  During the 1994-1995 term, SCAp was
involved in approximately 30 cases in which the Court granted
certiorari.<p>

If you are aware of cases that are likely to be presented to the
Court and the lawyer may need a little technical assistance, by all
means, encourage the lawyer to contact us.  Or if you find yourself
with a case that appears to be headed to the High Court and you
could use some advice about any matter -- procedural or substantive
-- just let us know.<p>
<hr>

