<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>SCAP JOB ANNOUNCEMENT</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#0000ff"
VLINK="#dd0000" 
ALINK="#ff0000">
<h3><center><FONT SIZE=+2>S</FONT>UPREME <FONT
SIZE=+2>C</FONT>OURT <FONT SIZE=+2>A</FONT>SSISTANCE <FONT
SIZE=+2>P</FONT>ROJECT<p>
<FONT SIZE=+2>P</FONT>ROJECT <FONT
SIZE=+2>C</FONT>OORDINATOR<p>
<blink>JOB ANNOUNCEMENT</blink><p>
<FONT SIZE=+2>O</FONT>CTOBER 1996<p></center></h3>
<hr>
<p>
    Spend your first year out of law school working on Supreme
Court cases for public interest firm with substantial Supreme
Court practice.  Job available approximately <b>August 1997-
August 1998</b>.<p>

    The Public Citizen Litigation Group, a Washington public
interest office of 10 lawyers founded by Ralph Nader and Alan
Morrison in 1972, operates a Supreme Court Assistance Project
to help small firm practitioners, legal services lawyers, and
other lawyers with little or no experience in Supreme Court
litigation.  The Project provides direct assistance to those
lawyers both before review is granted, either by helping with
the cert. petition or the brief in opposition, and, in those
cases in which review is granted, working with the lawyers on
the briefs and oral arguments.  In rare cases, the principal
role is assumed by a Litigation Group attorney, but generally
the Group's role is advisory.  We are looking for a recent law
school graduate for the position of <i>Project
Coordinator.</i><p>

    The work of the Coordinator focuses on identifying the
cases warranting assistance.  The Project seeks cases in which
important legal principles are at stake, and where the
attorneys for the side that we support  generally that of the
underdog  may lack significant Supreme Court experience. 
Most, but not all, of the cases are civil, rather than
criminal.  So far, most of the pre-grant cases involve
assistance to the party who won below, where our role is to
help devise a strategy to keep the case out of the Court and
thereby preserve a victory.  Increasingly, we have found ways
to broaden our work by reaching potential petitioners who
might wish to use our services.<p>

    The person who serves as Project Coordinator will spend a
substantial portion of his or her time reading all cert.
petitions, other than those filed <i>in forma pauperis</i>,
which are generally criminal cases.  Working under the direct
supervision of the Group's senior lawyer, the Coordinator
makes an initial judgment about whether the case is of no,
little, or considerable interest to the Project, and then
prepares a memo on those in which there may be some interest. 
Additional research and analysis are sometimes required to
determine whether assertions, such as a conflict among the
courts of appeals, are supportable.  The Coordinator then
makes an initial contact with the attorney to whom help is
being offered to explain the Project and the assistance that
we provide.  All cases accepted by the Court for full review
are considered for possible assistance by the Project.<p>

    Where our offer of help is accepted, one of the Group's
attorneys assumes principal responsibility for the case within
the office.  To the extent that the Coordinator has time, he
or she is encouraged to participate fully in all aspects of
the Project, including reading draft briefs and commenting on
them, conducting research (usually on discrete issues),
participating in moot courts, and attending oral arguments. 
From time to time, the Coordinator has worked, and will
continue to work, on other Litigation Group cases, either in
the Supreme Court or elsewhere.<p> 

    The salary is $27,720 (possibly somewhat more for
experienced applicants), plus fully paid comprehensive health
insurance and two weeks vacation.  An outside gift to help
repay student loans may also be available.  Applicants should
have a solid academic background, good writing and analytical
skills, and a knowledge of a wide range of subject areas that
arise in Supreme Court litigation (but not in depth).  Some
practical litigation experience in school or elsewhere is
preferred, but not required.  A strong preference will be
given to those who have a demonstrated commitment to public
interest work.  Minorities are strongly encouraged to
apply.<p>

    Applicants should send a cover letter, along with a
resume, a list of references, a copy of law school transcript,
and a writing sample to Brian Wolfman, staff attorney, at the
above address.  The writing sample should be legal in nature
(brief, memorandum, or research paper) and should be the
applicant's own work, not a collaborative piece or something
heavily edited by someone else.  Applications should be
received <b>no later than November 22, 1996</b>.  Interviews
will be either a lengthy telephone interview with several
people from our staff, or in-person.  Interviews will take
place in mid-December through early January, with the hope
that a decision will be made by early February.<p>

    Public Citizen is a no-smoking office.<p>
<HR>
