<html>
<head>
<title>History of the Line Item Veto Act of 1996</title>
</head>
<body>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#0000ff"
ALINK="#ff0000" 
VLINK="#dd0000">
<center><b>LEGISLATIVE SUMMARY</b></center>
<p>
<center><b>HISTORY OF THE LINE ITEM VETO ACT OF 1996</b></center>
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<p>

     <b>1.  <i>The House of Representatives</i> </b><p>

     On January 3, 1995, H.R. 2 was introduced and referred to the
Committee on Government
Reform and Oversight.  <i>See</i> H.R. 2, 104th Cong. 1st Sess.
(1995).  The bill was a broad-ranging
"enhanced rescission" line item veto, under which the President had
20 days after a bill is enacted
to veto items which he disapproved.  It entitled the President to
"rescind all or part of any
discretionary budget authority."  Sec. 2(a).  His authority was not
limited to items in the statute
itself, but included identifiable items in the legislative history. 
The bill provided that any
budgetary authority that is rescinded "shall be deemed canceled
unless" the Congress overrides it,
Sec. 3(a)(1), and that "any provision of law <i>vetoed</i> under
this Act . . . shall be deemed <i>repealed</i>
unless  . . . a rescission/receipts disapproval bill restoring that
provision is enacted into law."  Sec.
3(a)(2) (emphasis added).  In addition, it also authorized the
President to "<i>veto</i> any targeted tax
benefit" (one limited to a few persons), subject to the same
two-thirds override.  Sec. 2 (emphasis
added).<p>

     On January 12, 1995, the House Government Reform and Oversight
Committee held a joint
hearing with the Senate Government Affairs Committee, at which the
only dissenting witness was
Chief Judge Gilbert S. Merritt of the Sixth Circuit, who, as
Chairman of the Executive Committee
of the Judicial Conference, expressed concern about the policy
implications of a presidential line
item veto for appropriations for the judiciary.  <i>See</i> H.R.
Rep. No. 11, 104th Cong., 1st Sess. 13
(January 30, 1995) ("House Report").  A markup was held on January
25, 1995, and the bill was
reported favorably, with amendments, by a roll call vote of 30-11. 
<i>Id.</i> at 12.  <p>

     There were several committee decisions of note.  The period
during which the President had
the right to veto items was shortened from the original 20 calendar
days (not including Saturdays,
Sundays, or holidays), to 10 calendar days, not including Sundays. 
<i>Id.</i> at 2.  The term "targeted
tax benefit" was expanded somewhat so that the maximum size of the
group of taxpayers whose
benefits could be vetoed went from five in the bill as introduced
to 100.  <i>Id.</i> at 2, 26, 27.  An
attempt to exclude the judiciary was defeated by a vote of 17-29,
<i>id.</i> at 21, and efforts to sunset
the legislation were turned back by a vote of 17-22.  <i>Id.</i> at
31, 35.  <p>

     The House Report was clear about the purpose of H.R. 2: "to
change the tilt of the game from
one that favors spending to one that favors saving."  <i>Id.</i> at
7.  In discussing the problem which the
President had in obtaining congressional approval of rescissions,
the Report stated that the bill
"reverses the burden.  Presidential proposals will now become law
unless Congress takes action to
stop them."  <i>Id.</i> at 9.<p>

     Several other references clarify how the bill was intended to
work.  Thus, the committee
observed that its bill "strengthens the President's ability to
rescind (cancel) appropriated funds.  It
also allows the President to <i>eliminate</i> targeted tax benefits
. . .. "  <i>Id.</i> at 8 (emphasis added). 
Although the report refers to the actions of the President as
"recommendations" that various items
"be terminated," the report confirms that no prior action by
Congress is required since the
"recommendations will automatically become law after a fixed period
of time, unless Congress,
during a designated review period, votes by bill or joint
resolution to disapprove."  <i>Id</i>;  <i>see</i> <i>also</i>
<i>id.</i> at 10 (budget authority or targeted tax benefits will
automatically be terminated after a fixed
number of days unless Congress acts by a bill or joint resolution
to disapprove the President's
proposal); <i>id.</i> at 14 ("Any provision of law, as set forth in
a President's special message, shall be
deemed <i>repealed</i> unless a rescission/receipts disapproval
bill restoring that provision is enacted
into law.") (emphasis added).  <p>

     Although line item veto supporters often referred to the
experience of the states with the item
veto, the House Report recognized that "H.R. 2 differs
fundamentally from the kind of item veto
authority granted to governors in 43 states."  <i>Id.</i> at 11. 
Whereas state appropriations bills are
highly itemized, federal laws are not, and the Committee sees "no
reason to do so" because that
would "add an undesirable rigidity to agency operations." 
<i>Id.</i> Instead, Congress could continue to
appropriate with lump sums, and the President could "propose for
reduction or elimination any
dollar amount specifically identified in a bill or committee report
or joint explanatory statement
accompanying a conference report on that Act," so that the
President would have "greater power
and discretion than he would have with item veto authority." 
<i>Id.</i> at 12. <p>

     House floor consideration of the bill occurred on February 2,
3, and 6, 1995, 141 Cong. Rec.
H.1078-1142; 1168-1191; 1225-1264 (daily ed.), and was generally
less noteworthy for what was
said than for the amendments that were offered and rejected. 
<i><b>(See Footnote 1)</i> </b>Initially, two
amendments were adopted unanimously.  The first, offered by
Representative Clinger, the
Chairman of the Committee on Government Reform and Oversight, was
intended to clarify that,
although the bill permits the President to look to legislative
history and thereby go behind
appropriations bills, he "may not look to Office of Management and
Budget (OMB) or agency
justifications or other types of documents to rescind funds for
programs not specified by
Congress."  H.1106.  It was also intended to assure that the
President "may only rescind dollar
amounts, not bill language . . . [contrary to the practice] in some
states [where] the Governor
does have the power to actually effect statutory language." 
H.1106.  Another amendment,
sponsored by Representative Pelosi, was along similar lines and
specified that the President may
not "change any prohibition or limitation of discretionary budget
authority set forth in any
appropriations act."  H.1107.  <p>

     Most of the amendments offered were rejected.  Representative
Moran offered an amendment,
comparable to the one that had been previously rejected in
committee, to remove the authority to
rescind budgetary authority for the judicial branch.  H.1107.  That
amendment was rejected by a
vote of 119-309.  H.1115.  Three separate efforts were defeated to
broaden the authority of the
President to cut back on tax benefits of various kinds.  H.1116,
H.1125, H.1168, H.1170,
H.1235, H.1255.  Two other attempts to alter the scope of the
rescission authority were also
turned back.  Representative Skelton moved to limit the President's
cancellation authority to $50
million of discretionary budget authority and to exclude "any
program, project, or activity within
the major functional category for national defense."  H.1130.  That
amendment was defeated by a
vote of 52-362.  H.1138.  Representative Orton attempted to bring
contract authority within the
scope of the line  item veto, H.1225-34, but that was defeated by
a recorded vote of 65-360. 
H.1254.  An effort was made to impose a sunset date of January 1,
2000, H.1139, but that, too,
was strongly opposed by supporters and rejected by a vote of
153-258.  H.1142.       <p>

     The single most crucial vote was on an "expedited rescission"
substitute offered by
Representatives Wise, Stenholm, and Sprat.  Expedited rescission
would have established
procedures for voting on a President's proposed rescission under
the Impoundment Control Act of
1974, 2 U.S.C. Sec. 688.  As Representative Stenholm put it: 
"[t]he only question is, how much
power do you wish to cede to a President.  That is it."  H.1176. 
Even though 342 Members of
the House had voted for this approach in 1994, H.1171-72, H.1245,
and even though there was
no question as to the constitutionality of expedited rescission,
H.1185, the House twice voted it
down by margins of 167-246, H.1186, and 156-266.  H.1242-56. <p>

     The final amendment, which was adopted without objection,
created a mechanism for
expedited judicial review.  H.1138-39.  It gave standing to Members
of Congress, a hearing
before a three- judge district court in the District of Columbia,
direct appeal to the Supreme
Court, and expedition in both Courts.  The judicial review
amendment was offered by Rep. Deal
of Georgia, a strong supporter of the bill, who noted that "[s]ince
we are proceeding in a statutory
form for a line item veto and not a constitutional amendment, it
should be obvious that until that
constitutionality is clarified, it will be under a cloud."  H.1138. 
In his prepared statement, he
observed that "[h]opefully, the procedure established by my
amendment will result in a final
resolution regarding the constitutionality of line item veto
authority before the fiscal year 1996
appropriation bills are sent to the President."  H.1139.  His
statement further noted that "[i]f my
amendment for judicial review is not added to the bill, it is
unlikely that the courts would consider
the issue until the President exercises the line item authority." 
H.1139.  His position was
supported by Rep. Blute, another proponent, who observed that "this
is a good amendment which
simply ensures that any court challenge to H.R. 2 be considered on
an expedited basis."  <i>Id</i>. 
Congresswoman Collins, an opponent of the bill, also supported this
amendment because it allows
"a test case on this legislation constitutionally without having to
wait for the President to use the
line item veto authority this bill gives him."  H.1139. <p>

     At the end of the lengthy debate, a vote to recommit was
defeated, largely along party lines, by
a vote of 185-241, H.1263, followed by an affirmative vote on final
passage of 294-134. H.1264.<p>

<b>2.  <i>The Senate</b></i><p>

     In the Senate, there were two principal bills.  S. 4, an
"enhanced rescission" bill, was
substantially the same as H.R. 2, except that it did not permit
item veto of tax expenditures. S. 4
required a two-thirds override, allowed the President to reduce as
well as eliminate items of
budgetary authority, and was not limited to items appearing in an
appropriations bill itself.  <i>See</i> S.
Rep. No. 9, 104th Cong., 1st Sess. (1995); S. Rep. No. 13, 104th
Cong., 1st Sess. (1995). <p>

     The other vehicle, S. 14, was an "expedited rescission" bill,
similar to the Stenholm, Wise, and
Sprat substitute rejected on the House floor, except that it also
applied to new entitlement and to
tax expenditures.  <i>See</i> S. Rep. No. 10, 104th Cong., 1st
Sess. (1995); S. Rep. No. 14, 104th
Cong., 1st Sess. (1995).  Both bills were referred jointly to the
Committees on Budget and
Governmental Affairs.  On January 18, 1995, the Budget Committee,
Chaired by Sen. Domenici,
held hearings on both bills.  In his opening statement, the
Chairman stated that he preferred S. 14,
and described S. 4 as involving a "maximum shift in power." 
<i>Line-Item Rescission Authority:
Hearings on S. 4 and S. 14 Before The Comm. on the Budget, 104th
Cong., 1st Sess.</i> 2 (1995). 
<i><b>(See Footnote 2)</b></i>  In the words of its sponsors, S. 14
would have "guarantee[d] the President a
vote on his rescission proposals while maintaining the delicate
balance of power between the two
branches on spending authority."  S. Rep. No. 9 at 15 (additional
views of Sen. Domenici).   <p>

     Shortly thereafter, the Subcommittee on the Constitution,
Federalism, and Property Rights of
the Committee on the Judiciary held a hearing to consider two
proposed constitutional
amendments that would create a line item veto, S.J. Res. 2 and S.J.
Res. 16.  <i>See</i> <i>The Line-Item
Veto: A Constitutional Approach: Hearings before the Subcomm. on
the Constitution,
Federalism, and Property Rights of the Comm. on the Judiciary</i>,
104th Cong., 1st Sess (1995). 
<i><b>(See Footnote 3)</b></i>  At that hearing, Senator Biden, who
described himself as a supporter of a
statutory line item veto, opposed a constitutional amendment
because of its permanence, <i>id.</i> at 5,
6, 10, expressed his support for the concept of "separate
enrollment," <i>id.</i> at 10, but strongly urged
his colleagues to insist on a sunset provision.  <i>Id.</i> at
10-11.<p>

     Appearing for the Administration was Assistant Attorney
General Walter Dellinger of the
Office of Legal Counsel at the Department of Justice, who stated
that the President supported a
"strong line-item veto" bill, in particular S. 4.  <i>Id.</i> at
33.  He expressed his opinion that S. 4 is
"clearly constitutional" as "a very strong delegation of authority
to the President . . . not to
expend appropriated funds . . .."  <i>Id.</i> at 34.  He recognized
that the President's cancellation order
"is final and what happens in Congress is that Congress then must
vote a new bill to actually
proceed with that funding, which the President can then veto.  That
is why S. 4 is a two-thirds
bill."  <i>Id.</i>  When asked about the advisability of a
constitutional amendment, he expressed
reservations because of its permanence.  <i>Id.</i> at 35. <p>

        He also stated quite clearly what he thought would
<i>not</i> be constitutional.  Citing what he
called "a long tradition at the Office of Legal Counsel," and
invoking the views of three of his
predecessors in the Reagan and Bush Administrations, he stated that
all of them "have agreed the
President does not at present have that power constitutionally." 
<i>Id.</i> at 36.  He also said that they
all agreed that "Congress cannot literally give the President a
line item veto power by statute, and
that attempts that appear to literally give the President a line
item veto by statute are also
constitutionally invalid."  <i>Id.</i> at 36; <i>see</i>
<i>also</i> <i>id.</i> at 38.  <p>

     On the issue of separate enrollment, he noted that "[a]s much
as I regret saying so," it "also
raises significant constitutional issues" under the Presentment
Clause, or "at a minimum, it raises
such complicated questions under the Presentment Clause that it is
a foolhardy way to proceed
because if we and all our predecessors are right, I think that
which has to be presented to the
House is the thing that passed the House and the Senate and that
which passed the House and
Senate is the bill they voted on final passage, not some little
piece of it or a series of little pieces
of it."  <i>Id.</i> at 38.<p>

     In his prepared statement, Mr. Dellinger explored at greater
length the constitutionality of S. 4. 
While defending "enhanced rescission" on the ground that it was a
lawful delegation to the
President of discretion over spending appropriated funds, he
expressed doubts about the
constitutionality of the provision dealing with targeted tax
benefits because it purports "to
authorize the President to 'veto' targeted tax benefits after they
become law, thus resulting in their
'repeal.'"  <i>Id</i>. at 49.   He then observed that "use of the
terms 'veto' and 'repeal' is constitutionally
problematic [because Article I, Sec. 7 of the Constitution]
provides that the President only can
exercise his 'veto' power before a provision becomes law." 
<i>Id.</i>  He also observed that "the word
'repeal' suggests that the President is being given authorization
to change existing law on his own
[which] arguably would violate the plain textual provisions of
Article I, Section 7 of the
Constitution, governing the manner in which federal laws are to be
made and altered."  <i>Id.</i> <p>

     Mr. Dellinger's method of avoiding these "constitutional
shoals" would be to "recast" S. 4 so
that it "eliminates the word 'veto' from the targeted tax benefit
provision, and confers on the
President the power to <i>suspend</i> (rather than 'repeal') such
benefits."  <i>Id.</i>  These changes would
"preserve the purpose of the provision" and "would place the
targeted tax benefit provision on the
same defensible constitutional footing as the provision regarding
rescission of budget authority." 
<i>Id.</i><p>

     On February 22, 1995, the Senate Budget Committee reported out
S. 4 with amendments, but
without recommendation.  <i>See</i> S. Rep. No. 9, at 13.  The
Committee report makes clear that the
President's rescissions "would remain in effect unless Congress
passed a disapproval bill . . . . and
overcame the President's veto of that disapproval bill," <i>id.</i>
at 1 and that the Committee considered
the authority under S. 4 to be either "rescissions or repeals." 
<i>Id.</i> at 5.  <p>

     The Committee adopted two amendments.  <i>Id.</i> at 8.  The
first, offered by Senator Domenici,
added a sunset date of September 30, 2002 (Sec. 1114), and the
other (Sec. 1113), offered by
Senators Conrad and Snow, established a "lock box" to assure that
any savings from Presidential
rescissions would be devoted to deficit reduction and not spent for
other purposes.  Although he
voted to report out the bill, Sen. Domenici expressed "serious
reservations about S. 4" in his
separate views because he believed that it would "delegate too much
authority to the President
over the control of the budget."  <i>Id.</i> at 14.  He also
expressed his concern that "[o]nly a
Constitutional amendment can give the President the authority to
delete items in spending bills
and the Judiciary Committee has jurisdiction over the line item
veto constitutional amendment." 
<i>Id.</i> at 16.  Shortly thereafter, the Senate Governmental
Affairs Committee also reported S. 4 as
passed by the Budget Committee, without recommendation and with no
further amendments.  S.
Rep. No. 13, at 6. <p>

     S. 14 was also reported out by both Senate Committees, also
without recommendation.  S.
Rep. No. 10, at 9; S. Rep. No. 14, at 6.  The Committee on the
Budget made some small changes
to the bill as introduced, but under both versions, the President's
proposed rescissions would not
take effect until Congress had affirmatively approved them.  S.
Rep. No. 14, at 7-11; S. Rep. No.
10, at 9.  In addition, S. 14 would also apply to "targeted tax
benefits" which, like in the House's
version, were those limited to 100 or fewer persons.  S. Rep. No.
10, at 14; S. Rep. No. 14, at 11. <p>

     S. 4 then went to the Senate floor where it was considered on
March 16 (S.4074-89); March
17 (S.4125-45); March 20 (S.4153-96); March 21 (S.4212-60); March
22 (S.4295-58) and March
23 (S.4409-87).  Almost immediately, it was announced that the
"enhanced rescission" version of
the line-item veto contained in S. 4, which had been reported out
by both the Budget and
Governmental Affairs Committees, and which was similar to the
House-passed H.R. 2, would not
in fact be the approach that the Senate leadership supported. 
S.4075.  Instead, debate would be
on a "separate enrollment" proposal, on which bills had been
introduced.  S.4075-76. <p>

     The separate enrollment substitute was introduced by Majority
Leader Senator Dole.  S.4188-89.  Under separate enrollment, once
an appropriations bill passed both Houses in agreed upon
form, the enrollment clerks would divide the unified bill into as
many separate bills as there were
separate items of spending, and those separate bills would each be
presented to the President for
his signature.  In addition to the change in the basic form of the
line item veto, the most significant
changes from S. 4, as reported, were the additions of new targeted
tax benefits and new direct
spending, as subjects on which the President could exercise his
line item veto, and the addition of
a sunset date of September 30, 2000.  S.4189.<p>

     Because the Line Item Veto Act ultimately enacted was similar
to the enhanced rescission
version passed by the House in H.R. 2, and not the separate
enrollment substitute, much of the
Senate discussion is no longer relevant.  Nonetheless, despite
these differences, many of the same
issues were raised on the floors of both Houses, generally with the
same result.  Indeed, the
principal Senate sponsor of the line item veto, Sen. McCain,
recognized the essential similarity
between enhanced rescission and separate enrollment.  S.4076.<p>

     The most significant decision in both Houses was whether to
adopt a "strong line item veto"
(in the Senate, separate enrollment, in the House, enhanced
rescission) or to adopt expedited
rescission, essentially the same debate as had occurred in
committee between S. 4 and S. 14, and
had occurred on the House floor.  As Sen. McCain said at the outset
of the Senate floor debate,
"it will boil down to one single issue, have no doubt about it, and
that is whether we would have a
two-thirds vote on the part of both Bodies in order to override the
President's veto--that is what
43 Governors have and that is what the constitutional meaning of
veto is--or whether we will have
a majority vote of one House . . .."  S.4158.  Or, as he put it
earlier, the question "will be, is the
Congress of the United States prepared to transfer significant
power from the legislative branch of
Government to the executive branch of Government for the sake of
the future of our children?"
S.4079. <p>

     Sen. Coats, a co-sponsor with Sen. McCain of a "strong" line
item veto, described the Dole
substitute as one with bipartisan support "that is a real veto
requiring two-thirds of the Congress
to override . . .."  S.4192.  He subsequently referred to the
two-thirds requirement as "the core
concept of line item veto," S.4220, including separate enrollment
as a device that "also can be
described as line item veto . . .."  S.4221.  Similarly, another
supporter of the line item veto, Sen.
Craig, described the two-thirds override as "really at the heart of
all of this." S.4222.  Thus, near
the end of the debate, he observed that the "only material
difference remaining between the Dole
and Daschle [S. 14] versions is whether you want a line item veto
to be overridden by a majority
vote or a [two-thirds] vote."  S.4479.  A substitute "expedited
rescission" alternative, which was
very similar to S. 14, was introduced by Senators Daschle, Exon,
and Glenn, and a motion to
table it passed by a vote of 62-38.  S.4428.       <p>

     Two amendments were adopted on the Senate floor that are of
some significance.  The first,
the so-called Exon "lock box" amendment, S.4259, was agreed to by
consent.  S.4326.  The "lock
box" device ensures that any savings from a Presidential
cancellation are used solely to reduce the
deficit.  Thus, once the congressional review process has
concluded, the administrative and
legislative entities that keep track of the budget make the changes
permanent, thereby preventing
Congress and the President from spending the money on something
else, or from spending the
canceled funds for their appropriated purposes if circumstances
change.<p>

     The second adopted amendment was Sen. Simon's expedited
judicial review provision. 
S.4244.  Like its House counterpart, it provided for Member
standing, a special three-judge court,
direct appeal to the Supreme Court, and expedited consideration in
both Courts.  Sen. McCain
stated that he was "in agreement, except with one caveat," that a
severability clause be added. 
S.4244.  Sen. Simon said that he believed this could be worked out,
and Sen. McCain stated that
he wanted to ensure that if "one minor provision of the Act is
declared unconstitutional, I would
not want the entire Act to be declared unconstitutional."  S.4245. 
Shortly thereafter, the Senate
agreed to the Simon amendment which included a separate
severability provision.  S.4259.<p>

     Part of the willingness of all Members of the Senate to accept
the expedited judicial review
provision was the recognition that, even without the exercise of an
item veto, legislative practices
would change immediately as a result of the President's new power
to wield the item veto.  Sen.
McCain himself, at the opening of the debate, observed that "it
will be very hard to measure the
exact effect of a line item veto, because when a line item veto is
threatened, we will find a
dramatic reduction in the kinds of anecdotal appropriations which
have plagued this body's
reputation with the American people."  S.4076.  Sen. Coats observed
that "it will change the
spending habits of Congress . . . [w]e will never know the amount
of money we save for items
that will not be put in these new bills for fear of exposure. 
Because the President has the line-item
veto, it will change the way we put the bills together in the first
place."  S.4140.  Or, as another
strong line item veto supporter, Sen. Smith, observed, "if we pass
the line item veto, there is
going to be a lot less of the stuff put in the bill in the first
place.  That is for sure."  S.4142.  Sen.
Coats made a similar point later on:<br>

<blockquote> So we will never be able to total up the amount of
money that we have saved for our
constituents and for the taxpayer because the line item veto will
have accomplished its purpose --
its purpose being to prevent this kind of activity from taking
place in the first place; to prevent the
kind of embarrassment that we go through on an annual basis when we
discover the items that
have been slipped into the appropriations bills, slipped into
legislation, slipped into tax bills at the
last minute in conference behind closed doors late at night, and
then presented in a massive bill.</blockquote><br>

S.4221.  Or, as he also noted, the line item veto power "will
fundamentally change the way we
think and behave.  That fundamental change will means that items
which would have been
attached to appropriations bills or would have been incorporated in
the tax bills will not be,
because of the fear that they will be exposed to public scrutiny
before it finally becomes law."  <i>Id.</i> 
<i>See</i> <i>also</i> S.4240 ("My guess is that many will not see
the light of day because those items are
items that we know cannot generate a majority of support, otherwise
they would be brought as
individual items to this floor. . . [o]nly we know in our hearts
and in our minds what items we
might have attached if we had not had line-item veto.").<p>

     Another important theme throughout the Senate floor debate was
that the inclusion of the
authority to item veto limited tax benefits and new items of direct
spending (entitlement) was an
essential element of the ultimate compromise.  S.4125-26 (Stevens);
S.4126 (McCain); S.4127
(Coats); S.4174 (Lott, tax deals); S.4220 (tough negotiations to
bring in the tax and entitlement
aspects); S. 4234 (Coats, describing direct spending and tax
benefits); S.4296 (Santorum,
explaining bill had bipartisan support and reached tax benefits and
entitlement); and S.4420 (Kyl,
emphasizing the importance to Democrats of the tax benefits, lock
box, and sunset provisions). 
<i><b>(See Footnote 4)</b></i><p>

     With more than sixty Senators voting to reject Senator
Daschle's "expedited rescission"
substitute, passage of a separate enrollment bill was assured. 
When the final vote was taken on S.
4 on March 23, 1995, 69 Senators voted in favor and 29 opposed.
S.4484-85. <p>

<b>     3.  <i>The Conference</i></b><p>

     S. 4 was returned to the House where it was considered on the
floor on May 17, 1995. 
H.5090-97.  Rep. Clinger moved to strike the substance of the
Senate bill and replace it with the
House bill so that the matter could then proceed to conference. 
H.5090.  Speaking in support of
his motion, Chairman Clinger referred to the Senate version as a
"weaker bill" and stated that he
expected a "difficult conference" because the House bill "has a
potential constitutional challenge"
whereas the Senate bill "would require the enrollment of thousands
of bills to pass appropriations
in discrete line items requiring thousands of signatures and
guaranteeing future Presidents an
amazing case of writer's cramps as they deal with this as well as
creating some significant amount
of paperwork."  H.5091.  His motion was agreed to without a
recorded vote.  H.5094.<p>

     On March 21, 1996, nearly a year after both Houses had passed
a line item veto bill, the
Conference reached agreement.  <i>See</i> Line Item Veto Act, H.R.
Conf. Rep. 104-491, 104th Cong.,
2d Sess. (1996) (hereafter "Conf. Rep.").  Other than using the
bill number S. 4 as the vehicle, the
conference version bore no relation to the Senate-passed bill, but
was quite similar to H.R. 2 as
passed by the House.<p>

     First, the chosen version of the line item veto was not
separate enrollment but enhanced
rescission.  The law's full title is "An Act to give the President
line item veto authority with
respect to appropriations, new direct spending, and limited tax
benefits."  Conf. Rep. at 14.  The
President's item veto power is triggered when a bill or resolution
"has been signed into law
pursuant to Article I, Section 7 of the Constitution."  Section
2(a) (adding ICA Sec. 1021(a)). 
<i><b>(See Footnote 5)</i>  </b>The Conferees also reduced to five
days the time in which the President could
exercise his veto authority after signing.  <i>Id.</i>  <p>

     The Conferees explained that they "specifically include[d] the
requirement that a bill or joint
resolution must have been signed into law in order to clarify that
the cancellation authority only
becomes effective after the President has exercised the
constitutional authority to enact legislation
in its entirety.  This requirement ensures that the President
affirmatively demonstrates support for
the underlying legislation from which the specific cancellations
are then permitted."  Conf. Rep. at
20.  The Conferees intended that the cancellations would occur "as
soon as possible" and
provided a "maximum time" of five days only "to ensure that all
supporting material required for
inclusion in the special message can be provided by the
Administration."  <i>Id.</i> at 22.       The
President is given authority to "cancel" in whole any dollar amount
of discretionary budget
authority, any item of new direct spending, or any limited tax
benefit.  Section 2(a) (adding ICA
Sec. 1021(a)(1)-(3)).  The terms "cancel" or "cancellation" are
defined in section 1026(4).  With
respect to discretionary budget authority, "cancel" is defined to
mean "rescind."  <i>Id.</i> (adding ICA
Sec. 1026(4)(A)).  With regard to items of new direct spending,
such as new entitlement or
increases in existing entitlement, the term "cancellation" means
"to prevent [the item] from having
legal force or effect."  <i>Id.</i> (adding ICA Sec. 1026(4)(B)). 
<i><b>(See Footnote 6)</i>  </b>Similarly, with
respect to limited tax benefits, cancellation prevents "the
specific provision of law that provides
such benefit from having legal force or effect."  <i>Id.</i>
(adding ICA Sec. 1026(4)(C)).  The
Conference Report states, "[t]he term 'cancel' was specifically
chosen, and is carefully defined in
section 1026.  The conferees intend that the President may use the
cancellation authority <i>to
surgically terminate federal budget obligations.</i>"  Conf. Rep.
at 20 (emphasis added).  In contrast
to the House bill, which allowed the President to reduce as well as
to eliminate items, the final
version limits the power of the President to cancel items "in
whole."  <i>Id.</i> (adding ICA Secs.
1021(a), 1026(7)).  To further clarify that a cancellation of
budget authority terminates the
spending authority, the Act adopts a "lock box" procedure so that
the "savings" cannot be used
for a subsequent appropriation or direct spending measure or tax
benefits.  <i>See</i> Section 2(a)
(adding ICA Sec. 1024).   <p>

     Like the versions that passed both Houses, the President's
authority is not limited to items
specified in the legislation itself.  The veto power reaches not
only the "entire dollar of budget
authority" that is "specified in an appropriation law" but also
amounts "required to be allocated by
a specific proviso in an appropriation law for which a specific
dollar figure was not included."  <i>Id.</i>
(adding ICA Sec. 1026(7)(A)(i)).  The cancellation authority also
extends to amounts
"represented separately in any table, chart or explanatory text
included in the statement of
managers or the governing committee report accompanying such law." 
<i>Id.</i> (adding ICA Sec.
1026(7)(A)(ii)).  <i><b>(See Footnote 7)</i>  </b>An example in the
Conference Report--referring to use of a
table accompanying a Conference Report--illustrates the kind of
legislative materials the President
may use in exercising the item veto.  Conf. Rep. at 22-23.  The
President, however, "cannot use
this authority to modify or alter any aspect of the underlying law,
including any restriction,
limitation or condition on the expenditure of budget authority, or
any other requirement of law." 
<i>Id.</i> at 20.  <p>

     Line item veto of "limited tax benefits" remains basically as
it was enacted in both Houses. 
"Limited tax benefits" are "any revenue-losing provision" that
provides a "deduction, credit,
exclusion, or preference" to 100 or fewer taxpayers during any
fiscal year that the rule is in effect,
unless it is a transition provision, in which case the number of
taxpayers is 10 or fewer.  Section
2(a) (adding ICA Sec. 1026(9)).  One significant addition in the
Conference was a process for
identification of limited tax benefits.  Under a new provision, if
either the bill itself identifies a
provision as a limited tax benefit, or the Joint Committee on
Taxation does so, those are the
exclusive provisions that the President may cancel.  <i>Id.</i>
(adding ICA Sec. 1027)).  If neither of
these sources identifies any such benefits, however, then the
President may use the definitions
under section 2(a) of the Act (adding ICA Sec. 1026) to select
benefits to be canceled.  Finally,
the Act precludes judicial review of Congressional identifications
of a limited tax benefit.  <i>Id.</i> 
(adding ICA Sec. 1027(d)). <p>

     Under the Conference bill, the procedures to be followed for
the President to exercise a line
item veto are basically the same as in the earlier enhanced
rescission versions.  As a prerequisite to
issuing a cancellation order, the President must determine only
that the cancellation will "(i)
reduce the federal budget deficit, (ii) not impair any essential
Government functions, and, (iii) not
harm the national interest."  <i>Id.</i> (adding ICA Sec.
1021(a)(3)(A)).  The President must send a
single cancellation message for all items he wishes to cancel in
each law.  <i>Id.</i> (adding ICA
Sec. 1022(a)).  He has five calendar days, excluding Sundays, to
submit his message after
enactment.  <i>Id.</i> (adding ICA Sec. 1021(a)(3)(B)).<p>

     The cancellation order is effective immediately upon receipt
in the Congress.  <i>Id.</i> (adding ICA
Sec. 1023(a)).  As the Conference Report stated:
<br>
<blockquote>Upon receipt of the President's special message in both
the House of Representatives and the
Senate each [item] identified in the special message is immediately
canceled.  The cancellation of a
dollar amount of discretionary budget authority automatically
rescinds the funds.  With respect to
an item of new direct spending or a limited tax benefit, the
cancellation renders the provision void,
such that the obligation of the United States has no legal force or
effect. </blockquote>
<br>
Conf. Rep. at 22.  The Report also noted that the cancellation "is
nullified only if a disapproval bill
is enacted into law [in which case the] effective date for any
cancellation . . . is the original date
provided in the law to which the cancellation applied."  <i>Id.</i> 
Finally, even if Congress has
insufficient time to act before adjourning sine die, the
cancellation continues in effect, and the
disapproval period is started again in the next Congress.  Section
2(a) (adding ICA Sec.
1025(b)(3)).<p>

     The Act provides for expedited congressional consideration of
a disapproval bill.  <i>Id.</i> (adding
ICA Sec. 1025).  No Congressional approval is needed to make the
President's cancellation
effective.  Conf. Rep. at 22.  In essence, Congress has 30 calendar
days of session after receipt,
although in the Senate, if the process is underway when the 30 days
expire, the expedition rules
continue to apply.  In the House all items in the President's
cancellation message must be included
in a disapproval resolution, a limit that does not apply in the
Senate.  Section 2(a) (adding ICA
Sec. 1025(c)(2)).  The relevant House committee is given seven days
to report the bill without
amendment, and the only floor amendments that are in order are
those to strike a cancellation
item, which require the sponsorship of at least 50 Members. 
<i>Id.</i> (adding Sec. 1025(d)).  In the
Senate, additions or deletions of particular items are in order,
and there is no minimum number of
Senators required.  <i>Id.</i> (adding Sec. 1025(B)(4)).  After the
expiration of the 30 days for
expedited consideration, unless there is a disapproval bill enacted
within 10 calendar days, the
cancellation is permanent. <i>Id.</i> (adding ICA Secs.
1024(b)-(c)).<p>

     The Conferees also included a judicial review provision,
<i>see</i> section 3, 110 Stat. 1211 (codified
at 2 U.S.C. Sec. 692), although they deleted the requirement for a
three-judge court that was in
both the Senate and House bills.  There is no explanation in the
Conference Report for this
change, but it appears to have been prompted by a letter from then
Director of the Office of
Management and Budget, Alice Rivlin, stating the Administration's
opposition to three-judge
courts (copy attached).  Two other changes of note occurred in this
provision:  it was expanded
to cover "any individual adversely affected by [this Act]," and the
severability provision added in
the Senate was deleted.  Section 3.<p>

     The Conferees agreed that the bill would be made effective on
the earlier of the enactment of
"a seven-year plan for deficit reduction [and to] achieve a
balanced Federal budget," or January 1,
1997.  Section 5.  And while the sunset provision that the Senate
had insisted upon was included,
the sunset date was extended until January 1, 2005, giving the Act
a life of eight rather than five
years.  <i>Id.</i> <p>

     Not surprisingly, once agreement had been reached, the floor
debates on March 27 and March
28, 1996, primarily explained what had already taken place. 
S.2929-95 and H.2971-3028.  For
example, in his opening statement, Senator McCain described the
President's "cancellation
authority" as the power "to surgically eliminate Federal budget
obligations," which "automatically
rescinds the [discretionary budget] funds;" and for an item of new
direct spending or a limited tax
benefit, he observed "the cancellation renders the provision void,
such that the obligation of the
United States has no legal force or effect."  S.2930.<p>

     Senator Stevens, an earlier doubter but an eventual convert,
described the bill as "the most
significant delegation of authority by the Congress to the
President since the Constitution was
ratified in 1789 . . . It is a major, major, change in the policy
of the Congress toward the executive
branch."  S.2955.  He further called the veto "a major change in
the balance of Government
power.  It is really a check on the check of the checks and
balances."  S. 2957.  Other major
supporters of S. 4 echoed the same theme.  Senator Gramm said that
there is "no doubt about it --
and the distinguished Senator from West Virginia [line item veto
opponent and plaintiff Senator
Byrd] is right -- it changes the balance of power between the
Congress and the President in one
fundamental way:  It gives the President enhanced power to say 'no'
to spending."  S.2960. 
Another strong supporter, Senator Kyl, made a similar point: "Make
no mistake about it, this bill
will shift a great deal of new power to the President."  S.2978.<p>

     One last effort was made to stop the bill on the Senate floor. 
Senator Byrd moved to
recommit the Conference Report with instructions to substitute S.
14 in its place.  S.2949.  The
motion was tabled by a vote of 58 to 42, and the bill passed 69-31.
S.2995.<p>

     The proceedings on the House floor also produced an
unsuccessful attempt to recommit,
H.3024-25, which failed by a vote of 192-228, followed by a final
passage of 328 to 91.  H.3028. 
On April 9, 1996, President Clinton signed the Line Item Veto Act
of 1996.  <i>See</i> Public Law 104-130, 110 Stat. 1200 (1996).<p>
<hr>
<p>
<center><b>FOOTNOTES</b></center>
<p>
<p>
<b>1</b>   Unless otherwise indicated, all references to floor
debate are to 141 Congressional Record,
daily edition, with a prefix of S. or H.
<p>
<b>2</b>   Those hearings were a follow-up to a hearing held on
October 5, 1994, in the 103rd Congress. 
The record of that hearing assembles much of the prior legislative
material relating to efforts to create a line item veto, either
by statute or constitutional amendment.  <i>See</i> <i>Legislative
Line-Item Veto Proposals: Hearing
Before the Comm. on the Budget</i>, 103rd Cong., 2d Sess. (1994).
<p>
<b>3</b>   That Committee had previously held similar hearings on
April 11, 1989, and June 15, 1994,
and had collected a number of scholarly and other materials. 
<i>See, e.g.</i>, <i>Line-Item Veto: The
President's Constitutional Authority: Hearings Before The Subcomm.
on the Constitution of the
Comm. on the Judiciary</i>, 103rd Cong., 2d Sess. (1994).
<p>
<b>4</b>   Sen. Hatch, the Chairman of the Judiciary Committee,
also offered an amendment, narrower
than the one offered in the House, to exempt certain functions of
the Judiciary, not including
building of courthouses, from the Act.  S.4341.  After debate, a
motion to table the Hatch
Amendment was approved 85-15. S.4435-43
<p>
<b>5</b>    Citations are to the sections of the Act as set forth
in the Conference Report.  References are
also given to the new sections added to part C of Title X of the
Congressional Budget and
Impoundment Control Act of 1974.
<p>
<b>6</b>   "Direct spending" is defined to mean "(A) budget
authority provided by a law (other than an
appropriation law, (b) entitlement authority; and (c) the food
stamp program."  Section 2(a)
(adding ICA Sec. 1026(5)).  An "item of new direct spending" means
"any specific provision of
law that is estimated to result in an increase in budget authority
or outlays for direct spending
relative to the most recent levels calculated pursuant to section
257 of the Balanced Budget and
Emergency Deficit Control Act of 1985." <i>Id.</i> (adding ICA Sec.
1026(8)).  To be subject to the
President's cancellation power, legislation providing for direct
spending need not result "in a net
increase" in spending, as "[a] provision of a future law that
increases direct spending would be
subject to the President's cancellation authority whether or not it
is offset by another provision
that reduces direct spending or increases revenues in the same
law."  Conf. Rep. at 36.
<p>
<b>7  </b> <i>See also</i> Section 2(a) (adding ICA Sec.
1026(7)(A)(iv)) (enabling cancellation of procurement
costs based on the estimated costs multiplied by the quantities of
items specified in appropriations
laws or in accompanying committee reports). 
