<title>Letter to the Editor</title>
<meta name="Author" content="Common Machine#2">
<meta name="CreatedBy" content="WP Internet Publisher 6.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<center><img height=75 width=120 
src="/public_citizen/pclogo.gif"></center><p>

<h1>
<center>Letter to the Editor  Printed in the <i>Journal of Commerce</i> <p>

</h1></center>
<h2><center>September 6, 1996<p>

</center></h2>
<p>

The Editor<p>

The Journal of Commerce<p>

Two World Trade Center<p>

27th Floor<p>

N.Y. N.Y. 10048<p>

							August 15, 1996<p>

<p>

Dear Editor:<p>

<p>

Your recent editorial on the World Trade Organization (<i>The WTO at Work </i>8/15/96) shows a
fundamental lack of understanding about the enforcement power of this global bureaucracy.<p>

<p>

You claim that "The WTO has no police or army to enforce its rulings. It relies solely on the
good will of its member countries."  This may have been true prior to the Uruguay Round when a
consensus of member nations was required to adopt sanctions. For example, when the United
States ban on the sale of tuna caught using dolphin deadly purse seine nets was found to violate
GATT rules, the U.S. was able to block the ruling. <p>

<p>

Under the WTO however, a consensus of all nations is required to <i>block</i> rulings from taking
effect. WTO rulings must be implemented or automatic trade sanctions go into effect, also stop
able only by unanimous consent. This meant that when the WTO's very first ruling was against
U.S. Clean Air Act rules, the United States had three choices: change the regulation, face $150
million in trade sanctions or negotiate $150 million in compensation. When faced with this no-win situation, it is disappointing but not surprising that the United States Trade Representative's
office has announced it will change the Clean Air Act regulation which protects public health. .<p>

<p>

It is only because the WTO now has enforcement power that the Clinton Administration and the
Republican leadership are attempting to gut the U.S. dolphin protection standard which the U.S.
had safeguarded from the old GATT.  Mexico has threatened to take the highly successful
dolphin protection law to the WTO.  To avoid the high-profile embarrassment of "GATTzilla
eating Flipper for lunch" at the WTO, the Clinton Administration is pushing for a pre-emptive
capitulation. <p>

<p>

This power of the WTO to force governments to change environmental, health and labor
standards in order to avoid trade sanction is already wreaking havoc on democratically achieved
safeguards across the globe.<p>

<p>

							Sincerely,<p>

							Lori Wallach<p>

							Director, Public Citizen's Global Trade Watch<p>

									<p>

<p><hr>
<a href="http://www.citizen.org/gtw/gatt/gatthome.html#wto">Return to 
More on the WTO</a><p>
<a href="tradehome.html">Return to the Global Trade Watch Home Page</a><p>


</body>
