<title>105th</title>
<meta name="Author" content="Common Machine#2">
<meta name="CreatedBy" content="WP Internet Publisher 6.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<center><img height=90 width=200 src="/public_citizen/pclogo.gif"></center>
<h1>
<b>CONGRESS WATCH'S PRIORITY ISSUES FOR THE 105TH CONGRESS</h1></b><p>

<p>

Public Citizen is a non-profit research, lobbying and litigation organization founded by Ralph
Nader in 1971.  Congress Watch is a principal lobbying arm of Public Citizen and has the
following priorities for the 105th Congress:<b><p>

<u><p>

<a href="/congress/reform/home.html"><center>Campaign Finance 
Reform</center></a></u></b><p>

<p>

	The current campaign finance system is a scandal.  Monied interests control the legislative
agenda of the Congress because they control the purse strings of the campaigns.  Only the rich, or
the friends of the rich, can afford to run for office.  Incumbents accumulate massive war chests to
scare off potential challengers merely be holding out their hands at fundraisers attended by PACs
and lobbyists.  The public is outraged by this system and frustrated with Congress's failure to
change it.  <p>

<p>

	Parties and candidates spent nearly $2 billion on the 1996 elections, the most ever.   Outside
groups spent hundreds of millions more on independent expenditures and so-called issue
advocacy.  Tales of fundraising scandals and abuses were daily occurrences during the last few
months of the campaign, and investigations and recriminations will likely occupy the Congress
for months to come.  And for what?  The end result of this spending orgy was an election in
which less than half of the eligible electorate turned out to vote, and 95% of incumbent members
of the House (and all but one Senator) who sought reelection were successful.  <p>

<p>

	Public Citizen has long been committed to bringing about meaningful campaign finance reform,
and we will play a leading role in pushing for a major overhaul in the 105th Congress.  Such
reform should include a cap on spending in exchange for significant public resources, a ban on
soft money, and reductions in the influence of special interest PACs.  Unlimited party spending
and electioneering disguised as issue advocacy also must be addressed.  Congress must also
improve disclosure of campaign funding and enforcement of the election laws, which includes
providing adequate resources for the FEC to do its job. <p>

<b><u><p><center><a href="/congress/corwel/home.html">

Corporate Welfare</u></b></a></center><p>

<p>

	Each year, U.S. taxpayers subsidize U.S. businesses to the tune of more than $150 billion. Every
five years, the U.S. Treasury loses $1 billion because mining companies don't pay a fair market
value for minerals extracted from public lands. Companies such as Hershey International and
McDonalds receive some $69 million each year in public funds for advertising campaigns and
other promotions of their products as American agricultural exports.  Stopping public funding of
new roads in the national forests, which are used by timber companies to carry away trees they
bought from the government for next to nothing, would save about $50 million annually.  <p>

<p>

	Each dollar spent on these "aid for dependent corporation" welfare programs means one dollar
less for environmental programs, support for education, assistance to those in need, tax <p>

breaks for families, or deficit reduction.  During this Congress, Public Citizen will help lead a
major  push to reduce corporate welfare. Key votes will likely occur in the spring, when the <p>

budget is debated, and then in the summer and fall as specific appropriations bills, ladened with
corporate pork, are considered.<p>

<u><b><p><center><a href="/congress/fda/home.html">

Regulatory Roll Back</b></u></a></center><p>

<p>

	Today, Americans enjoy safer automobiles and consumer products, purer food and drinking
water, cleaner air, more reliable drugs and medical devices, and safer work places than ever
before.  These safeguards were under attack in the 104th Congress, and we expect a similar
assault on these important protections in the 105th Congress.           <p>

<p>

	Pro-industry Members of Congress want to cripple government agencies such as the EPA, the
FDA, and OSHA --  each charged with protecting the health and safety of the American public. 
Anti-regulatory extremists have a three-pronged approach to rolling back important health and
safety standards: 1) Paralyze regulatory agencies by requiring needless and excessively
bureaucratic procedures -- such as extensive cost-benefit analyses and risk assessments -- before
a simple standard to implement environmental, health and safety laws could be issued.  2) Attack
actual laws that guarantee health and safety protections.  At various times over the last two years,
serious attempts to roll back the Clean Air Act, the Clean Water Act, the Safe Drinking Water
Act, the Food, Drugs and Cosmetics Act and the Occupational Safety and Health Act all came up
for consideration.  3) De-fund important agencies and programs that ensure health and safety.<p>

<p>

	Anti-safety leaders and their special interest allies were thwarted in the 104th Congress, but they
are likely to be back with a vengeance in 1997-1998.  One probable bill will neutralize important
FDA protections.  Another may make a broader attack on all environmental, health and safety
laws.  Public Citizen is prepared to again take the lead to make sure that critical health and safety
standards are not rolled back.<p>

<p>

 <u><b><center><a href="/congress/civjus/home.html">Civil Justice 
Issues</a></center></b></u><p>

<p>

	For over 100 years, Americans injured by defective products, unsafe workplaces and medical
malpractice have had the right to seek compensation in courts of law before citizen juries.
America's civil justice system has been responsible for punishing corporations that  manufacture
defective products -- such as the Ford Pinto, school buses, asbestos, tobacco and the Dalkon
Shield -- and holding HMOs, hospitals and doctors accountable for reckless medical care.  Public
Citizen believes that Americans have a right to a trial by jury when they are injured by defective
products or negligent health care. <p>

<p>

	Because it has been a successful deterrent of corporate misconduct, in the last 15 years,
America's civil justice system has been under ferocious attack in Congress and state legislatures
by HMOs and doctors, insurance companies, oil and chemical polluters, big tobacco and auto
manufacturers seeking immunity for wrongdoing. Although corporations have been successful in
securing some limitations on liability in individual states, Public Citizen and other consumer
groups have stopped Congress from enacting federal limits on corporate liability.<p>

	But each year, the attack on the right to trial by jury intensifies. Last year, the bill actually passed
Congress but was stopped from becoming law by President Clinton's veto. In 1997, Public
Citizen will once again lead the effort to oppose another well-funded corporate effort to limit the
liability of reckless corporations and doctors. Votes will likely take place in the House <p>

and Senate during the Spring of 1997.  In addition to limitations on liability for defective
products and medical malpractice, key votes will likely occur on limiting the liability of railroads
and shipping companies. <p>

<b><u><p><center><a href"/congress/health/home.html">

Health Care Reform</u></b></center></a><p>

<p>

	One hundred forty-million Americans now get their health coverage through some form of
managed care. There has been an explosion of big business, profit-making managed care
companies that often put profits ahead of patient care. Some managed care companies have
included "gag rules" in their contracts with participating physicians, preventing them from fully
discussing treatment options with patients.  Many have financial incentives which reward doctors
for referring fewer patients to specialists.  Often decisions on what treatments will be authorized
are made by persons who have not examined the patients -- they may not even be fully qualified
medical professionals.  <p>

<p>

	Only a few states have adopted comprehensive measures to stop managed care abuses.  Many
Americans whose health care comes from self-insured, employer-sponsored managed care plans
are not protected by any state legislation because current federal law forbids states from
regulating such plans.	<p>

									  <p>

	Public Citizen continues to believe that fundamental health care reform that provides quality
universal care will only come when the U.S. adopts a single-payer system similar to Canada's. 
However, to protect those Americans who find themselves in managed care from abuses which
may threaten their health, Public Citizen is working for passage of federal legislation to provide
comprehensive, effective regulation of managed care and for a change in federal law to ensure
that states are able to protect the rights of all managed care enrollees within their state. <p>

<p>
<hr>
<a href="/congress/cwhome.html">Return to the Congress Watch Home Page</a>
<p>

<p>

<p>


</body>
