<TITLE>

</TITLE>
<BODY bgcolor="white">

<CENTER>
<IMG src="/pclogo.gif" width=185><BR>

<FONT size="1" color="#0a5397">Buyers Up </FONT><FONT size="1" color="red">&#149;</FONT><FONT size="1" color="#0a5397"></FONT>
<FONT size="1" color="#0a5397">Congress Watch </FONT><FONT size="1" color="red">&#149;</FONT><FONT size="1" color="#0a5397"></FONT>
<FONT size="1" color="#0a5397">Critical Mass </FONT><FONT size="1" color="red">&#149;</FONT><FONT size="1" color="#0a5397"></FONT>
<FONT size="1" color="#0a5397">Global Trade Watch </FONT><FONT size="1" color="red">&#149;</FONT><FONT size="1" color="#0a5397"></FONT>
<FONT size="1" color="#0a5397">Health Research Group </FONT><FONT size="1" color="red">&#149;</FONT><FONT size="1" color="#0a5397"></FONT>
<FONT size="1" color="#0a5397">Litigation Group </FONT>
<BR>
<FONT size="1" color="#0a5397">Joan Claybrook, President<BR></FONT>
</CENTER>
<P>
<FONT size="3" face="times">
<center>
<h3>
SPEAKER GINGRICH SHOULD NOT BE RE-ELECTED UNTIL AFTER THE HOUSE COMPLETES 
WORK ON THE ETHICS VIOLATIONS HE HAS ADMITTED </h3>
</center>

January 2, 1997<P>

Dear Member of the House of Representatives:<P>

The ethics violations to which Speaker Gingrich has admitted, as outlined in the Statement of the Investigative Subcommittee of the House Ethics Committee of December 21, 1996,  are serious.  Unfortunately, in an exercise of partisan spin control, certain
 Members of  the House and commentators in the press have minimized and distorted the findings of the Subcommittee.  Many even called for the punishment phase of this proceeding, which follows an investigation that lasted over two years, to be completed w
ithin two weeks so that the Speaker can be re-elected on January 7 without the cloud of an uncertain ethics sanction hanging over his head.<p>

Such an action would have seriously compromised the integrity of the proceeding and diminished public confidence in Congress.   Fortunately, the Ethics Committee has decided not to rush to judgment.  It has announced that it will begin the punishment phas
e on January 8, and will hold some type of public hearing before announcing a decision. <b><i>We strongly believe that Speaker Gingrich should not be re-elected until after the House has acted on the ethics case.</i></b>  Furthermore, prior to taking fina
l action, the House should ensure that all relevant documents in the case have been made available to the public and should insist that the Speaker testify under oath before the Ethics Committee in public session.  As discussed below, these steps will ass
ure the public that the serious charges to which the Speaker has admitted are not being swept aside in a partisan power play:  <p>

<b>1.  The House should not reelect Speaker Gingrich until after the Ethics Committee has completed its work and the House has voted on the sanction for the Speaker's ethical transgressions.</b>  The Speaker of the House is a constitutional office with en
ormous power and responsibility, second in the line of presidential succession.  While the office is often filled through a partisan vote, both parties have the duty to demand that the highest standards of ethics and integrity are maintained by the person
 who assumes the post.  It would be unconscionable for the House to elect Mr. Gingrich to this position while he faces a possibly serious ethics sanction.  If the Republicans, who control the House, wish to leave open the possibility of reelecting Speaker
 Gingrich after this proceeding is completed, they should elect a temporary or acting Speaker on January 7.<p>

<b>2.  All documents relevant to the Subcommittee's work should be made public. </b> This includes the report of Special Counsel James Cole and any written opinion or other work product of the tax counsel retained by the Subcommittee.  In addition, transc
ripts of the testimony of the Subcommittee's tax counsel and the tax counsel who appeared on behalf of Speaker Gingrich before the Subcommittee should be released along with all written submissions from Speaker Gingrich's counsel and tax experts.  Now tha
t Speaker Gingrich has admitted ethical violations in this case, there is simply no justification for keeping the results of the investigation secret.  The public has the right to review all relevant evidence against Speaker Gingrich in order to be able t
o inform its elected representatives of its views prior to the House making a final decision on sanctions for the Speaker and his possible re-election.  <p>

<b>3.  The House Ethics Committee's public hearing should include sworn testimony from Speaker Gingrich.</b>   The Committee has announced only that it will hear from Special Counsel Cole in the public hearing.  We believe it is essential that the Speaker
, and perhaps his counsel, testify as well.   After over two years of working behind closed doors, the Committee owes the public a complete opportunity to evaluate these matters before resolving them, particularly because the Subcommittee's Statement and 
the Speaker's response to it raise a number of unanswered questions.   <p>

Mr. Gingrich admitted that he should have sought legal advice about the use of two charitable foundations for a variety of politically oriented projects in which Mr. Gingrich was involved. It is elementary that charitable organizations cannot engage in pa
rtisan political activity.  The need to keep tax exempt activities and partisan politics separate is almost as well known as the separation between church and state.  This is not an arcane' concept, as some have claimed. Anyone who holds political office
 and is therefore conversant with federal election law must have at least some familiarity with this basic restriction on charitable organizations.<p>

If  Mr. Gingrich truly did not seek legal advice on these matters -- and a recent news report from the <i>Atlanta Journal-Constitution</i> on legal memos written by two attorneys who worked for GOPAC and the Progress & Freedom Foundation cast doubt on tha
t assertion -- then the failure to consult counsel may very well have been willful, not an oversight.  (See attached article.)  Before determining the appropriate sanction for the conduct to which the Speaker has admitted, the Ethics Committee must be sat
isfied that the admission is complete and truthful.  It should explore those questions in the public hearing and call on the Speaker to testify under oath.<p>

Also extremely troubling is the Speaker's admission that certain information submitted to the Committee on his behalf was "inaccurate, incomplete, and unreliable."  The Subcommittee cites thirteen separate "inaccurate" statements by Mr. Gingrich concernin
g the involvement of GOPAC in his college course. (See pages 20 and 21 of the Subcommittee's Statement of December 21, 1996).   These were not minor, inconsequential statements.  They went to the very heart of the Committee's inquiry -- whether the colleg
e course was political in nature and therefore inappropriate for funding by charitable foundations.  Mr. Gingrich repeatedly denied that GOPAC was involved in planning, designing, or administering the course, both in submissions to the Committee and in pu
blic statements for many years.  But the Subcommittee amassed substantial evidence known to the Speaker that the course was an integral part of GOPAC's activities in support of Republican candidates.  <p>

Mr. Gingrich and his defenders on Capitol Hill have suggested on numerous occasions that his lawyers bear responsibility for submitting inaccurate information to the Committee.  This explanation rings hollow.  In light of the number and specificity of the
 instances cited by the Subcommittee, the misrepresentations appear intentional.  Again, the Speaker's admission raises more questions than it answers, making the need for the Committee to hold a public hearing before recommending a sanction all the more 
apparent.<p>

<b><i>The charges against Speaker Gingrich are not a partisan squabble to be resolved through a party line power play.  They go to the heart of the integrity of the political process and the ethics process by which the Congress oversees the conduct of its
 Members.  The public is entitled to hold the Speaker and the Congress accountable for its actions.  It must have "accurate, complete, and reliable information" in order to do so.</i></b><p>

Thank you for your consideration.<p>

						Sincerely,
<p>
<p>

						Joan Claybrook
						President

<P>
