<body bgcolor="#ffffff">


<h2><center>Tuna/Dolphin Sign On Letter, February 7,
1996</h2></center><p>

<p>

Dear Congressman Miller:<p>

<p>

	<u>We the undersigned join the millions of
American fishers, consumers, and
environmentalists who support H.R. 2856,
the International Dolphin Protection and
Consumer Information Act of 1996.</u>  We
believe that your efforts, and those of
Senators Barbara Boxer and Joseph
Biden, to safeguard dolphin populations
against the GATT-imposed weakening of
the Marine Mammal Protection Act are a
rallying point for all congress members
who are concerned about the integrity of
U.S. laws in the age of the World Trade
Organization (WTO), the successor to the
GATT.<p>

<p>

	When Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo
visited Washington this past fall, the
Clinton Administration pledged that it
would repeal our historic dolphin
protection law by the end of January
1996! There is no GATT legal
requirement for the U.S. to repeal our law
now. Still, the Clinton Administration
agreed to repeal it because the inability to
get Congress to voluntarily comply with
the GATT panel is viewed as an
embarrassment to the Administration's
GATT/WTO Geneva mission.<p>

<p>

	You have undoubtedly received letters
from many environmental groups
concerned with dolphin conservation; and
thus you should be aware that the vast
majority of national, state and local
environmental and conservation groups
support the Boxer/Biden/Miller
legislation. The support of the members of
the Citizens Trade Campaign -- and our
strong opposition to H.R. 2823, the House
version of the Breaux/Stevens bill to
change the definition of "dolphin safe" --
focusses on two additional matters:<p>

<p>

1. 	<u>Setting a Bad GATT/WTO Precedent:
Congress Quickly and Quietly Kills
Democratically-Achieved U.S. Laws If the
GATT/WTO Opposes It.</u> <p>

<p>

	Even if your colleagues do not care about
this dolphin law, their actions with this
case will set the precedent for future
GATT/WTO rulings declaring that we
can no longer maintain our
democratically-achieved laws. America's
ability to set its own laws and control the
terms of access to its own consumer
markets are at stake. In its hearings and
debate on this environmental issue the
Congress must consider: <i>What law will be
attacked next?</i>  The European Union has
listed many U.S. defense, procurement,
and product standard laws as
GATT/WTO illegal. If Congress passes
the Steven-Breaux bill to gut the Marine
Mammal Protection Act, a long-standing,
court-tested and popularly-supported
measure, the Congress will have proved
what the bureaucrats at the GATT/WTO
already are saying: <i>GATT/World Trade
Organization rules take precedence over
U.S. law.</i> Support for the International
Dolphin Protection and Consumer
Information Act of 1996 is support for the
integrity of American democratic decision
making over "harmonized" international
trade rules.<p>

<p>

<p>

<p>

<p>

2. 	<u>U.S. Consumer Fraud</u><p>

<p>

	Unlike the Boxer/Biden/Miller legislation,
the Stevens-Breaux bill would allow tuna
to come into the U.S. and be labelled
"dolphin safe" even though it was caught
with techniques that would further harm
severely depleted dolphin populations.
The Act was passed after a massive public
campaign in which millions of school
children and ultimately all of the major
U.S. tuna companies pressured Congress
to stop the sale of dolphin-deadly tuna.
The tuna companies still support the
Marine Mammal Protection Act because
U.S. consumers demand dolphin safe
tuna. Under the current law, which your
bill respects and strengthens, the
companies know that no competitor can
sell tuna labelled "dolphin safe" if it is
not. The good news is that it is not
necessary to break faith with all of
America's school children and their
parents -- which is another reason for
your colleagues to publicly support and
co-sponsor the International Dolphin
Protection and Consumer Information
Act.<p>

<p>

Sincerely,<p>

<p>

MEMBERS OF THE CITIZENS TRADE
CAMPAIGN: <p>

<p>


Lori Wallach, Director, Public Citizen's Global Trade Watch<p>
Brent Blackwelder, President, Friends of the Earth<p>
Dan Seligman, Senior Fellow, Sierra Club<p>
Bob Nicklas, Government Affairs, International Brotherhood of Teamsters<p>
Bill Snape, Legal Council, Defenders of Wildlife<p>
Kathy Ozer, Director, National Family Farm Coaliton<p>
David Phillips, Director, Earth Island Institute<p>
Lauren Rothfarb, Director of Legislation, International Union of 
Electronic Workers, IUE<p> 
Patricia Forkan, Executive Vice President, Humane Society of the United 
States<p> 
Robert Wages, President, Oil, Chemical and Atomic Workers International 
Union<p> 
David Zwick, President, Clean Water Action<p>
Linda Golondner, President, Natioanl Consumer League<p>
Betsy Swartz, National Program Director, Friends of Animals<p>
Jamie Martinez, Secretary-Treasurer, AFL-CIO District 11<p>
Elliot Katz, DBM, President, In Defense of Animals<p>
Mark Ritchie, Executive Director, Institute for Agriculture and Trade 
Policy<p> 
Evy Dubrow, Vice-President, UNITE!<p>
Darryl Fagin, Legislative Director, Americans for Democratic Action<p>
Dan Swinney, Executive Director, Midwest Center for Labor Research<p>
