<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<p>
<center><img width=120 height=75 src="/public_citizen/pclogo.gif"></center>
<p>
<h1><center>Testimony of Lori Wallach</h1></center><p>

<h1><center>Public Citizen's Global Trade Watch</h1></center>
<p>

<p>

<h2><center> Trade Implications of Congressional Action on U.S. Dolphin 
Protection Laws</h2></center><p>


 <p>

<h3><center>Before the Senate Committee on Commerce, Science 
and Transportation</h3></center> <p>

<h3><center>Subcommittee on Oceans and Fisheries</h3></center>
<p>

<h3><center>April 30, 1996</h3></center>
<p>

<p>

<p>

	Mr. Chairman and members of the committee, on behalf of Public
Citizen and its members nationwide, thank you for the opportunity
to testify on the two bills, S. 1429 (Stevens-Breaux) and S. 1460
(Boxer-Biden,) before Congress which would alter the U.S. Marine
Mammal Protection Act (MMPA,) a long standing U.S. environmental
law that was successfully challenged in 1991 and 1993 as an
illegal trade barrier at the General Agreement on Tariffs and
Trade (GATT.)<p>

<p>

	 My name is Lori Wallach. I am the director of Public Citizen's
Global Trade Watch. Public Citizen is a consumer advocacy group
founded in 1974 by Ralph Nader. My testimony today is also
endorsed by the Citizens Trade Campaign of which Public Citizen
is a member group along with hundreds of other consumer, labor,
religious, environmental, family farm and other citizens groups
across the country. The combined membership of the Citizens Trade
Campaign member organizations is over 7 million nationwide. Both
the Citizens Trade Campaign and Public Citizen are members of the
Fair Trade Dolphin Safe Campaign. Please allow me to set the
record straight as to the position of labor unions on these
bills. The union members of the Citizens Trade campaign,
including Teamsters, UNITE!, IUE, and OCAW and their millions of
members nationwide support the Boxer-Biden bill and oppose the
Stevens-Breaux bill and are signatories to a recent letter
stating that position. The AFL-CIO takes no position on either
bill. <p>

<p>

	Congress' decision to change U.S. policies relating to the
protection of dolphins in tuna fishing undoubtedly has
significant environmental and conservation consequences and these
issues have gotten a significant amount of attention in the
Congress. My only comment in this area is not as a marine
biologist, but as an American citizen who cares about protecting
dolphins and who eats tuna fish. I have been struck that it does
not seem like a very good idea to change a policy that according
to the preambles of both proposed bills, has been remarkably
successful in meeting it conservation goal. This is more so the
case when there is such a significant split in the environmental
community as to whether either of these proposed changes actually
would undermine the successful dolphin conservation status quo.<p>

<p>

	My area of expertise is trade. From my perspective, the key issue
with these two bills amending the MMPA is their enormous
implications on U.S. international trade policy. <p>

<p>

	The MMPA was the first well-known, widely-supported piece of U.S.
environmental legislation successfully attacked at the GATT.<a 
href="#[1]"><b><u>[1]</u></b></a>
In that 1991 ruling, the GATT declared the sovereign right of the
U.S. Congress to set the conditions for a product's access to the
U.S. domestic market to be trumped by international trade
obligations under GATT. The United States was ordered to
eliminate the core provisions of our existing dolphin protection
law, the MMPA, that set domestic standards for tuna sold in this
market and enforced those standards as a condition of market
access. Under old GATT rules, the United States was able to block
the ruling instead of implementing it at the time. This was a
fortunate emergency brake for the Bush Administration, because
the 1991 GATT ruling set off a public furor. This case made GATT
known to the American public. Written about in Newsweek, the New
York Times and other national publications as the case of
"GATTzilla versus Flipper," it was this real life example that
brought home the threat that seemed inconceivable: an
unaccountable bureaucracy in another country telling the U.S.
Congress to kill a U.S. domestic law or pay sanctions to maintain
it. <p>

<p>

	Now, once again, GATTzilla vs. Flipper is back in play. <p>

<p>

1. Congressional MMPA Debate Is Viewed Worldwide as a Trade, Not
Environmental Issue.<p>

<p>

	To most of the world, this current U.S. debate about our dolphin
policy is viewed not as an environmental issue, but as a debate
about trade. Speaking to officials at the Geneva-based World
Trade Organization and in the trade offices of other governments,
it has struck me that it is only for U.S. domestic consumption
that this issue is being cloaked in an environmental spin. At the
World Trade Organization and in other nations' capitals, the
Stevens-Breaux bill is seen as the belated U.S. implementation of
the 1991 GATT order to eliminate core provisions of the MMPA. The
Boxer-Biden bill is viewed as an attempt to modify certain GATT
problems that are not vital to the MMPA's dolphin conservation
goals, but also as a resolute statement that the United States
will retain its sovereign right to set the standards for product
access into the U.S. domestic market. More broadly, the current
debate on U.S. dolphin protection policy is being viewed outside
the United States as setting a precedent for U.S. allegiance to
the World Trade Organization (WTO), GATT's new successor
organization, and will be viewed as setting a model for U.S.
compliance with the WTO's future rulings. <p>

<p>

	There is fairly wide awareness in the international trade world
that the Mexican government threatened the U.S. government in the
fall of 1995 that it would challenge the MMPA at the World Trade
Organization.<a href="#[2]"></b></u>[2]<u><b></a>  In the fall of 1995, when Mexican President
Ernesto Zedillo visited Washington to obtain a roll over for the
first installments in the billions of peso bailout loans Mexico
could not repay on time, he also obtained another promise from
the Administration. In exchange for a commitment that the Mexican
government would hold off its planned WTO challenge, the Clinton
Administration agreed to get rid of the MMPA through lower-profile congressional action.<a href="#[3]"></b></u>[3]<u><b></a> In retrospect, it may have been
a short-sighted deal to make considering the public and press
attention that has been raised by the prospect of the Clinton
Administration trying to eliminate in Congress important
provisions of U.S. dolphin protection law. Yet, the Clinton
Administration knew that if the Mexican government challenged the
MMPA at the WTO, the law would be again found to violate trade
rules. Only this time, the United States would no longer have the
capacity to block the decision -- thanks to the Administration's
push for the U.S. to give up its GATT veto and join the World
Trade Organization. <p>

<p>

	Thus, the sudden interest by the Clinton Administration in
changing the very core portions of the MMPA that the 1991 GATT
ruling demanded is being viewed for what it is in the trade
world: a pre-emptive cave in to implement the old GATT order to
avoid the enormous political embarrassment of having a popular
dolphin protection law become a well-publicized victim of the
WTO. And, to top it off, the Clinton Administration would face
being held WTO hostage by Mexico after having gone around
congressional opposition and 90% public opinion disapproval to
spend $30 billion U.S. tax payer dollars on a failed bailout of
wealthy investors in Mexico. By making the MMPA "go away" more
quietly via legislation such as the Stevens-Breaux bill, the
Administration is trying to get itself out of a high-profile WTO
no-win situation of either killing the dolphin law or paying
perpetual trade sanctions to Mexico. Considering that this was
exactly the sort of sovereignty threat that the Clinton
Administration promised Congress would not occur if Congress
supported the WTO, it is clear what the Administration's interest
is in implementing the 1991 GATT ruling against the MMPA. <p>

<p>

	However, it is less clear why Chairman Stevens, an articulate
opponent of the World Trade Organization for sovereignty reasons,
is willing to help the Administration avoid such well-deserved
embarrassment.<p>

<p>

	If Congress passes the Stevens-Breaux bill, Congress will have
proved what the bureaucrats at the GATT/WTO already are saying:
the United States must conform its domestic laws to the
GATT/World Trade Organization rules. The Clinton Administration
may have concluded that the strategy to avoid humiliation by a
WTO attack on a beloved U.S. law is to preemptively cave in.
However, Congress should not take the same strategy. Even for
those Members who voted for GATT/WTO, also arguing that it was
not a sovereignty threat, the damage of the precedent that would
be set by killing a GATT-attacked law is far worse than having to
admit to relying on bad information about the WTO's sovereignty
implications. This is especially the case after the rather
unavoidable embarrassment of the first WTO ruling in January
1996, which was against a U.S. environmental law, the
reformulated gasoline rules implementing some of the 1990
amendments to the Clean Air Act. In its outcome, tone, and
reasoning, the WTO's first ruling provides real life evidence of
the WTO's threat to democratic policy making, national
sovereignty and to environmental and health protections.<a href="#[4]"></b></u>[4]<u><b></a> The
WTO tribunal in this case declared that the means the United
States employed to implement public health improvements in U.S.
air quality under the Clean Air Act were not acceptable under WTO
rules. On April 29, 1996, the World Trade Organization's
appellate body ruled against the United States in what was the
only, albeit limited, internal, appeal on the case available to
the U.S. government. The Clinton Administration now faces a no-win situation regarding the clean air rules: allow in more dirty
Venezuelan gasoline undermining U.S. health and put U.S.
refineries who have already spent millions implementing the rule
at a competitive disadvantage that national security groups
estimate will put at least a quarter of the U.S. independent
refiners to bankruptcy or pay $150 million in trade sanctions to
Venezuela to keep the law. By implementing the GATT ruling
against the MMPA, the U.S. Congress is trapping itself with a bad
precedent of fidelity to the WTO's demands.<p>

<p>

2. At Issue Is Whether Congress or the WTO Will Set U.S. Domestic
Product Standards<p>

<p>

	The approach the Administration had taken to try to avoid the
political fallout of yet another messy trade issue with Mexico is
to attempt to confuse two different issues: international regimes
for fishery management versus U.S. domestic market standards. The
Administration has suddenly taken the position that in the area
of standards for tuna sold in the United States domestic market,
the U.S. must accept an international standard as a replacement
for its own domestic standard. This is also unfortunately, but
not surprisingly, the approach of the World Trade Organization,
which specifically limits the right of WTO  Member countries to
set unilateral conditions for access to their markets -- from the
U.S. Cuba embargo to the U.S. Section 301 trade law to U.S.
domestic standards for tuna fish.<p>

<p>

	Yet, it is vital to separate the two issues: one domestic and one
international. The MMPA is about U.S. domestic market standards.
After all, the MMPA concerns regulating what sorts of products
are allowed into our domestic market, not international fishing
practices generally. Fishers can fish however they want under the
MMPA. They just can't sell their fish in the U.S. market unless
they meet the MMPA's standards for domestic sale of tuna. These
U.S.-set standards were devised to compliment international
agreements in the area of dolphin protection by shaping the
powerful U.S. demand to meet the goal of dolphin conservation.
The U.S. domestic standard is clear and enforceable and is
maintained in the Boxer-Biden bill: no encirclement of dolphins
is catching tuna labelled dolphin safe for sale in the U.S.
market.<p>

<p>

	Meanwhile, the LaJolla process and the Panama Declaration go to
the second matter -- international fisheries practices. The
Panama Declaration was multilaterally derived as international
agreements should be: The goal of the agreement is to lower
dolphin mortality in tuna fishing. Normally, the United States
would sign onto such an international agreement and then enforce
its terms through domestic market access or other national
implementation mechanisms. This is how the United States
implements the Montreal Protocol (through Clean Air Act
provisions) or international driftnet and whaling conventions
(through the Pelly Amendment.) <p>

<p>

	However, in the name of ducking GATTzilla, the Clinton
Administration is pushing for an outright usurpation of the U.S.
domestic standards. Instead of domestic enforcement of an
international agreement, Stevens-Breaux would replace the clear
U.S. standard with a vague, unenforceable international standard:
no tuna can be sold in the U.S. labelled dolphin safe as long as
there were no observable dolphin deaths. Not coincidentally,
getting rid of the strong U.S. standard for "dolphin safe" and
thus getting rid of strong U.S. enforcement by eliminating the
conditions for U.S. market access, is precisely what the 1991
GATT panel ordered.<p>

<p>

3. Broad Negative Sovereignty and Trade Implications of the
Steven-Breaux Bill <p>

<p>

	Even if you do not care about the conservation of dolphins, the
trade implications of adopting the Stevens-Breaux bill are
broadly relevant. At issue is the capacity of the U.S. Congress
to adopt or enforce numerous other domestic policy measures,
including many unrelated to the environment. This is the case for
two reasons. First, as noted above, U.S. congressional action on
the MMPA will set a precedent as to what value the Congress will
give to GATT/WTO rulings against U.S. laws.<a href="#[5]"></b></u>[5]<u><b></a><p>

<p>

	But even more directly, the GATT jurisprudence that would be
adopted by U.S. congressional implementation of the 1991 GATT
ruling via a bill such as Stevens-Breaux has broad implications
on other policy areas. Included among the likely U.S. law
casualties under this WTO jurisprudence would be the driftnet
provisions dear to Chairman Stevens' heart and the shrimp
comparability standards that Senator Breaux has fought to put
into place.<a href="#[6]"></b></u>[6]<u><b></a> Most simply, if the U.S. does not defend its right
to control access to its market for tuna caught in ways that
protect dolphins, then the precedent will have been set so that
the U.S. cannot insist imported shrimp sold in this market be
caught in a manner required under the sea turtle conservation
policy, nor would we be consistent in enforcing driftnet fishing
rules.<p>

<p>

	The 1991 GATT ruling focussed on numerous grounds in ruling
against the MMPA. For instance, the panel found several elements
of technical discrimination under GATT Article III. <p>

However, the panel mainly focussed on the prohibition under GATT
for United States to set standards relating to the way a product
was produced (as compared to its physical characteristics.) Thus,
the GATT panel ruled that a can of tuna caught using dolphin safe
methods had to be treated exactly the same as a can of tuna
caught using dolphin deadly methods. In GATTese, this is the rule
forbidding market access conditionality based on unilateral
extraterritorial process standards. The panel's ruling that the
United States could not maintain laws regulating its own domestic
market with extra-territorial effects meant that Congress could
not require foreign producers to meet the same standards as
domestic producers for goods sold in the United States. <p>

<p>

	The same logic has dreadfully broad implications and is certainly
not a policy to which the U.S. Congress ought to subscribe.
Accepting the WTO prohibition of ever discriminating between
products on the basis of how they are produced or harvested would
remove from Congress the ability to ensure that U.S. industry
faces a level playing field within the U.S. market as regards
imported products. It would also eviscerate Congress'
effectiveness in many policy areas in which Congress is seeking
to promote certain political, labor, environmental or other
behaviors using the terms of access to the lucrative U.S.
consumer market as the incentive. What specifically does this
mean? One clear example has already come to light as regards
child labor. A proposed ban on the sale in the U.S. domestic
market of products made with child labor whether manufactured in
the United States or abroad has already been attacked as outside
of Congress' prerogatives because such a policy would be illegal
under GATT/WTO. Under GATT/WTO logic, a shoe is a shoe even if
one shoe was made in Louisiana under U.S. labor and environmental
laws and the other identical shoe was made by indentured child
labor in China. This is the natural application of the GATT
jurisprudence under the tuna-dolphin case that insists that
Congress must treat all cans of tuna alike unless the contents
are physically different.<p>

<p>

	This precedent would put at risk an enormous number of other U.S.
domestic policies on issues ranging from state taxes to
procurement to national defense to food safety. Thus, what is
really at stake here is who decides U.S. domestic policies and
America's sovereignty to set its own laws and control the terms
of access to its own consumer market. In considering the two
bills, I urge you to consider: What law will be attacked next at
the World Trade Organization? Maybe it will be something for
which you have fought for decades and about which you deeply
care. <p>

<p>

	Overall, the United States has not had a very good track record
in defending its laws at GATT. Now the WTO provides even stronger
enforcement. Since 1980, when the Tokyo Round of GATT first
included limitations on a country's domestic non-trade laws --
known in GATTese as "non-tariff barriers" --  the United States
has lost 80% of the cases raised by other nations against our
laws.<a href="#[7]"></b></u>[7]<u><b></a>  Recently, the United States has lost three GATT
challenges against its environmental laws and obtained a split
decision ruling against a part of a fourth environmental law.<a href="#[8]"></b></u>[8]<u><b></a>
There have only been four challenges against U.S. environmental
laws at GATT. <p>

<p>

	What U.S. law will be attacked next? The European Union, Japan
and Canada publish annual reports of U.S. laws they believe
conflict with trade rules that include many U.S. defense,
procurement, and product standard laws.<a href="#[9]"></b></u>[9]<u><b></a>  Past listing in these
other country's U.S. trade violation reports have provided grim
foreshadowing of the U.S. laws to be challenged. Past European
Union reports listed the CAFE standards and gas guzzler tax and
the Marine Mammal Protection Act's secondary embargoes which the
European Union then successfully challenged at the GATT.<p>

<p>

	A recent sampling of targeted U.S. laws in the European Union,
Japan and Canada's annual reports include: Section 301, the Cuba
boycott, multistate tax laws, Buy America provisions, the Nuclear
Non-proliferation Act, the asbestos ban, driftnet fishing and
whaling restrictions, turtle protections relating to shrimp,
federal and state raw log export bans, the Consumer Nutrition and
Education Labeling Act, state recycling laws, limitations on lead
in consumer products, and the Delaney Clause prohibiting
carcinogenic food additives.<p>

<p>

4. Boxer-Biden: A Compromise that Sets A Clear Trade Precedent
Protecting U.S. Sovereignty.<p>

<p>

	As a trade matter, the Boxer-Biden bill is a compromise offering
which carefully sets the precedent at GATT/WTO that the United
States will not blindly implement that institution's rulings
against our domestic laws. Boxer-Biden eliminates several
technical elements in the Marine Mammal Protection Act on which
the 1991 and 1993 GATT panels focussed. However, what is
importantly maintained is the principle that the United States
has the sovereign right to set standards for products to be sold
in its domestic market. Boxer-Biden provides a mechanism to
ensure this principle is enforced. <p>

<p>

	What technical problems are corrected in Boxer-Biden? The bill
eliminates a "national treatment" problem identified by the GATT
panels that is not essential to the effective operation of the
U.S. dolphin protection policy. GATT Article III generally
requires that countries do not treat foreign producers
differently than domestic producers. While the logic of this rule
from a trade perspective is to avoid arbitrary discrimination in
commerce based on nationality, in application it can cause
significant difficulties for domestic policy makers. Because the
U.S. government does not have police powers over foreign
producers, often the only way to enforce compliance with
standards for domestic sale of imported products it to condition
entry of the products of another nation into the U.S. domestic
market on meeting the standards.<a href="#[10]"></b></u>[10]<u><b></a> <p>

<p>

	The existing MMPA uses a comparability standard which sets a
maximum dolphin mortality rate for foreign fleets based on 1.25
times the U.S. rate. While this standard actually provides
preferential treatment for foreign fishers, as a technical matter
it is difficult to apply because the foreign standard cannot be
calculated until data is available for the U.S. fishers. The GATT
ruled that this was illegal discrimination between fishers of
different nations. To avoid this different treatment of domestic
and foreign fishers, Boxer-Biden sets exactly the same standard
for all fishers: they simply cannot use the encirclement
technique of tuna fishing.<p>

<p>

	As well, Boxer-Biden eliminates another national treatment
problem. Under the MMPA, if a fishing boat of a country fails to
meet the MMPA's standards, then the tuna from that entire
country's fishing fleet is not allowed into the United States.
This provision provided increased incentives for all tuna boats
to meet the dolphin safe standard. With the International
Tropical Tuna Association requiring an observer on each tuna
boat, Boxer-Biden lifts the nationwide ban on tuna imports
relying on each boat's observers to ensure compliance with the
"no encirclement" standard on a boat-by-boat basis. Boxer-Biden
thus shifts the focus from the nation to specific tuna fishing
boats. Under Boxer-Biden, standards are applied to a specific
boat's behavior. Thus, if one boat in a foreign fleet does not
meet the rules of not encircling dolphins, only the tuna from
that boat is not allowed into the United States. Tuna from other
boats from the same country would be allowed as long as those
boats are not catching tuna by encircling dolphins. This boat-by-boat focus removes the national treatment problem.<p>

<p>

	Where Boxer-Biden does not budge is in staking out three vital
policies where the World Trade Organization, not U.S. democracy
must give: <p>

<p>

	o The sovereign U.S. right to determine the standards for
products entering our domestic market through our domestic
democratic processes;<p>

<p>

	o The principle that U.S. producers should not be put at a
competitive disadvantage for meeting the laws of this land, while
foreign producers are given a pass; and<p>

<p>

	o The right to set effective U.S. domestic standards that take
into account not only a product's physical traits, but also the
way in which it was manufactured or harvested.<p>

<p>

	Thus, Boxer-Biden continues to condition access to the U.S.
market for domestic and foreign producers -- on a boat-by-boat
level -- on meeting an enforceable dolphin safe standard. That
is, to sell tuna in the U.S. market you must meet the same clear
standard of not encircling dolphins to catch tuna whether you are
a U.S. or foreign tuna fisher. <p>

<p>

5. Consumer Fraud: Public Reliance on a Fake "Dolphin Safe" Label<p>

<p>

	As a consumer group representing our large membership, I would be
remiss if I did not also raise the consumer fraud problems
Stevens-Breaux would cause.<p>

<p>

	Most simply, Stevens-Breaux would allow tuna to come into the
United States labelled "dolphin safe" even though it was caught
with the very encirclement techniques that killed hundreds of
thousands of dolphins before the Marine Mammal Protection Act was
passed. Stevens-Breaux would replace the standard of "no
encirclement" allowing tuna to be called dolphin safe merely if
an observer did not witness a dolphin die within their view
during fishing. (The standard for dolphin safe is Stevens-Breaux
is "no observable dolphin deaths.") First, given the size of tuna
ships, it is impossible that a single observer could witness the
obvious dolphin deaths that could occur at different areas on the
ship. Second, encirclement fishing uses explosives and motor boat
chase to round up dolphins and then requires the release of
trapped dolphins from nets before the mammals drown. Under these
circumstances, not seeing dead dolphins mixed on the deck with
tuna fish certainly does not ensure that dolphins are not dying
in significant numbers. Finally, there is not yet  evidence about
the effects on dolphins of the repetitive trauma, stress and
injuries dolphins suffer during encirclement. Yet, tuna caught
under these violent circumstances would be allowed into the
United States labelled as dolphin safe under the Stevens Breaux
bill as long as the sole observer did not actually witness a
dolphin death.<p>

<p>

	The MMPA was passed after a massive public campaign in which
millions of children, and ultimately all of the major U.S. tuna
companies, pressured Congress to stop the sale of dolphin-deadly
tuna. The tuna companies still support the MMPA because U.S.
consumers demand dolphin safe tuna. Under the current law,
consumers know that no company can sell tuna labelled "dolphin
safe" if a dolphin has been harassed or encircled during tuna
fishing. <p>

<p>

	Under the Stevens-Breaux bill this would no longer be the case.
The "dolphin safe" label consumers have come to rely on
guaranteeing one thing would actually have an entirely other and
unacceptable meaning -- Dolphin Deadly, but not in Front of the
Observer on the Tuna Boat. Thus, if neither the status quo can be
maintained or the Boxer-Biden bill with the strong standard
adopted, then Public Citizen would oppose the continuation of the
dolphin safe label under the definition of dolphin safe set forth
in the Stevens-Breaux bill. The U.S. consumer deserves to have an
honest label and if the weak, unenforceable standard of the
Stevens-Breaux bill were to become the law, the dolphin safe
label must go as its continuation would be a consumer fraud. <p>

Revealingly, the Mexican government rejected the option of
lifting the tuna embargo with permission to sell tuna in the
United States without the dolphin safe label. The Mexican
government knows the U.S. consumer demands dolphin safe tuna.
From their commercial perspective, committing consumer fraud by
labelling tuna caught using encirclement methods as dolphin safe
is the desired outcome of nations that do not want to fish in
dolphin safe ways.<p>

<p>

<center>Conclusion</center>
<p>

<p>

	Congressional action to change the MMPA has far reaching
implications for U.S. sovereignty and international trade policy.
Around the world, congressional action on U.S. dolphin policy is
understood to be a response to the GATT rulings against the U.S.
law which sets U.S. domestic standards for tuna fish to be sold
in the United States. If the U.S. Congress implements the GATT
rulings, and removes core provisions of the MMPA, a dangerous
precedent will have been set with implications on a wide range of
other U.S. domestic policies which other countries actually have
targeted as WTO illegal.<p>

<p>

	The World Trade Organization attempts to shift such domestic
policy questions as the standards for access to our internal
market away from citizen control and domestic democratic bodies
to negotiating committees and a dispute resolution body located
in Geneva, Switzerland which operate in secret and without the
guarantees of due process or accountability to U.S. citizens,
domestic legislatures or courts.<p>

  <p>

	The MMPA was the first case in which GATT tried to extend it
authority to demand changes in a well-know, beloved U.S. domestic
policy. Congress' actions on this legislation will directly
affect the future ability of the Congress and other legislative
bodies around the world to implement their democratically-established laws that may have a connection to trade. <p>

<p>

	It is inevitable that different policy goals will at times
conflict, for instance goals of maximizing international trade
and the goals of environmental protection. However, the decision
about which policy goal should take precedence in a particular
instance should be decided by those who will live with the
results -- in this case the American people and their
democratically elected representatives in Congress. <p>

<p>

	Thus, if Congress decides to change U.S. dolphin protection
policy, Boxer-Biden is the mechanism because it maintains U.S.
sovereignty and sets the precedent as regard U.S. Congressional
relations with the World Trade Organization.<p>

<p>
<hr>
