<body bgcolor="yellow">
<center><img width=120 height=75 
src="/public_citizen/pclogo.gif"></center><p> <h1><center>NAFTA Index
</h1><P>
<h2>Three Years of NAFTA Facts
</h2></center><P>
For Immediate Release:<br>
December 23, 1996<p>


<table border=1>
<tr><td>Percentage of Americans who say their views toward free trade are less favorable than a year ago as the result of what they know about NAFTA and GATT:1</td><td>52</td></tr>
<tr><td>Percentage who say their opinions are more favorable:2</td><td>27</td></tr>
<tr><td>Percentage of Mexicans who believe their country has had little or no success with NAFTA:3</td><td>67</td></tr>
<tr><td>Percentage of Mexicans who had a favorable opinion of the United States in 1991 (prior to NAFTA):4</td><td>75</td></tr>
<tr><td>Percentage of Mexicans who had a favorable opinion of the United States today:5</td><td>60</td></tr>
<tr><td>U.S. trade surplus with Mexico in 1993 (the year before NAFTA) :</td><td>$1.7 billion</td></tr>
<tr><td>U.S. trade deficit with Mexico in 1996 (three years after NAFTA) :</td><td>$16 billion</td></tr>
<tr><td>Germany's trade surplus with Mexico in 1995:6</td><td>$2 billion</td></tr>
<tr><td>Estimated number of U.S. jobs lost due to NAFTA as of October 1996:7</td><td>625,000</td></tr>
<tr><td>Number of U.S. workers certified by the U.S. Department of Labor as having been laidoff due to NAFTA in one narrow NAFTA re-training program:8</td><td>98,645</td></tr>
<tr><td>Approximate chances a laidoff U.S. worker will not find an equal or higher paying job:9</td><td>2 to 1</td></tr>
<tr><td>Median annual pay drop of a worker who is hired after being laidoff in the early 1990's:10</td><td>$4,420</td></tr>
<tr><td>Number of jobs lost in Mexico in 1995:11</td><td>1,850,000</td></tr>
<tr><td>Number of Mexicans who enter the job market each year:12</td><td>1,000,000</td></tr>
<tr><td>Number of Mexican Maquiladora workers in July 1996 (thirty months into NAFTA):13</td><td>761,705</td></tr>
<tr><td>Increase in Mexican Maquiladora jobs since NAFTA's passage:14</td><td>215,117</td></tr>
<tr><td>Number of jobs Allied Signal Chair Lawrence Bossidy predicted in 1993 his company would relocate to Mexico under NAFTA:15</td><td>0</td></tr>
<tr><td>Number of Allied Signal workers laidoff since NAFTA's passage due to "shift in production to Mexico," according to the U.S. Department of Labor:16</td><td>708</td></tr>
