<html>
<head>
<title>Fastrack</title>
<meta name="Author" content="Public Citizen">
<meta name="CreatedBy" content="WP Internet Publisher 6.1">
</head><center><img width=120 height= 75 
src="/public_citizen/pclogo.gif"></center>

<p>

<body bgcolor="#70db93">

<h1><center>Backgrounder: Fast Track</center></h1><p>

<p>

<p>

<b>Overview:  What Is Fast Track And How Does It
Work</b><p>

<p>

The term "fast track" is used to refer to
several related procedures used for
certain trade negotiations and for
congressional consideration of some
trade agreements that were devised by
President Richard Nixon and are codified
at 19 U.S.C.  2191, 2192, 2902 and
2903 which taken together:<p>

<p>

	 Delegates authority from the
legislative branch (which has exclusive
constitutional authority over regulation of
foreign commerce) to the executive
branch allowing the executive branch to
conduct trade negotiations and, <p>

<p>

	 Sets in advance of negotiations the
terms for congressional consideration of
any resulting trade agreement, requiring:<p>

<p>

		- Congress to vote only "yes" or "no"
with <u>absolutely no amendments</u> allowed
on a completed trade agreement and the
implementing legislation required to
bring all existing U.S. laws and policies
into conformity with such an agreement,
and<p>

<p>

		- Maximum of 20 hours of floor debate in
each chamber.<p>

<p>

		- Such a vote must occur within 60
legislative days after the agreement and
implementing legislation are presented to
Congress by the Executive branch.<p>

<p>

		- Not only the actual agreement, but the
domestic implementing legislation is
written by the Executive branch
bypassing regular congressional
committee procedures, such as mark ups. Statutory references for specific fast track provisions: No amendments to the implementing legislation or
the trade agreement are permitted under the fast-track procedures is 19 U.S.C.  2191(d).  The 60 day voting
requirement consists of two aspects contained at 19 U.S.C.  2191(e): The congressional committees to which
the implementing bill is referred have only 45 legislative days to review it but without any changes, at which
time it is automatically referred to the full House, and a floor vote must then be taken within 15 legislative days.
In calculating the time periods for action in either chamber, the days on which that House is not in session are
excluded. 19 U.S.C.  2191(e)(3). The limitation of debate to not more than 20 hours, divided equally between
those favoring and those opposing the legislation is 19 U.S.C.  2191(f)(2) &amp; (g)(2).<p>

<p>

<b>Unique Limitations on Congressional Authority, Role
in Trade Policy</b><p>

<p>

No other such severe limitations of
congressional authority exist in U.S. law.
For instance, while certain budget votes
are granted closed rules automatically
and in advance, such votes are on bills
shaped by Congress that have undergone
extensive congressional committee
process.<p>

<p>

Supporters of the fast track concept argue
that Congress must give up to right to
regular committee process and floor
amendments on trade agreements to
provide U.S. trade negotiators with
credibility that the terms they negotiate
with other countries won't be re-opened
by Congress. By banning any
amendments and also strictly limiting
Congress' role in overseeing actual
negotiations, fast track supporters argue
that the procedures force Congress into
accepting hard compromises made in one
area of negotiation needed to make gains
in others. According to this notion, fast
track forces to swallow many smaller
bitter pills in the name of a greater good
accomplished by the whole deal.<p>

<p>

Opponents of fast track argue that
Congress must have a greater role in U.S.
trade and investment policy given the
direct, domestic impact such policies will
have on their constituents. Additionally,
opponents have voiced concern that U.S.
negotiators do not necessarily represent
the full range of U.S. interests at the
negotiating table. Some argue that the
diffuse, but vital interests in good jobs
and high wages shared by most
Americans are subsumed to narrower,
more strongly articulated interests of
major corporations and investors. The
role of such corporations in
institutionalized in fast track, as that law
also established advisory committees
staffed with over 500 corporate
representatives to give private sector
input in exchange for Congress giving up
its previous greater involvement in trade
policy. Lawsuits by Public Citizen
against the lack of balance in the fast
track trade advisory committee system
since 1992 have resulted in token
representation of a few citizens'
organizations in these committees.<p>

<p>

Congressional concern about fast track's
limitation of a congressional role in trade
and investment policy has grown
considerably in since the 1993 passage of
the North American Free Trade
Agreement (NAFTA) and the 1994
passage of the Uruguay Round of the
General Agreement on tariffs and Trade
(GATT.) These agreements contained
lengthy provisions directly affected U.S.
domestic investment, environmental,
labor and consumer standards laws and
their implementing legislation
specifically changed hundreds of
provisions in such laws. Thus, these
agreements' results, unlike the results of
past trade agreements focussing on tariff
or quota reduction, have had direct and
personal effects on many Americans in
areas for which they hold their Members
of Congress accountable. <p>

<p>

As well, fast track allows many matters
unrelated to trade to be "superglued" onto
trade legislation. Because no
amendments are allowed, Congress is
thus forced into rejecting entire trade
agreements or approving special deals
and unsavory  amendments. For instance,
the GATT implementing legislation
included: unrelated provisions changing
important U.S. pension laws including a
special deal for a particular company that
has been protested by many senior
citizens; tax breaks to certain interests;
special access to communications
licenses for several specific companies;
controversial changes in the U.S. Savings
Bond Program; new requirements for
electronic tax filing and many more.<p>

<p>

Some Members of Congress have begun
to argue that the Legislative and
executive branches should redesign their
cooperation in the area of international
trade and investment to provide a more
balanced role for Congress. Given that
the regulation of international commerce
is Congress' constitutional role, Congress
has the power to redesign such a
relationship according to how much
authority is decides to delegates away to
the Executive branch.<p>

<p>

<b>Fast Track As A Congressional Delegation Of
Authority <p>

	To Negotiate<p>

</b><p>

The best way to think about how fast
track is applied to any specific agreement
is to think of it in two pieces: fast track
generally and application of fast track to
any specific negotiations.<p>

<p>

Currently, the overarching fast track
authority is expired and has been expired
for two years. The discussion about
whether fast track will include labor or
environmental language (a discussion
which is much more complicated than it
seems given that only certain types of
labor or environmental language will
have any effect whatsoever on actual
negotiating objectives) refers to the terms
of this overarching legislation's design.
Reauthorization of any fast track, or any
alternative trade negotiating authority
Congress might choose to confer on the
executive branch, will require a specific
vote of Congress on legislation
describing that delegation.<p>

<p>

If such an overarching fast track
authority is granted by Congress, to apply
fast track's rules to a particular trade
agreement, a President must request such
a specific delegation of negotiating
authority and of congressional no-amendments, limited debate vote.
Congress must vote not to stop automatic
application of fast track once this request
has been made. <p>

<p>

Specifically, to obtain negotiating
authority and such a pre-agreed closed
rule, the President must notify Congress
that he wants to negotiate a specific trade
agreement with fast-track procedures. Notification is at 19 U.S.C.  2902(c)(3)(C).  <p>

Congress may then vote to refuse the
application of fast-track procedures to a
specific agreement by a vote of both
Houses in any 60-day period, or by a
disapproval vote of either the Senate
Committee on Finance or the House
Committee on Ways and Means within
60 days of the notification of the
negotiations. Disapproval is at 19 U.S.C.  2903(c)(1)(A) &amp; (2).  <p>

<p>

If Congress grants such authority, the
President is then free to negotiate the
agreement. The President must next
involve Congress by notifying Congress
90 calendar days before he intends to
sign a trade agreement. After the
President enters into (<u>i.e.</u>, signs) the
agreement following the expiration of the
congressional notice period, he may
thereafter submit the signed trade
agreement, implementing legislation, and
certain required supporting information
to Congress for approval. <u>Id</u>.  2903(1)(B). The
implementing legislation must include a
provision approving the trade agreement,
and that legislation must be enacted into
law before any trade agreement
concerning nontariff trade barriers may
enter into force with respect to the United
States. 19 U.S.C.  2191(b)(1)(A); 2903(a)(1)(C). <p>

<p>

While the fast-track procedures establish
a maximum timetable for a vote on the
trade agreement, there is no requirement
that the congressional approval process
take the entire 60 or 90 day period.  The
timetable was accelerated for political
reasons for the congressional vote on
NAFTA.   Even though it was not readily
accessible to the public at that time, the
President submitted the implementing
legislation to Congress on November 4,
1993,.  The House voted less than two
weeks later on November 17, 1993, and
the Senate voted the following week on
November 22, 1993.  Thus, the period for
developing a full congressional record on
the trade agreement and its implementing
legislation can be truncated even further
than the fast-track timetable.<p>

<p>

The Congress is then required to have a
"yes" or "no" vote. If Congress votes yes,
it incorporates the terms of the actual
trade agreement as well as all
amendments in the implementing
legislation into U.S. federal law.<p>

<p>
<hr>
