<html>
<head>
<title>ACTION ALERT</title>
<meta name="Author" content="Chris McGinn">
<meta name="CreatedBy" content="WP Internet Publisher 6.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="c6004b">
<center><img width=120 height=75 
src="/public_citizen/pclogo.gif"></center><p> <h1>ACTION ALERT</h1>
	<a name="4"></a><u><b>USTR Anti-Forest Negotiations Exposed!<p>

GATTzilla attacks NGO eco-labels!<p>

</u>                                                       
<u><i>Contact:Charlene Barshefsky!</i></b></u> 202-395-3204<p>
Friday, September 27, 1996

                                                                         
                            <p>

This just in:<p>

<p>

At the third meeting of the
Intergovernmental Panel on Forests (IPF
III), which ends in Geneva today, USTR
delegates have inserted the following
bracketed text in the negotiating text on
Trade and Environment Relating to Forest
Products and Services.<p>

<p>

"The Panel ... agreed on the need to ensure that existing
and new certification and labeling schemes for forests
and forest products comply with the provisions of the WTO
Agreement on Technical Barriers to Trade."<p>

<p>

While this language is vague, it is
problematic for a number of specific
reasons, and appears to be part of a joint
Canadian-US push to get all timber
labeling schemes, including those
established by NGOs like <b>Smartwood
</b>and the <b>Forest Stewardship Council</b>,
brought under the trade-oriented
disciplines of the TBT. <p>

<p>

In campaign-speak, the USTR is
unleashing Gattzilla on NGO eco-labels.<p>

<p>

The following are the main problems and
uncertainties stemming from this US
proposal:<p>

<p>

	<u>The application of the TBT to private vs.
government schemes</u>. Private schemes
are only subject to the TBT indirectly, in
that some WTO members may be
required --- under Article 4 --- to take
reasonable measures as may be
available to ensure that private
standardizing bodies comply with the
Code of Good Practice (Annex 3 of the
TBT Agreement).<p>

<p>

	<u>The application of the TBT to voluntary
vs. mandatory schemes</u>. Voluntary
schemes, if covered at all, are subject
only to the Code's substantive disciplines.
The TBT Agreement, as well as all WTO
agreements, is a policy agreement
between governments.  It must be
understood as manifesting the policies
upon which the countries intended to
agree. In this context, it is unlikely that
governments intended to subject
voluntary, private ecolabelling schemes to
trade disciplines as contained in the Code
of Good Practice.<p>

<p>

By regulating the market activities of
private actors, the Code goes far beyond
the appropriate scope for
intergovernmental action and breaks from
the mandate traditionally granted to WTO
of reducing government interference with
markets. This is especially true if the
"reasonable measures" standard
contained in Article 4 is interpreted
restrictively.<p>

<p>

	If the Code is interpreted to be void of
environmental exceptions (in that its text
does not include the exceptions as
compared with TBT Article 2 that applies
to technical regulations and WTO Article
XX), then  the result would be that the
TBT Agreement would demand higher
standards of voluntary schemes (that are
covered by the Code).<p>

<p>

<b>While this Canada-US effort is still in its early stages, and the IPF text will not
be finalized until the next meeting of the IPF in February,  it would be very
useful to have US groups starting to ask pointed questions at the USTR in
Washington.  They need to know that we are on their case IMMEDIATELY.<p>

</b>
</body>
</html>
</DOC>
