<html>
<head>
<title>Public Citizen: NAFTA
Accountability Act Fact Sheet</title>
<meta name="CreatedBy" content="WP Internet Publisher 6.1">
</head>
<body>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#0000ff"
VLINK="#dd0000" ALINK="#ff0000"><p>

<h1><center>"NAFTA Accountability Act"</h1>
</center>
<center>S-1417; H-2651</center>
<p>

<center><b>Fix It or Nix It </b>-- A Performance Standard for <p>

the North American Free Trade Agreement<p>

</center>
<p>

On the 2nd anniversary of NAFTA's narrow passage, November 17, 1995,  Rep. Marcy
Kaptur (D-OH),  Rep. Peter DeFazio (D-OR), Rep. Duncan Hunter (R-CA) and Sen. Byron
Dorgan (D-ND) organized 29 bipartisan House Members and 4 Senators to introduce the
<a href="http://www.citizen.org/pctrade/nafta-act.html">NAFTA Accountability Act</a>. <u><p>

</u><p>

The NAFTA Accountability Act applies a basic "do no further harm" test to NAFTA.  The
bill requires objective measures of NAFTA's real performance in each category for which
NAFTA boosters promised benefits:  <b>jobs, wages, illegal drug flows, environmental and
health quality and human and labor rights. </b> Current data in these areas would be compared
with the same data before NAFTA took effect. <p>

<p>

If conditions now are at least equal to conditions before NAFTA, the legislation would have
no effect beyond generating the documantation of such a "break even". If conditions were
found to have become worse, the NAFTA Accountability Act would require NAFTA
renegotiation in those areas.<p>

<p>

If, after renegotiations, NAFTA still failed this "do no further harm" test, then the legislation
provides for the sunset-- the  termination of NAFTA's implementing bill.<p>

<p>

With the 11/15/95 Times-Mirror national poll showing growing public recognition of the
damage bad trade deals do to our wages and jobs, the NAFTA Accountability Act is a great
hook for educating on NAFTA's actual outcomes. The Times-Mirror poll found 55% of
Americans believe NAFTA is a job loser. A December 1995 poll in Mexico found that 66% of
the public believes NAFTA has not been positive for Mexico. <p>

<p>

The NAFTA Accountability Act provides a way to reverse the situation by terminating
congressional authorization if NAFTA fails a "do no harm" test and can not be fixed. <p>

 <p>

Asking Representatives &amp; Senators to cosponsor the Act also provides a hook to show them
how NAFTA has failed and to hold NAFTA supporters accountable. Cosponsoring is a way
for NAFTA-supporters to show a change of heart. The Act is a clever idea -- Members of
Congress who support it are merely voting to examine and document NAFTA's real life
outcomes. If NAFTA fails on its own terms, congressional legislative authorization for
NAFTA terminates. Like other legislation that is authorized for a certain period of time and
then "sunset" or expires, NAFTA would have to be reauthorized. Failure to reauthorize
would trigger NAFTA's 6 month exit clause.<p>

<p>

<hr>
<p>

Other Public Citizen Global Trade Watch links related to the Nafta Accountability Act:<p>

