<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Abraham Fuchsberg Fellowship</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#0000ff"
ALINK="#ff0000" 
VLINK="#dd0000">

<H1><CENTER><IMG HEIGHT=160 WIDTH=240
SRC="/public_citizen/pclogo.gif" 
ALT="PUBLIC
 CITIZEN">
</CENTER></H1>
<H1><CENTER><FONT SIZE=+4>T</FONT>HE  <FONT
SIZE=+4>L</FONT>ITIGATION
<FONT SIZE=+4>G</FONT>ROUP
</CENTER></H1>
<BR>
<center><b>ABRAHAM FUCHSBERG FELLOWSHIP<b><p>
<hr><p>
              <blink><b><i>Deadline - February 17,
1997</b></i></center></blink><p>
<hr>
<p>
Public Citizen is establishing a Fellowship in the name of Abraham
Fuchsberg -- a nationally-renowned trial attorney -- to provide
young lawyers with an opportunity to work on actual precedent-
setting public interest cases under the close supervision of
highly-experienced Public Citizen Litigation Group staff
attorneys.<p>
 
The Fellowship's goal is to imprint the value of public interest
law on young attorneys at the threshold of their careers, and to
demonstrate that lawyers can be a successful and powerful force in
protecting Americans' rights, health and safety.  Abraham Fuchsberg
is the embodiment of that tradition, and it is only fitting that
this Fellowship bears his name.<p>

The need for this Fellowship is great.  First, public interest law
firms need an infusion of new talent to enable them to respond
effectively to the emerging threats to our system of justice.  More
and more, corporations are relying on highly technical preemption
claims in an effort to cut off all remedies for injured victims. 
And the use of collusive class action settlements to resolve
cheaply and expediently the liability of companies that have
manufactured dangerous products or engaged in deceptive or
fraudulent sales practices is growing at an alarming rate.<p>

More than any other public interest law firm in the nation, Public
Citizen Litigation Group is at the vortex of these battles,
fighting to protect the rights of victims.  Last year alone, our
lawyers argued three preemption cases in the United States Supreme
Court.  And this Term, we are lead counsel in two important cases
before the Court, and co-counsel in two other cases, including the
massive Georgine asbestos class action case, in which we have been
co-lead counsel for the objectors. <p>

Establishing the Fuchsberg Fellowship is also imperative because of
the simple economics of law practice for young attorneys.  Law
students are especially hard-hit by the skyrocketing costs of
education.  All too often, the lure of the high salaries offered by
corporate law firms is overwhelming for talented but debt-laden
young lawyers.  <p>

The Fuchsberg Fellowship can offer young lawyers a way out of the
vicious cycle of debt-forced service at corporate law firms.  By
offering a modest but reasonable starting salary and an entree into
the practice of public interest law, the Fuchsberg Fellowship will
give young law school graduates a meaningful alternative that 
allows them to support themselves while also satisfying their
principles.<p>

We anticipate that the Fellow will work on a wide variety of cases,
but with a special emphasis in two areas -- preemption and class
action litigation.  Although our docket fluctuates, for the past
several years there has been a steep rise in the number of both
preemption and class action cases, and we expect that trend to 
continue.  In view of the high volume of these cases, and the
absence of other public interest involvement in them, this will be
a major focus of our work.  We would expect that the Fellow would
work on both trial and appellate court matters, and we would make
every effort to ensure that the Fellow has the opportunity to argue
in court, as well as write briefs and participate fully in the
litigation process.  <p>

The Fellow will work side-by-side with Public Citizen Litigation
Group staff attorneys, who rank as perhaps the most experienced
group of public interest advocates in the nation.  In the
aggregate, they have practiced law for over fifteen years, and have
been at Public Citizen over a decade.  One lawyer, the Public
Citizen Litigation Group's co-founder and first director, Alan B.
Morrison, has been with the organization for twenty-five years. 
Three other lawyers, including David C. Vladeck, the Group's
current director, have been with Public Citizen more than fifteen
years, and each has practiced law for twenty years or more.  The
remainder of the lawyers average nearly ten years in practice.  Not
only are they experienced, they are also teachers.  Staff lawyers
serve as Adjunct Professors of law at Harvard, NYU, Georgetown and
American Universities.  Thus, there can be no question that the
Fuchsberg Fellow will be given the highest quality supervision.
 
The Abraham Fuchsberg Fellowship will be continuously occupied,
except for the time needed to select appropriate candidates.  The
Fellows will rotate every twelve months, and will be recruited
through the law schools, individual faculty members, public
interest consortiums (like the National Association of Public
Interest Law and the Equal Justice Foundation), and a large network
of law clerks.  Candidates will be selected by the President of
Public Citizen and the Director of the Public Citizen Litigation
Group from among the applicants. We plan to have the first Abraham
Fuchsberg Fellow join Public Citizen in September, 1997.<p>
<hr>
<p>
Send questions or comments about the Abraham Fuchsberg Fellowship
to:<BR>
<ADDRESS> the Litigation Group<A
HREF="mailto:LitigationGroup@citizen.org">&lt;litigationgroup@cit
izen.org></A>
</ADDRESS>

</BODY>

