<html>
<head>
<title>Supreme Court Assistance Project</title>
</head>
<BODY COLOR BGCOLOR="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#0000ff" VLINK="#dd0000">
<body>
<h1><center><FONT SIZE=+4>S</FONT>UPREME <FONT SIZE=+4>C</FONT>OURT 
<FONT SIZE=+4>A</FONT>SSISTANCE <FONT SIZE=+4>P</FONT>PROJECT</h1> </center>
	1995 marked another successful year for the Supreme Court Assistance Project in identifying cases with the
potential of a broad public impact.  Many lawyers arguing cases before the Supreme Court have no background
in practicing before the Court, and the experience can be different from arguing before other courts, even for very
seasoned lawyers.  Our expertise and knowledge have become a valuable resource to litigants, and helps to ensure
that the Court is presented with the strongest possible arguments.  We help attorneys who have been successful
in lower courts to preserve their victories by assisting them in drafting briefs arguing that the Court should not
grant review.  And where review is granted, we assist lawyers in drafting their briefs and in preparing for oral
argument.<p>

<p>

	During the 1994 Term, SCAP was involved in approximately 30 of the 80 cases heard by the Court. During
the 1995-96 Term, the Project has offered assistance 17 times in the pre-<i>certiorari</i> stage-- that is, before the
Court grants review.  Public Citizen lawyers have participated in 9 cases that have already been argued, and we
are assisting in another 10 cases that will be argued before the Term ends.<p>

<p>

	Here are a few significant cases we worked on during 1995 that have been decided by the Court.<p>

<p>

<i><b>	Heintz v. Jenkins</i>.</b> We assisted the counsel for the consumer in a Supreme Court case presenting the issue
of whether attorneys are exempt from the requirements of the Federal Debt Collection Practices Act.  In a
unanimous ruling, the Supreme Court ruled in favor of the consumer, and held that there was no exemption for
attorneys, nor any doctrine that would permit attorneys involved in collecting debts through litigation to ignore
the requirements of the Act. <p>

<i><b><p>

	Johnson v. Jones</i></b>.  We assisted counsel for the plaintiff in a civil rights case that presented an important
issue concerning the ability of government officials to appeal before a final judgment, a practice that can frustrate
or, at a minimum, delay recovery by victims of civil rights abuses.  In a unanimous decision, the Supreme Court
rejected arguments by the federal government and state officials that officials charged with civil rights violations
should be permitted to take an immediate appeal from any ruling by a trial judge rejecting an official's claim that
he or she is entitled to judgment, even if the official's claim is based on factual issues, rather than purely legal
issues.<p>

<i><b><p>

	Wolens v. American Airlines</i>.</b>  Our continuing activity monitoring claims that consumer rights are
"preempted" by federal statute took to the airways in a division that landed in 1995.  We worked with lawyers
who persuaded the Supreme Court to let passengers who belong to American Airlines' frequent flier program sue
the airline for breach of contract.  The suit challenged a 1988 decision by American to raise the number of miles
needed to earn free trips or other benefits, and the Supreme Court agreed the passengers' claim was not
preempted.<p>

<p>

<i><b>	Gutierrez de Martinez v. Lamagno</i></b>.  Even the most unusual cases find their way to the Supreme Court
Assistance Project.  Late one night, a vehicle driven by an off-duty DEA agent in Barranquilla, Colombia, who
was allegedly intoxicated and accompanied by a civilian companion, collided into the car of several Colombian
civilians, causing them serious injuries.  The civilians sued the DEA employee in federal court in Virginia, where
the employee resided, seeking compensation for their injuries.  The DEA agent claimed that he is immune from
liability under the Federal Tort Claims Act, which exempts any federal employee from suit when acting within
the scope of his or her employment.  The U.S. Attorney from Virginia certified, without giving any reason, that
the DEA Agent employee was acting within the scope of his employment, and the lower courts held that a "scope
of employment" certification, however wrong it may be, is absolutely final and is not subject to correction by the
court.<p>

<p>

	After the Supreme Court decided to review the case, the Litigation Group entered the fray, helping the
Colombian attorney prepare his briefs and oral argument.  In a 5-4 victory, the Supreme Court held that the U.S.
Attorney's certification is <i>not</i> final, and the court has a duty to review "scope of employment" issues, which will
finally allow the car accident victims in this case--and others like them--their day in court. <p>

<p>

<p>

<p>


<table border width=100% cellpadding=5>
