<head>
<title>Separation of Powers</title>
</head>
<BODY COLOR BGCOLOR ="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#0000ff" VLINK="#dd0000">
<body>
<h1><center><FONT SIZE=+4>S</FONT>EPARATION OF <FONT 
SIZE=+4>P</FONT>OWERS</h1> </center>
<b></b><p>

<p>

	Within the legal profession, the Litigation Group is probably best known for our landmark litigation in the field
of separation of powers.  While this may seem an esoteric area with seemingly little connection to the lives of
ordinary Americans, that is not so.  Arrogation of power by any branch of government inevitably harms citizens. 
This year,  we had only one matter in active litigation that involved a separation of powers issue. Two proposals
before Congress, however, raised vital separation of powers issues on which we weighed in.<p>

<p>

<b>	Airports Authority Litigation</b>  After two rounds of litigation, including a major victory in the Supreme
Court, this case may finally have come to a close.  The main issue in this case was whether Congress, in
delegating control over the airports in the Washington, DC region to a local authority, could retain control over
the authority by selecting the members of a board of review that could overrule the authority's decisions.  In the
first phase of the case, the Supreme Court struck down a review board composed of Members of Congress on
the ground that it violated the principle established by the Court in <i>INS v. Chadha</i> (another case we handled) that
Congress may act only through legislation, and cannot override an administrative body in any other way.  <p>

	After our initial victory, Congress amended the law to give it power to select many of the board members and
to require that the authority's key decisions could not take effect until Congress had been given an opportunity
to override them.  In another major victory, the court of appeals held that this scheme also violated the
Constitution on <i>Chadha</i> grounds.  The Airports Authority sought review in the Supreme Court, but its petition
was denied.  Congress needs to amend the law once again, and we are hopeful that Congress will give up its quest
to exercise supervisory power over the authority.<p>

<b><p>

	Line-Item Veto</b>. We have long held the view that bills to give the President line-item veto are
unconstitutional, and we argued strenuously against the adoption of such legislation which passed both Houses
of Congress in 1995.  The House and Senate versions differ substantially, and no conference has yet been held
to iron out those differences.  We have made our views known to key legislators and committee staffs and, if a
bill is signed into law, will likely commence litigation to have the veto provision declared unconstitutional.<p>

<p>

<b>	Balanced Budget Amendment</b>.  In the aftermath of the Republican takeover of Congress, proposals were
introduced in both Houses to add a balanced budget amendment to the Constitution.  While proponents of the
amendment followed the procedures set forth in the Constitution, we argued that the provision was unwise
because it would be unmanageable and would produce enormous inter-branch friction because of the inherent
difficulties in accurately forecasting and tracking federal revenues and expenditures.  We were gratified to see
this effort fail, but recognize that this issue is likely to be raised again in 1996.<p>

<p>

<p>

<p>

<p>


