<head>
<title>Regulation of the Professions</title>
</head>
<BODY COLOR BGCOLOR="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#0000ff" VLINK="#dd0000"
<body>
<h1><center><FONT SIZE=+4>R</FONT>EGULATION OF THE <FONT 
SIZE=+4>P</FONT>ROFESSIONS</h1> </center>
<b></b><p>

	This area has always been  of considerable activity by Litigation Group lawyers because of our
commitment to open the flow of information relating to the availability and cost of legal services to
consumers to enable them to make better informed hiring decisions.  Litigation Group lawyers
handled the first Supreme Court case recognizing that commercial speech is entitled to First
Amendment protection, and over the years we have litigated a number of the most significant
commercial speech cases involving the regulation of the professions.<p>

<p>

	<b>Schwartz v. Welch</b> This matter is the first case to go to trial on the question whether states may
severely restrict the ability of lawyers to advertise on television and radio. We represented a
consortium of lawyers, media groups, and consumers who argued that lawyer advertising gives
consumers important information about where to find lawyers able to handle their problems at an
affordable price.  We also argued that advertising promotes price competition.  <p>

<p>

	After a week-long trial, the presiding judge ruled in our favor and 
against the state across the
board.  He held that the First Amendment requires a state to have a strong interest in restricting
broadcast advertising and that the state had failed to show that broadcast advertising created any
problems in Mississippi, let alone the sort of problems that justified the sweeping rules Mississippi
had imposed.  Because of the strength of the district court's ruling, the State decided not to appeal.<p>

<p>

<b>	Colorado</b>. Our success in Mississippi led to our being asked to assist a group of Colorado lawyers
trying to fend off a state bar proposal to institute lawyer advertising rules similar to those enacted in
Mississippi.  We have drafted extensive submissions to the Colorado Bar and anticipate having to
appear on this matter before the Colorado Supreme Court in 1996.<p>

<p>

<p>

<p>


<table border width=100% cellpadding=5>
<tr><td><a href="http://www.citizen.org/public_citizen/litigation/annual_rep/govcorp.html">Government &amp;
