<html>
<head>
<title>Government Secrecy</title>
</head>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#0000ff" ALINK="#ff0000" 
VLINK="#dd0000">
<body>
</CENTER></H1>
<H1><CENTER><FONT SIZE=+4>G</FONT>OVERNMENT<FONT
SIZE=+4> S</FONT>ECRECY
</CENTER></H1>

<b></b>   Measured by sheer numbers, the Litigation Group has
handled more cases challenging government secrecy than
any other category of case.  We believe that these cases are
vitally important.  They give the public a window on
how their government is operating and  why critical policies were
implemented.  They also enhance government
accountability, since decision-makers know that they will be called
on to defend the policy choices they make.<p>

  <p>

     This year was consistent with our historic practice.  At any
given point, we had at least a dozen pending cases
challenging government secrecy - either the government improperly
withholding records, or courts entering
sealing orders that bar the public from reviewing important court
files.  We discuss a few of the most noteworthy
cases on our docket.<p>

<p>

<b>  Armstrong v. Executive Office of the President</b>. This
precedent-setting case, pending for seven years,
has already established that the electronic records generated by
the White House and the rest of the Executive
Branch are subject to the federal open government laws. In 1995 we
scored a number of additional victories. <p>

<p>

     First, the government released over 3,000 e-mail records used
by the White House and the National Security
Council during the Reagan Administration.  After being recovered
from backup tapes preserved as a result of our
earlier victories, the records were processed under the Freedom of
Information Act (FOIA).  We believe that this
is the first time that e-mail records have been recovered from
electronic storage devices to respond to a FOIA
request.  <p>

<p>

     The e-mail records released by the government contained many
new insights concerning the foreign policy
activities and internal politics of the Reagan Administration. 
Although the government claimed that significant
portions of these electronic mail records were exempt from
disclosure under FOIA provisions relating to
classified and national security information, we successfully
demonstrated that many of these exemption claims
were untenable, which resulted in the government releasing
additional portions of the records.  A number of the
remaining exemption claims made by the government were upheld by
the district court, and our challenge to some
of them are on appeal.  One of our clients in this case, the
National Security Archive, used the messages secured
in this litigation to compile a book on the importance of
electronic mail as a record of government decision
making and policy, entitled <i>White House e-mail</i> (November,
1995).<p>

<p>

     Second, on a separate issue in the same litigation, the
National Security Council has asserted that it is not an
agency for purposes of the FOIA or the Federal Records Act, a novel
claim that, if successful, would exempt the
NSC from any obligation to preserve and disclose government records
in accordance with these statutes.  In
February, 1995, the trial court rejected the NSC's contention
ruling, on the basis of an  extensive record that we
had compiled, that the history and activities of the NSC showed
that it functions as an agency of the federal
government by issuing rules, adjudicating disputes, and performing
other agency functions.  The NSC took an
appeal, and we are awaiting a decision.<p>

<p>

     Third, the National Archives adopted new regulations that
explicitly direct all federal agencies to preserve and
maintain electronic records as part of their records management
program.  As a result, agencies throughout the
government are now required to issue directives informing staff of
their obligation to preserve electronic mail
records and to monitor compliance with these directives.  These new
regulations mark a significant victory,
particularly since as recently as 1993 the National Archives and
the White House were adamantly proclaiming
that agencies were free to disregard their electronic mail systems
for purposes of compliance with the Federal
Records Act.<p>

<p>

<b>  American Historical Association v.  Peterson</b>. As a result
of the <i>Armstrong v. Executive Office of the
President</i> litigation, the White House was unable to carry out
plans to destroy Presidential records stored on the
White House electronic mail system at the end of the Bush
Administration.  Instead, the Archivist, Don W.
Wilson, signed an agreement with former President Bush that
purported to give Mr. Bush control over the
disposition of any Presidential materials on backup tapes and hard
drives from the White House computer system. 
At the end of 1994, we filed an action to prevent the National
Archives from implementing the Bush-Wilson
Agreement, which was disturbingly similar to former President
Nixon's effort to retain control over the Watergate
tapes after he resigned.  In February, the trial court ruled that
the Bush-Wilson Agreement violated the
Presidential Records Act and was an unconstitutional effort by the
former President to control public records. 
The Clinton Administration took an appeal from this ruling, but
later abandoned the appeal, marking the death
knell of this effort to retain private control over public records.
<p>

<p>

<b>  Public Citizen v. DOJ and National Archives.</b>  This FOIA
lawsuit is yet another outgrowth of the
<i>Armstrong</i> and Bush/Wilson litigation.  We are seeking
correspondence exchanged between the Department of
Justice and the National Archives and Records Administration, and
George Bush's and Ronald Reagan's lawyers
concerning the disposition of electronic records created by the
Executive Office of the President during the terms
of Presidents Reagan and Bush.  The government will likely claim
that the documents are internal agency
memoranda protected from disclosure under FOIA--an argument we
believe is untenable since the
correspondence was shared with a wide-range of non-governmental
personnel.  <p>

<p>

<b>  Hammock v. Hoffmann LaRoche.</b> For the last four years we
have been trying to unseal health and safety
records submitted in a damages action brought in a New Jersey state
court by a woman who, while pregnant, was
given Accutane, an anti-acne medicine that causes birth defects.<p>

<p>

     We  filed a motion with the court to make the health and
safety data used in the case public.  After the trial
court and intermediate appellate court rejected our efforts, the
New Jersey Supreme Court granted review for the
express purpose of establishing standards for protecting public
access to court records in New Jersey.  In August,
the Court ruled in our favor in an opinion that is a resounding
endorsement of the view that court records are
presumptively subject to public access and should only be placed
under seal in the most extraordinary
circumstances, particularly when the records relate to public
health and safety.  The case was remanded to the trial
court with instructions to review the records concerning Accutane
in accordance with the strict standards set forth
in its opinion.<p>

<p>

<b>  FDA Drug Safety Data</b>. Still pending on our docket are
three FOIA cases seeking access to FDA health and
safety data relating to drugs.  One case seeks records relating to
the "fentanyl lollipop," a narcotic lollipop used
to relax children in preparation for surgical procedures.  We
believe that it is a bad idea to equate narcotics with
candy and are concerned that the active ingredient is too potent
for pediatric use.  Another case seeks access to
data on the experimental drug FIAU, which was being developed to
fight hepatitis, but caused irreversible liver
damage in humans.  We have succeeded in getting a significant
amount of data in this case, but the case is still
under review.  Finally, building on the FIAU case, we have sued the
FDA to get access to records concerning all
experimental drugs whose testing has been halted because of serious
adverse health effects in humans.  Our
concern is that the FDA is too lax in allowing human trials to
begin before the agency has carefully reviewed the
necessary animal studies.<p>

<p>

<b>  Levy v. CIA. </b>Our client is a writer preparing a biography
of Morris "Two-Gun" Cohen--a British subject
and a Canadian citizen who was a confidant of Sun Yat-Sen and
active in Chinese affairs in the 1920s to 1940s. 
When our client asked the CIA for any documents on Cohen, who died
in 1970, the CIA refused even to confirm
or deny the existence or nonexistence of responsive records.<p>

     In the district court, the CIA argued that it had a policy of
refusing to confirm or deny the existence of
documents as to any request pertaining to a foreign national.  The
judge found that the CIA's policy might be
subject to exceptions in some cases, but that this case was not one
of them.  An appeal on behalf of Mr. Levy is
pending.<p>

<p>

<b>  Sims v. Department of State</b>. For   the past five years,
Professor John Sims has been trying to pry loose
a full set of the government's documents relating to the litigation
of the Pentagon Papers case.  To assist him, we
have brought a number of FOIA cases against several government
agencies, including the Departments of State,
Defense, and Justice, and the National Security Agency.  Based
largely on the documents he has obtained through
FOIA, Professor Sims has published an extensive critical account of
the litigation.<p>

<p>

     This year, our litigation against the Department of State on
Prof. Sims' behalf succeeded in gaining access to
yet another series of long-withheld documents, casting further
doubt on the government's claim that the release
of the Pentagon Papers caused harm to our nation's diplomatic
efforts.  Although we have already largely
prevailed, litigation is ongoing with regard to a few remaining
records withheld by the Department.<p>

<p>

     In addition, the Second Circuit granted our motion to unseal
the records filed under seal in the Second Circuit
Stage of the <i>Pentagon Papers</i> Case, revealing for the first
time the transcript of the <i>in camera</i> proceedings before
the Second Circuit and the special appendix filed by the
government.<p>

<p>

<b>  Westinghouse Steam Generators</b>. On behalf of the Union of
Concerned Scientists and Public Citizen's
Critical Mass Energy Project, we have successfully intervened in
litigation pending in federal court in Pittsburgh
to unseal records pertaining to the safety of Westinghouse steam
generators installed in two nuclear electric
generating facilities in Western Pennsylvania.  The premature aging
of Westinghouse steam generators has
resulted in at least fourteen lawsuits by utilities against
Westinghouse.  When our motion to intervene in the
<i>Duquesne Light Co, et al. v. Westinghouse Electric Corp.</i>
case was granted, over 7000 documents were under
seal.  That case went to trial, and the vast majority of the
documents we sought became public.  We first reached
a settlement with the plaintiff utilities that lifted the seal on
additional documents.  Then in 1995, the trial judge
ordered Westinghouse to produce evidence to demonstrate that it
would suffer competitive harm from lifting the
seal on the remaining documents.  As a result, we were able to
reach a settlement with Westinghouse in January
1996.  A number of key documents, including summary judgment
materials, the parties' pre-trial statements, and
more than 400 exhibits that the utilities had produced supporting
their allegations against Westinghouse have
now been unsealed.<p>

<b>  Insurance Forum v. Insurance Commission</b>. This matter  is
a New York State freedom of information 
case brought by a newsletter that focuses on insurance issues to
gain access to reports submitted by insurance
companies that detail all improper sales activities and practices
the companies engaged in over the past few years. 
The New York Insurance Department called for these reports after an
investigation showed wholesale violations
of the Department's fair sales practices rules.  The case is fully
briefed and is awaiting decision.<p>

<p>

<b>  Nixon Tapes Case. </b>After President Nixon had resigned from
office, he attempted to take all his papers and
the White House tapes with him, but Congress stepped in and passed
a law requiring the National Archives to
take control of the papers, return the purely private materials to
Mr. Nixon, and make the rest public as soon as
possible, subject to certain exemptions that generally follow the
FOIA.<p>

<p>

     In March 1992, more than 17 years after the law was passed, we
brought suit on behalf of Wisconsin history
professor and Nixon scholar Stanley Kutler, seeking a court order
to force the Archives to comply with the law,
especially for the more than 200 hours of as-yet-unreleased
Watergate tapes. The former president intervened,
and the case became tied up in procedural knots, in part because
the Archives has failed even to return copies of
the private portions of the tapes to Mr. Nixon.   Mr. Nixon died in
April 1994 and his executors were substituted
for him.  Thereafter, the parties agreed to court-supervised
mediation in an effort to resolve the matter. 
Unfortunately, there are significant legal and practical
difficulties, but we are continuing to press this most
important matter.<p>

<p>

<p>

<p>


