<html>
<head>
<title>Election Law</title>
</head>
<BODY COLOR BGCOLOR ="#ffffff" text "#000000" LINK="0000ff" VLINK="#dd0000">
<body>
<h1><center><FONT SIZE=+4>E</FONT>LECTION <FONT SIZE=+4>L</FONT>AW</h1>
</center>
<b></b><p>

<p>

     We continued our work challenging state laws that prevent
minor political parties from cross-nominating major party
candidates for political office, a strategy known as "fusion." 
forty states
forbid third parties from giving their own party's nomination to a
major party candidate, thus forcing
third parties to sit out a race or to run someone against major
party candidates whom they would
otherwise support.  This restriction limits the opportunities of
third parties, inasmuch as many voters
are afraid of "wasting" their vote on a minor party candidate, even
if they are sympathetic to the third
party's platform.<p>

<p>

     In 1995, we handled cases challenging anti-fusion laws in both
Pennsylvania and Minnesota, and
lost both in the trial courts.  Only five days into 1996, however,
a federal appeals court agreed with
us, striking down the Minnesota law that prohibited a new,
progressive party from cross-nominating
a state legislator who was sympathetic to the new party's agenda. 
The Minnesota ruling now creates
a split in the circuits since a different court of appeals upheld
a Wisconsin anti-fusion law in an earlier
decision, which increases the likelihood that the Supreme Court
will resolve this question.  Our
challenge to a similar restriction in Pennsylvania is pending in
another appeals court.<p>

<p>

<p>

<p>


