<head>
<title>GOVERNMENT & CORPORATE
RESPONSIBILITY</title>
</head>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#0000ff" ALINK="#ff0000" 
VLINK="#dd0000">
</CENTER></H1>
<body>
</CENTER></H1>
<H1><CENTER><FONT SIZE=+4>G</FONT>OVERNMENT & <FONT
SIZE=+4>C</FONT>ORPORATE
<FONT SIZE=+4>R</FONT>ESPONSIBILITY
</CENTER></H1>

<p>
<p>

<table border width=100% cellpadding=5>
<tr><td><A HREF="#CR">Corporate Responsibility</a>
<td><A HREF="#CA">Class Actions</a>
<td><A HREF="#PRE">Preemption</a><tr><td><A
HREF="#GA">Government Responsibility</a>
<td><A HREF="#FL">Food Labeling</a>
<td><A HREF="#TRANS">Transportation</a></table>
<p>

<p>

<p>

<h3><center></b><A NAME="CR">CORPORATE
RESPONSIBILITY</a><b></h3>
</center>
<p>

This component of our work has always had two basic strands--serving as a watchdog to make
sure that
the government enforces the laws that are designed to protect the public, and combating the use
of
corporate power that jeopardizes the rights and well-being of the American consumer.  This
year,
however, our corporate accountability work took center stage, <p>

especially with regard to abusive class action settlements and preemption.<p>

<p>

<center><i><A NAME="CA">Class Actions</a></i><p>

</center>
<p>

     1996 marks the 30th anniversary of the federal courts' modern class action rules.  When
put into place in 1966,
the class action rules were lauded as a means of empowering individual plaintiffs with relatively
small claims
by permitting them to band together to litigate their claims in one suit.  Within the last few years,
however,
manufacturers of defective products have seized on the class action device as an expedient and
often cheap
way of disposing of all of the claims against them in a single proceeding.<p>

<p>

     Sometimes these class action settlements obtain reasonable relief for class members.  But
all too frequently,
the relief proposed for class members is paltry, while their lawyers walk away with a mammoth
legal fee.  Our
participation in these cases is vital.  Once lawyers for  the class and the defendant cut a deal, it
can be very
difficult to persuade judges to reject the settlement.  Also, there are few lawyers who are willing
to object to
excessive fees being paid the plaintiffs' counsel as part of the settlement.  For these reasons,
many private
lawyers are unwilling to advocate on behalf of the interest of absent class members.  Without
our involvement,
there would be no effective counterforce to present the interests of class members, as a few
examples make
clear.<p>

<p>

     <b>General Motor Side-Saddle  Trucks<i>.</b>  </i>In this class action, more than 5
million GM truck owners sought
damages and a fix for their pick-up trucks that they alleged were deadly fire hazards because the
"side-saddle"
gas tanks are located outside the frame of the truck.  The settlement provided class members
with a coupon
toward the purchase of a new GM truck or minivan, but <i>no</i> repair for their trucks and no
money for the class
members to seek a repair on their own, although the class lawyers were to be paid about $10
million in fees. 
After a brief hearing, the trial court approved the settlement.<p>

<p>

     On behalf of several truck owners, Public Citizen appealed to a federal appeals court in
Philadelphia, which
struck down the settlement as unfair.  The court's landmark 104-page decision set strict
standards for settling
future consumer class actions and for the award of reasonable attorney's fees.  Critical to the
court's ruling was
its admonition that, in order to secure court approval, class action settlements must confer real
value on the
class members.  GM sought review in the Supreme Court, but we successfully fought that as
well.  We are
now working toward a trial or settlement that  would give the class members an opportunity to
fix their trucks,
at GM's expense, and have negotiated for Public Citizen to be represented on the plaintiffs'
steering committee
to ensure that consumers have a voice at the table if settlement discussions resume.<p>

<p>

<i><b>    </i>Bronco II Utility Vehicles<i>.</i></b>  This class action, filed on behalf of
700,000 Bronco II sports utility vehicle
owners, alleged that the vehicle's boxy design led to hundreds of deadly "roll over" accidents. 
The class
sought a fix of the vehicle and money damages because the resale value of the vehicle had
dropped
substantially.  However, the settlement with Ford provided warning stickers and a "safety" video
(plus a
whopping $4 million for the class' lawyers), but did nothing to fix the Bronco IIs or to pay 
damages to the
owners.  Despite a full-court press by Ford and plaintiffs' counsel, a federal judge in New
Orleans reviewed
evidence from our safety experts and threw out the settlement on the ground that it provided the
class members
with "effectively zero."  The court also found  that the $4 million fee request--which Ford agreed
to
pay--was evidence of possible collusion between Ford and the class lawyers.  Since the court's
decision, we
have been working with a group of lawyers seeking to advance the case to trial and achieve  a
fair resolution
for the owners of the defective Bronco IIs.<p>

<p>

<b>  Chrysler</b> <b>Minivans (Hanlon).</b>  This case involves a defect in nearly four
million Chrysler minivans
manufactured from 1984 to 1995 which causes the rear liftgate latches to pop open in collisions. 
According
to the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA), at least 35 people have died in
accidents
in which the liftgates opened.  Many of the victims have been young children.  In March 1995, in
response
to a NHTSA investigation, Chrysler announced that it would replace all rear liftgate latches free
of charge. 
Soon thereafter, a nationwide class action settlement was reached providing nothing more for
the class  than
what the class was already entitled to receive under Chrysler's agreement with NHTSA.   On
behalf of the
Center for Auto Safety and several individual minivan owners, we submitted extensive
objections to the
settlement, which focused mainly on the lack of value conferred by the settlement and the
outlandish fee award
of  $5 million to class counsel.<p>

<p>

     A federal judge in San Francisco approved the settlement over objections from us and
other minivan owners. 
We have appealed and expect argument to be heard this year.<p>

<p>

<i><b>    </i>Ford Mustang Convertibles (Dale<i>).</i> </b>This class action case
involved a settlement on behalf of owners of
1983-1986 Ford Mustang convertibles that allegedly were defectively designed, causing a lack of
crashworthiness and wind noise and water leakage into the car.  Although the cost of fixing each
car would
be only $600, the settlement would provide each class member with a $400 non-transferable
coupon, valid
for only 12 months, that could be used only toward the purchase price of any new Ford car or
truck.<b>  </b><p>

     Representing dissatisfied class members, Public Citizen filed objections to the
settlement.  We argued that the
settlement was worthless to the vast majority of class members because most members would
not want to buy 
a new Ford, or would not be able to afford a new car within the limited 12 month period. 
Nonetheless,
without making specific findings regarding the fairness, adequacy, or reasonableness of the
settlement, the
judge approved the settlement and just under $1 million in attorneys' fees.  Following our
suggestion,  the
court did, however insist  that this settlement not preclude claims for death or personal injury
resulting from
the defect.   We have appealed, and we expect argument before the  California Court of Appeals
in the Spring
of 1996. <i><b><p>

<p>

     </i>Asbestos Class Action</b> <b>(Georgine).</b>  Until the early 1970's, use of
asbestos was widespread and many
workers, such as insulators and boiler room operators, were heavily exposed to it.  Tragically,
when inhaled
into the lungs, asbestos causes many serious diseases,  including several deadly cancers.  This
class action
concerns an attempt by 20 asbestos  companies to get out of the tort system forever. <p>

<p>

     The companies convinced several plaintiffs' lawyers to bring, and immediately settle, a
class action case which
would shunt future claims of workers injured by asbestos into a workers' compensation-type of
process run
by the 20 companies, with strict limits on the amount of money recoverable.  The class consists
of as many
as 20 to 30 million people who have been exposed to asbestos on the job, but who have yet to
manifest any
illness or disease as a result of the exposure.<p>

<p>

     On behalf of several asbestos victims, asbestos advocacy groups, and labor unions, the
Litigation Group,
working with asbestos plaintiffs' lawyers who refused to join the class counsel,  challenged this
settlement as
unfair and as an unconstitutional effort to deprive future asbestos victims--who currently may
not even know
that they were exposed to asbestos--of their day in court.  After months of preparation and a
multi-week trial,
the trial judge in Philadelphia approved the settlement.  We appealed the decision, and the court
of appeals
heard argument in November 1995.  We expect a  decision sometime in 1996.  <p>

<p>

<b>  Arsenic (Hayden).</b> The asbestos class action is not the only effort to use the federal
courts to set up a cheap
compensation scheme for people who may have been exposed to a toxic substance but have not
yet manifested
an injury.   In <i>Hayden v. Elf Atochem, N.A.</i>, the owner of a chemical plant in Bryan,
Texas reached a
settlement with class counsel binding all present and future claimants alleging injuries arising
from exposure
to arsenic which the plant spewed out for decades.  The class originally sought relief only for
property
damages and medical monitoring, and the court certified the action as an "opt-out" class,
meaning that any
class member who did not want to be bound to the agreement could decide not to participate. 
During
settlement negotiations, however, class counsel agreed to include present and future injury
claims, and to
eliminate the opt-out rights of class members.  The resulting mandatory settlement created a
trust fund which
must be distributed in full to class members over the next seven years, although the record
reflects that the
latency period to develop disease from arsenic exposure lasts up to 40 years, with most of the
illnesses not
becoming manifest until well after the seven year period expires.<p>

<p>

     We represent class members who lived in Bryan for two years and were exposed to the
arsenic.  They now
live out of state and did not receive notice of the action.  They object to the proposed settlement
because it
would eliminate their rights to receive <i>any</i> compensation for future illnesses that develop
after the expiration
of a seven-year period and because they have not been given the opportunity to opt out of the
settlement. The
federal magistrate-judge handling the case approved the settlement.  We have appealed to the
district judge,
claiming that the magistrate was wrong in approving the settlement.  If the district judge agrees
with the
magistrate, we will take our arguments to the Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit.<p>

<p>

<b>  Heart Valve Class Action<i>.</i></b>We  continue our work on behalf of the victims of
the Bjork-Shiley Convexo-Concave artificial heart valve, which was implanted in over 80,000
patients worldwide during the early 1980's. 
The valve has a tendency to fracture once in the body, resulting in death or serious injury.  After
Public
Citizen's Health Research Group uncovered evidence of the valve's defective design and
manufacturing and
of the manufacturer's efforts to hide the truth about the valve's problems, it petitioned the Food
and Drug
Administration to remove the valve from the market in 1984, which resulted in the valve's
withdrawal from
the market in 1986.<p>

<p>

     In 1990, the Litigation Group challenged a class action settlement in Cincinnati which
we believed sold the
patients short in terms of monetary recovery, payments for valve replacement surgery, and other
benefits. 
Working with other advocates, our objections were noted favorably by the judge, and the
settlement was
substantially overhauled to address many of our concerns.<p>

<p>

     Public Citizen remains involved in the case to work for the fair implementation of the
settlement which will
be ongoing for many years.  We are the only opponents of the class counsel's gargantuan $33
million fee
request, which, if approved, will come directly out of the patients' recoveries.  We filed lengthy
objections to
the exorbitant fee request in the Fall of 1995, and we await the court's decision.<p>

<b><p>

     Breast Implant Settlement</b>.  Our involvement in this matter dates back to the late
1980s, when Litigation
Group lawyers filed a Freedom of Information Act case for Public Citizen's Health Research
Group (HRG)
against the Food and Drug Administration to compel the disclosure of health and safety records
showing the
serious adverse health affects associated with silicone-gel breast implants.  Once these records
were made
public, we represented our HRG colleagues who led the charge to get the FDA to restrict the sale
of silicone-gel implants.<p>

<p>

     A nationwide class action case was filed and tentatively settled in 1994. We became
active participants to
ensure that there will be adequate compensation for all affected women, including those who are
not currently
experiencing serious illness.  We have also raised questions about the amount of attorneys' fees
to be paid and
the method by which fees should be calculated.  The settlement has now unraveled because the
main
defendant, Dow-Corning, filed a bankruptcy petition, which effectively freezes all litigation
pending against
it.  As a result of Dow-Corning's filing, we have had to become active in the bankruptcy
proceeding as well.<p>

<p>

     <b>Oat Cereal Case</b>. We failed to persuade a judge in Chicago to reject a class
action settlement involving
General Mills, which was sued after a contractor sprayed an unapproved pesticide on oats used
in the
company's cereals.  Although the pesticide had been approved for spraying on other cereal
products and did
not pose any health hazard to the public, General Mills agreed to end the case by promising to
redeem $10
million in new coupons which would be generally available to consumers and to pay the class
lawyers $1.75
million in cash (not coupons).  We challenged this settlement because it conferred no value on
consumers who
actually purchased the tainted cereal, and we argued that the attorney fee amounted to a
whopping $2,000 an
hour for some of the lawyers' time.  Ultimately, the judge decided that approving the settlement
would be
more beneficial to class members than letting the case go to trial, where consumers (and their
counsel) might
recover nothing.  For a variety of reasons, we have decided not to appeal.<p>

<p>

<b>  Ditlow Defense<i>.</i></b> This matter  is not a class action case, but is instead an
outgrowth of our work on GM's C/K
pickup trucks, which are the subject of the class action settlement discussed above.  In this case,
we
represented Clarence Ditlow, the director of the Center for Auto Safety, who had been a leading
critic of the
fire-prone pickups.  As a result of Ditlow's criticism of GM and its lawyers, Ditlow was the
target of a libel
action brought by one of GM's outside lawyers.  Following a discovery dispute in that litigation,
Ditlow was
harshly and unfairly sanctioned by a court in Detroit--GM's home court.  GM then used the
sanction award
against Ditlow to attack him relentlessly in the press.  We appealed the sanction to the Sixth
Circuit, which,
in a unanimous opinion, reversed the penalty against Ditlow and explained that Ditlow's conduct
had been well
within the letter of the law.  We have been informed that GM does not intend to purse this
matter any further.<p>

<p>

<center><i><A NAME="PRE">Preemption</a></i><p>

</center>
<p>

     The Constitution gives Congress the power to pass laws that supersede or "preempt" state
laws that are
inconsistent or in conflict with a federal statute or with rules issued by a federal agency.  Until
recently,
preemption questions arose infrequently, and generally in the context of complex regulatory
areas--like the
regulation of the price of natural gas. <p>

<p>

     Lately, however, preemption has become the favorite defense of manufacturers whose
products or
services are regulated in any way--even peripherally--by the federal government.  But most
federal regulatory
statutes contain no remedy at all for people injured by the regulated product.  State tort law has
historically
served that function.  Thus, if a court finds that a federal statute "preempts" state law, the injured
party is
generally left with no remedy at all.  Below we describe several of our preemption cases this
year.<p>

<p>

<b>  Maritime law</b>. As noted above, in <i>Yamaha v. Calhoun</i> we obtained a
significant Supreme Court ruling that
preserves state law claims for victims in accidents occurring in the territorial waters of the
United States. 
Although we had not handled the case in the lower courts, the Calhoun family turned to the
Litigation Group
for representation in the Supreme Court because of our dual expertise in Supreme Court practice
and
preemption law.  In our view, the key to victory was to push the Court away from Yamaha's
focus on the need
for uniformity, which it claimed could be achieved only by a federal standard (wrongly, in our
view), and
towards the goal of ensuring reasonable compensation for the families of those killed in boating
accidents. 
Our strategy paid off in an unanimous Court ruling that closely followed the argument  we
advanced.<p>

<p>

<b>  Medical Devices</b>.  For five years the Litigation Group has been fighting medical
device manufacturers
who claim that, because the federal Food, Drug, and Cosmetics Act allows their products to be
marketed,
victims of dangerous and defective medical devices have no remedy under state law.  The
manufacturers claim
that federal law "preempts" an award of compensation for victims no matter how defective the
device and no
matter how serious the patient's injury, even if it can be shown that the manufacturer defrauded
the FDA into
allowing the marketing of the device in the first place.<p>

<p>

     In several early cases, the courts were sympathetic to the companies' arguments and
threw out the claims
of patients seriously injured, or even killed, by defective medical devices.  But in 1995 we
turned the corner
with several important, although partial, victories, in which we were able to persuade federal
appeals courts
in some regions of the country that Congress never intended the medical device laws to act as a
complete bar
to state tort claims.  We knew, however, that the issue was so important as to make Supreme
Court review
inevitable.<p>

<p>

     Our most important victory came in <i>Lohr v. Medtronics</i>, a case concerning a
defective pacemaker.  A
Florida trial court ruled that the FDA's determination that Medtronic's pacemaker was
"substantially
equivalent" to pacemakers marketed prior to the enactment of the 1976 medical device law
preempted all state
law claims for damages.  The Eleventh Circuit reversed, and held that some of Lohr's state-law
tort claims
could proceed to trial.  Shortly after <i>Lohr</i>, the Ninth Circuit in California reached a more
far-reaching result,
finding no preemption of any damages claims regarding a device that the FDA had actually
approved.  Both
the Eleventh and Ninth Circuit's rulings acknowledged the division within the circuit courts on
this issue.  In
January, the Supreme Court granted review in <i>Lohr</i>, and set the case down for argument
in April.  <i>Lohr</i> should
decide the scope of federal preemption in this crucial area, a process we began years ago to
resolve the
preemption issue in a way that provides adequate protection to consumers.<p>

<center><p>

<i><A NAME="TRANS">Transportation</i> </a><b><p>

</center>
<p>

     Cars.</b>  We continue to be active participants in litigation brought by automobile
manufacturers to invalidate
a New York state law requiring manufacturers to disclose the speed at which a car's bumper
sustains serious
injury.  Federal law requires that the bumpers protect the <i>car</i> at speeds of five miles per
hour and greater,
although the bumper itself may be completely destroyed.  New York law, on the other hand,
focuses on what
happens to the bumper in low-speed collisions, because the cost of repairing a damaged bumper
may run into
hundreds or thousands of dollars, and low-speed fender-benders are all too common.  The trial
court upheld
New York's disclosure statute, but the industry appealed.  We filed an extensive <i>amicus</i>
brief and provided
substantial assistance to the state.  Argument was held in December 1995, and we expect a
decision in early
1996.<p>

<p>

<i><b>    </i>Federal Express<i>.</i></b> We are representing consumers who are suing
Federal Express for aggressively
advertising its second-day delivery as the lowest rate around, when second-day delivery was not
the least
expensive way to ship some smaller packages.  A federal judge in Tennessee held that the
consumers' claim
is preempted on the dubious theory that the Airline Deregulation Act stripped the public of the
right to sue an
airline for misrepresentation.  We have appealed, and argument is set in the Sixth Circuit in
early 1996.<p>

<p>

<i><b>    </i>Airlines.</b> We are also representing a passenger who suffered an injury
when, during the acceleration that
follows take-off, the door on a food service cart flew open and slammed against his knee.  The
airline claims
that the federal aviation laws, which provide that the Department of Transportation regulate an
airline's
"service," preempt state tort law and deprive the injured passenger of <i>any</i> remedy.  A
trial judge in Oregon
agreed, and we have appealed to the Ninth Circuit.  As in the medical device field, courts are
taking differing
positions on the question of whether this sort of personal injury relates to airline "service" so that
tort claims
are preempted.  Consequently, we are using this case and others to create sufficient conflict
among the lower
courts that the Supreme Court will be compelled to step in.<p>

<p>

<h4><center></b><A NAME="GA">GOVERNMENT
ACCOUNTABILITY</a><b> </h4>
</center>
<b>  <p>

     Clinical Laboratory Testing</b>. This case involves a major women's health issue.  In
1988, congressional
hearings revealed dangerous deficiencies in laboratory medical testing.  Congress  passed a law
to correct that
situation by, among other things, setting out tougher standards for laboratory personnel
qualifications and for
proficiency testing of cytologists, who read PAP smear slides.  Unfortunately, the regulations
issued by HHS
disregarded certain aspects of the new law, and as a consequence  were far too lax.  Because this
issue is so
crucial to women's health, we brought suit to compel HHS to follow Congress' direction
regarding laboratory
personnel qualifications and cytology proficiency testing.  <p>

<p>

     In a major ruling, the district court agreed with us and directed HHS to issue new
regulations that complied
with the law.  HHS has appealed that decision, and oral argument in the appellate court is
scheduled for
March, 1996.  <p>

<p>

<b>  Medical Device Amendments</b>. In the late 1980s, congressional hearings and reports
put a spotlight on
several weaknesses in the medical device laws and the FDA's implementation of those laws.  In
1990,
Congress amended the medical device laws to correct these deficiencies, and thus further to
protect patients
from unsafe or ineffective products.  Four years later, when the FDA had yet to implement some
of the 1990
amendments, Public Citizen sued.<p>

<p>

     Our lawsuit challenged the FDA's failure to issue regulations implementing six
provisions of the 1990 law. 
Prompted by the litigation, the FDA issued regulations for five of the provisions --not
surprisingly, those on
which our case was strongest.  In a December decision on the remaining regulation, the trial
judge rejected
the FDA's argument that Public Citizen was not a proper plaintiff but also ruled that the agency
did not
necessarily have to issue the final regulation we requested.  Having effectively won on five out
of six issues,
we decided not to appeal the one loss.<p>

<p>

<b>  Food Stamps</b>. Our efforts to settle litigation against the Department of Agriculture
are winding up.  In
1993, we won a case brought on behalf of three individuals against the USDA, challenging its
policy of cutting
food stamp benefits to those poor citizens who receive cash assistance in paying their utility
bills.  USDA
appealed, but then agreed to stop counting utility payments as income on a nationwide basis. 
Thus, we
obtained the principal relief we had been seeking--a great victory for those who rely on food
stamps.  In the
meantime, we had brought a second suit, seeking reimbursement for all individuals in South
Dakota whose
food stamp benefits were wrongly withheld under the policy.<p>

<p>

     Both the appeal and the second suit have been stayed pending settlement negotiations. 
The settlement will
provide withheld food stamps to the class of South Dakotans whose benefits were reduced under
the USDA
policy.  The settlement has been finalized and was recently presented to the Court for approval, 
which is
required under the class action rules.<p>

<p>

<b>  Generic Drugs</b>. Prescription drug manufacturers are now contending that the 1994
law, which ratified the
United States' participation in the new World Trade Organization, increased the terms of drug
patents.  This
issue is important, particularly to elderly consumers, because extending patent terms delays the
time when less
expensive, generic drugs can be brought to market.  We represent a number of consumer groups
as amici
urging a federal appeals court not to accept the manufacturers' argument that they are entitled to
a patent
extension.  The case is likely to be decided in 1996. <p>

<p>

<center><i><A NAME="FL">Food Labeling</a><b></i><p>

</center>
<p>

     </b>In 1990, Congress enacted landmark legislation--known as the Nutrition Labeling
and Education
Act--requiring food retailers to provide certain nutritional information and to make accurate
statements when
they make claims about a food's content and health effects.  In most respects, that law was
properly
implemented by the Food and Drug Administration.  The agency's implementation did, however,
leave two
significant gaps, which we have tried to compel FDA to fill.  Moreover, the statute has been
subject to attack
in a number of courts by the dietary supplement industry, and, in this regard, we have tried to
support the
FDA.<p>

<p>

<b>  Truth in Restaurant Menus</b>. Although permitted nowhere in the 1990 labeling law,
the FDA issued a
rule exempting restaurant menus from the requirement that nutrient-content claims (such as
"lean" or "low
cholesterol") and health claims ("this cereal reduces the risk of cancer") be accurate.  This
exemption has a
significant effect on consumers because about one-half of all food dollars are spent in
restaurants, and
consumers want accurate information on menus just as they do on foods they buy in retail stores. 
The
Litigation Group sued the FDA on the ground that the law does not contain an exemption for
restaurant menus,
and hence the FDA's exemption is unlawful.  Within weeks of our suit, the agency agreed to
publish a
proposed rule rescinding the menu exemption if we would put our lawsuit on hold (which we
did).  But no
sooner did we agree than the FDA reneged, leaving the menu exemption in place.  In mid-1995,
we renewed
our suit asking the court to strike down the menu exemption.  A decision is expected in early
1996.<p>

<b><p>

     Labeling of Fresh Produce and Fresh Fish.</b> Under the 1990 law, Congress allowed
labeling of fresh
produce and fresh fish to be done on a voluntary basis, without mandatory sanctions, but if, and
only if, the
grocery industry was in "substantial compliance" with labeling guidelines published by the FDA. 
The FDA
defined substantial compliance to mean compliance by only 60% of the retail food industry, and
we sued on
the ground that 60% was not "substantial compliance."  In a disappointing ruling, a federal court
of appeals
disagreed with us, holding that the FDA had acted within its discretion.  As a result, many
consumers will be
deprived of important nutritional information for fresh produce and raw fish.<p>

<p>

<b>  Challenges to the Labeling Act's Constitutionality. </b>One key component of the 1990
law is the
prohibition against food and dietary supplement manufacturers making unsupported health
claims, such as
"Omega-3 fatty acids reduce the risk of heart disease."  This requirement is of particular concern
to Public
Citizen since all too often consumers seek  unproven cancer preventions and cures, lured by
overblown claims
about the efficacy of health foods and supplements.  The dietary supplement industry has
challenged the
constitutionality of this portion of the statute in many courts around the country.  Representing
Public Citizen,
the American Cancer Society, the American Heart Association, and the Center for Science in the
Public
Interest, we have filed <i>amici</i> briefs defending the constitutionality of the Act.  Thus far,
we have been
uniformly successful, and we will continue our efforts to protect this part of the Act.<p>

<p>

<table border width=100% cellpadding=5>
<tr><td><a
