<html>
<head>
<title>Worker's Rights</title>
</head>
<BODY COLOR BGCOLOR="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#0000ff" VLINK="#dd0000">
<body>
<h1><center><FONT SIZE=+4>W</FONT>ORKER'S <FONT SIZE=+4>R</FONT>IGHTS</h1>
</center>
<b></b><p>

<p>

<b>	Harsh Limitations Periods</b>. 1995 brought the culmination of our efforts to establish a fair statute of
limitations for workers to bring claims based on the federal plant closing law.  Several federal courts had relied
on a 1983 Supreme Court decision requiring that claims for breach of a union's duty of fair representation must
be brought in court within the six month deadline that workers have to file unfair labor practice charges with the
National Labor Relations Board.  Since 1983, we have been working to confine that approach to such "fair
representation" cases, while employers have been arguing that six months should be the standard time for filing
all labor law cases.  Building on a victory we helped obtain in 1989, which established that union democracy suits
need not be filed within six months, the Supreme Court, in a case we briefed but did not argue, held that plant
closing cases are also subject to a longer period, and the reasoning of the decision should make clear that the six
month period is very much an exception, not the rule.<p>

<p>

<b>	Preemption of State-law Labor Claims.</b>	We also continued our work against federal preemption of state
labor law claims, which dovetails with our more general preemption work discussed above.  We obtained a nice
victory in the Eighth Circuit, where a member claimed that he had been fired for filing a workers compensation
claim, and the employer was able to take his case from state court, where he had secured a preliminary injunction
of reinstatement, into federal court on the ground that his rights under a union grievance procedure superseded
his state-law rights.  We successfully argued that he could pursue his state wrongful discharge claim, but even
more important, we secured a ruling that such claims cannot be removed from state court.  Happily for our client,
but unfortunately for the development of the law, the employer decided not to take this case to the Supreme Court.<p>

<p>

<b>	Sanctions</b>. We spent substantial effort during the past year helping public interest and civil rights lawyers
avoid punitive sanctions.  In the most important of these cases, which is discussed above, we fought off an effort
by General Motors to obtain almost $50,000 in sanctions from Center for Auto Safety director Clarence Ditlow. 
In another case, referred from our Georgia office, we persuaded a trial judge to lift a smaller sanction imposed
on a civil rights lawyer for pursuing a claim that employees of a county tax office had suffered retaliation for
criticizing the authorities. In a third case, we ensured that lawyers for the Government Accountability Project
could obtain a hearing on charges that they abused a nuclear contractor in a whistleblower case (the lawyers were
cleared in a settlement reached before the hearing).<p>

<b><p>

	Teamster Election</b>. Work began in 1995 on representation of the Teamster reform movement in the
battle for re-election of the reform slate in the International Brotherhood of Teamsters.  As a result of that slate's
election in 1991, Public Citizen has been able to work arm-in-arm with the Teamsters union across a broad range
of issues in Congress and the courts.  As was true during the 1991 election, the election is being held, pursuant
to a consent decree between the government and the union, under the supervision of independent court-appointed
officers.  Both because the union's status as a coalition partner is now at stake, and because important union
democracy principles are at stake, we have become deeply involved in election-related legal work.  We helped
shape the court-approved election rules and are now in the trenches on numerous allegations of election
violations.  Our principal role has been to help members pursue charges alleging that the Teamster old guard, led
by Jimmy Hoffa's son who is their candidate for president, has been using local union funds in a variety of ways
to campaign, in violation of the court-approved rules.<p>

<p>

<p>

<p>


<table border width=100% cellpadding=5>
<tr><td><a href="http://www.citizen.org/public_citizen/litigation/annual_rep/govcorp.html">Government &amp;
Corporate
Responsibility</a>
<td><a href="http://www.citizen.org/public_citizen/litigation/annual_rep/conprotec.html">General
Consumer
Protection</a>
<td><a href="http://www.citizen.org/public_citizen/litigation/annual_rep/govsec.html">Government
