<html>
<head>
<title>General Consumer Protection</title>
</head>
<BODY COLOR BGCOLOR="#ffffff" text="#000000" LINK="#0000ff" VLINK="#dd0000">
<body>
<h1><center><FONT SIZE=+4>G</FONT>ENERAL <FONT SIZE=+4>C</FONT>ONSUMER 
<FONT SIZE=+4>P</FONT>ROTECTION</h1> </center>
<b></b><p>

<b>	Trade School Cases</b>. We are litigating   a number of cases for students who were victimized by fly-by-night trade schools that took advantage of the federal guaranteed student loan program.  During the late 1980's,
requirements for the federal loan program were relaxed in a way that increased the ability of vocational schools
to obtain federally funded loans for their students.  Corrupt and poorly operated schools took advantage of this
change by recruiting students with the promise that they would be trained for better paying skilled jobs.  The
training, however, was not provided, many of the schools collapsed or filed for bankruptcy when regulators
starting asking questions, and students were stuck with the obligation to repay loans for an education that they
never received. <p>

<p>

	One major issue in these cases is whether students can raise the school's misconduct as a defense to
repayment of the loan.  Financial institutions responsible for these loans have argued that the federal loan
program preempts ordinary consumer law remedies and requires students to repay the loans regardless of fraud
or other misconduct by the school.  During 1995, we persuaded the Supreme Court to tell an appellate court in
Washington, DC to take a second look at its ruling that students cannot bring lawsuits to present such defenses
to non-repayment of their loans.  At the same time, we represent the plaintiff in another action presenting this
issue that is now being appealed to the DC Circuit.  These cases present important issues concerning the scope
of consumer remedies and preemption that affect the rights and obligations of hundreds of thousands of students
who participated in the federal loan program. <p>

<p>

	We have also pursued relief in the bankruptcy court on behalf of students who attended a vocational school
that filed for bankruptcy.  During this past year, the bankruptcy court agreed with our argument that the students
who were never given notice of the bankruptcy should be given the opportunity to file claims.  Over 100 claims
have now been submitted and, during the coming year, we hope that many of the students defrauded by the school
will be able to recover a limited amount under the special priority afforded to certain consumers under the
bankruptcy laws. <p>

<p>

	Finally, under the student loan program, accrediting agencies were responsible for ensuring that schools
provide quality education, but misconduct by the accrediting agencies was a major source of abuse.  This year
we succeeded in persuading the District Court for the District of Columbia to certify a class action on behalf of
students of a local trade school to pursue a fraud claim against the accrediting agency that was responsible for
accrediting the school.  This case represents one of the first efforts to hold  an accrediting agency responsible for
the representations made concerning vocational schools under the federal loan program.	<p>

<b><p>

	Fair Credit Reporting Act</b>. At the end of 1995, we were asked to file a certiorari petition in an important
case under the Fair Credit Reporting Act.  This statute was enacted by Congress to protect consumers from
inaccurate credits reports, to give consumers a right to have inaccurate reports corrected, and to empower
consumers to sue when credit agencies fail to comply with the Act.  Regrettably, the lower federal courts have
construed the Act in a grudging way, and we have taken over a case in which the Second Circuit held that a
consumer could not sue to correct an inaccurate report until after he or she has been denied credit due to the error. 
That ruling means that consumers, like our client, who try for a year to force a credit agency to correct inaccurate
information, can sue only if they take the highly irrational step of applying for credit that they know will be denied
due to the inaccurate credit report.  Because this decision is inconsistent with that of other courts of appeal, we
believe we have a chance of obtaining Supreme Court review.<p>

<p>

<b>	Corporate Governance</b>. As part of our work to promote corporate accountability, we built on a 1993 court
ruling that rebuffed Wal-Mart's efforts to exclude a shareholder proposal asking the company to prepare a report
on the company's record on equal employment opportunity and affirmative action.  In 1995, a federal appeals
court in New York ordered Wal-Mart to pay the attorneys' fees of the shareholders who submitted the resolution,
a decision which may help to deter other companies from resisting inclusion of shareholder proposals on their
proxy statements.<p>

<p>

<center><i><b>Tobacco</b></i><p>

</center>
<p>

	Another consumer protection area of great concern to us is tobacco-related litigation.  We have long been active
in tobacco issues and have represented smoking control activists, but this year has seen an intensification of those
efforts.  Our work has taken a number of forms, but all are unified by the idea that tobacco--the  nation's leading
cause of illness and death-- needs to be regulated more strictly.<p>

 <p>

<b>	FDA's Proposed Regulations</b>. During the summer of 1995, the FDA proposed to issue regulations to
make it far more difficult for minors to obtain cigarettes and smokeless tobacco products.  Labeling smoking as
a "pediatric disease," the FDA concluded that, since most smokers become addicted to tobacco products while
still in their teens, the most important public health measure it could take would be to prevent young people from
experimenting with tobacco products.  To do so, the FDA has proposed 1) restrictions that would make it more
difficult for teens to obtain tobacco products, 2) restrictions on advertising that might be accessible to minors,
and 3) a massive public education campaign.  	Although the comment period was quite brief, we recognized
the importance of the FDA's proposal and the dearth of tobacco control activists with substantial legal resources. 
Mobilizing our staff, we prepared a 160-page comment that analyzed the key legal issues underlying the FDA's
proposal: preemption, statutory questions regarding the power of the FDA to regulate tobacco, and First
Amendment issues.  Our comments were the only ones supporting the FDA's proposal that contained any
substantial legal analysis.  In contrast, the tobacco companies and their advertising industry allies inundated the
FDA with comments, one running over 2,000 pages.  We expect that once the FDA finalizes its rule, we will be
active in the litigation that will inevitably follow.<p>

<p>

<b>	Merrell Williams</b>. Mr. Williams is a former paralegal for a Louisville law firm that represented the Brown
&amp; Williamson Company, a major cigarette manufacturer.  Mr. Williams has been sued by his former employer
and Brown &amp; Williamson for copying Brown &amp; Williamson documents while he was at the law firm, and the
court entered an order forbidding Mr. Williams from discussing anything that he may have learned as a paralegal
with anyone, including his lawyers.  While we and our Louisville co-counsel finally got that order set aside as
applied to his lawyers, the company has filed criminal contempt charges against Mr. Williams for allegedly
violating the initial court order by disseminating Brown &amp; Williamson records to the media.<p>

<p>

<b>	Cliff Douglas</b>. Cliff Douglas was a key witness for ABC News in a $10 billion libel action brought against
it by Philip Morris for ABC's Day One broadcast alleging that the cigarette companies manipulate nicotine levels
in cigarettes.  Prior to the settlement of that case, we represented Mr. Douglas in his deposition, and succeeded
in staving off Philip Morris' efforts to force Mr. Douglas to reveal the identity of "Deep Cough," an industry
insider who assisted ABC.<p>

<p>

<b>	EPA Tobacco Litigation. </b>We  represent a group of public health organizations in litigation brought by the
tobacco industry to invalidate EPA's pathbreaking 1993 report on the dangers of second-hand tobacco smoke. 
We lost a preliminary battle over whether the industry's suit could be heard before the EPA had taken any final
action, and the case is proceeding through the discovery process.<p>

<p>

<p>

<p>


<table border width=100% cellpadding=5>
<tr><td><a href="http://www.citizen.org/public_citizen/litigation/annual_rep/govcorp.html">Government &amp;
Corporate
