<P>
<H3><A NAME="t5">5. History of European integration</A></H3>
The history of European integration is the subject of both a research theme and a permanent research 
project financed by the Research Council of the Institute. The focus of teaching and research tends to 
shift to make full use of the potentialities afforded by the 30-year rule governing release of official 
government archives in most Community countries and the European Community itself. The archives 
of the Community are deposited at the European archives in Florence, run by the Institute, and 
provide an extra resource base for the research projects.<P>
When the permanent project on the history of the European Community started in 1983 it 
concentrated largely on the problems of the immediate post-war reconstruction, from both a national 
and an international perspective. The focus then shifted to the period 1950-58, where it attempts to 
explain the nature and timing of attempts, both successful and failed, at formalized interdependence 
in Europe. Under Professor. Grifith`s. direction the project covered not only those initiatives 
involving the 'Six' (such as the Coal and Steel Community, the European Economic Community, 
Euratom and the Political Community), but also those in the wider frameworks of the OEEC, NATO 
and GATT as well as within smaller regional sub-groupings such as the Benelux and EFTA. The 
seminars reflect these interests, but will increasingly move beyond these concerns to attempt to lay the 
groundwork for the next generation of research.<P>
Additionally from 1991 to 1995 a research project was directed by Dr <A HREF="krige.html">John Krige</A> on the topic of post-
war big science in Europe. This will focus upon how national European governments, individually 
and collectively, responded to the challenge of the USA and the USSR in the fields of high energy 
physics, atomic power and space technology. This work is supported by the availability of the 
European Space Agency archives in Florence and, indeed, the writing of ESA's history is a central 
goal of the project.<P>
In future the permaent research project on European integration will be paying more attention to 
socio-political aspects, concentrating in particular on the study of allegiance, viz. the set of factors 
that bring the citizens of a country to give their loyalty to instittutions, be they supra-national, 
international or national.<P>
<I>Teaching staff with research interests in this area</I><P>
