<P>
<H2><A NAME="faci">B. Facilities for historians</A></H2>
<H3>1. Library</H3>
<P>
The History section of the Library is part of a relatively recent academic and research collection that 
has been built up since 1976. Its contents reflect the variety of the research that has been undertaken 
in the Department since then, covering the period from the Renaissance to the present day. The 
Library thus possesses, as its basic <I>corpus</I>, an international collection of the literature on the 
history of Europe and its component states, in all the Community languages. In particular, it has a 
solid core of reference works for bibliographic searches and works, mostly published after 1976, 
relating to the history of all European countries. Works not in the Library may be ordered on Inter-
Library Loan. The History collection itself, which is the largest in the Library, also contains a very 
extensive periodicals section, including complete collections (often dating back to 1945) of many 
journals. Books and periodicals are also kept as microfilms or microfiches, and the Library possesses, 
for example, the complete <I>Goldsmith-Kress Library</I> of economic literature from the 16th to 
the 19th Century. Computerized facilities are available for bibliographic searches and access to 
databases, and the Library has a large collection of official sources relating to the history of European 
integration.<P>
<P>
<H3><A NAME="heccomp">2. Historical</A> 
Computing Laboratory</H3>
The departmental programme in historical computing aims to provide programming assistance for 
staff and research students whose work makes a significant use of the computer, and to develop 
original software routines for handling particular types of source-material. Emphasis is at present 
placed on tailoring data-entry software and developing source-oriented database facilities for different 
types of research project. Current projects being developed within the programme involve computer 
analysis of, among other kinds of sources, bills of lading, parish records, cadasters, nominal census 
lists, Inquisition trial records and descriptions of <I>charivaris</I>. Particular emphasis is placed on 
information retrieval, on procedures for nominal record linkage, and on broader questions of 
historical database construction through computer analysis of demographic, judicial and notarial 
records.<P>
The programme is now based on a small Historical Computing Laboratory, run in conjunction with 
the Institute's Computing Centre by the departmental computing assistant, Mr. Michael Goerke. It is 
at present based on Macintosh and MS-DOS microcomputers, and is linked to the Institute's central 
Hewlett Packard UNIX computer. A limited number of laptop microcomputers are available for data 
entry in archives.<P>
<P>
<H3>3. Missions</H3>
Limited funds are available each year to provide assistance for research students visiting archives and 
libraries outside Tuscany. Subject to the availability of funds and supervisor's approval, research 
students can normally expect to go on three missions each year, outside the intensive seminar periods. 
The Department can usually cover travel costs and make a contribution towards subsistence 
expenses.<P>
