<HR>
<B><A HREF="brewer.html">John Brewer</A></B>, <A NAME="brew">born</A> in 1947 was educated at 
Cambridge and Harvard Universities, and has taught at Cambridge, Yale, Harvard and the University 
of California at Los Angeles, where he was Director of the Clark Library and of the Center for 17th 
and 18th Century Studies between 1987 and 1991; His publications include, <I>Party Ideology and 
Popular Politics</I>(1976); <I>An Ungovernable People; the English and their Law in the 
Seventeenth and Eighteenth Centuries</I> (1980), edited with John Styles; with Neil McKendrick 
and J.H. Plumb, <I>The Birth of a Consumer Society</I> (1982); <I>The Sinews of Power: War, 
Money and the English State, 1688-1783</I> (1989); Edited with Roy Porter, <I>Consumption and 
the World of Goods in the 17th and 18th Centuries</I> (1993). His interests include cultural and 
political history, literary and political theory, art history and material culture. His research project at 
the Institute is on graphic culture in Europe in the early modern era.<P>
<B><A HREF="chaudhuri.html">Kirti N. Chauduri</A></B>, <A NAME="chau">born</A> in 1934, is the 
occupant of the Institute's Vasco da Gama chair. He took his doctorate in economic history at the 
University of London in 1961, and was research fellow (1961-1963), then lecturer (1963-1974) and 
reader at the School for Oriental and African Studies of the University of London, where he has been 
professor since 1981. Since 1990 he has been a fellow of the British Academy. He has written six 
books, dealing particularly with the British East India Company from 1660 to 1760, and with trade 
and Civilization in the Indian Ocean from the emergence of Islam to 1750, taking the Indian Ocean 
as an economic unit. His latest book "Asia before Europe" (1990) presents the comparative history in 
the same broad period of the societies bordering the Indian Ocean, on the basis of a structural analysis 
of fundamental features of their economics and civilizations. His work at the Institute is aimed at 
providing a reinterpretation of Northern European historiography and Spanish and Portuguese 
historiography and at setting up a database of both primary and secondary sources for the history of 
European expansion. <P>
<B><A HREF="delille.html">G&eacute;rard Delille</A></B>, <A NAME="deli">born</A> in 1944, took his 
Master's in history in 1968 at the University of Grenoble, his third-cycle doctorate (under the 
supervision of F.Braudel and M.Aymard) at the University of Paris VII in 1971, and the State 
doctorate in 1982 at the University of Paris-I Sorbonne. From 1973 to 1976 he was a member of the 
French School of Rome. In 1977 he was appointed to the CNRS, where he has been research director 
since 1993. Since 1992, he has also been simultaneously director of studies at the Ecole des hautes 
&eacute;tudes en sciences sociales, Paris. Before coming to the Institute, he was working at the French 
School of Rome, to which he was seconded by the CNRS. Since 1986 he has, in collaboration with the 
French School and the anthropological laboratory of the Coll&egrave;ge de France, been directing the 
Manduria project, using as chief source an exact genealogical network extending over five centuries 
in Southern Italy, supplemented by varied archival sources (notarial, judicial, private, ecclesiastical, 
medical). He is a specialist in early modern history, more specifically Italy from the sixteenth to the 
eighteenth centuries, an area in which he has published four monographs  and a large number of 
articles. His research interests are in social history, especially historical demography and 
anthropology. He is a member of the editorial board of Quaderni Storici.<P>
<B><A HREF="fontaine.html">Laurence Fontaine</A></B>, <A NAME="font">born</A> 1946, took her 
doctorate at the University of Lyon II in 1983, under the supervision of Y. Lequin. She was Jean 
Monnet Fellow at the European University Institute in 1987-8. Before coming back to the Institute 
she was CNRS Research Associate (1st class) at the Centre for Historical Research of the Ecole des 
hautes &eacute;tudes en sciences sociales, Paris. She has published two books (and many articles) on peddlers 
in Oisans in the last century and in Europe between the 15th and 19th centuries. Her research at the 
Institute will be on institutions and social practices related to credit in Europe between the 16th and 
19th centuries.<P>
<B><A HREF="hufton.html">Olwen Hufton</A></B>, <A NAME="huft">born</A> in 1938, holds a B.A. 
in History from Royal Holloway College University of London and a doctorate in History from the 
University of London. She also holds an M.A. in history from the University of Oxford and from 
Harvard. From 1966 to 1987 she was Lecturer, then Reader and Professor, at the University of 
Reading. Since 1987 she has been Professor of European History and Women's History at Harvard 
University. She is Fellow of the Royal Historical Society and Co-editor of the Cambridge Studies in 
Early Modern History. Her chief work has been on the Social History of the 18th century Europe 
(especially France) in a comparative perspective (dealing particularly with urban life, the least 
favoured social classes and the phenomenon of violence), and on women in Europe in the 
Renaissance and the Early Modern period. <P>
<B><A HREF="leboutte.html">Ren&eacute; Leboutte</A></B>, <A NAME="lebo">born</A> in 1952, graduated 
from the University of Li&egrave;ge, where he also took his doctorate in 1985 with a study in labour 
reconversion and the demographic transition in industrial basins downstream of Li&egrave;ge in the 19th and 
20th centuries. In 1976 he taught at the $&eacute;coles normales de l'$&eacute;tat, Li&egrave;ge, and from 1977 to 1989 he 
was conservator of the Museum of Walloon life and the Coal and Steel Museum. Since 1981 he has 
been assistant lecturer, then lecturer, at the University of Li&egrave;ge, and since 1989 has been attached to 
the State Archives in Namur. His academic interests range from industrial archaeology and the 
history of technology to historical demography and anthropology. His present research, from a 
comparative, long-term viewpoint, relates to the life and death of industrial basins in Europe in the 
period from 1750 to 1990.<P>
<B><A HREF="milward.html">Alan S. Milward</A></B>, <A NAME="milw">born</A> 1935, is a doctor of economic history at the London 
School of Economics (1960). He was Lecturer at the universities of Edinburgh (1960-5) and East 
Anglia (1965-9), then Associate Professor of Economics at Stanford (1969-71) and Professor of 
European Studies at UMIST till 1983. From 1983 to 1986 he was Professor of History at the 
European University Institute, directing the permanent research project on European integration. 
Before coming back to the Institute he was Professor of Economic History at the LSE (1986-95). He 
has been Visiting Professor at EHESS, the European College at Bruges and the universities of Illinois 
(Urbana), Siegen, Oslo and Trondheim. He has written some ten books and numerous articles on the 
economic development of Continental Europe, on economic aspects of the Second World War and on 
the history of Europe since 1945 (in particular the <I>Rescue of the Nation State</I>, published in 
1994). His research is on the history of European integration.<P>
<B><A HREF="passerini.html">Luisa Passerini</A></B>, <A NAME="pass">born</A> in 1941, studied 
history and philosophy at the University of Turin, where she later on (1985-93) taught Methodology 
of Historical Research. In the meantime she had been researcher at the Universities of Dar es Salaam, 
Tanzania, and Lusaka, Zambia, and teacher in Italian schools. She has been Visiting Professor at the 
New School for Social Research, N.Y., at the Universities of Perth and Sydney, Australia, and at New 
York University. She was a fellow of the Wissenschaftskolleg, Berlin, and of the 
Kulturwissenschaftliches Institut, Essen. Her research interests have ranged from the history of 
fascism to the history of youth and women's movements, approached from the point of view of a 
history of subjectivity (using memory as a historical source and posing questions related to what it 
means to be a subject of history). Her research at the Institute concerns the political use of certain 
concepts of love and their connection with European identity.<P>
<B><A HREF="reis.html">Jaime Reis</A></B>, <A NAME="reis">born</A> 1944, is a graduate of the 
Fletcher School of Law and Diplomacy (universities of Tufts and Harvard). He took his doctorate in 
modern history at Oxford, and agr&eacute;gation at the New University of Lisbon. He was Lecturer at the 
Universities of Leicester (1974-6) and Glasgow (1976-78), before being appointed to the Economics 
Faculty of the New University of Lisbon (Assistant Professor in 1978/9, Associate Professor from 
1979 to 1985, full Professor from 1985 to 1993); he was Dean from 1986 to 1990. Before coming to 
the Institute, he was research director at the Institute for Social Science of Lisbon University. He is on 
the editorial boards of several Iberian journals, and a founding member of the European Historical 
Economics Society (EHES). He is the author of several publications on the economic history of Brazil 
at the turn of the century, on the economic, monetary and financial history of Portugal from the mid-
19th century to the Second World War, and on the gold standard and international monetary systems. 
His research at the Institute will be on the long-term economic performance of peripheral European 
countries, in particular comparing Scandinavia and Mediterranean Europe between 1850 and 
1950.<P>
<B><A HREF="romanelli.html">Raffaele Romanelli</A></B>, <A NAME="roma">born</A> in 1942, studied 
at the University of Rome, where he graduated in Political Sciences. He has been lecturer in political 
history at the University of Trento, Faculty of Sociology (1970-71), Associate Professor of Italian 
History at the University of Macerata (1971-74) and Associate Professor of Contemporary History at 
the University of Pisa (1974-93). His chief work has been on political and administrative history of 
19th century Italy (dealing particularly with the problems of local government and of electoral 
systems), on the study of European bourgeoisies in a comparative perspective, and on the social 
history of patrimonies and the wealthy elites. His research interests focuses on the relations between 
social history and institutional history. In this perspective, at present he is working on family 
relations in 19th century codes, and on the history of Italian local government. At the Institute he 
leads a research project on the comparative analysis of electoral mechanisms in the European 
representative systems.<P>
