<HEAD>

<TITLE>Department of Law - European University Institute, Florence, Italy 
</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="#ffffff">

<H1><IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="../iue.gif">EUI - Department of Law
</H1>

<UL>
<LI><A HREF="#org">Organization of studies</A> 
<LI><A HREF="#them">Teaching and research themes</A> 
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="#european">European law</A> 
<LI><A HREF="#comparative">International and comparative law</A>

<LI><A HREF="#contextual">Legal theory and law in context</A>

</UL>

<LI><A HREF="#staff">Teaching staff</A> 
<LI><A HREF="#info">Further Information</A> 
<LI><A HREF="#pub">Publications</A> 
</UL>
<HR>

The identity of the department can be described in three terms:
it is <A HREF = "#european">European</A> in its character, <A HREF = "#comparative">comparative</A>
in its approach and <A HREF = "#contextual">contextual</A> in
its methods.
<P>
The European character of the activities in the Law Department
can be found in any of its research projects in different degrees
(for details see below under the individual projects). Legal problems
of the European Community are the central focus of some projects.
While in some other projects of the department, the issues of
harmonization and unification in a European perspective are not
the principal focus, their relevance is implicit in all projects,
which are all directed towards the emergence of European legal
problems and solutions. In addition to Community law, teaching
and research in the department focuses on the law of the Council
of Europe and its Member States, with special attention to the
protection of fundamental rights in Europe under the ECHR. In
thesis topics as well, the issues of European legal institutions
and the development of a body of European law are at the centre
of the department's research interests. The department cooperates
intensively with the Robert Schuman Centre and assists in an interdisciplinary
approach to problems facing the Community.
<P>
The department's approach is comparative. At present, all professors
in the department are comparative lawyers and the approach of
the projects is to compare aspects of different legal orders.
This is also true for research students' theses, for which the
comparative character of their analysis is a minimal requirement.
The fields of comparative law which the department covers are
quite broad. However, given the present size of the department,
a concentration on certain fields is necessary. The Law Department
therefore intends to focus its activities in comparative law on
the main legal problems of the political and economic systems
in Europe.
<P>
It is a characteristic feature of the Law Department that its
methods are contextual. 'Law in context' is a specific approach
to legal problems which has developed in the Law Department and
which the department intends to continue and to strengthen in
the future. Rather than analyse law in purely technical fashion,
these methods set it in its social, political and economic context.
In both teaching and-research, such disciplines as legal theory,
economic analysis of law and legal sociology therefore occupy
an important place.
<P>
The seminars and research projects of the Law Department seek
to approach the topics studied in a comparative, Community and
interdisciplinary perspective. The international background of
teaching staff, the collaboration of a large number of visiting
professors chosen for their specific competences and the active
involvement of research students from different Community countries
and university systems are all valuable here. Both research and
seminars take advantage of contributions from specialists in other
disciplines (history, political science, economics) whenever a
different academic approach seems useful for the analysis and
more detailed treatment of the topics concerned.
<H2><A NAME="org">Organization of studies</A></H2>

<H3>The Doctorate in Law</H3>

Like the three other departments, the Law Department offers a
three-year course leading to the doctorate. The general rules
governing admission and the course of doctoral studies are given
in Chapter III of this prospectus. In the first year, new research
students on the doctoral programme follow a series of seminars
jointly with LLM students, described in point (c) below.
<H3>One-year Master's Degree (LLM)</H3>

Since 1984 the European University Institute has been offering
law students a one-year programme leading to the degree of Master
in Comparative, European and International Law (comparable with
a British LLM).
<P>
The research students, counselled and supervised by a professor
in the department, participate in departmental seminars and write
a dissertation which is the basis for the conferment of the degree.
The dissertation is normally submitted at the end of the course,
but the final date for the submission of the LLM thesis is to be on 
1 October following the researcher's entry
into the programme.
<P>
Admission, residence and seminar participation requirements are
the same for LLM students as for those intending to take the doctorate.
<H2>Teaching and research themes</H2>

<H3><A NAME="european">European law</A> </H3>

Teaching and research focus upon European Community law, its links
with the law of the Council of Europe, and European economic law.
<P>
In the area of European Community law, the following topics are
emphasized- the EC legal order; institutional structure; legislative
acts and procedures; judicial remedies and judicial review; EC
law and national law; European courts and European integration;
the effectiveness of European Community law; diversity, differentiation
and subsidiarity; the dual character of supranationalism; Maastricht
and the European institutions after 1992; the Community legislative
process; levels of decision-making and their interrelation; the
implementation of Community law. Special emphasis is placed on
both the mastery of the technical aspects of law and an ability
to appreciate and analyse these aspects in their social, political
and economic context (two to three hours per week).
<P>
As well as these general questions of Community law, links with
the law of the Council of Europe are specifically treated. These
have made the protection of fundamental rights in Europe a special
focus of research being pursued on a permanent basis.
<P>
The Community's areas of action as expanded through the Single
European Act (for example, internal market, structural policies,
technological development, environmental protection, social policy
and European political cooperation) are dealt with in specific
projects and seminars. Research projects also deal with the control
of fraud against the Community, regulation of foodstuffs in the
internal market, and contextual approaches to Community law.
<P>
European economic law includes, as well as the legal rules establishing
the common market, European commercial law and European company
law.
<P>
Research students working in this area can benefit from the close
relations the Institute has with the various European institutions
represented on its Research Council (the Parliament, the Commission,
the European Court of Justice); there are possibilities of spending
trainee periods at one of these during the course of research.
They will also find very useful the conferences and symposia on
European questions organized regularly by the department or by
the Robert Schuman Centre, involving members of those institutions.
<H4>Teaching staff working in this area</H4>

<UL>
<LI><A HREF="deh.html">Professor Renaud Dehousse</A> 
<LI><A HREF="diez.html">Professor Luis Mar&iacute;a D&iacute;ez-Picazo Gim&eacute;nez</A>

<LI><A HREF="snyd.html">Professor Francis Snyder</A> 
</UL>

<H4>Examples of thesis subjects</H4>

The Single European Act: contract work and public procurement.
<BR>
The application of European Law in air transport. <BR>
Implementation of Community decisions by national administrations.
<BR>
The European Parliament's control over the foreign policy of the
European Community. <BR>
Harmonization of EC social security law after 1993.<BR>
EC powers relating to the environment.<BR>
German unification and European unity. <BR>
Spatial delimitation of the field of application of Articles 85
and 86 of the Treaty of Rome.<BR>
The physical protection of consumers in Community law.<BR>
Franchising and Community competition law.<BR>
Television competition and Community law.<BR>
Community aid rules and their effects on the Spanish system.<BR>
The rights of the defence in proceedings for application of Articles
85 and 86 of the EEC.<BR>
The legal protection of privacy in Scandinavian countries.<BR>
The European convention on Human Rights and Spain.<BR>
The Community Charter of the Fundamental Social Rights of Workers.
European regulation of the insurance sector.<BR>
Relations between local authorities and the European Communities.
<BR>
High technologies and cooperation between firms.<BR>
Controls on concentrations of firms in American, European and
French-law.<BR>
Social dialogue and collective bargaining at European level.
<H3><A NAME="comparative">International and comparative law </A>
</H3>

The department's strong points in this teaching and research area
are:
<UL>
<LI>relations between different levels of legal order;
<LI>comparative constitutional law;
<LI>public international law, particularly its role in the elaboration
and implementation of foreign policy and in human rights protection
at world and at European level;
<LI>nationality law, in comparative aspects and in (private) international
law;
<LI>aliens law in the countries of Western Europe (including law
on refugees);
<LI>labour and social law, including individual employment, industrial
relations and social security;
<LI>environmental law, particularly as regards cross-border pollution;
<LI>gender studies.
</UL>

<H4>Teaching staff working in this area</H4>

<UL>
<LI><A HREF="alst.html">Professor Philip Alston</A> 
<LI><A HREF="camp.html">Professor Marie-Jeanne Campana</A> 
<LI><A HREF="ehl.html">Professor Claus Dieter Ehlermann</A> 
<LI><A HREF="joer.html">Professor Christian Joerges</A> 
<LI><A HREF="krav.html">Professor Yota Kravaritou</A> 
<LI><A HREF="diez.html">Professor Luis Mar&iacute;a D&iacute;ez-Picazo Gim&eacute;nez</A>

</UL>

<H4>Examples of thesis subjects</H4>

Refugees' status in the Europe of 1993.<BR>
The conclusion of international treaties in comparative constitutional
law. Legal rules on transport of toxic wastes. <BR>
Export of toxic wastes.<BR>
A comparative study of judicial review of administrative action.
<BR>
Emergency legislation and the constitutional system in selected
European countries. <BR>
Public-service broadcasting and its regulation: new challenges
to old principles. <BR>
The right to asylum in the context of creating a uniform refugee
policy for the European Community. <BR>
Equal treatment for men and women in the labour law of Community
Member States. <BR>
Implementation of policy instruments in waste-oriented legislation
and the effect on recycling and reduction of waste. <BR>
The rights of defence in administrative courts.<BR>
Protecting the European cultural heritage: Community action and
national measures. <BR>
Relations between the Community and common-law Member States.
<BR>
Assessment of, and compensation for, environmental damage. <BR>
Freedom of association and workers' rights of expression.
<H3><A NAME="contextual">Legal theory and law in context </A>
</H3>

Legal philosophy and legal theory are areas in which the differences
in approach among the various European legal traditions come out
most clearly and in which the renewal of ideas and approaches
has been most profound. The Institute plays an active role in
this exchange of ideas and in these debates and has hosted a number
of the outstanding figures in them at symposia and conferences
or as visiting professors, including: N. Luhmann, J. Habermas,
A. Aarnio, J. Broeckman, M. Troper, K. H. Ladeur, N. MacCormick
and R. Dworkin. The department's own work involves the theory
of autopoiesis and its possible application in law as well as
the contribution of analytical philosophy to legal reasoning and
its legal interpretation. Weinberger's and MacCormick's neo-institutionalist
theory is used towards a new definition of law and its relationship
with morality. Within this approach special attention is paid
to 'perverse' legal systems (in particular the national-socialist
one).
<P>
Among the interdisciplinary approaches special mention should
be made of the area of women's studies where the Institute has
a well-established interdisciplinary tradition and which provides
the subject for the 1994/95 European Forum (Gender and the use
of time). As far as its legal elements are concerned, work is
being done, taking into account gender in legal subjects in labour
law (notably at Community level), and on feminist approaches to
law in the context of cultural diversities.
<H4>Teaching staff working in this area</H4>

<UL>
<LI><A HREF="joer.html">Professor Christian Joerges</A> 
<LI><A HREF="lade.html">Professor K. H. Ladeur</A> 
<LI><A HREF="krav.html">Professor Yota Kravaritou</A> 
<LI><A HREF="torr.html">Professor Massimo La Torre</A> 
<LI><A HREF="snyd.html">Professor Francis Snyder</A> 
</UL>

<H4>Examples of thesis subjects</H4>

Genetic resources and legal concepts of inheritance in Europe.
<BR>
Joint ventures. <BR>
Individual responsibility and normative order in common law with
particular reference to the formation and development of Scottish
criminal law. <BR>
Equality and positive discrimination in the USA and Europe.<BR>
Comparative law and comparative linguistics: the case of the European
Communities. <BR>
The theory of property law and public ownership: an economic analysis
of law.<BR>
Constitutional courts and the construction of the constitutional
State. <BR>
Critique and reconstruction of the classical legal model of the
limited company.<BR>
Rationality in legal argumentation: does discourse theory offer
an alternative?
