<HR>
<H2><A NAME="acad">The European Law Academy and its publications</A>
</H2>
<P>
The <STRONG>European University Institute</STRONG> is a post-graduate research
institute set up by the Member States of the European Union. Its mission is to
contribute to the development of Europe's cultural and academic heritage in both
its unity and diversity. It carries out this mission through teaching and
research at the highest university level. To date the Institute's activities in
the field of law have primarily centred around two programmes: a PhD programme
and an LLM programme.</P>
<P>
The <STRONG>Academy of European Law</STRONG>, established by the Institute in
1990, extends the Institute's traditional programmes into a larger field of
interest. The main activity of the Academy is the holding of annual summer
courses on European Law and the Protection of Human Rights in Europe. The
courses of the Academy, given by leading authorities in the respective fields,
are subsequently published by Kluwer International in an annual publication, the
<A HREF="aeltoc.html">Collected Courses of the Academy of European Law (AEL)</A>.
This year sees an innovation in the structure of the Summer Course, with the
decision to divide it into two parts. There will thus be one session on European
Union law and another on the protection of human rights in Europe. Participants
will be able to opt for participation in one session or in both. Each session is
composed of three main elements, namely: the Distinguished Lectures, delivered
by leading authorities on issues of current interest in Europe; the General
Course, covering general background information; and the specialized courses,
focusing on topics relevant to law in context.</P>
<P>
The Academy will hold its <STRONG>Eighth Session</STRONG> from 23 June to 4
July 1997 for the <STRONG>European Union Law course</STRONG> and from 7 to 18
July 1997 for the <STRONG>Human Rights course</STRONG>.</P>
<P>
The Academy also publishes the <A HREF="ejiltoc.html">'European Journal of
International Law'</A> which aims to provide a forum for debate and analysis of
current important issues within the Union, and in international law. The
<A HREF="efpb.html">European Foreign Policy Bulletin</A> publishes documents
issued in the framework of the common foreign and security policy of the
European Union.</P>
<P>
The Directors of the Florence Academy of European Law are Professors
<A HREF="http://www.iue.it/LAW/alst.html">Philip Alston </A>,
<A HREF="http://www.iue.it/LAW/deh.html">Renaud Dehousse</A> and
<A HREF="weiler.html">Joseph H.H. Weiler</A>.</P>
<HR>
<H2><A NAME="org">Organization </A></H2>
<H3>Languages </H3>
<P>
Courses are held in English and French; simultaneous translation is not
available. As participants must be able to follow courses in both of these
languages, a prerequisite for admission is a strong command of one language and
at least a passive knowledge of the other.</P>
<H3>Schedule </H3>
<P>
Courses are held every morning on weekdays and, if necessary, on some afternoons
as well. Participants are requested to stay in Florence for the entire duration
of the session. Attendance at all courses is obligatory. A certificate of
participation is issued at the end of each session.</P>
<H3>Workshops </H3>
<P>
In addition to the teaching programme, workshops are held on various topics of
current interest. These are intended for smaller groups (not more than 25 to 30
participants) and offer ample opportunity for discussion with the lecturers and
amongst the participants.</P>
<H3>Eligibility </H3>
<P>
Participation in the Summer Sessions is open to students of law and related
fields and lawyers of all nationalities. Participants should be law graduates or
have been enrolled in a recognized law programme for at least one year.
Enrolment numbers are limited and admission is based on merit. A certain number
of places are open to legal practitioners in order to increase their
understanding and appreciation of European law and human rights law and their
application and practice.</P>
<H3>Enrolment Fees </H3>
<P>
There is an enrolment fee of ECU 250 for each course, payable on acceptance of
admission. For applicants who choose to attend both courses, the fee is ECU 400.
Fees are waived for students in receipt of a scholarship.</P>
<H3>Scholarships </H3>
<P>
A limited number of scholarships are generally awarded to participants from
Eastern and Central Europe. In exceptional cases, fee-waivers may also be
granted. Decisions on scholarships and fee-waivers are at the discretion of the
Directors of the Academy and are based on need. They do not cover travel
expenses. However, several national and international organizations, for
example, the Deutsche Akademische Austauschdienst, also offer scholarships for
participation at the Summer Courses.</P>
<H3>Accommodation </H3>
<P>
The Academy assists participants in finding accommodation for their stay in
Florence. The cost of housing for a period of two weeks is estimated to be
approximately ECU 400. The Academy does not accept responsibility for hotel
reservations made on behalf of participants. Therefore, participants may be
requested to pay part of the cost in advance. Upon arrival, participants should
make arrangements for payment of hotel bills directly with the hotel manager.
Please note that the Academy does not provide medical insurance and cannot cover
medical fees. Participants are advised to purchase international medical
insurance in their home country before leaving.</P>
<H3>Application </H3>
<P>
Applicants should use the Academy's application form for the current year and
write in English or French directly to: </P>
<P><EM>European University Institute <BR>Academy of European Law <BR>Villa
Schifanoia <BR>Via Boccaccio, 121 <BR>I-50133 Firenze <BR>ITALY</EM></P>
<P>
The <A HREF="euform.html">application form</A> is made available here for printing
(access the form and print with your browser's print function). 
Alternatively it can be downloaded in <A HREF="euform.ps">postscript format</A>. 
</P>
<P>
In addition to the application form, applications should include the following: 
</P>
<UL>
<LI>a typed <EM>curriculum vitae</EM>
</LI>
<LI>a letter explaining the applicant's field of interest and reasons for
wishing to attend the session at the Academy, whether or not they are in gainful
employment and, where appropriate, reasons for applying for a scholarship
</LI>
<LI>a photo, to be glued to the marked place on the application form
</LI>
<LI>at least one reference letter from one of the applicant's professors.
</LI>
</UL>
<P>
Submission of other materials, such as copies of diplomas or publications, is
not necessary. Applications must be mailed by express post or equivalent to
ensure arrival by April 15 of the current year.
</P>
<H3>The Diploma of the Academy </H3>
<P>
A limited number of participants who already have advanced knowledge in the
fields of European Union law and/or the law of the European Convention on Human
Rights may request to sit the Academy's examinations. Successful participants
will be awarded the Academy's Diploma either in European Law or in Human Rights
Law. Exceptionally, the Diploma may be awarded cum laude. Applicants should
indicate if they wish to be candidates for the Diploma in their application.
Such requests are in no way binding.</P>
